<HEADLINE>Judges delay on soldiers' appeal</HEADLINE>
<EDITION>1</EDITION>
<PAGE>8</PAGE>
<RECORDNO>975208450</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
JUDGMENT was reserved yesterday in the appeal by two Scottish soldiers serving
life imprisonment for murdering a Belfast teenager.
Scots Guards James Fisher and Mark Wright were convicted at Belfast Crown Court
last February, of murdering Mr Peter McBride, 18, in the New Lodge area in
September 1992.
When the week-long appeal ended yesterday, the Lord Chief Justice Sir Brian
Hutton said it would take some time to deliver judgment because of the detailed
submissions he and the two other judges had to consider.
``We will try to deliver judgment as soon as possible,'' he added.
Fisher, 27, from Glendale Place, Belmont, Ayr, and Wright, 22, from Arbroath,
Tayside, admitted at their trial that they shot Mr McBride as he ran away.
They denied murdering him and said they opened fire because they thought their
lives were in danger as they believed he was carrying a ``coffee jar'' bomb.
Lawyers for the soldiers claimed that vital witnesses had lied in their
evidence because they were hostile to the British Army.
However, the Crown argued that Lord Justice Kelly, who presided at the non-jury
trial, was entitled to convict the soldiers on the basis of all the evidence in
the case.
The soldiers were taken back to Maghaberry Prison, near Lisburn, where they
have been held since they began their life sentences.
</TEXT>
