<HEADLINE>Arms trial jury hears of terror gun deal</HEADLINE>
<EDITION>2</EDITION>
<PAGE>7</PAGE>
<RECORDNO>975208451</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
AN Orangeman travelled from Scotland to Liverpool for the 12th of July march
and a gun deal, a court was told yesterday.
Mr John Johnston, one of six men on trial on charges involving terrorist
activities, was trying to buy two rifles, it was alleged.
When the deal was done, it was alleged, Mr Johnston said he was going to
contact a flute band to get the guns to Ireland.
Mr Johnston, 49, of Campbell Crescent, Laurieston, Falkirk, a former master of
his local Orange Lodge, is on trial accused of conspiring to further the cause
of the Ulster Volunteer Force by acquiring weapons to endanger life or cause
serious damage to property.
The five other accused are Francis Hives, 45, of Liverpool; William McArthur,
42, of Bonnybridge; David White, 29, of Airdrie; Alexander Davidson, 23, and
Lindsay Robb, 28, both from Lurgan in Northern Ireland.
Mr Johnston's alleged gun dealing activities were revealed to the High Court in
Glasgow by his friend Henry Hardie, 46, of Park Avenue, Laurieston, who is also
a past master of the local Orange Lodge.
Mr Hardie told Mr Ian Bonomy QC, prosecuting, that Mr Johnston organised dances
for the Loyalist Prisoners Welfare Association, at which hooded paramilitaries
urged help from their Scottish comrades to win the ``long and bloody war'' in
Northern Ireland.
Mr Hardie also alleged that Lindsay Robb showed him a handgun when he went to
Ireland to visit him.
Cross-examined by Mr Robb's defence QC, Mr Donald Findlay, Mr Hardie said he
would not be surprised to learn that the RUC had given Mr Robb a gun perfectly
legally for personal protection purposes.
Mr Hardie, who said that he spent much of his time in Liverpool drunk, admitted
that Mr Johnston ``talked a good game'' and liked people to see him as a man in
the know who knew people of influence.
He said people took what he said with a pinch of salt.
The trial continues.
</TEXT>
