<HEADLINE>Hundreds reported killed in rebel blast</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>MOHAN SAMARASINGHE</BYLINE>
<EDITION>3</EDITION>
<PAGE>10</PAGE>
<RECORDNO>975208453</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
Colombo
SRI LANKA'S state-run National News Agency said today that up to 500 civilians
were killed on Wednesday when a truck being loaded with explosives by Tamil
rebels blew up in a northern guerrilla-held town.
State television reported that about 100 guerrillas of the Liberation Tigers of
Tamil Eelam (LTTE) were among more than 500 people killed in the blast in
Chavakachcheri, about 10 miles east of the rebel bastion of Jaffna.
However other sources put the death toll much lower. Western aid workers in
Colombo said they had information that four Tiger rebels were killed and 67
people were taken to hospital for treatment.
Sri Lankan Army officials said there had been an explosion in which civilians
might have been killed but a spokesman said: ``Chavakachcheri is under rebel
control. We have no way of getting a first-hand confirmation.''
The National News Agency quoted a Tamil civilian who crossed into the
government-held town of Vavuniya as reporting the 500 deaths.
Other civilians who arrived in Vavuniya from Chavakachcheri said that nine
guerrillas were killed. They said nothing about civilian deaths in
Chavakachcheri, a northern coastal camp for civilians fleeing the fighting in
Jaffna.
The Sri Lankan Army said it planned to recruit 10,000 troops to help tighten
its grip on the Jaffna peninsula and prepare for what it hoped would be a final
onslaught against the rebels.
Military spokesman Brigadier Sarath Munasinghe said the army hoped to complete
the recruiting drive within a month.
The campaign is being matched by LTTE rebels, who have opened centres in areas
under their control and are seeking young fighters.
Eleven soldiers were killed today when rebels attacked an army foot patrol at
Punani in the eastern Batticaloa district, the military said.
The army cut off Jaffna town completely this week, leaving no way of escape for
about 2000 guerrillas holed up there.-Reuter.
</TEXT>
