<HEADLINE>Looting and burning as blue helmets prepare to make way for Nato force Goals achieved, says Karadzic</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>KURT SCHORK</BYLINE>
<EDITION>3</EDITION>
<PAGE>10</PAGE>
<RECORDNO>975208454</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
Sarajevo
BOSNIAN Serb leader Radovan Karadzic said tonight that his people welcomed
peace and had achieved their goals in the Ohio agreement to end the war
``It is good for peace to begin, for our people to live in peace,'' he told
Bosnian Serb television.
``I can say we achieved our goal: we have half of Bosnia, more than 40 cities,
and also good land,'' he said.
Earlier in north-west Bosnia, Bosnian government troops looted a UN base as
Nato stood by to deploy the advance guard of a much tougher international force
to police the peace deal.
There was no hiding Bosnian Serb resentment over elements of the deal
negotiated on their behalf by their Serb paymaster, President Slobodan
Milosevic.
Karadzic warned that the planned handover of Serb suburbs of Sarajevo to the
Muslim-Croat federation would lead to further fighting unless it was
renegotiated.
``We accepted peace but we will search for a solution to Sarajevo,'' he said in
his first public comment on the Dayton agreement.
Senior Bosnian Serb hardliner Momcilo Krajisnik said on the same programme that
Milosevic had left him on the sidelines for 15 days at Dayton. He accused the
Serbian leader of being only interested in the lifting of UN sanctions on his
country.
``We accept the peace,'' Karadzic told this evening's broadcast aimed at
persuading diehard rebels that their leaders did their best and all further
armed resistance would be futile.
Leaders of Serb-held Sarajevo suburbs have vowed to fight to defend them, but
Karadzic said: ``The time has come to use political means to achieve our
goals.''
Looking subdued and sombre Krajisnik said ``Milosevic outvoted us'' on the
issue of deploying Nato troops on Serb-held land, something the rebels were
against.
The Serbian president also agreed to a giveaway of territory in western Bosnia
which the rebels had wanted to hold on to, he said.
Bosnian government troops looted a UN base in north-west Bosnia. A UN spokesman
said 200 soldiers fired machineguns over the heads of Bangladeshi peacekeepers
guarding the base.
There were also reports from UN officials that Croat forces were burning and
looting houses in an area of north-west Bosnia which is scheduled to revert to
Serb control under the peace agreement.
UN spokesman Lieutenant-Colonel Chris Vernon said Bosnian government troops had
entered a Bangladeshi-manned base at Velika Kladusa in the Bihac enclave and
carried off equipment including nine vehicles.
``Bosnian Army personnel entered the camp and effectively went through the camp
taking what they thought fit against the protests of the Bangladeshis,'' Vernon
said.
The 80 Bangladeshi peacekeepers were spending their last night in the camp,
which was due to be handed over to the British.
The incidents of looting and burning came as UN peacekeepers prepared to
withdraw from Bosnia to make way for Nato combat troops, or change helmets and
come under Nato command. The Nato troops are expected to have much more
aggressive rules of engagement than the UN force.
Alliance sources in Brussels said Nato may get a green light soon, possibly
early next week, to send advance units of the 60,000-strong peacekeeping force
to Bosnia and Croatia.
Their job would be to check out roads, bridges, and communications links needed
by I-FOR, the Nato-led Implementation Force which will be the biggest ground
operation ever mounted by the Alliance.
US Defence Secretary William Perry made clear today that the full-scale Nato
force would operate all over Bosnia, including in Bosnian Serb-held areas which
were mainly closed to UN peacekeepers.-Reuter/AP
</TEXT>
</DOC>
