<HEADLINE>Police get bravery awards</HEADLINE>
<EDITION>2</EDITION>
<PAGE>7</PAGE>
<GRAPHIC>photograph</GRAPHIC>
<RECORDNO>975208455</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
POLICEWOMAN Julie Kirkpatrick had heard Glasgow's reputation for mean streets
and violent characters.
However, the policewoman didn't expect to be threatened with a loaded gun only
three days after leaving training college.
Despite her inexperience, Ms Kirkpatrick, 26, had no hesitation in giving chase.
Yesterday, Ms Kirkpatrick and Constable Kenneth McCann, 34, received bravery
citations at an awards ceremony at Strathclyde Police Headquarters.
Ms Kirkpatrick and Mr McCann were on patrol in June last year, three days after
Ms Kirkpatrick completed her training, when they saw three men arguing outside
a pub. As the pair approached the group, one of the men pulled out a
semi-automatic pistol.
He ran off, with the two officers chasing him.
``He threw the gun away but we managed to catch him and get him to the
ground,'' said Mr McCann.
At yesterday's ceremony, Constable Peter Wands received a Royal Humane Society
Resuscitation Certificate.
Mr Wands was on patrol in January when he saved the life of a 17-month-old baby
who had stopped breathing.
The officer gave the boy heart massage and almost certainly saved the baby's
life.
Three detectives also received bravery citations for foiling the armed robbery
of a sub post-office in Newarthill.
The only British policeman to have been shot with a machine-gun picked up a top
bravery award yesterday - and said he believed the time had come for routine
arming of officers.
Detective Sergeant Michael Stubbs collected a High Commendation at a ceremony
at New Scotland Yard.He had been hit in the temple by a bullet from an
Czech-made 9mm sub-machine gun during a pursuit of armed robbers in south
London.
</TEXT>
