<DATE>951125</DATE>
<HEADLINE>Drivers question tour coach safety</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>By DUNCAN BLACK</BYLINE>
<EDITION>3</EDITION>
<PAGE>4</PAGE>
<RECORDNO>975208457</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
BUS drivers in Scotland have called for an international investigation into the
number of UK holidaymakers who die in Continental coach crashes.
They are urging European politicians to set up a committee to examine issues
such as drivers' work schedules and the age of vehicles.
The call came from the T&amp;G union's Scottish bus workers' annual conference in
Glasgow where delegates representing more than 9000 staff expressed serious
concern.
``Most people who travel to the Continent think that when they arrive at the
airport or ferry terminal, the most dangerous part of their journey has been
completed,'' said Mr Des Divers of the Glasgow passenger district committee.
``But, as we know, in many instances the most dangerous part is just
beginning.''
Between 1989 and 1993, 138 people had been killed and 714 seriously injured in
coach accidents on European roads, he said, and the union was awaiting
publication of the latest figures, which it feared would show a dramatic rise.
It wants prosecution of coach companies who force drivers to work impossible
schedules. By doing so, such operators make drivers risk their own and their
passengers' lives through driver fatigue.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO>GH951125-000009</DOCNO>
<DOCID>GH951125-000009</DOCID>
<DATE>951125</DATE>
<HEADLINE>Cocaine dealers jailed for 30 years</HEADLINE>
<EDITION>2</EDITION>
<PAGE>3</PAGE>
<RECORDNO>975208458</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
Two drug dealers were each jailed for 30 years yesterday for an international
#125m cocaine smuggling plot.
George Sansom, 42, the cousin of ex-England football star Kenny Sansom, was in
charge of marketing the drug while ``money man'' Coleman Mulkerrins, 53,
masterminded the operation.
Amid tight security at Snaresbrook Crown Court in east London, Judge Andrew
Brooks told the pair he had a duty to protect young people who may be tempted
by the ``dreadful drug'' and mentioned the tragic recent case of Leah Betts.
The defendants showed no emotion when they were sentenced.
The court heard that Mulkerrins put up #200,000 in June 1992 to buy a ship to
transport cocaine.
The vessel loaded the drugs off the coast of Venezuela. It docked in Charlton,
London, in November 1992.
The 795-kilo consignment was loaded into a van which was driven to a lock-up in
Deptford, said prosecutor Anthony Glass QC.
Then the cocaine, which had been the subject of a 12-month surveillance
operation, was seized.
At that stage, six men, mainly members of the ship's crew, were arrested.
Mulkerrins was arrested in May last year while Sansom was only recently
extradited from Spain.
Father-of-two Sansom, who called his cousin Kenny Sansom as a character witness
in his trial, had been living with his family in Tenerife.
In June this year, a jury hearing Mulkerrins' and Sansom's trial at Snaresbrook
Crown Court was given round-the-clock police protection.
However, a month into the trial the jury was discharged after complaints of
``unwarranted attention''.
The case was transferred to Norwich Crown Court, where the jury convicted
Mulkerrins and Sansom of being knowingly concerned in the illegal importation
of cocaine.
Mulkerrins, of Twickenham, and Sansom, of West Dulwich, both London, denied the
charge and maintained they had nothing to do with the drugs plot.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO>GH951125-000010</DOCNO>
