<DATE>951125</DATE>
<HEADLINE>Courier pulls strings to get orchestra to concert</HEADLINE>
<EDITION>1</EDITION>
<PAGE>7</PAGE>
<RECORDNO>975208459</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
A DOUBLE stroke of luck brought the BBC Scottish Symphony Orchestra to Metz
last night for the concluding concert of their mini-tour of France.
Earlier in the day, it had looked as though the SSO might have been stranded in
Bordeaux because of a 36-hour national transport strike. The orchestra was
supposed to have flown to Metz on a charter flight that wasn't there.
The SSO had gone to Bordeaux airport early yesterday morning without any real
hope of getting a flight north.
Provisional arrangements had been made to abandon the last concert in Metz and
keep the orchestra in Bordeaux for another night. The courier representing the
Paris-based IMG Group - the promoters of the tour - spent yesterday morning on
the telephone and found a single flight operating towards midday from Bordeaux
to Orly airport in Paris. It contained enough vacant seats for the 87 people in
the orchestra party.
Then the courier hired three coaches to pick them up in Paris in the early
afternoon for a four-hour motorway journey to Metz.
``We had some luck with finding a plane and then we had some more luck with
getting coaches,'' said the courier. She said she had no idea how the
replacement flight and the coaches would be paid for. The bills, she said,
would be sent to IMG in Paris who presumably would have contingency insurance
arrangements.
The SSO arrived at their hotel in Metz only an hour and a half before the start
of the concert, where they were performing James MacMillan's percussion
concerto with Evelyn Glennie.
The SSO is due to fly home this morning, though it was not clear yesterday
afternoon if the backlog of air traffic would cause a delay, or if the
orchestra's charter plane would arrive in Metz.
Michael Tumelty reports on the BBC SSO tour in Monday's arts page.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
