<DOCNO>GH951125-000012</DOCNO>
<DOCID>GH951125-000012</DOCID>
<DATE>951125</DATE>
<HEADLINE>Man called to give medical help at accident finds that the victim was his daughter Crash horror for a father</HEADLINE>
<EDITION>3</EDITION>
<PAGE>4</PAGE>
<GRAPHIC>PHOTOGRAPH</GRAPHIC>
<RECORDNO>975208461</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
A MALE nurse, called to give help at the scene of a school bus accident
yesterday, found his daughter dead at the side of the road.
Emma Seaton, 11, died as she crossed the road from the bus with sister Ruth,
nine, who saw Emma being struck by a passing van and thrown into the air.
Emma and Ruth would normally have cycled the mile-and-a-half from the family
home in the Loch Ness village of Dores to 17-pupil Aldourie primary. However,
because of a planned school outing to ballet later in the day at Eden Court
Theatre, in Inverness, the girls left their bikes at home and had gone by bus
instead.
They lived with their father Tim, 32, mother Heidi, 30, and year-old baby
brother, Duncan.
Mr Seaton, a staff nurse at Craig Phadrig Hospital, Inverness, said: ``I got a
phone call from a lady living in the house opposite the school to come quickly
because there had been a bad accident.
``I thought this was probably an exaggeration but when I got there, I found
Emma lying on the verge where she had landed.
``I checked her over and found her to be dead, killed instantly I would think.
I then carried her into the school to lay her down in privacy.''
Mr Seaton, son of an Inverness United Reformed Baptist minister, the Rev
William Seaton, added: ``The whole family is devastated.''
Mrs Janice MacBeth, the head teacher, immediately closed the school for the day
and the children, shocked by the tragedy on their doorstep, were sent home.
Some older children who were being taken farther on to Inverness Royal Academy
in the town also had to return home.
The Seatons are neighbours of Mrs Audrey Gillies, whose daughter, Michelle, 24,
was killed three weeks ago along with her boyfriend in a car crash on the
Dundee-Perth road.
The postmistress, Mrs Lily Donald, said: ``One of the neighbours had to sit
with Mrs Gillies. This just brought back her own very recent family tragedy.
``Emma was a lovely, cheery wee girl just full of life. She was a keen fiddler
and a member of the harriers in Inverness.''
The van was driven by car mechanic Neil Ellis, from the nearby village of
Foyers. Police said later that a report was being prepared for the
procurator-fiscal.
</TEXT>
