<HEADLINE>Judge allows child to live in free-love religious sect with history of abuse Boy to stay with cult mother</HEADLINE>
<EDITION>2</EDITION>
<PAGE>3</PAGE>
<RECORDNO>975208462</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
A 28-YEAR-OLD mother was yesterday given permission by a senior judge to bring
up her three-year-old son in a notorious free-love religious sect with a
history of child abuse.
In a controversial judgment, Lord Justice Ward said he accepted that the
Children of God - now known as The Family - had changed and had ``come in from
the cold''.
He accepted assurances from the mother and sect leaders that they had turned
their backs on the past and on the evil teachings of their late founder, who
was condemned by the judge as a sex-obsessed child molester and pornographer.
The Family had been told by the judge that its only hope of salvation in law
was to denounce its beloved ``father'', David ``Moses'' Berg, and admit he was
wrong to promote child sex as part of his ``Law of Love''.
Berg, regarded by followers as a prophet, died at the age of 75 last November.
The sect's worldwide membership at that time included 100 adults and 194
children in the UK.
The judge said the worst excesses of Berg's corrupt teachings had been purged
many years before. ``They have come in from the cold. They carry some mud from
the past on their coat but, if they choose, they can wash it off.
``Then they can sit at society's supper table, eccentric guests perhaps, but
welcome for all that. We must all be ready to welcome the return of the
prodigal son,'' he said.
The ruling came after a bitter and costly lawsuit brought by the child's
58-year-old grandmother, who had the boy, referred to only as S, made a ward of
court eight days after his birth.
During a 75-day private court hearing last year - a record for a wardship case
- the judge heard from disaffected former members of the 12,000-strong
worldwide sect.
In the damning 135,000-word judgment handed down earlier this year and made
public yesterday, Lord Justice Ward said The Family had to come to terms with
its past before the High Court would allow the boy to remain with his mother.
Its leaders must recognise that, in the past, children had been harmed by
``sexually inappropriate behaviour'' amounting to widespread abuse.
Granting the mother care and control of S, the judge said he would remain a
ward of court and must live within the court's jurisdiction so his progress
could be monitored.
The Family, which describes itself as a fellowship of independent Christian
missionary communities, currently has nearly 300 members in the UK, two-thirds
of whom are children. The sect rents six properties in Scotland, England, and
Ireland, in which family groups live together.
Spokeswoman Rachel Scott said most of the events referred to had happened a
long time ago in other countries and many allegations had been discounted or
disproved in criminal cases.
However, Family Action Information and Resource, which monitors cults, called
on members of The Family to denounce Berg and warned it would prove virtually
impossible to ensure undertakings given to the judge would be upheld.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO>GH951125-000014</DOCNO>
<DOCID>GH951125-000014</DOCID>
<DATE>951125</DATE>
<HEADLINE>Teacher's dangerous driving caused death</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>Loudon Temple</BYLINE>
<EDITION>2</EDITION>
<PAGE>3</PAGE>
<RECORDNO>975208463</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
LOUDON TEMPLE
A teacher whose dangerous driving left one man dead and four seriously injured,
will have to wait three weeks to find out his fate.
Car passenger John Hannah, 56, of Sycamore Avenue, Beith, Ayrshire, died after
the head-on smash with a car driven by physical education teacher Donald
Henderson.
A jury heard that the vehicle in which Mr Hannah was travelling was momentarily
hidden from view in a dip in the road as Henderson's car pulled out over double
white lines to overtake on wrong side of the road.
Henderson, 41, an assistant principal guidance teacher at Renfrew High School,
was found guilty of causing death by dangerous driving after trial at Paisley
Sheriff Court.
Henderson himself was in a coma for two days in Southern General Hospital and
spent a further two months in hospital recovering from head injuries.
Four of the injured had to be freed from the wreckage by firefighters.
Sheriff David Pender deferred sentence for three weeks and called for social
inquiry reports and a community service assessment. Henderson was released on
bail.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO>GH951125-000015</DOCNO>
<DOCID>GH951125-000015</DOCID>
<DATE>951125</DATE>
<HEADLINE>Briton murder revives call for death penalty</HEADLINE>
<EDITION>3</EDITION>
<PAGE>10</PAGE>
<RECORDNO>975208464</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
Johannesburg
A STATE premier called for a referendum on bringing back the death penalty in
South Africa after visiting the family of a murdered Briton today.
``People have got the right to discuss the whole question of the death
penalty,'' said Tokyo Sexwale, leader of the Gauteng province, as he comforted
the family of British-born businessman Jeremy Bennett, who was shot dead by car
hijackers on Tuesday.
``This thing must go to a referendum. It hurts nobody, it's part of
democracy,'' said Mr Sexwale.
Former president F.W de Klerk ordered a moratorium on executions in February
1990. This year judges ruled that the death penalty violated South Africa's new
democratic constitution and its Bill of Rights.
Mr Sexwale echoed calls by Justice Minister Dullah Omar for merciless
prosecution of car hijackers, who struck 28 times in two days in Gauteng this
week alone.
Mr Bennett, who moved to South Africa in the 1970s, was shot dead in front of
his 10-year-old daughter Samantha as he stopped his car outside the family's
Johannesburg home.
One of three men who approached the car shot Mr Bennett in the head through the
front window. The men fled in another vehicle but police said their intention
had been to steal Mr Bennett's car.-Reuter.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO>GH951125-000016</DOCNO>
<DOCID>GH951125-000016</DOCID>
<DATE>951125</DATE>
<HEADLINE>NEWS DIGEST</HEADLINE>
<EDITION>3</EDITION>
<PAGE>4</PAGE>
<FLAG>NEWS DIGEST</FLAG>
<RECORDNO>975208465</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
Firms cash in
on enterprise
FIVE businesses in Argyll and the Islands are to receive #351,000 in grants
from the local enterprise company to help with expansion.
They include #195,000 for a visitor centre at the Isle of Arran Distillery,
conditional on EU Objective One funding, and #11,900 for refurbishment at
Stonefield Castle Hotel, near Tarbert, Kintyre.
Bank demand
FINANCE union Bifu yesterday handed in a petition with more than 10,000
signatures calling for Scotland's bank holidays to be protected. The petition
to the committee of Scottish Clearing Bankers in Edinburgh warned that
industrial action could result from any changes.
Healthy gift
CHARITY organisation Women of Lothian yesterday presented cheques to the High
Blood Pressure Foundation at Western General Hospital, Edinburgh, and
Wellbeing, the health charity for women and babies. The money will allow free
electronic blood-pressure monitoring in Edinburgh next spring and help a
Scotland-wide study of babies who die of birth asphyxia.
Police hostage
A POLICEMAN was held hostage for 20 minutes by a driver who repeatedly
threatened to kill him. The 47-year-old officer had stopped his Jaguar patrol
car on the A1M near Durham beside a Mitsubishi car when the driver, aged about
30, overpowered him and dragged him down an embankment. He drove off after
ripping out the radio handset in the Jaguar.
Prize delay
DUE to the continuing postal dispute, the closing date for entries for the
Prize Crossword, Nasty No Nine, and Who She? competitions in today's Weekend
Extra will be announced after the postal service has returned to normal, so
please hang on to your entries meantime.
More jobs
ANOTHER 180 jobs are to be created in Northern Ireland, it was announced
yesterday. A #3.3m investment by Dungannon Meats will mean 140 jobs over two
years and Synthetic Textiles is expanding in Newry, County Down, providing 39
jobs over three years.
Drugs death
A 26-YEAR-OLD woman died  last night in what is thought to be the region's 97th
drug death of the year. Ms Tracy Mirrlees fell ill at her home in Inchfad
Drive, Drumchapel.
Window plunge
WINDOW cleaner James Milne, 53, of Hawthorn Street, Leven, was taken to
hospital with head and arm injuries yesterday when he fell 25 feet from his
ladder at a hotel in Leven.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO>GH951125-000017</DOCNO>
<DOCID>GH951125-000017</DOCID>
<DATE>951125</DATE>
<HEADLINE>Crackdown on drink drivers</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>WILLIAM TINNING</BYLINE>
<EDITION>2</EDITION>
<PAGE>3</PAGE>
<RECORDNO>975208466</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
SCOTLAND'S eight police forces began breath-testing drivers yesterday at the
start of their 10th annual crackdown on festive drink driving.
The 41-day campaign, which will be launched officially on Monday in Paisley,
got under way at 7am and will run until 7am on Wednesday, January 3.
Police chiefs are hopeful of improving on last year's drink-driving figures,
which saw a total of 1101 drivers proving positive or refusing to take a test -
2.3% of the total of 47,566 drivers stopped during the campaign.
Last year's figure was higher than the 2% of the previous year, although the
number of drivers testing positive or refusing to take a test in 1993/94 was
1121 - 20 more than in 1994/95.
The theme of this year's campaign will again be ``Drinking and driving wrecks
lives'' but it will include the message ``Don't drive - dial'' - a reference to
a campaign featured on 20,000 posters and seven million cards urging motorists
to use other means of transport if they want to drink alcohol.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO>GH951125-000018</DOCNO>
<DOCID>GH951125-000018</DOCID>
<DATE>951125</DATE>
<HEADLINE>Ecstasy main drug for youth of Europe</HEADLINE>
<EDITION>3</EDITION>
<PAGE>10</PAGE>
<RECORDNO>975208467</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
Strasbourg
THE controversial rave-scene stimulant Ecstasy has become the favourite
recreation drug after cannabis for West European young people, according to a
report to the Council of Europe.
Two researchers from Amsterdam, Dirk Korf and Barend Werth, noted that while
occasional users of the synthetic drug tend to be well-educated, many on the
margins of society now take bigger and more frequent doses.
``Ecstasy has been reported most frequently as the new drug trend in Europe
although this is largely confined to Western Europe where ecstasy has become
the second most popular drug next to cannabis among young people,'' the report
said.
A panel of the 38-nation Council was also told by criminal experts today that
the consumption of Ecstasy at raves was creating new public order problems.
Belgian police lieutenant Michel Ost said a report showed that about 20% of
road accident victims were under the influence of Ecstasy.
Earlier this year, US researchers found new evidence that consumption of the
drug could cause permanent brain damage leading to mood disturbances.
``We mustn't sow panic,'' said Ernst Buning, a drug specialist from Amsterdam.
``The number of deaths directly linked to Ecstasy in Europe is below the 100
level. It is negligible compared with alcohol and nicotine.''-Reuter.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO>GH951125-000019</DOCNO>
<DOCID>GH951125-000019</DOCID>
<DATE>951125</DATE>
<HEADLINE>Education is `big business'</HEADLINE>
<EDITION>2</EDITION>
<PAGE>3</PAGE>
<RECORDNO>975208468</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
SCOTTISH higher education is a big business in its own right, generating
millions of pounds of income and many thousands of jobs, according to a major
report published yesterday.
The findings will be used by university and college principals to bolster their
campaign against further cuts in Government funding, planned over the next
three years.
Professor John Arbuthnott, convener of the body which commissioned the report -
the Committee of Scottish Higher Education Principals - warned that a further
squeeze on resources would be damaging for a sector which had shown itself to
be highly successful, and impressive in the way it gave value for money.
The report on the impact of Scottish higher education on Scotland's economy, by
Strathclyde University economist Professor Iain McNicoll, proved once and for
all that universities and colleges were not ivory towers, Professor Arbuthnott
said.
The report, based on the latest figures for income and expenditure in
higher-education institutions, shows they had an income of #1100m, with #793m
from the public purse, and the remainder from the private sector and overseas.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO>GH951125-000020</DOCNO>
<DOCID>GH951125-000020</DOCID>
<DATE>951125</DATE>
<HEADLINE>Ferguson in hiding after release</HEADLINE>
<EDITION>2</EDITION>
<PAGE>3</PAGE>
<GRAPHIC>photograph</GRAPHIC>
<RECORDNO>975208469</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
EVERTON and Scotland footballer Duncan Ferguson was released from Glasgow's
Barlinnie Prison yesterday after serving exactly half of a three-month prison
sentence.
The former Rangers striker was one of 35 prisoners released before dawn from
the Victorian-built jail but was the only one to be picked up by a
chauffeur-driven limousine.
The hired burgundy Daimler, sent up to collect him by his club, is understood
to have ferried the 23-year-old footballer straight back to Merseyside, where
he remained in hiding last night.
Everton manager Joe Royle refused to comment on the player's whereabouts at an
informal players' lunch at Goodison Park yesterday. He would only say: ``We are
talking football today. Nothing about Duncan at the moment.''
The club is still discussing whether to lodge a petition for a judicial review
of Ferguson's 12-match suspension by the Scottish Football Association, arguing
that he is being forced to serve his punishment twice over. That move would
effectively suspend his ban until the review is completed and would free him to
play.
It had been suggested that the player would put in an appearance before
Everton's home match against Sheffield Wednesday at Goodison today. However, a
club spokeswoman said yesterday he would not attend the match and that he would
resume training on Monday.
A media posse had pursued Ferguson's limousine as far as the M6 motorway after
it left Barlinnie yesterday but lost contact with the vehicle near Penrith,
Cumbria.
The Daimler had swept out of the prison at 6.35am, whisking Ferguson past 30
journalists and four diehard Everton supporters who had earlier driven north
from Liverpool to see him being released.
The limousine, which had tinted windows and black curtains to thwart
photographers, had been parked inside the prison overnight with the driver
returning to Barlinnie early yesterday to pick up the player.
Scottish Prison Service spokesman John Gerrie defended Ferguson's release
procedure as a ``perfectly normal arrangement'' for any high-profile or
celebrity prisoner.
The four Everton supporters set out on the 200-mile trip north at 2am yesterday.
Ferguson made football history by becoming the first professional footballer to
be jailed for an on-the-field assault on a fellow player. He was sent to
Barlinnie on October 11 when three appeal judges ruled the three-month sentence
he received for headbutting John McStay was not excessive.
WILLIAM TINNING
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO>GH951125-000021</DOCNO>
<DOCID>GH951125-000021</DOCID>
<DATE>951125</DATE>
<HEADLINE>Struggling ferry gets reprieve</HEADLINE>
<EDITION>3</EDITION>
<PAGE>4</PAGE>
<RECORDNO>975208470</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
THE struggling summer ferry service between Ardrossan and the Isle of Man has
been saved.
Operators Caledonian MacBrayne, who run the service jointly with Manx company
Steam Packet, disclosed the reprieve at a travel exhibition in London.
The weekly crossing had faced being scrapped in September after both companies
admitted that it had attracted few passengers during its two years of operation.
However, it is to be given one last chance, although its season will be reduced
from 12 to seven weeks.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO>GH951125-000022</DOCNO>
<DOCID>GH951125-000022</DOCID>
<DATE>951125</DATE>
<HEADLINE>Hospital food row</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>Alan Macdermid, Medical Correspondent</BYLINE>
<EDITION>1</EDITION>
<PAGE>5</PAGE>
<RECORDNO>975208471</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
By ALAN MacDERMID
Medical Corresponden
t
JUNIOR doctors on night duty at Glasgow Royal Infirmary face a return to
vending machine cuisine because an extension to canteen hours was a financial
flop.
The overnight service, which ran from 10pm to 1am, is likely to be withdrawn
because of what the management say is a poor uptake by staff.
However, junior doctors' representative Nizam Mamode, a vascular surgery
registrar, said yesterday: ``We are extremely angry about this. The trust does
not seem to understand that junior doctors are often on their feet all day and
most of the night. They require the basic right of a hot meal.
``If the service is withdrawn, doctors' only access to food overnight in the
entire hospital will be a poorly stocked vending machine.''
A hospital spokesman said: ``This service didn't exist until it was introduced
as a three-month experiment. We are the only hospital in Scotland providing
this service.
``The three months is up and we have extended it but we are looking at whether
it is possible to continue. We have about 250 people working here overnight but
we were finding that 32 nurses and eight doctors were turning up.''
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO>GH951125-000023</DOCNO>
<DOCID>GH951125-000023</DOCID>
<DATE>951125</DATE>
<HEADLINE>FOREIGN DIGEST</HEADLINE>
<EDITION>3</EDITION>
<PAGE>10</PAGE>
<FLAG>Foreign Digest</FLAG>
<RECORDNO>975208472</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
Leeson in dock
in Singapore
SINGAPORE: Nick Leeson appeared before a Singapore court yesterday to face 11
fraud and forgery charges over the #860m collapse of Barings Bank.
The 28-year-old former futures trader, arrested on arrival in Singapore
yesterday after his extradition from Germany, was remanded in custody for a
week and taken to prison.
Axeman strikes
WELLINGTON: A man ran amok with an axe in the offices of a New Zealand
newspaper, smashing up #86,000 of equipment. Staff at the North Island Bay of
Plenty daily huddled under their desks as the man, who police said had been
made bankrupt when the newspaper called in a debt, went on the rampage. No-one
was hurt and he gave himself up.
Premier better
ATHENS: Greek Prime Minister Andreas Papandreou, who has pneumonia, was taken
off a respirator yesterday and was breathing normally. Papandreou, 76, who was
taken to hospital on Monday, was ``improving steadily''.
`Love potion' kills
ATLANTA: Four men died when they swallowed an alleged aphrodisiac sold at
grocery stores and tobacco shops in Georgia. The brown, rock-like substance,
which includes dried toad secretions and causes hallucinations, is supposed to
be applied externally but was not labelled.
Tiger attacks boy
RALEIGH: A three-year-old boy was attacked by his family's pet Bengal tiger on
Thanksgiving Day and spent 14 hours in surgery for severe head and face wounds.
Tyler William Forsythe was in critical condition after the attack by the
year-old tiger, which his family bought from a North Carolina pet dealer.
Shell talks back
LAGOS: Shell placed full-page advertisements in the South African press
yesterday defending its human rights record in Nigeria and denying collusion
with its military rulers. The company has come under fierce attack for not
pulling out after the Nigerian Government executed nine rights activists
belonging to the Ogoni minority.
Salinas scandal
MEXICO CITY: Another scandal has broken over the rule of former Mexican
president Carlos Salinas de Gortari when Swiss police said they had arrested
his sister-in-law in a drugs investigation. Paulina Castanon, wife of Salinas's
brother Raul, was held as she tried to withdraw #56m from a Swiss bank account
using false documents.
Japan quakes
TOKYO: An earthquake measuring 6.6 on the Richter scale jolted east and south
Hokkaido, Japan's northernmost island, early today.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
