<DOCNO>GH951125-000025</DOCNO>
<DOCID>GH951125-000025</DOCID>
<DATE>951125</DATE>
<HEADLINE>Foster child scalded in unattended bath, court told</HEADLINE>
<EDITION>3</EDITION>
<PAGE>4</PAGE>
<RECORDNO>975208474</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
A TWO-YEAR-OLD girl suffering from severe scalding wasnot taken for hospital
treatment by her foster carer for two days, a court heard yesterday.
The girl, who cannot be named for legal reasons, was eventually taken to the
Royal Hospital for Sick Children, Edinburgh, where it was found she had
suffered scalding to more than 23% of her body.
Haddington Sheriff Court heard it alleged that the accident happened when carer
Lana Hillhouse, 34, went to answer a telephone call.
The court also heard that parts of the child's legs, which had to be skin
grafted, may be scarred for life.
Mrs Hillhouse denies having, on August 12, caused the girl unnecessary
suffering by leaving her neglected and unattended in a bath of running hot
water and failing to seek medical attention when the accident happened.
Mrs Hillhouse, of Grange Crescent East, Prestonpans, East Lothian, also denies
an alternative charge of recklessly placing the child in a bath, turning on
mixer taps, allowing the bath to fill with water, then walking out of the
bathroom leaving the infant unattended, whereby the child was scalded by hot,
running water.
Burns specialist Dalvi Humzah, the plastic surgeon called to treat the girl,
said the injuries were consistent with sitting in a bath of hot water.
Mr Humzah said the child had suffered superficial second degree burns.
The court heard that the specialist had allegedly been told by Mrs Hillhouse
that she had got engaged in a telephone call while the child was in the bath.
It was claimed the foster carer heard screams and ran to the bathroom.
Mr Humzah, 31, alleged that Mrs Hillhouse informed him she had patted the child
dry and applied a cream to the skin. Two days later, it was claimed, after the
child took ill and had been vomiting, Mrs Hillhouse had taken the infant to
hospital.
The trial  was adjourned.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO>GH951125-000026</DOCNO>
<DOCID>GH951125-000026</DOCID>
<DATE>951125</DATE>
<HEADLINE>Anger burns over French welfare cuts</HEADLINE>
<EDITION>3</EDITION>
<PAGE>10</PAGE>
<ARTICLETYPE>features</ARTICLETYPE>
<GRAPHIC>photograph</GRAPHIC>
<RECORDNO>975208475</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
NICHOLAS POWELL
Paris
UP TO 100,000 people marched in protest along the boulevards on the right bank
of Paris yesterday, releasing balloons, carrying dummies stuffed with tubes to
represent the sick state of France's welfare system, and singing ``Juppe Bye
Bye'' to the tune of ``Johnny Be Good''.
Nicole Notat, leader of the socialist-leaning CFDT union, had angered many of
her members by approving the recent government scheme of welfare reform and had
to be protected by bodyguards.
They were not numerous or big enough, and when the boos turned to blows, Notat
had to be taken to safety: for yesterday's strike and marches by public sector
and some private sector workers were not only the biggest nationwide protest in
many years, they were also by far the angriest.
When France goes on strike, Paris usually does most of the protesting, but
yesterday the whole country was out. Not only the big provincial cities, but
towns of middling size, from Cherbourg in Normandy to Mulhouse in the east,
staged demonstrations. There were even 20,000 marchers in Bordeaux, the
eminently respectable city of which Prime Minister Alain Juppe is mayor. And
15,000 people took to the streets of quiet, conservative Tours.
Communications throughout the country seized up. There were virtually no
Metros, buses, or suburban trains in Paris, and people struggling into work
transformed the city's streets into a gigantic growling traffic jam. The rail
network and the domestic airline Air Inter were all but idle and Air France
only flew long-distance. The Channel Tunnel Eurostar train was blocked
yesterday morning and there were no ferries between Calais and Dover or Corsica
and Marseille.
Schools stayed open, but only to house children who turned up, not to teach
them. Hospitals ensured only emergency services, electricity and gas workers
were off, there was no post, and, because of the stoppage by print workers, no
newspapers either.
This was far, far more than the thought of grumbling that Prime Minister Juppe
had steeled himself for 10 days ago in the National Assembly, when he announced
a wide-ranging plan to reform France's chronically-overdrawn welfare system. He
introduced across-the-board tax increases and changes to civil service
retirement schemes which allow employees to contribute for shorter periods than
people in the private sector.
Mr Juppe's right-wing parliamentary colleagues, joined in the event by a fringe
of the small socialist opposition in the National Assembly, were unanimous in
applauding his courage. Demoralised that the lowest popularity of any Prime
Minister since 1958, Mr Juppe had even been seen to smile. Yesterday, he was
called into the Elysee Palace for an unscheduled meeting with President Chirac
to discuss the extent of the damage.
The protest could have been even worse, had the trades union Force Ouvriere,
the most influential in the country's civil service, not preferred to call a
separate day of protest later. As it happened, many FO workers joined
yesterday's strike anyway.
All that upheaval is more than a sticky patch of protest against the
belt-tightening exercise whose benefits will soon show. Latest economic
provisions, published last week, are dire and show that the government's recent
measures could be little use in the long term after all.
Economic growth from April to September this year was under 1% and the outlook
for 1996 it even worse - worse in fact than anyone had expected. The
government's painfully worked out autumn budget, a report in Le Monde newspaper
suggested, could even become obsolete on account of the unexpected slowdown in
the economy, while the billions of pounds of extra taxes which Mr Juppe
announced in his recent welfare scheme could slow down consumer spending even
more.
The slightest drop in unemployment, meanwhile, still over the dangerous three
million mark, and which President Chirac promised so often and so loudly to
make his priority of priorities, looks now like an elusive hope indeed. By
sticking to that policy of maintaining the franc, cutting public spending, and
getting the economy into the appropriate shape to comply with the conditions
for a single European currency by 1999, Mr Juppe and President Chirac have
worked themselves into a corner. And with such deep and widespread anger in the
country, something, as those many thousands of people proved yesterday, has got
to give.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO>GH951125-000027</DOCNO>
<DOCID>GH951125-000027</DOCID>
<DATE>951125</DATE>
<HEADLINE>Father of `family from hell' jailed for driving offences</HEADLINE>
<EDITION>1</EDITION>
<PAGE>8</PAGE>
<RECORDNO>975208476</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
The father of Scotland's so-called Family from Hell is today starting another
stretch behind bars.
Gordon Graham was jailed for a total of 10 months after admitting two charges
of failing to provide a breath test, driving without proper insurance, and
driving while banned.
Graham, 40, was also given another life driving ban when he appeared from
custody at Peterhead Sheriff Court yesterday.
The court had heard earlier that Graham had a criminal record stretching back
15 years, including a ``substantial'' number of driving offences since 1988.
His solicitor, Mr Larry Flynn, claimed Graham was suffering from paranoia and
had threatened to take his own life.
Mr Flynn said Graham had set fire to one of his socks in a cell at the court
after the last hearing as he waited to be sent back to Craiginches Prison, in
Aberdeen.
Graham had burns to his lower leg requiring skin graft treatment and spent two
weeks under police guard at Aberdeen Royal Infirmary, he added.
Earlier, Mr Flynn told the court: ``My client has made various remarks of a
suicidal nature to me. Since August, he has become a completely different
character.''
He said Graham had been heavily affected by his family's highly publicised
eviction from a council house in Glenrothes, Fife, earlier this year, following
complaints of anti-social behaviour.
After their eviction, Graham and his wife Anne and several of their children,
moved to the quiet Moray Firth village of Rosehearty, near Fraserburgh.
Mr Flynn asked Sheriff Kieran McLernan to consider a long period of probation
as an alternative to prison.
Handing down the sentence, Sheriff McLernan said Graham had had a number of
last chances to avoid prison and had not taken them.
``It took a conscious decision to move your family to the North-east and it
took a similar decision to drive while you knew you were banned for life.''
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO>GH951125-000028</DOCNO>
<DOCID>GH951125-000028</DOCID>
<DATE>951125</DATE>
<HEADLINE>Illness warning for students</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>Jonathan Northcroft Craig Watson</BYLINE>
<EDITION>2</EDITION>
<PAGE>3</PAGE>
<RECORDNO>975208477</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
Illness
warning
for
students
CRAIG WATSON,
JONATHAN NORTHCROFT
CRAIG WATSON,
JONATHAN NORTHCROFT
AN 18-year-old Scots university student is critically ill with meningitis.
Mr Christopher Scott, a first-year student at Stirling University, is in
Stirling Royal Infirmary intensive care unit. Mr Scott, said to be from
Falkirk, became ill on Thursday and was taken to hospital, where his condition
worsened overnight.
In Lincoln, five people have died and two are still seriously ill after
contracting the disease. Health officials in the city yesterday announced that
they were to start a major immunisation programme to halt the outbreak, which
started last month.
Friends who had come into contact with Mr Scott in the last 10 days have been
traced and given treatment. Last night, an appeal went out for those who may
have slipped through the net.
After consultation with public health officials, the principal of Stirling
University, Professor Andrew Miller, sent a statement to all 2000 students
resident in campus accommodation.
He said: ``Christopher was admitted to hospital on Thursday with meningitis.
Only a small group of people could be at risk of contracting the infection from
Christopher.
``To the best of our knowledge, these people have been traced and given the
appropriate treatment. Students sharing lecture theatres, dining halls, and
general accommodation are not at risk and do not require treatment.
``However, if they have had close personal contact with Christopher, for
example kissing, in the last 10 days, they should ring a special number or
contact their GP. Normally, such close contact does not give increased risk.''
Mr Miller said the symptoms to look out for were flu-like with severe headaches.
Stirling students who think they may be at risk have been told to contact their
GP or the porter or security at the university on 01786 467000.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO>GH951125-000029</DOCNO>
<DOCID>GH951125-000029</DOCID>
<DATE>951125</DATE>
<HEADLINE>Berlusconi pledges to defy corruption summons</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>BEATRICE COLNAGO</BYLINE>
<EDITION>3</EDITION>
<PAGE>10</PAGE>
<RECORDNO>975208478</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
ITALIAN media magnate Silvio Berlusconi said today that he would probably
refuse to appear before magistrates probing alleged illegal party financing by
his Fininvest company.
Berlusconi, due to stand trial in January on corruption charges related to the
Fininvest media empire, has repeatedly accused Milan anti-graft investigators
of waging a political campaign against him.
He told reporters at a news conference at his home outside Milan today that he
had been ordered by magistrates to appear for questioning on November 30, but
would refuse to turn up.
``I do not think I will present myself because I do not see the need to meet
people who are only trying to harm me,'' he said.
Berlusconi's running battle with Milan's ``Clean Hands'' team of anti-graft
magistrates broke new ground yesterday when Judge Maurizio Grigo ordered the
arrest of Giorgio Vanoni, finance director of foreign subsidiaries of Fininvest.
Vannoni is suspected of making a 10bn lire (#4.6m) payment to former socialist
premier Bettino Craxi in 1991 through a Panama-based company All Iberian, which
has links to Fininvest.
It is the first time investigators have alleged that money flowed directly from
Berlusconi's company into Craxi's coffers.
Berlusconi, Prime Minister for seven months last year and leader of the
centre-right Freedom Alliance, has denied any wrongdoing by Fininvest and
called the investigation an attempt to destroy him politically.
Berlusconi is due to stand trial in January with 11 other men on corruption
charges in a separate case.
Arrest warrants were also issued yesterday for Craxi, currently a fugitive in
Tunisia, and two close associates.
``The news we heard yesterday is false,'' Berlusconi said, adding that he had
no inten-tion of standing down as leader of the Freedom Alliance. ``Only 10
million citizens could      make me take a step backwards.''
He said All Iberian did not belong to Fininvest. The payment was not directed
at Craxi but was part of a contractual relationship with a Tunisian film
producer.
Judicial sources in Milan said investigators had a duty to question Berlusconi
because he was Fininvest's chairman at the time the alleged payment was made.
The claims of payments passing from the company to Craxi, the most despised
politician in Italy, could cause severe damage to Berlusconi's public image in
the build-up to an early General Election widely expected for early next year.
Berlusconi said earlier his friendship with Craxi was no secret.
``Everybody knows that I was a friend of Bettino Craxi,'' he said today. ``They
also know that Fininvest quite legally financed the Socialists and other
parties through publicity spots and discounted advertising.''-Reuter.
</TEXT>
