<DATE>951125</DATE>
<HEADLINE>Mail order jobs at risk from strike</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>By KEN SMITH</BYLINE>
<EDITION>2</EDITION>
<PAGE>2</PAGE>
<RECORDNO>975208479</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
MAIL-order firms are reporting tens of thousands of pounds worth of business
being lost and the possibility of staff being laid off next week because of the
mail strike.
One firm, Scotland Direct, of Lanarkshire, is considering taking court action
against the leaders of the dispute.
Mr Arthur Bell, whose mail-order companies supply a range of goods including
gourmet foods, whiskies, and collectibles, said the situation was very serious,
with trade down by more than #20,000 a day.
Not only are his 65 staff dependent on a smooth flow of orders but hundreds of
other workers, who supply them with goods, will suffer financially.
``It is a very damaging and an immensely stupid dispute. It's putting at risk
the jobs of innocent people and the jobs of the postmen themselves,'' he said.
Mr Bell is to contact Trade Secretary Ian Lang to suggest that the Royal Mail's
monopoly on letter delivery should be ended.
``But I will have to fax it to him, as I can't post it to him,'' he added.
Ms Pollyanna Stokoe, Edinburgh manager of the Direct Marketing Association,
said it would not be long before firms were seriously affected by the strike.
She feared that clients from the south of England would think twice about
dealing with Scottish companies in the future, because of the additional risk
of disruption.
Mr Jim Torrance of cosmetic mail order firm, the Body Centre, in Fife, said:
``People in England don't know there is a strike up here and so their orders
are being caught up in the post and getting lost.''
He also is having to consider laying off staff.
In the general business field, ScottishPower is considering contingency plans
for putting out bills if the strike goes on. The power company mails out 20,000
a day.
Mr Bill Anderson, Scottish secretary of the Federation of Small Businesses,
said banks should take a lenient position with firms unable to pay in cheques
because they are caught up in the dispute.
However, some firms are bypassing some of the strike's effects by taking mail
directly to England for posting, and life assurance and pensions company
Scottish Widows has asked staff to volunteer to deliver mail personally to
local addresses.
q Students waiting for their loans to be processed by the Student Loans Company
are asked to contact the loans administrator at their university or college.
</TEXT>
