<HEADLINE>Court told of Ian Maxwell's `gamble' with pension fund</HEADLINE>
<EDITION>3</EDITION>
<PAGE>4</PAGE>
<RECORDNO>975208480</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
THE Old Bailey was told yesterday that Mr Ian Maxwell played a ``vital role''
in pledging shares to secure a loan for the ailing Maxwell empire, even though
he knew they belonged to the pension funds.
On the third day of his closing speech to the jury, prosecutor Alan Suckling
QC, said the Crown was not suggesting Mr Maxwell was the ``prime mover'' in
pledging shares worth #22m in the Israeli company Teva. However, he ``played a
vital role in securing the loan in an emergency''.
He said Mr Maxwell, 39, who has not given evidence, was ``plainly no fool''. He
was a director of most of the important companies in the group.
Mr Suckling said the evidence had been that Mr Maxwell normally took great care
to check what he was signing and frequently sought advice from the pension
funds' administrator on documents delivered for his signature.
Mr Suckling said, however, that he had not sought advice from the administrator
over the pledging of the Teva shares and like the other two defendants ``had
kept quiet about it''.
Mr Suckling claimed it was ``inconceivable'' that he had not been aware that
the shares belonged to the pensioners and not to the Robert Maxwell Group.
Mr Suckling said that, like the other defendants, he had been dishonest and
taken a gamble with the pension funds which he knew was not in the interests of
the pension funds ``in a last desperate effort to prop up the group which meant
so much to them''.
The third defendant, former Maxwell financial advisor Larry Trachtenberg, was a
director of BIM (Bishopsgate Investment Management) which administered the
pension fund, said Mr Suckling, and knew his duty was to manage shares for the
benefit of the pensioners - ``not to prop up a failing group with a risk the
shares might never be returned''.
Mr Maxwell, his brother Kevin, 36, and Mr Trachtenberg, 42, deny conspiracy to
defraud the pension funds. The trial continues.
</TEXT>
