<DOCNO>GH951125-000032</DOCNO>
<DOCID>GH951125-000032</DOCID>
<DATE>951125</DATE>
<HEADLINE>Doctor found no mental disorder</HEADLINE>
<EDITION>1</EDITION>
<PAGE>5</PAGE>
<RECORDNO>975208481</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
Doctor
found no
mental
disorder
A DOCTOR called to examine a troubled teenager just a fortnight before she
hanged herself in jail dismissed her as an attention seeker, an inquiry heard
yesterday.
The joint inquiry into the deaths at Cornton Vale prison in June of Kelly
Holland and fellow inmate Arlene Elliot, both 17, heard that the un-named
doctor was called by a worried deputy prosecutor in Miss Holland's home town of
Hamilton.
Police had reported Miss Hamilton for breach of the peace after she twice tried
to throw herself out of a second-storey window.
Procurator-fiscal depute Stuart Cassidy told the inquiry he received a police
report on June 7 that Miss Holland had been found drinking in an empty flat in
Hamilton by two nearby residents.
They called police and tried to talk to her, but Miss Holland ran at the window
and tried to throw herself out.
She got the top half of her body out of the window before the men hauled her
back in.
Mr Cassidy said he remembered her from a previous case in which she had
vandalised teachers' cars at a local school and was found wandering around the
playground ``striking or stroking'' at her wrist with a piece of broken glass.
He said, as a lay person, he thought she might be mentally ill so he called a
doctor to examine her.
``The doctor told me that he didn't consider her to be suffering from any
mental disorder.......He used the phrase that she was an attention seeker,''
said Mr Cassidy.
``He said that he had dealt with her in the past and when he saw her on this
occasion she appeared to be in a better frame of mind than before.''
Mr Cassidy said he informed the social work department he was worried about
Miss Holland and released her after making sure there was a member of her
family at the court to see her home.
Two weeks later, she was re-arrested on a charge of breach of the peace and
remanded in custody to Cornton Vale. On June 23, she was found dead in her
cell, hanging from a noose torn from a bedsheet.
Sheriff Principal John Maguire, who is conducting the inquiry, asked Mr
Cassidy: ``You released her on the basis that prosecuting somebody for
attempting suicide is a somewhat bizarre predicament for the State?'' Mr
Cassidy replied: ``I just didn't think it would be appropriate.''
Earlier, the inquiry heard from consultant pathologist Dr Hosie Tavadia that it
would have taken Miss Holland a maximum of two minutes to die after putting the
noose round her neck.
The inquiry, at Stirling Sheriff Court, continues on Monday.
</TEXT>
