<HEADLINE>Moscow on alert for radiation hot spots</HEADLINE>
<EDITION>3</EDITION>
<PAGE>10</PAGE>
<RECORDNO>975208482</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
Moscow
THE Russian capital's emergency radiation detection system was on alert today
after a container of radioactive material allegedly planted by Chechen rebels
was found in Moscow park.
At the same time, officials scrambled to reassure the public there was nothing
to fear and Tass news agency said the monitoring system had not detected any
more hot spots.
``The container found in Moscow is not dangerous in any way,'' said Interior
Minister Anatoly Kulikov.
Independent NTV television, which unearthed the radioactive container in a
Moscow park yesterday, said Chechen rebel commander Shamil Basayev had revealed
the location earlier this month.
The Federal Security Service, a successor to the KGB, recovered the material
last night and was investigating. The container did not pose a danger to the
environment or to people, FSS spokesman Alexander Mikhailov told a news
conference.
He thanked NTV for turning it over, but chastised reporters for uncovering it
on their own. He said it could have been booby-trapped.
NTV has been highly critical of the Kremlin's 11-month war against separatist
Chechnya.
Federal officials identified the contents of the container as caesium 137, a
radioactive isotope used in cancer research and radiation therapy. It was not
clear if or how the Chechens intended to use it.
``This radiation level is not dangerous for passers-by, but if you keep it in
your pocket for two weeks, you will get cancer,'' said Vladimir Asmolov, head
of the Nuclear Safety Institute.
The Emergency Situations Ministry activated its a radiation detection system,
which consists of 46 mobile sensors throughout Moscow. Police were ordered to
step up checks on roads into Moscow and at railway stations.-AP.
</TEXT>
