<DOCNO>GH951125-000034</DOCNO>
<DOCID>GH951125-000034</DOCID>
<DATE>951125</DATE>
<HEADLINE>MP seeks care unit inquiry</HEADLINE>
<EDITION>3</EDITION>
<PAGE>4</PAGE>
<RECORDNO>975208483</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
PROBLEMS of serious breakdowns of discipline and management have affected a
child-care unit in Fife, an MP has claimed.
Mr Henry McLeish, Labour MP for Central Fife, has accused Fife's director of
social work, Mr Allan Bowman, and senior management of allowing the situation
to deteriorate. He is seeking an immediate inquiry into Rimbleton House in
Glenrothes. It houses and educates youngsters with a range of difficulties.
He claimed: ``Staff morale is at rock bottom and kids are going as they please
through the facility. There is a lack of discipline being exercised at
Rimbleton House and, as a result, young people are getting out.
``Rimbleton House is simply not functioning properly. I want to know why this
is the case and why the director of social work and senior management have
allowed the situation to deteriorate to such an extent.''
He believed the unit had been earmarked for closure but no closure time-scale
had been issued.
``There has been a serious breakdown in communications, management, and
discipline and it's now spilling over into the local community. I'm fed up with
all the complaints and I have written to Fife region's chief executive asking
for a full report,'' said Mr McLeish.
The council's social work chairman, Councillor Charles Laing, admitted that
Rimbleton House needed to close. He added that it was the only residential-care
provision managed and run by the social work department, so it was expected to
cater for the needs of a range of children and young people with an extremely
diverse variety of problems.
The plan was to replace Rimbleton with smaller, more homely, units aimed at
meeting the needs of small numbers of youngsters.
Crisis care units for emergency admissions were also possible but because of
the reform of local government, the plans had been held up.
New admissions have been restricted and social work staff are working to move a
number of children on to foster care or other accommodation.
</TEXT>
