<DOCNO>GH951125-000035</DOCNO>
<DOCID>GH951125-000035</DOCID>
<DATE>951125</DATE>
<HEADLINE>Murder ruling on baby stabbed in womb</HEADLINE>
<EDITION>2</EDITION>
<PAGE>3</PAGE>
<RECORDNO>975208484</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
A MAN who stabbed his pregnant girlfriend ultimately causing the death of their
baby daughter could have been tried for murder, the Lord Chief Justice, Lord
Taylor, ruled yesterday.
Attorney General Sir Nicholas Lyell had asked judges in the Court of Appeal to
rule in a test case that the man had committed either murder or manslaughter.
However, Lord Taylor immediately allowed yesterday's ruling to go to the House
of Lords.
He stressed that his decision would not have any implications for doctors
carrying out abortions.
Mr Simon Hawksworth QC had argued that no offence could be committed against a
child who was as yet unborn and therefore not legally recognised as ``a person
in being''.
The victim gave birth three months prematurely. Her baby, which bore a stab
wound in her abdomen, died four months later.
Two years ago, her boyfriend was acquitted of murdering the child.
Now a new point of law has been formulated which will mean anyone causing
unlawful injury to a foetus or a pregnant woman which eventually causes the
death of the child may face manslaughter or murder charges.
</TEXT>
