<DOCNO>GH951125-000036</DOCNO>
<DOCID>GH951125-000036</DOCID>
<DATE>951125</DATE>
<HEADLINE>Railways sell-off thrust into turmoil Labour hails court ruling</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>By ROY ROGERS Industrial Correspondent</BYLINE>
<EDITION>3</EDITION>
<PAGE>1</PAGE>
<RECORDNO>975208485</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
RAIL privatisation was thrust into turmoil yesterday when the courts allowed a
crucial legal challenge to cuts in services.
The High Court ruling was won by the pressure group Save Our Railways, which
includes 19 local authorities, the rail unions, the Railway Development
Society, and Transport 2000.
Leave was granted to seek a full judicial review of what SOR claims are
unlawful decisions by franchising director Roger Salmon to reduce services by
up to 50% in some cases.
Labour immediately hailed the court ruling as a triumph for the
anti-privatisation campaign. Shadow Transport Secretary Clare Short said the
Government ``should order an immediate halt to privatisation''.
SOR had argued that, under the terms of the Railways Act, service levels in the
franchises should have been based on the existing timetable.
Mr Justice Brooke agreed to a full hearing, which will open on December 7, a
few days before the first three passenger-franchise contracts are due to be
signed in readiness for Great Western Trains, the London, Tilbury, and Southend
service, and South West Trains to become the first privatised passenger
services by April 1.
Labour transport spokesman Brian Wilson described the events as ``absolutely
wonderful news for our railway industry and everyone who has been fighting
against the Tory's dogmatic obsession with breaking it up''.
He added: ``We have known from the start that the policy was politically
bankrupt. Now we are on our way to demonstrating that it is also legally flawed.
``Many Tory MPs, if they have an iota of sense, will welcome this decision as a
blessed relief which gives them the opportunity to tell Ministers that rail
privatisation must be abandoned.''
Mr Wilson said it was ``a day many of us have been working towards''.
He went on: ``It is an interim stage but I believe it spells the beginning of
the end for rail privatisation.''
Mr Jimmy Knapp, general secretary of rail union RMT, saw it as ``a tremendous
victory for rail users all around the country''. The court had exposed the
mythology called the franchise of passenger services as a dupe to secure severe
cuts.If SOR wins the case, the whole franchising programme would be set back
considerably. Mr Salmon would have to decide on fresh Passenger Service
Requirements but only after laying down criteria.
It was the lack of such criteria and suggestions that he had not acted in
accordance with Government undertakings that appeared to win over Mr Justice
Brooke.
The initial undertakings were that franchised services would be based on
existing BR timetables with no significant reductions and only ``tinkering at
the margins''. Mr Justice Brooke seemed particularly put out that under Mr
Salmon's PSR for the East Coast Inter City line, Doncaster faced losing 50% of
its services to and from London.
Save Our Railways said that many services were in fact being cut by one third
or more under the minimum service requirements laid down for future private
users by Mr Salmon.
Mr Nigel Pleming QC, for SOR, said an instruction from former Transport
Secretary John MacGregor aimed at safeguarding services based on existing
timetables and protecting the travelling public had not been obeyed. He said:
``In these circumstances, passenger service requirements have not been lawfully
set and it would be a wrong exercise of power to let franchises on that basis.''
Mr Justice Brooke said the SOR case was ``properly arguable'' in relation to
one tranche of services due to be privatised and gave leave for a full hearing
to take place on December 7. These involve the sell-off of InterCity East
Coast, Gatwick Express, Midland Main Line, and Network South Central.
However, he said it would not be appropriate to give leave with regard to
another tranche involving Great Western Trains, South West Trains, and London
Tilbury and Southend Trains as the court still had to be convinced that the
applicants had not delayed too long in launching their challenge.
He directed that the application with regard to those services should be
adjourned until the December hearing after Mr Salmon offered an undertaking not
to agree any of those franchises pending the challenge without first giving SOR
48 hours' notice so that it could lodge an objection.
Mr Salmon said last night that he was satisfied that the PSR he had set were in
accordance with the objectives, instructions, and guidance issued to him by the
Transport Secretary.
He added: ``Today's hearing merely ascertained that there is a point to be
argued and not the merits of the argument. The Office of Passenger Rail
Franchising will strenuously defend its position at the judicial review.'
</TEXT>
</DOC>
