<HEADLINE>Talks progress marred by lengthening picket lines Strikers' ranks swell to 5500 A series of angry clashes with workers passing picket lines in Hamilton yesterday typified the strikers' mood of growing resentment towards management.</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>CHRISTOPHER REEKIE KEN SMITH Bruce McKain</BYLINE>
<EDITION>3</EDITION>
<PAGE>1</PAGE>
<RECORDNO>975208486</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
By BRUCE McKAINPOLICE were called to angry demonstrations on the postal
workers' picket lines yesterday as more staff joined the strike.
However, the Royal Mail's top executive in Scotland personally took charge of
the negotiations and said he was optimistic that a solution could be found.
Mr John Mackay, director and general manager for Royal Mail Scotland and
Northern Ireland, and Mr John Keggie, divisional officer for the Communication
Workers Union, broke off from talks in Edinburgh to say progress had been made.
``We are currently involved in very fruitful discussions and we are both
optimistic. It is looking hopeful,'' Mr Mackay said.
``For the first time this week, both parties are in a positive frame of mind,''
said Mr Keggie.
They later resumed negotiations which are due to continue today but the strike
still goes on as attitudes on the picket lines harden.
Police had to escort workers past pickets in Edinburgh as they were jeered at
by the strikers. Other working staff have been wearing balaclavas to try to
obscure their identities while driving mail vans past striking colleagues.
In scenes described by one observer as reminiscent of the miners' strike in
1984-85, a crowd of 200 workers chanted, shouted, and waved fists outside West
Port House, the Royal Mail headquarters in Edinburgh, as a line of police
officers kept watch and sometimes restrained them.
Demonstrators surged forward to the main entrance and beat with their fists on
the glass doors, which are secured by an entry system, as a figure thought to
be from management was spotted in the foyer. Police ushered the demonstrators
away from the steps.
At the building's goods delivery entrance in Lauriston Place, demonstrators
booed and shouted insults at employees leaving or entering and at people seen
at the windows. Taxis arriving were surrounded, and there were shouts of
``scab''.
Although management appeared more conciliatory, the strikers saw it
differently. They were incensed that management had stopped paying wages due to
them directly into their bank accounts. Instead they were told to collect giros
at their places of work.
Angry strikers say they were given no notice of the change and that it meant
there were no funds in accounts to make mortgage and other standing payments.
Management say it was simpler to issue giro cheques rather than attempt to key
all the changes in to the payments computer.
Pay slips were waved by strikers which purported to show that workers had
received small sums, such as #12 and #20, for items such as tax rebate, instead
of the week's wages of about #150 expected.
Further offices in the Central Belt of Scotland joined the dispute, swelling
the number of postal workers on strike to 5500. About 12 million items of mail
are now languishing in piles in the sorting offices.
Mail-order businesses are warning of possible job losses if the dispute
continues much longer and the Scottish Chambers of Commerce has offered itself
as mediator to try to end the dispute.
Mr Mackay has not said whether he is willing to move on management's insistence
that workers must return to normal duties and staff at the Portobello office,
where the dispute began, must work the new duties that management want before
further negotiations can take place.
As he talked to union officials, the Post Office went back to court to seek
legal backing to force the Communication Workers Union to hand over its
disciplinary rules. It wants to know whether the union's repudiation of the
strike is genuine.
A judge granted the request.
The Post Office had complained to the union but the union maintained that it
was doing everything in its power to prevent local officials behaving in this
way.
The strike spread yesterday to Helensburgh, Dumbarton, Milngavie, Uddingston,
Kirkintilloch, Grangemouth, Auchterarder, and Dunblane. Management denied union
claims that Aberdeen was also affected.
Around 80 staff in Hamilton made their dispute official by following Government
procedures to have a properly constituted ballot.
Mr Keggie again emphasised the union's advice that it was an unofficial strike
and said the union was prepared to use the whole week-end to try to resolve it
and restore the service by Monday.
Mr Mackay said it was the worst postal strike yet to affect Scotland.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO>GH951125-000038</DOCNO>
