<DATE>951125</DATE>
<HEADLINE>SNP lays parliament plans</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>EXCLUSIVE By ROBBIE DINWOODIE Scottish Political Corresponden</BYLINE>
<EDITION>3</EDITION>
<PAGE>1</PAGE>
<RECORDNO>975208487</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
t
THE SNP plans to gatecrash the St Andrew's Day devolution celebrations next
week, joining Conservatives in the party-pooping by launching a document
outlining how an independent Scotland would take its place in the world.
Of the inevitable suggestion that, like Scottish Secretary Michael Forsyth's
intervention next Thursday using a lecture to suggest possible constitutional
changes within the Union, the SNP are simply engaging in a spoiling exercise,
party chief executive Michael Russell was dismissive.
He said: ``I don't think the convention has any right to assume that Scotland's
national day should be its alone, given that its plans do so little for
Scotland. After all, what amounts to a third launch of the same set of timid
proposals is hardly calculated to set the heather on fire.''
The SNP dipped in The Herald poll last month after a summer of mounting
success, and they are clearly concerned that the celebratory launch of home
rule proposals next Thursday, coupled with a robust Unionist counter-attack,
could freeze them out of the picture.
On St Andrew's Day SNP leader Alex Salmond will launch a new document spelling
out in detail what an independence parliament would consist of - its
membership, voting method, powers, and relationship with the England, Europe,
and the wider world.
The document launched at Edinburgh City Chambers, with SNP Lord Provost Norman
Irons in attendance along with Nationalist councillors from across the country
and members of the party hierarchy present, has been brought forward several
weeks to ensure the party's voice is not missing on the day.
``Our clear blueprint for a genuine Scottish parliament - its operation and
powers, particularly the rights and duties of our citizens, is something we
have been working on for some time,'' said Mr Russell.
``It seems appropriate to ensure that this confident vision is outlined at the
same time as the convention's powerless scheme and the tinkering at the margins
of the Union that is the Tories' alternative to real change.
``We are therefore going to put that vision up front on St Andrew's Day to
ensure that from that day on the complete range of choices available to the
Scottish people in the run-up to the next General Election is articulated.''
He said it was in Labour and Tory interest next Thursday to pretend that only
devolution and the Union were on offer, adding: ``John Major's admission that
Scotland is a perfectly viable independent unit was an indication that the
Tories want to polarise the debate between themselves and Labour.
``The real debate is between what type of change happens  and that is between
Labour and the SNP. It is only right that people have all the options before
them next Thursday.''
The document will pull together previous policies and conference decisions to
outline a 200-seat parliament with two-thirds of members elected directly by
constituencies by proportional representation, and the remaining third drawn
from lists to ensure party, gender, and geographical fairness.
The first measure passed in the initial four-year term will be a Bill of
Rights. The age of majority will be 16, the Queen will remain head of state,
and Scotland would become the sixteenth member of the European Union and 186th
member of the United Nations, a non-nuclear state with strong, conventional
forces.
After Thursday's launch Mr Salmond will head for Brussels where he will deliver
a toast at the St Andrew's Day dinner of the Scottish European Association.
``By combining our new report with an indication of our European vision, we can
give a complete outline of the benefits of independence,'' said Mr Russell.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO>GH951125-000039</DOCNO>
<DOCID>GH951125-000039</DOCID>
<DATE>951125</DATE>
<HEADLINE>School could be built for profit</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>By BARCLAY McBAIN Education Correspondent</BYLINE>
<EDITION>3</EDITION>
<PAGE>1</PAGE>
<RECORDNO>975208488</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
A LABOUR council is having talks with the Scottish Office about using the
Government's controversial private finance initiative for a new #10m state
secondary school in the Stirling constituency of Scottish Secretary Michael
Forsyth.
The main teachers' union, the Educational Institute of Scotland, last night
expressed concern about an ``insidious move towards privatisation'', with the
emergence of the profit element in the public education service.
Stirling Council said yesterday that replacing Balfron High, an overcrowded,
magnet secondary, with a new school was a priority.
However, the unitary council, which will assume control for education next
year, has concluded that its borrowing consent from Government will be no more
than #3m a year, an unrealistic option for Balfron's urgent needs.
The new councils, which will be short of cash because of tough Government
settlements and the disaggregation of the regions, are coming under increasing
pressure to use the initiative for school capital projects.
It involves the private sector building, owning, and operating projects for
profit. Stirling Council is seeking clarification from the Scottish Office
about the operating - or managing part of the initiative in relation to schools.
It wants to ensure that the education authority, which employs teachers and
other staff, continues to manage the new school.
Councillor Ann Strang, vice-chairwoman of the authority's children's committee,
said: ``The Scottish Office accepts that there are some obstacles to this type
of arrangement but suggests they are not insurmountable.''
The head teacher of Balfron High, Mr Jim Fleming, said: ``I am delighted to
know that the needs of the school are being taken very seriously. The present
state of affairs is unacceptable.''
However, he emphasised that there was no interest among school board members in
opting the school out of local authority control.
The school has to operate a one-way system in corridors at break times because
of the pressure of pupil numbers. The board is so concerned about overcrowding
that it has asked for health and safety officials to be called in.
Mrs Helen Liddell, who speaks for Labour on Scottish education, said management
of any PFI-built school was the critical issue.
``Local authority control must predominate. We would not tolerate any
circumstances in which the private sector was involved in the provision of
education.''
However, Mr Ronnie Smith, general secretary of the EIS, said: ``This is a
development which is wholly driven by the dogma of injecting the private sector
into public-service provision.''
He called for openness in the bidding process to establish if PFIs were cheaper
and more efficient.
If the talks came to fruition, the new Balfron High would be the first state
school to be built under the initiative.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO>GH951125-000040</DOCNO>
<DOCID>GH951125-000040</DOCID>
<DATE>951125</DATE>
<HEADLINE>Trust told to make more cuts</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>By GRAEME SMITH</BYLINE>
<EDITION>1</EDITION>
<PAGE>1</PAGE>
<RECORDNO>975208489</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
ABERDEEN Royal Hospitals Trust has had its revised financial plans rejected by
the Scottish NHS executive and has been given until Christmas Eve to come up
with more savings.
The trust has been asked for a more detailed plan. The new deadline is to
ensure ``that every reasonable step is taken to reduce costs to match income''.
A first revised plan was submitted last month when it was revealed that the
trust was heading for a #2m deficit this financial year.
Yesterday, the board's statement to staff said it intended to submit a staged
plan by December 24 which would show that it would achieve its financial
targets by March 31, 1997.
``We shall also, of course, seek to increase our income through detailed
discussion with our purchasers and by offering additional activity,
particularly to reduce lengthy waiting times,'' the board said.
``We will be examining all areas of expenditure with particular emphasis on
administrative costs, and costs not directly related to patient care with a
view to making savings. We shall also seek to ensure that the organisation of
our services and use of supplies is as efficient and effective as we can make
them.''
The statement continued: ``This will require close involvement of all our staff
and we seek your co-operation in identifying areas where there may be potential
for savings or for more efficient operation.''
A trust spokesman said the NHS executive was simply seeking more details of how
the trust proposed to achieve the cuts ``and we will be seeking the help of the
staff for this''.
He added: ``We have to be more specific about where we expect the income to
come from and where we expect to make savings. The first deadline was
reasonably short. We would not want patient care to suffer because we have a
high standard in Aberdeen.''
The trust had met staff and they had said they would work with the management
towards providing the detail required.
A Scottish Office spokesman said last night: ``It is the trust's responsibility
to ensure that its costs match its income. Its pledge to tackle organisation of
its services and administration costs is very much in line with the requirement
of Ministers to reduce these and transfer the savings to patient care.
``Further work is being carried out by the trust on its financial plans. We are
pleased to see the trust's commitment to make progress in this area.''
The one-time flagship NHS Trust - the first in Scotland - had been ordered to
prepare a survival package when the extent of its financial problems emerged
three months ago.
Fears were expressed that wards would close, operations would be delayed, and
nurses axed as it tried to cut its budget at short notice. Eventually, Grampian
Health Board came up with a #1m rescue package to ease the #1.75m deficit.
The problems came to light in the summer when a senior consultant claimed that
the trust was ``technically bankrupt'' and described its financial affairs as
``an absolute mess''.
Trust management initially denied a cash crisis but were later forced to admit
that there had been an exchange of letters with the Scottish Office. Despite
the backing of the trust, in September, finance director Douglas Lindsay
announced his resignation from next March.
</TEXT>
