<HEADLINE>Relationships still not outlawed</HEADLINE>
<EDITION>2</EDITION>
<PAGE>3</PAGE>
<RECORDNO>975208490</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
OPEN sexual relationships still lie at the heart of The Family religious cult,
a member admitted yesterday.
The Family, formerly known as The Children of God, has nearly 300 members in
the UK, two-thirds of whom are children. The sect rents around six properties
in Scotland, England, and Ireland in which family groups live together.
Children are schooled at home and have little contact with the outside world.
All adults work within the community and share their income and possessions.
The sect said yesterday it had renounced the teachings of its late founder
David Berg, who promoted child sex as a principle of his Law of Love.
The cult opened the doors of one of its homes, a three-storey manor house in
rural Leicestershire.
Mr Gideon Scott, 44, one of the 20 adults in the house, said the group now
accepted David Berg was wrong.
``He himself said he was wrong to have written in that way. We do renounce his
teachings.''
Mr Scott said there were now rules to prevent child abuse within the sect.
However, he admitted adults within The Family had open sexual relationships.
Mr Scott has 12 children, ranging in age from seven months to 23 years, all by
his wife Rachel, 43.
He said: ``Sexual relationships between adults are their own personal affair.
It is up to the individual concerned.''
Four families, including the Scotts, live at the Leicestershire home. Each
couple has their own bedroom and the children share dormitories.
The sect has two similar homes in Leicester.
The children have lessons together and take part in scheduled activities every
evening.
One of the Leicestershire children, eight-year-old Mariangela, said she was
reluctant to see life outside the home.
``I don't think I would like to be a child living outside here. I think it is a
very nice home. It is fun because I have lots of friends.''
Another girl, Victoria, six, said she had never seen a normal school.
``My mum and dad told me it wasn't very nice. I like it here because I have got
lots of people to talk to. A lot of people say it is not very nice outside.''
Mariangela's parents, Andrew and Phoebe Barker, share a bedroom on the same
floor as their children's dormitory.
Mr Barker said he joined the sect 18 years ago when he was in Afghanistan
looking for ``enlightenment''.
Mr Barker, 42, said: ``People take the sensational and salacious lines about
our lives. It is not all about sex. It affects our lives the same as it does
anybody else. A very small percentage of our time is spent on sex.''
</TEXT>
