<HEADLINE>Housing plea over mental illness</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>By KEITH SINCLAIR</BYLINE>
<EDITION>1</EDITION>
<PAGE>8</PAGE>
<RECORDNO>975208491</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
RESISTANCE to Care in the Community projects aimed at integrating the mentally
ill into the local community stem from ignorance and a lack of understanding of
the problems associated with mental illness, according to the chief executive
of the national housing agency, Scottish Homes.
In a hard-hitting address to a conference hosted by the Scottish Council on
Mental Health, Mr Peter McKinlay yesterday called for a better understanding of
the problems if Care in the Community projects throughout Scotland were to be
implemented successfully.
Stressing that a closer partnership between housing agencies, health care and
social work professionals, and community care was essential to this success, Mr
McKinlay said housing managers ``must be sensitive of, but not pander to, the
Not in my Back Yard (Nimby) Syndrome'' and urged other agencies to work with
Scottish Homes to promote a better understanding of mental health problems.
He said: ``In the context of mental illness, ignorance inspires fear while
knowledge inspires understanding. We all must therefore work together to help
promote a better appreciation of the difficulties and an acceptance of the
solutions. What we must all strive to achieve is integration, not isolation.''
Mr McKinlay, whose agency has invested almost #400m in the provision of more
than 2000 homes in support of Care in the Community since 1989, also stressed
that, because the experience of mental illness is not the same for everyone,
housing and care packages must be flexible and effective.
He told conference delegates that, crucially, the agencies involved in Care in
the Community ``must never forget we are concerned with individuals who,
whatever their disabilities, have the same claims to civil rights and respect
as citizens as you and me. They must be treated as we would wish others to
treat us.''
Outlining Scottish Homes' role in community care planning, Mr McKinlay said
earlier that the agency had developed grant mechanisms which were designed to
encourage more organisations to develop and manage community-care housing
projects.
The agency had also undertaken valuable research and information-gathering
exercises, the results of which were available for use by all other agencies
involved in Care in the Community.
Mr McKinlay said four principles, which apply across a range of community care
client groups including those suffering from mental illnesses, underpinned
Scottish Homes' approach to Care in the Community.
``Firstly, we believe people with mental health problems should be part of the
community where they live. They should be able to live in homely settings, with
flexible care and support which enables them to live as independently as
possible within their own communities.
``Secondly, we believe housing should be small scale and integrated into local
communities. This is essential to overcome the isolation experienced by many
people with mental health problems and ensure their successful integration into
the local community.''
He added that Scottish Homes also believed in working in partnership with the
public, private, and voluntary sectors involved in Care in the Community, and
that the role of the individual lies at the heart of successful Care in the
Community.
``We believe this is best achieved when health care, social work, and housing
professionals involved the individual and their carers in the decision making
process as early as possible. I particularly welcome hospital discharge
programmes which take into account individual preferences.''
</TEXT>
