<HEADLINE>`Bad faith' claim over discipline makes judgment necessary, says QC Postal union told to hand over rule book</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>By BRUCE McKAIN Law Correspondent</BYLINE>
<EDITION>2</EDITION>
<PAGE>2</PAGE>
<RECORDNO>975208492</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
AS the unofficial postal strike in central Scotland intensified, a judge last
night ordered the Communication Workers' Union to hand over its disciplinary
rules.
The Post Office wants to look at the rules so that it can decide whether the
union's disavowal of the unofficial industrial action is genuine.
The union has formally repudiated the strike as it is required to do under the
1992 Trade Union and Labour Relations Act. But Mr Neil Brailsford QC, counsel
for the the Post Office, alleged at the Court of Session yesterday that local
officials were still inciting members to carry on the dispute.
The Post Office had complained to the union but the union maintained that it
was doing everything in its power to prevent local officials behaving in this
way.
Mr Brailsford said the Post Office view was that the steps being taken by the
union were ineffective and it might be that it should be doing more to
discourage the actions of local officials.
However, without a sight of the disciplinary rules which would reveal the
powers of the union, the Post Office could not come back to court and say what
the union ought to be doing.
A request for a copy of the rules had been refused, making it necessary to come
to court.
Mr Mungo Bovey, for the union, argued that the disciplinary rules were none of
the Post Officer's business.
Before any order for production of the rule book could be made, there had to be
a claim that the union was acting in bad faith in failing to discipline local
officials. Such a claim could not be made in this case.
Mr Bovey argued that a failure by the union to take disciplinary action might
be a responsible step. If trade unions were to be suspended or disciplined this
could make an already heated situation much worse.
He stressed that there was nothing ambiguous about the union's denouncement of
the strike. Officials had been abused at meetings for urging colleagues to go
back to work.
Lord Dawson decided that the arguments of the Post Office were well-founded.
For reasons best known to themselves, the union had declined to hand over the
rules, but Lord Dawson ruled that the Post Office was entitled to see them so
it could determine whether or not the union had genuinely disowned the strike
action.
q Police in Hamilton are investigating a complaint from two striking postmen
that a senior Royal Mail employee drove a van through the banner they were
holding on a picket line.
The incident was alleged to have happened yesterday at Leechlee Road.
Chief Inspector Malcolm Mackie said: ``We are investigating a complaint from
two male pickets that their banner was damaged when a vehicle drove through
it.''
He added that the pickets had behaved well and he thanked them for
co-opertating with police during their demonstration.
</TEXT>
