<HEADLINE>Drama at death probe Friends run off in tears</HEADLINE>
<EDITION>1</EDITION>
<PAGE>5</PAGE>
<RECORDNO>975208493</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
TWO grieving friends of teenagers who drowned when a bridge collapsed into a
rain-swollen river ran from court in tears yesterday.
One woman began sobbing during police evidence and then hurried out shouting:
``You are lying.''''
Another weeping relative who went with her turned to Sheriff Bruce Kerr QC and
said: ``I'm sorry.''
Minutes later, during the fatal accident inquiry at Glasgow Sheriff Court, Mr
James Gibson, l8, who escaped when the car plunged into the River Kelvin, on
December ll last year, also ran from the court and could be heard sobbing
loudly outside.
The emotions came to a head during the evidence of Constable Ian Smeall, 37,
who was one of the first officers at Gavell Bridge, Twechar, on the Sunday
afternoon when the accident happened.
The inquiry is into the deaths of John Furay, l7, of The Strone, St John's Way,
and James McClement, l7, of Kelvin Way, both Twechar.
James Gibson, of Differ Avenue, Twechar, kicked open the door of the VW Polo
and escaped.
Mr Smeall told Mrs Margaret Porter, leading the evidence, that he and a
colleague were checking the roads for flooding.
They met firemen who told them the bridge on Gavell Road had collapsed.
He said they drove through flood water and stopped just short of the bridge on
the Queenzieburn side.
Mr Smeall said he got out of the police Land Rover to inspect the damage and
told his colleague, Constable Wilkie to contact their division control.
As he returned to the vehicle, more bits of the bridge were collapsing. This,
he said, happened shortly after 3pm.
He told Mrs Porter there was a gap in the road surface of the bridge.
``It was approximately eight feet. It may have been more. It was quite a
substantial gap,'' he said.
Mr Smeall said he also saw cracks appearing on the sides of the bridge as more
and more of it gave way.
He went on: ``As I came back off the bridge, a large section fell into the
water. The gap was now approximately double the size.''
The officer said he told his control that the flood water was rising and he was
instructed to move back from the bridge.
Mr Smeall said he had no road cones in the vehicle.
He told Mrs Porter he requested that cones be delivered to the area and also
asked that neighbouring ``D'' Division be informed of the bridge collapse.
The officer said he requested that ``D'' Division attend at the Twechar side of
the bridge to close off the road.
He looked over the river and could see traffic turning back on the Twechar side.
The constable said he was informed that ``D'' Division was having difficulty
getting a car to the Twechar side.
He later heard that a four-wheel-drive police car was on its way.
Mr Smeall said he could not see any other vehicles approaching the Twechar side
and assumed police had sealed it off.
He told Mrs Porter he later heard a vehicle had gone into the river with people
in it and he went back to the Queenzieburn side of the bridge.
He saw people on the other side and they were shouting: ``There's a car in the
water and there are two boys in it.''
Shortly afterwards, he was instructed to take another vehicle and attempt to
get to the Twechar side of the river via Kilsyth.
When he arrived he saw ``a line of cones'' at the junction blocking the road to
the bridge.
It was at this point that woman began shouting and hurried from court in tears,
followed shortly afterwards by James Gibson.
Mr Smeall said a man told him there were voices coming from the river but he
and others searched the river but saw and heard nothing.
Questioned by solicitor James Carmichael, for the McClement family, he agreed
his memory of times that day was hazy and that he had taken no notes.
He said the weather was too bad to take notes and he knew everything was being
recorded by force control.
The inquiry was continued until January.
</TEXT>
