<HEADLINE>Court told of road rage horror attack</HEADLINE>
<EDITION>2</EDITION>
<PAGE>7</PAGE>
<RECORDNO>975208494</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
A DISABLED former Ministry of Defence executive was brutally beaten up in a
horrific ``road rage'' attack, a court was told.
The alleged victim was attacked because he was ``going too slow''.
Mr Ian Lothian, 48, of Carronshore, Falkirk, told Falkirk Sheriff Court he was
driving his wife's Volvo 340 at 20/25 mph in a 30mph area in King St,
Stenhousemuir, on July 1.
He said he was approaching a zebra crossing.
Mr Lothian, who was invalided out of the MoD in 1988 because of crippling
arthritis, said he had an orange disabled sticker on the windscreen.
He claimed that Derek Godfrey, 22, of Beaufort Drive, Falkirk, drove his
Volkswagen Golf right on his tail.
He said: ``The driver flashed his lights. When I got to the pedestrian
crossing, he pulled out and overtook me then cut in sharply in front of me
causing me to brake sharply.
``A car coming the other way had to swerve to avoid running into the white
Golf.''
Mr Lothian said that, further along the road, Mr Godfrey stopped and got out
his car: ``He approached the front of my Volvo and started to kick it.''
Mr Lothian, who walks with the aid of a stick, said: ``I asked him to stop
kicking my car and told him to see reason.''
He claimed Mr Godfrey then came at him ``like a boxer leaving his corner for a
fight''.
Mr Lothian, who was allowed to give evidence sitting down, told the court Mr
Godfrey kicked him in the arms, legs, groin, and stomach.
He said he fought to stay on his feet. ``I knew that if I was down on the
ground, I was going to be very vulnerable.''
Mr Lothian said he suffered lacerations to his arms, stomach, and legs.
He said his doctor suspected his ribs had been cracked or broken. The casualty
department at Falkirk Royal Infirmary put his arm in a sling.
He said he suffered nightmares after the alleged assault: ``I would wake up in
the night and I had been dreaming that I was lying on the ground and that he
was going to kick me.''
He said he noted Mr Godfrey's car registration number as he sped off and
reported the incident to police.
Mr Lothian told the court: ``The only thing I did to annoy him was to drive
within the speed limit. It was a completely unprovoked attack.''
Constable Brian Tennant said Mr Lothian was ``distressed'' when he interviewed
him and his arms and face were grazed. One arm was in a sling and there was
damage to the offside wing of the Volvo.
The policeman said that when he went to Mr Godfery's home, he told him: ``It is
me that you are looking for.''
He alleged that Mr Godfrey said in a statement: ``As he went down, he gave a
wee squeal, so I gave him a boot.''
Mr Godfrey told the court he acted in self defence. He claimed Mr Lothian
attacked him with his stick.
Depute fiscal Petra Collins told him: ``You were the one with the road rage.
``You were driving in an appalling manner that day.
``He was going too slowly for you. You took out your anger on him.''
Mr Godfrey replied: ``I did nothing other than in self defence.''
He denies driving dangerously, or carelessly, and assaulting Mr Lothian by
pulling his sunglasses off, seizing him by the body, knocking him to the
ground, and repeatedly kicking him on his legs and body to his injury.
The trial before Sheriff Ian Donaldson was adjourned till next month.
</TEXT>
