<HEADLINE>Railtrack urged  not to be `bullied'</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>Ian Wilson, Chief Reporter</BYLINE>
<EDITION>1</EDITION>
<PAGE>5</PAGE>
<RECORDNO>975208495</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
By IAIN WILSON
Chief Reporter
AN MP yesterday urged Railtrack not to be ``bullied'' by the Government into
selling land for a road widely regarded as vital to a plan to transform
Stirling town centre.
Scottish Liberal Democrat Ray Michie insisted Railtrack should not sell unless
the Scottish Office agreed to fund a #75,000 feasibility study into reopening a
Stirling-Alloa rail link. She also described the refusal to sell as principled
and commercially appropriate.
But it emerged later that Railtrack has repeatedly been offered contributions
towards the study from Forth Valley Enterprise.
Mrs Michie's comments coincided with the Scottish Office and Railtrack opening
talks on the disputed land at Stirling station.
If the ground is not released, access will be curbed to a mainly derelict
15-acre site with potential to boost the town's economic fortunes.
The Government-backed Stirling Initiative's #20m plans for the site, Forthside,
include offices, housing, and a visitor centre.
Approval for the #5m acccess road, which would also relieve traffic congestion
in the area, was made possible by special additional borrowing consent from the
Scottish Office.
However, Railtrack believes there should be ``a level playing field'' between
road and rail investments - a view supported by Mrs Michie, who argued that
road schemes, unlike the railways, never have to justify their costs.
Railtrack said the Scottish Office talks follow a failure to agree terms for a
sale. Nothing was resolved yesterday. The Scottish Office said talks will
continue at a later date.
</TEXT>
