<HEADLINE>Private sector `holds key to rented homes'</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>By FRANCES HORSBURGH Local Government Correspondent</BYLINE>
<EDITION>1</EDITION>
<PAGE>5</PAGE>
<RECORDNO>975208496</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
PRIVATE-sector money is not evil and should not be seen as coming from the
devil, Scottish Housing Minister Raymond Robertson told delegates at a
conference in Edinburgh yesterday.
Mr Robertson was pushing the Government's current agenda of trying to persuade
local authorities to transfer housing stock to alternative landlords with
access to private-sector investment.
The new landlord, he stressed, would be required to continue to provide rented
housing, and any profits would be ploughed back into the housing stock.
The conference, organised by Waverley Housing Management - which took over
homes previously owned by Scottish Homes in the Borders - was warned that
councils which remained as major providers of housing faced a future where
there would be very tough limits on public expenditure.
At present, the process of transfer for councils or for Scottish Homes was
lengthy, the Minister said, and the Scottish Office would soon publish
guidelines to help speed it up.
</TEXT>
