<HEADLINE>Policy that led to solicitor's dismissal `a complete sham'</HEADLINE>
<EDITION>2</EDITION>
<PAGE>7</PAGE>
<RECORDNO>975208497</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
THE sacking of a lawyer by one of Scotland's best-known legal firms, after she
refused to work nights, was a case of ``victimisation dressed up as
management'', her solicitor claimed yesterday.
Mr Jack Quar, who is representing Ms Eileen Paterson in her unfair sacking and
sex discrimination claim against Ross Harper, said the new policy which led to
her sacking was a ``complete sham''.
An industrial tribunal in Glasgow was told earlier that the firm, based in the
city's Ingram Street, drew up a policy document requiring all solicitors to
take part in a night-duty rota, to offer clients in custody continuity of
representation.
There was concern the firm was losing clients because so many different
solicitors were dealing with them at various stages in criminal proceedings.
A policy document was drawn up with the aim of achieving continuity of
representation but it meant Ms Paterson, 36, of Pollokshields, Glasgow, who is
married to advocate Robert Skinner and has two young children, would have to
take her turn on night duty, being called out to see clients in police custody.
The tribunal was told that Ms Paterson had been excluded from the rota when her
first child was born nine years ago.
In his final submissions, Mr Quar said the policy was a ``complete sham'' and
continued: ``Nobody else's terms and conditions were to change, only Mrs
Skinner's. This is a situation where an employee, for a long number of years,
has not done call outs and it has been recognised by the firm that she has
good, sound reasons for not doing so, and then there is a change in her terms
and conditions.
``This is victimisation dressed up as management,'' he submitted.
Mr Quar added that the policy change was not implemented after Ms Paterson's
dismissal.
Solicitor Stephen Miller, for Ross Harper, said the policy document did not
just affect one employee, it included changes to the bonus structure and
removed the fixed annual salary increases.
Ms Paterson is seeking compensation. The tribunal will issue its decision at a
later date.
Solicitor Liam O'Donnell, who was named in evidence the previous day, handed in
a letter to the regional chairman of the industrial tribunals, pointing out
that he had not complained about Ms Paterson's exclusion from the call-out rota.
Mr John Carruthers, a partner with the firm who had given evidence, issued a
statement confirming that Mr O'Donnell had never made such a complaint and that
he had not intended such an interpretation to be placed on his evidence.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO>GH951125-000049</DOCNO>
<DOCID>GH951125-000049</DOCID>
<DATE>951125</DATE>
<HEADLINE>Labour council in talks on privately-financed school</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>By BARCLAY McBAIN Education Correspondent</BYLINE>
<EDITION>1</EDITION>
<PAGE>2</PAGE>
<RECORDNO>975208498</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
A LABOUR council is having talks with the Scottish Office about using the
Government's controversial private finance initiative for a new #10m state
secondary school in the Stirling constituency of Scottish Secretary Michael
Forsyth.
The main teachers' union, the Educational Institute of Scotland, last night
expressed concern about an ``insidious move towards privatisation'', with the
emergence of the profit element in the public education service.
Stirling Council said yesterday that replacing Balfron High, an overcrowded,
magnet secondary, with a new school was a priority.
However, the unitary council, which will assume control for education next
year, has concluded that its borrowing consent from Government will be no more
than #3m a year, an unrealistic option for Balfron's urgent needs.
The new councils, which will be short of cash because of tough Government
settlements and the disaggregation of the regions, are coming under increasing
pressure to use the initiative for school capital projects.
It involves the private sector building, owning, and operating projects for
profit. Stirling Council is seeking clarification from the Scottish Office
about the operating - or managing - part of the initiative in relation to
schools.
It wants to ensure that the education authority, which employs teachers and
other staff, continues to manage the new school.
Councillor Ann Strang, vice-chairwoman of the authority's children's committee,
said: ``The Scottish Office accepts that there are some obstacles to this type
of arrangement but suggests they are not insurmountable.''
The head teacher of Balfron High, Mr Jim Fleming, said: ``I am delighted to
know that the needs of the school are being taken very seriously.''
However, he emphasised that there was no interest among school board members in
opting the school out of local authority control.
Mrs Helen Liddell, who speaks for Labour on Scottish education, said management
of any PFI-built school was the critical issue.
``Local authority control must predominate. We would not tolerate any
circumstances in which the private sector was involved in the provision of
education.''
However, Mr Ronnie Smith, general secretary of the EIS, said: ``This is a
development which is wholly driven by the dogma of injecting the private sector
into public-service provision.''
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO>GH951125-000050</DOCNO>
<DOCID>GH951125-000050</DOCID>
<DATE>951125</DATE>
<HEADLINE>Scout Christmas service launched</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>By LYNNE ROBERTSON</BYLINE>
<EDITION>2</EDITION>
<PAGE>2</PAGE>
<RECORDNO>975208499</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
Scout Christmas
service launched
AS tonnes of mail continued to pile up in Edinburgh yesterday, local Scouts
were gearing up for the launch of their annual Christmas card service.
The Scouts, who have made deliveries within the city for the last three years,
begin collecting cards from outlets throughout the capital next week.
However, Mr Alan Willoughby, area secretary of the Edinburgh Scouts, stressed
that the 15p festive service could not be used as an alternative to postal
deliveries.
``We are not able to carry anything other than Christmas cards. If the public
decided to post other mail, we would not be able to post it for them,'' he
explained.
The Scouts' secretary explained cards posted via the festive Scout service took
a little longer to reach their destination than the conventional postal route.
``It can take anything up to three weeks for the cards to be delivered, the way
our system operates,'' he said.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO>GH951125-000051</DOCNO>
<DOCID>GH951125-000051</DOCID>
<DATE>951125</DATE>
<HEADLINE>Call for seal cull to help feed starving in Africa</HEADLINE>
<EDITION>1</EDITION>
<PAGE>3</PAGE>
<RECORDNO>975208500</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
A SCOTS councillor yesterday called for thousands of seals to be culled and for
the meat to be sent to starving children in Africa.
Furious animal rights activists criticised the idea as ``insulting'' and
``absolutely ridiculous''.
The call came as police inquiries continued into the illegal slaughter of 23
baby seals on an Orkney beach just a few miles from Councillor Norman Smith's
home.
Councillor Smith, who represents the St Margaret's Hope ward on the Orkney
Islands Council, said: ``A harvest of adult seals could be authorised and the
carcasses used profitably for pet food.
``In a week or two, Save the Children will be to the fore. Starving children
might relish some cans of seal meat. After all, Orcadians were eating seals
within living memory.''
However, Ms Alero Harrison, of Save the Children, was horrified at the
suggestion.
``This is a totally inappropriate suggestion. We would refuse seal meat if it
was offered to us,'' she said.
Yesterday, John Robins of Animal Concern accused Councillor Smith of using any
excuse to justify a cull.
``It is an insult to the people of Africa to suggest that they be fed on the
carcasses of dead seals.''
</TEXT>
</DOC>
