<HEADLINE>Council boycott threat to Shell</HEADLINE>
<EDITION>2</EDITION>
<PAGE>2</PAGE>
<RECORDNO>975208501</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
A SCOTS council is threatening to boycott Shell as a protest over what it
claims are horrendous conservation problems in Nigeria.
Dumbarton district blames the oil company's drilling operations for the
pollution in Ogoniland - the part of Nigeria which executed protester Ken
Saro-Wiwa and the Ogoni people have been fighting to protect for more than 30
years.
The council is to write to Shell chairman John Jennings demanding the immediate
clean-up of the area, restoration of lands and lakes, and compensation for the
Ogoni people.
If Shell does not comply, the council will immediately ban the use of Shell
petrol and all other products.
The decision was reached after housing boss Doreen Phillips criticised Shell
and Nigeria's military regime for the devastation in Ogoniland.
``Sanctions are slow but it is the only way we can react,'' she said. ``We will
not use their petrol and will take Shell off our tender list if they do not do
this.
``It is the only weapon we have as ordinary people but we can use it and we can
do this.''
The move follows an appeal by green lobbyists Friends of the Earth, Greenpeace,
and The Body Shop to take action against the multi-national.
They claim that the activities of the Nigerian Government, Shell, and other
multi-national oil companies have led to the widespread degradation and
pollution of the region.
The Ogoni are mostly farmers and fishermen whose land and water is essential
for their existence.
Tory councillor Bill Morrison urged the council to wait for a reply from Mr
Jennings before taking any action.
</TEXT>
