<HEADLINE>British soldier `forgets' blaming co-accused</HEADLINE>
<EDITION>3</EDITION>
<PAGE>10</PAGE>
<RECORDNO>975208502</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
A BRITISH soldier accused of killing a young Danish woman told a court in
Cyprus today that he could not remember giving damning evidence against one of
his two co-defendants, as alleged by police.
Rifleman Jeff Pernell, 23, from Oldbury, Midlands, also told the court that
some bloodstains on his shirt were his own from a wound inflicted by police,
while other bloodstains were ``from inside the car''. He did not elaborate.
Pernell and fellow soldiers Alan Ford, 27, from Birmingham, and Justin Fowler,
26 from Falmouth, stationed at the British base of Dhekelia, have denied
charges of abduction, conspiracy to rape and the manslaughter of 23-year-old
tour guide Louise Jensen last year.
Pernell took the witness box and under persistent questioning by prosecutors,
denied any memory of a conversation he had with a police officer that
incriminated Ford.
``The police officer was asking me questions and I was talking back to
him.......I can't remember,'' said Pernell, who added that he was tired at the
time and had been drinking.
Yesterday Inspector Democritos Georgiou told the court that shortly after the
three soldiers were detained at a roadblock close to base Pernell told him:
``Alan did it.......he got out of the car with her.......he returned alone.''
The three soldiers are accused of bundling Jensen into their yellow Mini Moke
after knocking her off her boyfriend's motorcycle on the outskirts of the
resort. Her battered body was found in a shallow roadside grave two days later.
All three soldiers were found with what prosecution alleges were bloodstained
clothes.
Pernell said some of the stains on his shirt were from a forehead wound
inflicted by police officers.
When quizzed about other blood stains, he replied: ``(They were) from inside
the car.''
``You are a liar,'' said prosecutor Petros Clerides.
``You can say what you like,'' Pernell shot back. ``You weren't there.''
The three-judge court then stopped this line of questioning as the first issue
to be settled was whether the court should rule Pernell's alleged comments on
Ford admissible evidence.
Defence lawyer Antonis Andreou urged the court to rule the alleged conversation
inadmissible because Pernell was in no state at that time to give police a
voluntary statement.
The hearing continues.-Reuter.
</TEXT>
