<HEADLINE>Trustees warn harbour wall is cracked and close to collapse</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>By KEITH SINCLAIR</BYLINE>
<EDITION>1</EDITION>
<PAGE>2</PAGE>
<RECORDNO>975208503</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
THE trustees of one of the most picturesque harbours in the North East, at
Cruden Bay near Peterhead, have warned that it is in such a poor state of
repair that it may collapse and become unuseable unless remedial work costing
up to #250,000 is carried out.
Members of Cruden Bay Harbour Committee plan to meet representatives of Banff
and Buchan District Council and Grampian Enterprise at the harbour on Monday to
discuss the problem of funding repair work on its external wall.
They say that despite improvements costing #120,000 two years ago, mainly on
the internal part of the harbour and funded equally by the council and the
enterprise company, the outer part of the structure is in a dilapidated state
and has developed several cracks of more than 12ft in length which are wider
than a man's fist.
Mr Bob Quinn, chairman of the committee, said yesterday that failure to repair
the outside of the harbour could result in it being breached and becoming
unuseable, which would have a detrimental affect on two important local
industries, fishing and tourism.
The tiny tidal harbour, which was built before the turn of the century by the
Earl of Erroll, is used as a salmon fishing station and by local inshore
fishermen and leisure craft.
Mr Quinn said: ``About two years ago, the district council and Grampian
Enterprise poured more than #100,000 into bringing the internal part of the
harbour up to its present state, which is wonderful. We said why not do the
outside wall first but they said no and it has been completely neglected since
then.''
He added that, although Banff and Buchan District Council has already allocated
#100,000 in its 1996-97 budget for work on the outside of the harbour, the
trustees fear that the finance will not be forthcoming because of local
government reform next April when the new Aberdeenshire Council assumes control.
``We are concerned that the money they have put by will not be used for that
purpose but for something else in Aberdeen,'' he said.
Grampian Enterprise pointed out yesterday that the total expenditure on
environmental improvements two years ago - which were designed to ``increase
the attraction of the harbour to tourists'' - included #16,000 allocated for
work on the harbour wall.
Mr David Halliday, director of property at Grampian Enterprise, said it was
sympathetic to the situation and was ``seeking to explore potential
assistance.''
</TEXT>
