<HEADLINE>Toll fight is backed</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>DAVID ROSS Highland Correspondent</BYLINE>
<EDITION>1</EDITION>
<PAGE>5</PAGE>
<RECORDNO>975208504</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
HIGHLAND Council yesterday voted unanimously to campaign for the abolition of
the present toll structure on the Skye Bridge and will press the Scottish
Office for a change in policy.
A high-powered working group was set up and authority given for the deployment
of staff and resources for the campaign, which will go to Europe if no
satisfaction can be won.
The campaign motion was signed by all six members of the council's Skye and
Lochalsh area committee and moved by its chairman, Dunvegan Councillor Allan
Beaton, who said afterwards: ``The fact that all the councillors from all over
the Highlands have given us their support is enormously encouraging.''
Earlier, he had told the council: ``The motion sets out quite clearly the aims
of the people of Skye and Lochalsh and that is to rid ourselves as soon as
possible of the iniquitous toll system imposed on the Skye Bridge. We live in a
fragile economic situation in a scattered rural environment.
``What encouragement is it for tourists to have to pay #4.30 over a mile of
road, or for a tour coach to pay #37.50 to drive over the same distance? We are
a captive audience in that we have no alternative viable means of getting off
the island.''
A Scottish Office spokesman responded: ``Highland Regional Council, Skye and
Lochalsh District Council, and Highlands and Islands Enterprise accepted that a
privately funded toll bridge would secure the fixed crossing much sooner than a
publicly funded one.
``A public local inquiry was held in January 1992 to look at all issues related
to the bridge and the toll regime and no objections were raised at that time by
any of the local authorities. However, if the Highland Council has new evidence
to present, we shall look at it on its merits.''
</TEXT>
