<HEADLINE>Plan to raise U-boat fleet for salvage sale back to Germany</HEADLINE>
<EDITION>1</EDITION>
<PAGE>5</PAGE>
<GRAPHIC>photograph</GRAPHIC>
<RECORDNO>975208505</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
Plan to raise U-boat fleet for
salvage sale back to Germany
A GROUP of ex-Royal Navy senior officers plan to raise 100 U-boats scuttled in
British waters after World War II, break them up on a remote Scottish island,
and ship the ``expensive'' metal back to Germany.
They have already been given permission by the Ministry of Defence to bring up
the submarines, currently lying in at least 300ft of water off the coast of
Northern Ireland.
Now a consultant for the group, a salvage consortium, has written to Shetland
Islands Council suggesting a disused mine near Sullom Voe oil terminal be used
for the salvage work.
The bizarre proposal is being treated with thinly-veiled scepticism in most
council departments and a planning application is almost certain to be refused.
Mr Charles Osbond, of Derbyshire-based Charterwood Consultancy Services, said
in the confidential letter that he was seeking a site for the consortium, which
includes ``several ex-Royal Navy personnel of significant rank and service''.
He claimed that the old Sullom Mine, in Northmavine, would be ideal for
dismantling the U-boats for their expensive metals because it has a mooring
jetty nearby.
Mr Osbond is understood to have links with the mine's owners - Jeniva Landfill
Ltd, of Radcliffe on Trent, Nottingham, recently took over the mine from local
owners.
``Some 20 vessels a year would be brought in, with all explosives and diesel
expertly removed at the lifting site in the Irish Sea,'' he writes.
``The vessels range in weight from 790 to 2200 tonnes and in total would
provide some 150,000 tonnes of saleable material.
``Broadly speaking, the proposal would be to use Gaza Jetty as the mooring
point and transport the vessels to Sullom Mine, where dismantling would take
place.
``The consortium would need an export jetty for the metals in cargoes of around
20,000 tonnes and I would propose the use of 90m by 40m stone barges, which
could be moored to the head of the jetty, loaded, and then towed to the final
destination in Germany.''
Mr Osbond says the project would last for five years and create 100 full-time,
locally-recruited jobs.
He admits that the plan is ``environmentally sensitive'' but says a firm of
experts, Pell Frischman of Wakefield, would carry out anti-pollution control.
Shetland Island Council's chief executive, Mr Malcolm Green, said the council
received many unusual proposals and requests for help and considered them all
seriously.
However, the council's director of planning, Mr Jimmy Anderson, said the area
around the mine, two miles from the Sullom Voe terminal, was totally unsuited
for such a proposal.
``There are houses at the head of the jetty and if it was to be turned into a
breaker's yard for submarines, the disruption caused to people living there
would be unacceptable,'' he said.
A spokeswoman for the Ministry of Defence said officials believed there were
between 104 and 120 U-boats lying on the seabed over a wide area roughly 30
miles off the northern coast of Ireland.
</TEXT>
