<HEADLINE>`Good Samaritan' janitor smashed school windows in his bid to protect children School's safety row led to protest</HEADLINE>
<EDITION>1</EDITION>
<PAGE>7</PAGE>
<GRAPHIC>photograph</GRAPHIC>
<RECORDNO>975208506</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
A Highland primary school janitor, who feared for the safety of 250 pupils,
smashed two dozen windows he thought were dangerous at his school, a court was
told yesterday.
A six-year-old girl had already been injured at Hilton primary school in
Inverness after falling through a pane of glass in a fire door.
The authorities had been warned about the ``accident waiting to happen'' at the
school by janitor John Angus McDonald.
The school refused to replace the windows with reinforced safety glass because
of insufficient funds, Inverness District Court heard yesterday.
McDonald, of Castle Heather Drive, Inverness, admitted vandalising 24 window
panes on March 12 this year. They were all single-glazed panes on doors and
fire exits.
Depute fiscal John Bamber said police were called when McDonald, a first
offender, was seen approaching the school with a hammer.
Defence agent Craig Wood said McDonald, who has since left his post, had
continually complained about the lack of reinforced windows in the school since
beginning the job last August.
Legislation introduced in 1992 requires all schools to replace ordinary glass
at low levels with toughened glass or safety panels by 1996.
In November last year, Theresa O'Donnell was rushed to hospital with serious
cuts. She required stitches to her face after a fire door smashed when she fell
against it.
Mr Wood said McDonald had approached headmaster Iain Telford before and after
the accident but was told there was not enough money to do anything about it.
``In a state of desperation, he just cracked and, as the good Samaritan, he
took the matter into his own hands and broke the windows.
``He thought this would bring the matter to the authorities immediate
attention. ''
Mr Wood said: ``McDonald did this for the best of reasons.''
Highland Regional Council yesterday confirmed that all windows had since been
replaced with toughened glass.They added: ``He is no longer employed by us. Mr
Alistair Mathieson JP admitted the case was ``an unusual one'' and deferred
sentence on McDonald for 12 months for good behaviour.
Mr McDonald refused to comment after the case, but Theresa's mother, Elizabeth
of 17 Kildonan Crescent, Inverness said: ``John did what hundreds of mothers
wanted to do. His action has probably prevented another child being hurt.
Unfortunately, it came too late to stop my daughter being injured.''
Mrs O'Donnel was angered to learn that the authorities knew of McDonald's
complaints before Theresa's accident.
``It is so infuriating. It just makes me even more determined to win
compensation from the council for Theresa's injuries.''
</TEXT>
