<HEADLINE>Private detectives checked on Wests</HEADLINE>
<EDITION>3</EDITION>
<PAGE>4</PAGE>
<RECORDNO>975208507</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
GLOUCESTERSHIRE social services used private detectives to check up on
Frederick and Rosemary West while their children were in care, it emerged
yesterday.
The detectives were used in 1993 by the council, which was concerned that the
couple were breaching a court order preventing unsupervised contact with the
chidren.
A detective agency provided information which helped social services return to
court to enforce the order, said a spokesman.
He said it was not unusual to employ private detectives in certain cases.
``This is an example of the many steps taken by the county council to protect
the children,'' he added.
The Wests' five younger children were taken into care in August 1992 by social
services, following allegations of abuse.
In July 1993, the Wests walked free from court - their trial on abuse
allegations abandoned when two witnesses declined to give evidence.
However, the younger children remained in care and the police investigation
began that led to the discovery of the Cromwell Street killings.
Gloucestershire County Council said yesterday the West children were put on the
At Risk Register in 1992. They were not on it previously.
</TEXT>
