<HEADLINE>Dounreay poll called a fraud</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>By DAVID ROSS Highland Correspondent</BYLINE>
<EDITION>1</EDITION>
<PAGE>6</PAGE>
<RECORDNO>975208508</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
A FORTHCOMING referendum on reprocessing foreign nuclear waste at Dounreay was
yesterday described by Caithness and Sutherland MP Robert Maclennan as an
attempted fraud, largely orchestrated by outside groups.
The poll will be conducted by the independent Electoral Reform Ballot Services
and a result is expected in the middle of next month. It will be paid for
through a public appeal organised by Caithness Against Nuclear Dumping.
Mr Maclennan said: ``This so-called referendum is nothing of the sort. It is a
device mounted in Caithness, backed, if not suggested, by Greenpeace, as one
shot in a long campaign to close Dounreay.
``Unlike a proper referendum this poll can decide nothing as its outside
backers know perfectly well. What the poll could do, however, is damage the
prospects of Dounreay maintaining a role as a scientific centre employing
directly over 1000 people.
``If they were honest about it, the poll promoters would say that they want to
see Dounreay mothballed. Instead, they claim to be targeting only the proposal
to use Dounreay's expertise in research reactor fuel reprocessing to win new
international contracts. They know Dounreay has safely developed these
world-leading skills over 30 years. They know every step in the process has to
be approved by independent scientific regulators.''
Mr Maclennan said that the referendum's organisers knew that Dounreay would
send the waste back to the country of origin; that the movements of such
materials had been safely handled under strict regulation for decades.
``But they also know that the way finally to close down Dounreay is to chip
away at the remaining work which can support the Dounreay site; first imported
fuel reprocessing then all nuclear reprocessing.
``This poll is supported by cynical, manipulating lobbyists who have made their
own careers out of trying to inflate fear of science. These lobbyists did not
seek the backing of any locally elected representatives for their action.
``I hope their so-called referendum is seen for what it is, an attempted fraud
on the public.''
Cand's secretary, Mrs Marjory MacKenzie, said last night: ``Does Robert
Maclennan really think that the people of Caithness are so intellectually
wanting that they could be led by the nose by an outside group?.
``We got a donation of #3000 from Greenpeace and it was very welcome, and we
said thank you. That was the sum total of our contact with the group. The idea
grew out of a public meeting on October 16 which was attended by four
councillors and Dounreay representatives. Mr Maclennan didn't manage to attend.
``If the people of Caithness think we are stupid, they will tell us so when
they answer a question that has been agreed as balanced by the Electoral Reform
Ballot Services. They wouldn't have accepted it, had it not been balanced.''
</TEXT>
</DOC>
