<DATE>951125</DATE>
<HEADLINE>Lang goes on attack</HEADLINE>
<EDITION>1</EDITION>
<PAGE>6</PAGE>
<RECORDNO>975208509</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
PRESIDENT of the Board of Trade Ian Lang last night launched one of the
strongest attacks so far on Labour's constitutional plans for Scotland.
The former Scottish Secretary said they would be immensely damaging and added:
``From my new Cabinet position, it now is clearer to me than ever that the
Scottish economy is inextricably linked with the wider British economy.''
Mr Lang, speaking in Penrith, said that was why it was vital that businesses
had a level playing field, not one sloped against them because of a separate
parliament imposing rules and regulations that would consign them to a
different division.
Mr Lang argued that would be the consequence of Labour's proposals for a
tax-raising parliament in Edinburgh, adding that Labour's plans would ``totally
neglect the needs of the Scottish economy, Scottish business, and Scottish
jobs''.
Mr Lang added: ``The way forward must be to continue to build on the strengths
of our constitution, not to undermine them by creating a separate parliament in
Edinburgh.''
</TEXT>
