<DOCNO>GH951125-000061</DOCNO>
<DOCID>GH951125-000061</DOCID>
<DATE>951125</DATE>
<HEADLINE>MP defends New Zealand mission</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>By ALISON DANIELS</BYLINE>
<EDITION>1</EDITION>
<PAGE>6</PAGE>
<RECORDNO>975208510</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
THE cost of a Scottish Affairs Committee mission to New Zealand as part of a
study of Scottish agriculture has been exaggerated, it was claimed yesterday by
one of the MPs who was unable to join nine colleagues for the 12-day trip.
Liberal Democrat MP Ray Michie said estimates that it could cost the taxpayer
#50,000 were inaccurate. Her remarks were backed up by a Scottish Affairs
Committee spokeswoman who said the total cost could be calculated only at its
conclusion.
The trip, whose participants include three English MPs, has been widely
criticised in Westminster coming just weeks after the Commons agreed to tighter
controls on MPs' behaviour.
Although committee staff were reluctant to give details for ``security
reasons'', it emerged that the group, led by Kilmarnock and Louden MP Willie
McKelvey, will spend five days visiting beef, dairy, and sheep farms in the
Wellington area. They will also tour a vineyard and visit fruit producers.
On Monday, the MPs will spend the day with the High Commission being briefed by
agriculture officials on animal welfare and other farming issues. The MPs will
spend their first two days at the four-star James Cooke Centra Hotel in
Wellington which charges $235 (#100) a night for a single room.
Ms Michie and Mr Allan Stewart, Tory MP for Eastwood, both turned down the
opportunity to join the fact-finding mission. Ms Michie said she had been
unable to go because of prior constituency commitments.
On the cost of the trip, Ms Michie said: ``I really don't know, I'm afraid. I
understand what is printed in the papers is incorrect.''
</TEXT>
