<DATE>951125</DATE>
<HEADLINE>Battle for Govan intensifies</HEADLINE>
<EDITION>1</EDITION>
<PAGE>6</PAGE>
<GRAPHIC>Photograph</GRAPHIC>
<RECORDNO>975208511</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
THE bitter battle for Labour's Govan parliamentary nomination has intensified
following a victory for Mr Mohammed Sarwar, over Mr Mike Watson MP, in the
Pollokshields/Kingston branch.
Mr Sarwar took the branch nomination by 62-11, having earlier failed to win
at Govan/Drumoyne and Langside/Shawlands.
Across the three branches, Mr Sarwar polled more votes.
However, Mr Watson has 50 nominations from union branches and affiliate
organisations while Mr Sarwar has just four.
Mr Watson has also won the Govan Constituency executive nomination.
The final membership vote takes place on December 14.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO>GH951125-000063</DOCNO>
<DOCID>GH951125-000063</DOCID>
<DATE>951125</DATE>
<HEADLINE>Accent on West Coast line</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>Stuart Trotter</BYLINE>
<EDITION>1</EDITION>
<PAGE>6</PAGE>
<ARTICLETYPE>feature</ARTICLETYPE>
<FLAG>commons sketch</FLAG>
<RECORDNO>975208512</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
ALL statements to the effect that Transport Secretary Sir George Young is not
interested in the West Coast main line are, from here on, inoperative.
We can reveal that he travels on it regularly. Only two weeks ago, he was in
the cab of a train from Birmingham to Coventry and visited a signal box where,
we are informed, the technology was extremely modern.
Sir George was allowed to make a station announcement at the signal box which,
he said, was widely commended for its clarity. He blew things rather, however,
by adding that ``the absence of a Birmingham accent may have confused some
passengers''.
MPs' sleaze bonus
THE Grim Reaper is moving in. A recent survey shows increased levels of
emotional stress being experienced by MPs. Among the main symptoms were a
tendency to eat, drink, or smoke too much (45%), tiredeness or exhaustion
(44%), a declined interest in sex (38%), lack of sleep (37%), and indigestion/
sickness (21%).
Followers of the Nolan Committee and its recommendations may be interested in
the following: ``MPs who spent more than 10, and in some cases 30 hours, in a
work role outside of parliamentary life, experienced significantly lower
physical stress levels than colleagues similarly engaged for less.''
Root of the question
TREMENDOUS concern at the number of English MPs tabling Scottish Questions. Ten
of the first 20 questions put down for Scottish Question Time in the House on
Wednesday, came from such well-known Scots as Anthony Steen (South Hams), Harry
Greenway (Ealing North), and Lady Olga Maitland (Sutton and Cheam).
Scottish Secretary Michael Forsyth insists that as we have a UK Parliament,
there is every reason for English MPs to take an interest in Scottish affairs.
Others, such as the Liberal Democrats' Ray Michie, reckon this is a classic
example of why a Scottish parliament is required to ensure that Scottish issues
are properly discussed by the representatives of Scottish constituencies. Even
more, perhaps, for Mr Forsyth to sort it out on St Andrew's Day.
Convenient legacy
SCOTLAND'S heritage is being heavily debated these days, with Mr Gordon
Prentice, Labour MP for Pendle, anxious to know what measures the Secretary of
State will take to ensure the structure and fabric of historic buildings in
Scotland is properly preserved.
He wants traditional slate and stone quarries reopened so the materials can be
used once again.
Even that may not be enough for Labour colleague Brian Wilson, MP for
Cunninghame North, who suggested in the House that a physical memorial should
be erected to the poll tax and argued, for some reason, that a derelict public
toilet in Stirling could be adapted for the purpose.
Home-brew fears
OVER to their lordships, where we learn terrible things about what the imports
from Europe of alcoholic drinks are doing to our domestic trade. According to
Lord Mackay of Ardbrecknish, Customs estimates that beer imports are equivalent
to about #130m, though the industry puts the figure at nearer #367m. Beer
drinkers will be interested to note that during questions on the subject,
Labour peer Lord Peston said it was a matter of the ``utmost gravity......''
Treasury views crash
GENUINE commiserations to Treasury Chief Secretary William Waldegrave, whose
brand new ministerial car was written off in a collision in Whitehall. Never
mind, there'll be another one along in a minute.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
