<HEADLINE>Customers only</HEADLINE>
<EDITION>1</EDITION>
<PAGE>14</PAGE>
<ARTICLETYPE>Correspondence</ARTICLETYPE>
<RECORDNO>975208513</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
OUNCILLOR Anderson is quite correct in what she notes about the status of
Scottish banknotes (November 22).
The Clydesdale Bank cash dispenser at Glasgow Airport has for some considerable
time been supplying Bank of England notes to its customers rather than their
own notes. I can well imagine their explanation as regards the needs and
experiences of travellers using the service as they pass through the airport to
far-flung places.
I cannot, however, imagine any logical explanation, that might satisfy me at
least, that the Bank of Scotland might care to offer about a sign which I
witnessed in their East Kilbride branch. The notice intimated that the business
tellers could supply Bank of England notes only to customers. Why?
Iain Hutchison,
14 Fleurs Crescent,
Erskine.
</TEXT>
