<DOC>
<DOCNO>GH951125-000065</DOCNO>
<DOCID>GH951125-000065</DOCID>
<DATE>951125</DATE>
<HEADLINE>Junior Chamber congress</HEADLINE>
<EDITION>1</EDITION>
<PAGE>14</PAGE>
<ARTICLETYPE>Correspondence</ARTICLETYPE>
<RECORDNO>975208514</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
THE 50th World Congress of Junior Chamber International was held in Glasgow
between 4 and 11 November 1995. The event, held in a different location
throughout the world each year is the annual meeting of Junior Chamber
International and attracts young business people to a week of business,
training, and social events.
On behalf of the congress organising committee I would like to thank everyone
in Glasgow and surrounding areas for their support and encouragement which
enabled the event to be hosted by our city. Not only did Glasgow Junior Chamber
of Commerce receive considerable support from the public sector but we also
received support from both large and small companies in the private sector.
This is not only appreciated but was essential for the event to be staged.
More than 4200 delegates from over 100 countries throughout the world attended
the congress making it the largest world congress ever held in Europe.
Glasgow can be proud of the feedback from the delegates. The city demonstrated
its true culture with many delegates commenting on the friendliness of the
people in the city and the feeling of personal safety both during the day and
evenings. Delegates were also amazed at the architectural beauty of the city
and the spectacular surrounding scenery.
The city, its business, businesses in the surrounding area, and Glasgow
citizens can be proud of the achievement in representing Glasgow and Scotland
to an international audience in a way which delegates will positively remember.
Duncan Tannahill,
Chairman,
Congress Organising
Committee,
21 West George Street,
Glasgow.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO>GH951125-000066</DOCNO>
<DOCID>GH951125-000066</DOCID>
<DATE>951125</DATE>
<HEADLINE>Bitter pills of an old killjoy Profile / THE BUDGET</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>William Russell</BYLINE>
<EDITION>1</EDITION>
<PAGE>13</PAGE>
<ARTICLETYPE>Profile</ARTICLETYPE>
<GRAPHIC>Cartoon</GRAPHIC>
<RECORDNO>975208515</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
LONG-WINDED, a notorious killjoy with an aversion to alcohol and a definite
down on motorists, given to using highly technical language, with few friends
at the outset of its annual public appearance, and even fewer by the end, the
Budget has had a long and chequered life. It is subjected each year to violent
verbal abuse from whoever is in Opposition at the time, is invariably the cause
of a financial crisis in the City, not to mention fiscal despair in the living
rooms of the land, and considered by all to be more political pie in the sky
than pounds in the pocket when it comes to tax cuts.
It is also afflicted, from time to time, with what one could call fiscal
incontinence. The Budget leaks. The recent change from being a springtime, hey
nonny, nonny non-event, to a product of the season of mists and mellow
fruitfulness has done it little good. Nor has the fact that its current
begetter, the present Chancellor of the Exchequer, the Hush Puppy one, released
from the Trappist vows which bound his successors, never seemed to stop talking
in the run-up to its delivery this week. The hush of yesteryear, which started
immediately after Christmas, has never seemed so desirable.
The Budget as we know it was born in 1733, its name being derived from
bougette, the French for a little bag. A satirical pamphlet about William Pitt
the Elder, then Prime Minister and Chancellor of the Exchequer, contained a
cartoon showing the great man as a quack doctor opening his bag - or budget -
containing pills and potions, and the joke stuck.
The Budget had, of course, existed long before that because throughout history
the books of state have always had to be balanced - or cooked. The first known
attempt to draw up a proper balance sheet was made in 1362 under Edward III
and, as is always the case, once the accountants had their foot in the door
there was no stopping them. They took over.
The financial statement was originally delivered on Lady Day, March 25, but in
1754, when the calendar was changed, the date was moved to April 6. Thereafter,
give or take a week or two, the Budget was delivered some time in March or
April until two years ago when its birthday was moved to the autumn. The Budget
speech usually consists of two parts: a resume of the economic situation, which
the Commons listens to as best it can, since hardly anybody, including, on
occasion, the Chancellor, knows what the man is talking about, followed by a
detailed list of the measures to be introduced to raise the money needed to
keep the Government going.
This is the bit which everyone awaits with bated breath. Will the price of
wines, spirits, and beer go up? Will the cost of petrol rise? Will there be tax
cuts? Will the mega-rich end up being swinged, or will it be the poor who get
the pain? Will it be a Budget for All Seasons, a Drinkers' Budget, a Bash the
Motorist Budget, a House Owners' Budget, a Whack the Scroungers Budget, a Soak
the Rich Budget Until Their Pips Squeak as Denis Healey once threatened, or a
Bribe the Electorate Budget? Infinite is its variety.
Sometimes the process of delivery takes ages. Gladstone spoke for five hours in
1853, while in the present century the longest-winded Chancellor was Lloyd
George, who spoke for four hours 51 minutes in 1909, minus a 30-minute comfort
break, allegedly to rest his voice. Today the tendency is to keep it short,
probably little more than an hour in length, although sometimes it seems longer
than that because Chancellors are seldom among the great political orators. One
man's hour can seem a lifetime.
The Budget, a bit like Moses in the basket, is brought to the Commons in the
red despatch box first used by Gladstone in 1860, along with whatever tipple
the Chancellor of the day requires to help him get through the ordeal, because
delivering it requires fortitude. To steady their nerves, Chancellors are
allowed to take a drink of their choice to the Commons despatch box at which
the speech is delivered. Disraeli favoured brandy and water, the ascetic Sir
Stafford Cripps, who delivered Labour's austerity measures in 1948, 49, and 50,
pure water, although Hugh Gaitskell, who followed him, proved not all
socialists are killjoys, and delivered his 1951 Budget on a mixture of rum and
orange.
Derick Heathcoat-Amory, the Tory Chancellor in 1958, 59, and 60 sustained his
strength with a mixture of cold milk, honey, and rum, while Selwyn Lloyd, Tory
Chancellor in 1961 and 62, drank whisky. Denis Healey, Labour's long-serving
Chancellor, delivered his Budgets in 1974 (twice), 75, 76, 77, and 78 on
brandy, while James Callaghan, another Labour killjoy Chancellor, delivered his
in 1965, 66, and 67 on tonic water.
The Conservative water drinkers included John Major, 1990, Anthony Barber, 1972
and 73, Peter Thorneycroft, 1957, Rab Butler, 1952, 53, 54, and 55, and Harold
Macmillan, 1956. Nigel Lawson, 1985, 86, 87, 88, and 89, proved a man for all
seasons, starting off on Scotch and soda, but ending up on spritzers.
Although much remarked upon, the tipple seldom bears any resemblance to the
content of the Budget, teetotal Chancellors often letting alcohol off
scot-free, drinkers penalising it.
The delay in announcing tax changes - the speech normally starts at 3.30pm -
was to allow the Stock Exchange to close so that nobody made a killing. Budget
leaks are common, although ones with financial implications rare, the last of
any note coming when Hugh Dalton in 1947 inadvertently let slip something to an
evening paper journalist while making his way to the Chamber and had to resign.
Those were the days. Now politicians cling on like grim death whatever the
crime.
The Budget is sometimes genuinely controversial. The Opposition always pretends
it is for party political reasons, although they may be lying in their teeth
because sometimes it is exactly what they would do were they in power. Lloyd
George's 1909 Budget, which introduced the Land Tax, had the roughest ride in
living memory. During the ensuing debate the closure, that is a motion to
suspend the sitting of the House, was moved 106 times, and 549 divisions were
held. On that occasion the MPs spent 90 hours trudging through the division
lobbies. The Budget can be a hard task master.
It was a historic Budget for another reason. The Commons having done its worst,
the Lords went even further and threw it out by 350 votes to 75. This led to a
General Election and the passing in 1911 of the Parliament Act which destroyed
their lordships' power to veto legislation.
One of the wisest things said about the Budget was uttered by Iain Macleod, who
remarked he had rarely known one acclaimed in April that did not show signs of
coming apart by July. Winston Churchill, who delivered his Budgets in 1925, 26,
27, 28, and 29, said that whenever a Chancellor did something which was popular
he had probably done something unwise, and Nigel Lawson, whose Budgets are
listed above, said that anybody who became Chancellor to be popular had chosen
the wrong job, but then he was never popular in any job.
Norman Lamont called being Chancellor a humdrum activity, which could explain
his humdrum Budgets.
There have been many Chancellors, 19 since the end of the last war for
starters, of whom only Roy Jenkins is generally considered to have made a
success of the job, although, being an honest Chancellor, his refusal to buy
votes with golden promises may have cost Labour the 1970 General Election. He
was certainly the most literate, both in the literary and economic sense, made
the best speeches, and balanced the best books. His Budgets not only worked,
they were entertaining.
Sir Geoffrey Howe was considered the dullest - he got called a dead sheep by
his opposite number, Healey - although formidably competent. His Budgets also
worked. It was he who set up the Thatcherite state, not that she thanked him
for it. By common consent, the worst of all was Barber, not that it stopped him
getting a peerage or doing well thereafter in the City. It is not what you do
that counts, but who you know, and being a Budget-maker means you know lots of
people.
Next week's Budget has great expectations to live up to. Will it be a
tax-cutting Budget? As the poet said, if winter comes can spring be far behind?
For winter read tax cuts, for spring a General Election.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
