<DOCNO>GH951125-000067</DOCNO>
<DOCID>GH951125-000067</DOCID>
<DATE>951125</DATE>
<HEADLINE>Light and dark Scottish opinion should prevail</HEADLINE>
<EDITION>1</EDITION>
<PAGE>14</PAGE>
<ARTICLETYPE>Leader</ARTICLETYPE>
<RECORDNO>975208516</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
SUGGESTIONS about altering the hours of daytime are apt to put Scots in a
tizzy, especially the further north we find ourselves. In some ways nothing
much changes - any darkness lopped off one end of the day is simply re-attached
at the other. As it happens, however, Scots opinion prefers to find what light
there is in the morning rather than the evening, which explains the present
situation. Proposals to change this in Britain in the interest of European
business efficiency will make little headway, though the possibility that there
might be fewer accidents could be more compelling.
Actually the proponent of the change is ready to make an exception for Scotland
(and his readiness need not elicit any hostile response), but the fact is that
we hardly need European uniformity in this matter. The world's business
community is now active round the clock. Much of its activity is electronically
generated and is entirely independent of light or dark. The best-known example
is world stockmarkets which act continuously, responding when on stream (in
their local time, that is) to what has been happening elsewhere in their
darkness. Are other businesses much different in this age of computers?
Such questions can be tested in a living laboratory that is the United States,
which has managed a successful integrated economy across a continent of immense
geographic diversity, characterised by several distinct time zones. Nothing in
the American experience suggests that economic development has been inhibited
or adversely affected by this phenomenon which is considerably more significant
there than it would be here, simply because of the differences in scale.
Indeed, the main Scottish objections to the proposed change derive from what
are perceived as the unattractive social consequences of long, dark mornings,
especially in the far north and the far west. This view should prevail: it can
hardly be to its disadvantage that it is the popular one.
</TEXT>
