<DOC>
<DOCNO>GH951125-000069</DOCNO>
<DOCID>GH951125-000069</DOCID>
<DATE>951125</DATE>
<HEADLINE>Future role as ambassador</HEADLINE>
<EDITION>1</EDITION>
<PAGE>14</PAGE>
<ARTICLETYPE>Correspondence</ARTICLETYPE>
<RECORDNO>975208518</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
LIKE undoubtedly vast numbers of people across the nation and worldwide, I had
the opportunity to witness the Princess of Wales present one of the most candid
and I believe honest interviews I have ever had the occasion to experience.
I had been led to speculate in the course of media reports prior to the
interview that her standing and credibility in the eyes of the public might be
seriously and irrecoverably damaged.
In fact, I discovered a very articulate and sensitive lady who was utterly
convincing in her sincerity and remarkably honest concerning her personal life.
To discuss openly the most sensitive aspects of her personal feelings and
private life requires a courage which few of us possess and which we can admire
only from a distance.
I was left with the impression that far from being damaged, her reputation
could only be enhanced.
It is disgraceful that we, the public, in order to satisfy our curiosity,
should subject any human being, however popular or involved in public service,
to the extent of exposure given to the Prince and Princess of Wales. The result
of the pressure of constant and unrelenting media pressure is now clear for all
to see.
More remarkable still is the fact that despite her difficulties she remains
loyal to the Prince of Wales and very fair in her appraisal of the characters
involved.
The nation should be proud of this remarkable woman who I feel certain will
continue to receive public support.
She commented that she envisaged her future role as an ambassador for this
country. I would consider, given the extent of public interest and affection
openly shown to her, both abroad and at home, that this is a goal to which she
has already aspired and in which she has overwhelmingly succeeded.
Was she simply being characteristically modest? Could we hope for a better
ambassador? Perhaps the public will answer these questions for her in the
fullness of time.
Hugh O'Hare,
89 Aitken Road,
Hamilton.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO>GH951125-000070</DOCNO>
<DOCID>GH951125-000070</DOCID>
<DATE>951125</DATE>
<HEADLINE>Minister praises private road to success</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>By LYNNE ROBERTSON</BYLINE>
<EDITION>1</EDITION>
<PAGE>6</PAGE>
<RECORDNO>975208519</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
THE latest section of the A74 to be upgraded to motorway standard was opened
yesterday by Scottish Roads Minister Lord James Douglas-Hamilton.
Speaking at the ceremony on the stretch between Ecclefechan and Eaglesfield,
Lord James stressed the Government's commitment to upgrading the M6 and A74
economic artery in and out of Scotland.
He claimed the introduction of private finance into the trunk road programme
allowed projects to be completed earlier.
He pointed to the Skye bridge as an example of how private finance could
accelerate the roads programme.
``This introduction of private finance into the trunk-road programme has
allowed projects to come forward sooner than would otherwise be the case and
has brought with it the benefits of private-sector initiatives,'' he said.
The opening of the new motorway completes the southern section of the A74
upgrading programme, giving motorists more than 25 miles of continuous motorway
between Cleuchbrae and the Border.
He described the new section of motorway as ``a shining example'' of the
success of the design and build contract.
``As a result of the greater degree of design and construction innovation which
this form of contract affords, together with the contractors' increased
responsibility for project management, this project has been completed six
weeks ahead of schedule at the tendered price and with no claims,'' said Lord
James, who revealed that a dedicated cycleway was to be developed over the
length of the A74 as part of a #5m initiative.
The Roads Minister also said tenders would be sought next summer to upgrade the
Baillieston to Newhouse ``missing link'' of the M8 between Glasgow and
Edinburgh to motorway standard.
Lord James also said that congestion at one of Scotland's greatest bottlenecks
would be eased when the M8 extension project between Newbridge and the
Edinburgh city bypass was opened in two weeks' time.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO>GH951125-000071</DOCNO>
<DOCID>GH951125-000071</DOCID>
<DATE>951125</DATE>
<HEADLINE>Old turkeys for festive television</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>Allan Laing</BYLINE>
<EDITION>1</EDITION>
<PAGE>13</PAGE>
<ARTICLETYPE>feature</ARTICLETYPE>
<GRAPHIC>photograph</GRAPHIC>
<RECORDNO>975208520</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
DON'T hold your breath for cutting-edge television this Christmas. There will
be more turkeys on the box than there will be on the table. Bah humbug would
appear to be the order of the day. The week. Maybe even the month. Indeed,
there is good reason to believe that Britain may finally have seen the end of
the once-familiar TV excellence over the festive season.
Though the complete schedules have yet to be announced, early indications
suggest that the terrestrial channels have had not only a humour bypass but a
lobotomy to that part of the brain which controls the imagination. There is a
deep and depressing sense of deja vu.
Once upon a time Christmas wasn't Christmas until you had the family squabble
over what to watch. Clearly times have changed. In the interests of happy
families, perhaps, they've made television so anodyne this year that no-one
will argue over choice. That's because there is none.
The truth is that the good old days, when TV channels saved their big guns for
the Christmas and New Year period, are well and truly over. There was a time
when the schedulers would store a special Minder or a Morse or a Spender in a
bid to win the seasonal ratings battle. Not any more. Now it makes sound
financial sense to show them on a wet winter Wednesday night - that way they
get higher viewing figures and a bigger return on their advertising profits as
a consequence.
Behind this change in strategy is the realisation that people, particularly
young people, have better things to do with their time on Christmas Day than
sit glued to the box.
Think about it. Not so long ago, you could look forward to a decent first-run
movie to keep you occupied as you picked the turkey bones. But thanks to the
video rental boom, we've all seen every film we ever wanted to. There is no
longer such a thing as a Big Movie premiere on television.
Believe it or not, people have become more sophisticated, less slavishly
devoted to the four main terrestrial channels. They have a far greater choice
of home entertainment. In addition to video, there's satellite and cable. Then
there's computer games, CD-Roms, and even the more traditional board games
vying for our attention on Christmas Day. Some folk have even discovered that
it's good to talk.
So this year television appears to have thrown in the towel. We cannot yet pass
judgment on BBC1's choice of Christmas Day movies (not Mary Poppins again,
surely) because they've yet to be announced, but ITV has hardly pushed the boat
out with Ghostbusters II in the afternoon and Sister Act in the evening.
Elsewhere, it's round up the usual subjects. How's this for an inspiring list
of programmes on BBC1? Top of the Pops, Last of the Summer Wine, Eastenders,
and - at the prime time of 6.40pm, mark you - a programme of favourite clips,
chosen by Mike Yarwood (who's he, dad?), of ``classic highlights'' from
Christmas past. Haud me back. You have to wait until almost 10pm before you
find a programme worth watching (a one-off special episode of One Foot in the
Grave).
ITV is equally predictable. Coronation Street and, well, Coronation Street.
Surely some mistake? Sadly not. There's a half-hour episode at lunchtime and
then an hour-long ``bonus'' edition at 7pm. Clearly, the imagination factory's
assembly line has been working overtime at Granada. Ah, but there's always
Robson and Jerome. Who they? They're the two actors from Soldier, Soldier
who've been given their own 30-minute murderalongasong show on Christmas night.
Still, there's BBC2 and Channel Four for intellectual stimulation and fearless
programming. Then again, perhaps not. Both stations appear to have lost their
bottle. They have their moments (a two-hour recording of La Boheme, a screening
of Kenneth Branagh's Much Ado About Nothing, and ageing pop star Phil Collins
performing Unplugged on BBC2; Blur in Concert and almost three hours of John
Osborne's last work, England, My England, on C4 but the rest is pretty boring
and predictable.
Boxing Day television is little better (Eastenders, Generation Game, Christmas
in Emmerdale and Michael Barrymore). Maybe it's worse, when you come to think
about it.
Highlights? Difficult one. There are a couple of promising dramas later in the
week on ITV (Circles of Deceit, a two-hour thriller starring Dennis Waterman as
an ex-SAS man working for a secret government department, and McCallum, a
one-off pilot from STV featuring John Hannah as a forensic pathologist). After
that, you're struggling. There's always the New Year, but that's another sad
story. Anyone got a Trivial Pursuits game I can borrow?
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO>GH951125-000072</DOCNO>
<DOCID>GH951125-000072</DOCID>
<DATE>951125</DATE>
<HEADLINE>Access to forests</HEADLINE>
<EDITION>1</EDITION>
<PAGE>14</PAGE>
<ARTICLETYPE>Correspondence</ARTICLETYPE>
<RECORDNO>975208521</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
WE deplore the attack of the Scottish Landowners Federation on local
authorities which fail to negotiate access agreements when Forestry Commission
woods are sold (November 18).
The blame lies with the Government not local authorities for continuing with a
forestry disposals policy in the absence of any effective arrangements to
safeguard public access.
The Government's model access agreement allows the new private landowner the
right to close the former FC wood for up to six months of the year, every year,
for pest control, management, and conservation reasons.
The agreement even allows the new owner to open the wood for one day and then
reimpose another six-month ban. Why should local authorities spend their scarce
resources on such a silly system?
Why should Scottish Natural Heritage or local enterprise companies risk grant
assistance on access facilities in such woods when access security is so weak?
The SLF is also wrong in claiming there is no loss of access after sale. In
1993 the Ramblers' Association undertook a consultation exercise with over 100
owners of former FC woods in Britain, asking if they still supported the
freedom to roam policy that operated under FC ownership.
Fewer than one in five of the new owners replied to confirm that this was still
their access policy.
In Sweden privatisation of the state forest service has been proceeding without
controversy. This is because in Sweden, and many other European countries, the
public has a right of access to all state and private forests. Transfer of
ownership does not lead to loss of access.
If the Secretary of State for Scotland wants to continue selling our forests he
needs new access legislation, not more bureaucratic and ineffective access
agreements.
Dave Morris,
Scottish Officer,
Ramblers' Association,
Crusader House,
Haig Business Park,
Markinch,
Fife.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO>GH951125-000073</DOCNO>
<DOCID>GH951125-000073</DOCID>
<DATE>951125</DATE>
<HEADLINE>Effluent washed up by the tide of free speech</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>Stewart Lamont</BYLINE>
<EDITION>1</EDITION>
<PAGE>14</PAGE>
<ARTICLETYPE>Features</ARTICLETYPE>
<RECORDNO>975208522</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
THERE is a curious and paradoxical thing happening in our country with regard
to free speech. In many respects there has never been so much of it about. Gone
are the days when the press barons would conspire with the Establishment to
hide uncomfortable facts about the monarchy.
We can hardly hold that view in a week in which the treasonable conduct of the
former King Edward VIII was exposed once and for all, and the peekaboo Princess
flung open the doors of the royal bedchamber.
Free speech has become so established that not only may the cat look at the
king, she may claim the right to scratch his eyes out in public.
This principle has been adopted by a number of radio and television
interviewers who seem to believe that politeness towards those who stumble into
their studios in the early morning or late evening is as anathema to them as it
would be for the cat to shake hands with a mouse which has invaded his
territory. These supercilious people do not so much think themselves equal with
the public figures they are questioning - they seem to think they have a right
to be rude.
The tide of free speech has brought many gains but it contains much effluent.
Trash TV, the dramas which rely on four-letter words as a symbol of
``realism'', the frantic pursuit of values which invert the cosy middle-class
world which the newsreels used to pretend was Britain. Mrs Whitehouse has
turned into Dame Edna, and Mr Pastry into Sir Les Patterson.
It is easy to lament this situation, and easier still to appear rather foostie
and puritanical in doing so. What worries me is not the extension of freedom of
speech but the unwillingness to extend it far enough.
At present we have a situation in which public figures are criticised,
miscalled, investigated, scrutinised, ridiculed. This is usually justified on
the grounds of either: free speech; the public has a right to know; nobody
should enjoy rights denied to the general public.
I have no quarrel with any of these but my point is that we have now reached a
situation in which free speech is being denied to public figures; and in which
``the right to know'' is being extended to matters which the general public
would vehemently dispute if applied to themselves instead of the easy target of
public figures.
Some recent examples. Claire Short MP tried to answer honestly a question about
the use of cannabis and she found that there are limits to free speech for
politicians. Ditto Nicholas Soames MP, and friend of Prince Charles, who gave a
candid response to the Dianarama programme within minutes of transmission. His
comments were immediately used as grounds for his resignation. If ever there
were cases of failure to address the real issues, it is the pillorying of these
two people.
Paint was recently thrown over the Tory party chairman as he entered
Parliament. The issue immediately became the response time of the police, not
the yobbish behaviour of the assailant.
In the coming days we will be treated to the sight of postal workers picketing
in their industrial dispute. How will they use their free speech? Will it be to
persuade, to demonstrate the strength of their case - or will it be to
intimidate and frustrate the rights of others? We shall see, but I suspect that
we will see many examples of the ``ordinary man'' acting in ways he would be
the first to condemn in politicians.
My sympathy is for politicians of all parties. Most media persons who write and
broadcast about them derive income from a variety of sources, yet are never
asked to disclose their private finances.
It is perfectly proper that the parliamentary question system should not be
able to be bought, nor that MPs should be in hawk to business or trade union
interests, but there are provisions to prevent this and the idea that MPs
should make total disclosure of their financial affairs is only fair if it is
made universal.
It is then we see how absurd it is. TV interviewers made to disclose their
share portfolio before interviewing industrialists? Lawyers made to open their
driving licence before representing clients on motoring offences? Teachers made
to state their religion before applying for certain posts? (Come to think of it
. . .)
The ordinary citizen would not tolerate for a moment the kind of intrusion into
his private life which is the everyday stuff of politics. If there are
fundamental rights of free speech and freedom of information then they must
apply across the board.
If I have a right to know how much the Tory Party chairman pays for
dry-cleaning his suits, or George Galloway for buying his, should I not have
the right to know how much Jimmy McSwachle is getting in social security for
his bidie-in and their brood of illegitimate children? The money in both cases
comes from the state - so why should we not all be told? This whole issue is
not about free speech at all. It is about a seachange in our society, a swing
of the pendulum from elitism to egalitarianism. It is about snobbery being
supplanted by inverted snobbery, and a lowest common denominator in values.
The only way to achieve a proper balance is by the Golden Rule - by treating
others as we would wish to be treated by them. It won't reclaim a lot of the
ground that has been lost, but it would be kindlier to politicians and royalty.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO>GH951125-000074</DOCNO>
<DOCID>GH951125-000074</DOCID>
<DATE>951125</DATE>
<HEADLINE>Business grants</HEADLINE>
<EDITION>1</EDITION>
<PAGE>14</PAGE>
<ARTICLETYPE>Correspondence</ARTICLETYPE>
<RECORDNO>975208523</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
AS there has been no denial published since Mr Andrew T Bell's letter in The
Herald (November 11), is it fair to assume the accuracy of his claim of
Kwik-Fit Insurance Services being given a grant of #2.5m? Mr Bell is astounded.
Many of your readers will share his astonishment.
The insurance market is finite and there are already too many chasing business,
some employing aggressive indiscriminate selling methods and ensnaring the
unwary, so why a grant to a parent company not content with what it was created
to do, viz, the fitting of exhausts and tyres?
A newcomer to insurance will inevitably result in enticing both insured and
staff from established companies. How can this possibly justify a grant and of
such magnitude?
Let the shoemaker stick to his last and if there are indeed resources available
for grants then such should be given to the deserving, of which there are
indeed many. Swan Hunter was a supreme example of need and yet its cry for less
than #1m went unheeded, with the consequence of the loss of a skilled workforce
and, nearer home, the shameful disregard shown to Rosyth Naval Dockyard.
The creation of largely part-time clerical jobs is not what is needed in
Lanarkshire in particular, it is creative work by its skilled artisans employed
full time.
E J Hart,
Camis Eskan Coachhouse,
Helensburgh.
</TEXT>
