<DOC>
<DOCNO>GH951125-000075</DOCNO>
<DOCID>GH951125-000075</DOCID>
<DATE>951125</DATE>
<HEADLINE>Housing prospects Chancellor under pressure</HEADLINE>
<EDITION>1</EDITION>
<PAGE>14</PAGE>
<ARTICLETYPE>Leader</ARTICLETYPE>
<RECORDNO>975208524</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
THE housing market has been so dismal these past five years that the very
notion of its recovery must invite scepticism. Yet, although its plight this
time down has been unusually severe, housing has long had a cyclical nature
with several marked booms since 1945 followed by periods of relative decline or
stagnation, whose real nature has previously been disguised by inflation. This
time the inflationary mask has slipped - and the damage is seen to have been
done, and suffered, with re-possessions and negative equity, not to mention the
assaults on mortgage tax relief. Given the importance of this experience for
Tory electoral chances, it is no wonder that the Chancellor is under immense
pressure to try to make modest amends next week.
He will not want to do so. His Treasury advisers have long been anxious to
reduce, even to end if possible, the whole business of mortgage tax relief.
They will not want to relent now, though back bench Tory MPs have very
different views given their exposure to irate constituents. In fact, it may be
possible for Ken Clarke to do nothing next week yet still preside over a
recovery in the housing market. Anything he does do may simply speed up
developments already underway, according to one reputable specialist forecaster
with a City bank, who believes that the market will recover from the middle of
next year to end up 2%, and be 6% better in 1997, and another 9% better the
following year.
That would be great news for mortgage payers; the drawback for the Tories is
evident in the dates. The recovery will certainly precede the next General
Election, yet its main effect will be felt in the two following years when Tony
Blair could be ensconced in Downing Street. But possibly anticipation could be
enough to encourage some resurgence in Tory fortunes. Lower interest rates
would help but the only other ammunition in the Chancellor's locker is the
abolition of stamp duty on house purchase. There is a good case for its
retention - private housing attracts no taxation since the abolition of
Schedule E, but if Mr Clarke has to make a gesture, Stamp Duty, or its loss,
could provide it.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO>GH951125-000076</DOCNO>
<DOCID>GH951125-000076</DOCID>
<DATE>951125</DATE>
<HEADLINE>Power of a poem that has touched the nation</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>Jennifer Cunningham</BYLINE>
<EDITION>1</EDITION>
<PAGE>13</PAGE>
<ARTICLETYPE>Features</ARTICLETYPE>
<RECORDNO>975208525</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
Do not stand at my grave and weep;
I am not there. I do not sleep.
I am a thousand winds that blow.
I am the diamond glints on snow.
I am the gentle autumn's rain.
When you awaken in the morning's hush,
I am the swift uplifting rush
Of quiet birds in circled flight.
I am the soft stars that shine at night.
Do not stand at my grave and cry;
I am not there. I did not die.
IT HAS become the most popular poem in Britain, although it has probably been
around for the best part of a century and its author is unknown. An 11-line
verse, almost certainly originally 12 with the fifth or sixth now missing, has
been requested by more than 10,000 people after it was broadcast on BBC
television's Bookworm programme on Remembrance Sunday.
What should we make of this, hot on the tail of equally sudden popularity for
Auden's Funeral Blues following Four Weddings and a Funeral?
The professor cautions us not to jeer, notes the five and a half couplets
instead of six, and points to the sincerity of the emotion. The poet says: ``In
a funeral context, the voice of the dead person is what people want to hear.
The poetry promoter says: ``It hits the spot.'' The literary theologian
dismisses it as Disneyland Wordsworth. Usually-cynical colleagues pronounce it
``good'' even ``beautiful'', but please don't read it at my funeral.
Its new status is directly attributable to a young soldier with a fondness for
poetry. In 1989, 24-year-old Lance Bombardier Stephen Cummins was killed by an
IRA landmine in Londonderry. Shortly before that he had sent his parents a
sealed envelope to be opened in the event of his death. It contained a copy of
the poem, which was read at his funeral.
It was also read three years ago at the funeral of Rachel Nickell, the young
mother murdered on Wimbledon Common and at the memorial service on the 25th
anniversary of Marilyn Monroe's death in 1987.
Such enormous enthusiasm for reading a poem at funerals which was not only not
Christian but specifically at odds with Christian doctrine refuted any claim
that we might live in a vestigially Christian society, according to the Rev Dr
David Jasper of the Centre for the Study of Literature and Theology at Glasgow
University. Admitting that his honest opinion gave him a bad conscience because
so many people were apparently drawing comfort from it, he nevertheless said:
``I personally see it as a sad comment on an inability to contemplate the
reality of the world we live in. This pastiche of Romantic pantheism offers
such fragile comfort that it may leave them with greater pain.''
His colleague in the Department of English Literature, Professor Philip
Hobsbaum, recognised that the sentiment had immediate popular appeal. ``What
this poem does is trigger an emotion that is already there. When reading it
this morning, I was reminded irresistibly of a very dear friend of mine who
committed suicide three years ago. At such times if we can find something
written by someone else expressing these emotions it is a great consolation.
``I do not jeer at these things. They are very sincere and people reach out
through them. There are a lot of reasons why people want to be propped up and
edified when things are going against you. This does not create anything new or
open up new territory. Once people do start reading poetry, they will go on. I
do not mind where people start as long as they go on to read new things,'' he
said.
At St Andrews, one of the few professors to produce as well as study poetry,
Douglas Dunn, said: ``It has a gentle, but positive voice, is very direct, full
of imperatives. It is interesting that it took a television broadcast to bring
this to people's attention. A lot of people no longer read poetry, it is not
taught in schools in the way it used to be, but they do associate metaphor with
poetry and that is what they want; they do not want poetry to be written in
everyday language.''
Tessa Ransford, director of the Scottish Poetry Library, confirmed that many
people sought comfort from poetry at a time of bereavement and often went on to
become regular readers of poetry.
``People want something which speaks to them directly and simply,'' said
Christopher Meade, director of the Poetry Society, who believes that the
British public is hungry for poetry.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO>GH951125-000077</DOCNO>
<DOCID>GH951125-000077</DOCID>
<DATE>951125</DATE>
<HEADLINE>The last post?</HEADLINE>
<EDITION>1</EDITION>
<PAGE>14</PAGE>
<ARTICLETYPE>Correspondence</ARTICLETYPE>
<RECORDNO>975208526</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
THE striking postal workers should sort themselves out lest they join the
dinosaurs into extinction. I have enjoyed the past few days without junk-mail.
Any important correspondence has reached me by fax - and perhaps the stimulus
of this strike will further develop the fax ethos which took root in the last
major postal strike.
I am missing a few cheques and my recent income tax payment is languishing in a
sorting office somewhere, but with a little more encouragement from the postal
workers BACS and other electronic systems will flourish. And my Christmas tip
to the postman will become redundant.
T S Mann,
Crofthill,
30 Drymen Road,
Bearsden.
</TEXT>
