<DOC>
<DOCNO>GH951125-000078</DOCNO>
<DOCID>GH951125-000078</DOCID>
<DATE>951125</DATE>
<HEADLINE>The modern world</HEADLINE>
<EDITION>1</EDITION>
<PAGE>14</PAGE>
<ARTICLETYPE>Correspondence</ARTICLETYPE>
<RECORDNO>975208527</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
IN her article on the media coverage of the West case, Margaret Vaughan asks
the question: ``Should we expect the real world to be sealed off from the world
of imagination?'' (November 23).
What I observe in today's materialistic culture are scores of examples of an
``unreal world'' being presented (or sold) to people's senses.
The world of sexual abuse, murder, violence, rape, etc, would be received by
the general public more readily if our modern culture were not so riddled with
ugly, unreal, unwholesome things such as junk food, bad housing conditions,
passive entertainment industries, and obscene uses of the written and spoken
word.
The modern human being's soul is already contracted and hurt by all that goes
on in the world - we just can't stand any more evil or injustice.
Is it any wonder that the West case is the straw that breaks the camel's back?
I'm suggesting that what we need more of in our daily lives are encounters with
people and the world which fill our imaginations with pictures of beauty,
truth, and morality.
Individuals, parents, communities, the media, and society as a whole would
serve the world well by taking up my suggestion.
Francis M O'Hare,
8 Finlarig Street,
Glasgow.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO>GH951125-000079</DOCNO>
<DOCID>GH951125-000079</DOCID>
<DATE>951125</DATE>
<HEADLINE>Dispute over savings</HEADLINE>
<EDITION>1</EDITION>
<PAGE>6</PAGE>
<RECORDNO>975208528</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
A POLITICAL row has followed disclosures that an option to deal with South
Ayrshire's sewage problems by pumping effluent up the coast to Irvine may now
be taken up despite having never been put before councillors.
Ayr MP Phil Gallie, who raised the matter at Westminster earlier this week, is
calling for a Scottish Office inquiry into the affair and Strathclyde
councillors have expressed their disappointment that they were not given the
chance to consider sewage pumping as an option. Last night, senior Irvine
councillor Jack Carson attacked the plan to pump sewage to an existing
treatment plant at Meadowhead near Irvine.
``We have just passed the European standards for bathing water for the first
time in eight years. This proposal for additional sewage treatement is the last
thing we want. We have planning powers and we will fight it all the way,'' he
said.
COSLA yesterday disputed the ``unrealistic'' #86m central support savings which
the Scottish Secretary claims will be made from local government reorganisation.
The Convention of Scottish Local Authorities said there was scope for savings
in central support services but not the extent of #96m in a full year and #86m
next year as claimed by Mr Michael Forsyth.
Cosla claimed existing employees had the right to transfer to the new councils
and said it would take some time for them to decide staffing requirements after
April 1 next year.
Even when the exercise was completed, Cosla said it expected savings of #40m to
#50m, but emphasised these would be matched or exceeded by the extra costs of
delivering regional services over 29 mainland authorities, rather than the nine
as at present.
</TEXT>
