<DOCNO>GH951125-000081</DOCNO>
<DOCID>GH951125-000081</DOCID>
<DATE>951125</DATE>
<HEADLINE>Shell and Nigeria Sanctions hurt wrong targets</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE></BYLINE>
<EDITION>1</EDITION>
<PAGE>14</PAGE>
<ARTICLETYPE>Leader</ARTICLETYPE>
<RECORDNO>975208530</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
THE Nigerian generals are attracting even more opprobrium than the Greek
colonels in their day. It is thoroughly deserved. Reaction has to be considered
and controlled all the same and the proper objects of contempt identified and
targeted. The aim must always be to help Nigeria in the future and not, by
excess of zeal, do it unintentional damage. That might seem to be obvious but
there are signs that damage to the country's economic development could easily
come from the identification of Shell, and its hopes to build up a natural gas
industry in the Niger Delta, as in effect enemies of the country.
That is an entirely misplaced judgment which can itself do only harm. Shell is
a huge international business with a soundly based reputation for environmental
awareness. It would hardly operate in a single country in a manner entirely
distinct from its normal mode. Shell in Nigeria is the largest foreign
participant in the hydro-carbon industry but there are others (not exactly
minnows themselves) and that diversity need not be forgotten. The physical
suffering imposed on Ogoniland derives from the inadequacy of state provision
and control. The responsibility lies with the government, albeit not an elected
government. A great part of the case against previous Nigerian administrations
and certainly against the present military regime is the way in which they have
ignored their duties in order to extract as much money as possible from the
region. The generals are the proper target for foreign disapproval and where
sanctions are involved these ought to be on the sort of weaponry from which
some at least of the generals' power derives. More sweeping sanctions affecting
the whole country should be avoided. They will hurt the mass of Nigerian people
but not the brass hats who repress them. The parallel wih Iraq might usefully
be remembered: sanctions hurt the wrong targets.
If the attempt is made to stifle the development of the Delta oil and now
natural gas deposits tomorrow's Nigeria will be the poorer and its people will
not thank their would-be benefactors. Of course some Western opinion hates
multi-national companies, but that should hardly determine its strategy against
Nigeria's dictators.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO>GH951125-000082</DOCNO>
<DOCID>GH951125-000082</DOCID>
<DATE>951125</DATE>
<HEADLINE>In defence of teenagers</HEADLINE>
<EDITION>1</EDITION>
<PAGE>14</PAGE>
<ARTICLETYPE>Correspondence</ARTICLETYPE>
<RECORDNO>975208531</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
I WAS amused but not surprised at your correspondents' reaction to my letter
defending young Scots people (November 20 and 22).
I stick to my guns in defence of teenagers; middle-aged people always look back
on their teenage years with rose-tinted spectacles and forget that if they
looked at the newspapers and magazines of that period they would find
middle-aged people pouring out their poisonous words about teenagers.
As for Mr Martin's letter, I would point out that if we take the raising of the
Scots Guards in 1642 as the earliest Scots regiment raised on British soil to
the retreat of the Argyll and Sutherland Highlanders from the barren rocks of
Aden we have about 300 years of Scots soldiers dealing out death and
destruction to people with black, brown, and yellow skins.
Within the ranks of these regiments and others we had children as young as 11
and 13 often standing in the ranks of the famous British square.
Who will be our possible enemies that we in Scotland have to have a standing
Army of teenagers ready to die on behalf of comfortable middle-aged,
middle-class, armchair strategists.
John Carlyle,
36 Albert Road,
Glasgow.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO>GH951125-000083</DOCNO>
<DOCID>GH951125-000083</DOCID>
<DATE>951125</DATE>
<HEADLINE>Theatre Royal centenary</HEADLINE>
<EDITION>1</EDITION>
<PAGE>14</PAGE>
<ARTICLETYPE>Correspondence</ARTICLETYPE>
<RECORDNO>975208532</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
FURTHER to Keith Bruce's welcome and informative article on the centenary of
Glasgow's Theatre Royal, could I add one vital strand to the theatre's rich
history, as the cradle of the Repertory Theatre in Scotland as it existed and
flourished in the thirties and forties (November 13).
Usually in conjunction with Edinburgh's Royal Lyceum this period provided a
social centre to Glasgow's playgoing, with its permanent booking facilities; it
also gave regular patrons an invaluable education in theatre of all kinds and
eras, with Scottish work by no means ignored.
The centre of activity was the Brandon-Thomas company, but notable achievements
were those of the earlier Masque Theatre, and later on Ronald Adam's Howard and
Wyndham Players and the starry (in 1940 and usually historically overlooked) H
M Tennent Players, which even presented a rare Bridie, Susannah and the Elders,
and which had Michael Denison and Dulcie Gray as junior company members.
Dr Tony Paterson,
12 Victoria Crescent Road,
Glasgow.
C
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO>GH951125-000084</DOCNO>
<DOCID>GH951125-000084</DOCID>
<DATE>951125</DATE>
<HEADLINE>Clock Bill fails to chime with Forsyth</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>Margaret Vaughan</BYLINE>
<EDITION>1</EDITION>
<PAGE>13</PAGE>
<RECORDNO>975208533</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
Clock Bill
fails to
chime with
Forsyth
IF Michael Forsyth were to fall on his knees and shake a frustrated fist, it
would not have to be at some unseen spirit in the sky. Unlike Basil Fawlty, he
has a target for his wrath.
It is the form of John Butterfill, a benign political cove from the twilit
resort of Bournemouth. From out of the dark recesses of the Tory backbenches he
blundered into view this week with his plan for a time zone at Hadrian's Wall.
Mr Butterfill, who emerged top of the poll for a Private Members' Bill, is to
introduce a Bill to turn England's clocks forward an hour, harmonising with
Europe, and leaving Scotland in a timewarp.
He indicated he would not oppose any move for different time bands north and
south of the Border. The Scots may stay in the dark ages if they so choose, he
said, questioning whether ``the whole of British time and the whole of how we
run should be dictated by crofters in the West of Scotland.'' Different time,
different country, different planet?
Like poor old uncomprehending Manuel, at his bumbling best, he unwittingly left
Mr Forsyth striking a discordant chime with his own party colleagues. For the
plan to extend daylight hours is reported to have found sympathy in several
ministries where Ministers believe there would be economic advantages to a
switch to Central European Time.
But it undermines somewhat the 16-year struggle to convince Scots that the
Conservative Party truly, madly, deeply, believes, honest, in the union.
In an incandescent performance, reminiscent of Basil's preferred method for
dealing with dumb waiters, Mr Forsyth issued his political colleague with a
swift poke in the eye: ``We are one United Kingdom and we do not want to be
divided by a time zone,'' Mr Forsyth fizzled. ``It is the sort of thing I would
expect to hear from a Scottish nationalist, not a Conservative and Unionist,''
he fumed. Ouch!
Downing Streert, however, was noncommittal over the Government's attitude
towards the proposed Bill: ``There are a range of views on this subject. It is
not one, historically, that the Government has taken a formal view on,'' a
spokesman mused.
On Thursday night Mr Forsyth intends to steal the thunder from the
devolutionist lobby's proposals by using a memorial lecture for former Labour
stalwart Dick Stewart to announce his new plans for the governance of Scotland,
to safeguard the union and, hopefully, his Stirling seat. Mr Butterfill's
somewhat divisive proposals may have blunted the sharp edge of his unionist
argument.
But then, as has been so wearily often remarked, Mr Forsyth has shown new
colours since his return to Scotland. Following the banishment to Social
Security that followed his unfortunate falling out with most of his Scottish
ministerial colleagues, and virtually the entire ranks of the Conservative and
Unionist Association membership, his uncompromising Thatcherite stance vanished
like the morning star when he came homeward to think again.
The descriptions of him in Mrs Thatcher's memoirs as ``the real powerhouse for
Thatcherism at the Scottish Office'' and the only political foe to be feared by
opponents hardly match up to his new image as ``Braveheart'' Forsyth, the
doughty champion of all things Scottish in Cabinet.
He would, he promised, be Scotland's man in the Cabinet, not the Cabinet's man
in Scotland. But, as he was reminded by the former political adviser to his
predecessor as Scottish Secretary, Ian Lang, just a few days ago, that is a
risky role to play.
A newspaper article by Alan Young warned that by setting himself up as
Scotland's champion against his Cabinet colleagues he implicitly portrayed the
Cabinet - and therefore, presumably, the Tory party - as Scotland's enemy.
What this suggests, says Young, is that Forsyth, or a source close to him, is
willing to distance himself from the Government of which he is a member by
acting as Scotland's stout defender in a running battle. But by doing so, Young
acutely argues, he undermines the Union the government is pledged to preserve.
Perhaps, after all then, Mr Butterfill has done the Scottish Secretary a
favour. He has allowed Michael Forsyth to be seen to fight Scotland's dark
corner against the dying of the Tory light. Then, come the next General
Election, a small star may still shine over Stirling.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO>GH951125-000085</DOCNO>
<DOCID>GH951125-000085</DOCID>
<DATE>951125</DATE>
<HEADLINE>Administer a truth drug</HEADLINE>
<EDITION>1</EDITION>
<PAGE>14</PAGE>
<ARTICLETYPE>Correspondence</ARTICLETYPE>
<RECORDNO>975208534</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
IT was interesting to read of Detective Superintendent John Bennett's warning
to other police forces investigating similar incidents not to expect any
assistance from Rosemary West (November 24).
Now that she has been convicted of 10 murders and considering the evidence of
her disgusting treatment to some, if not all of her victims, is it not time,
particularly now that MI5 are to become involved in criminal investigations, to
use their expertise and to give her a truth drug to ensure that there are no
more skeletons in the cupboard.
Stuart Waldman,
24 Kingsburgh Drive,
Paisley.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO>GH951125-000086</DOCNO>
<DOCID>GH951125-000086</DOCID>
<DATE>951125</DATE>
<HEADLINE>Vatican ban</HEADLINE>
<EDITION>1</EDITION>
<PAGE>14</PAGE>
<ARTICLETYPE>Correspondence</ARTICLETYPE>
<RECORDNO>975208535</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
LIKE Anne McKay who is saddened at Mr Blackshaw's letter over Archbishop
O'Brien's forced retraction of his Imprimatur from the pack, HIV - A Christian
Response, I too find myself saddened.
Saddened that such wilful intransigence to the findings of the Magisterium of
her own church can be evinced by a teacher of a Catholic school (November 22).
For despite Vatican II the Catholic Church remains an eternal autocracy. The
archbishop, by his humility and compliance, evidently sees this. Why not Mrs
McKay?
She informs us that the packs now lie on her shelf with nothing within. An
infallible way to prevent the spread of the Aids virus via sexual contact.
Of course this calls for self control; as does the entire economy of salvation.
Her council, like the pack itself, is one of despair.
The real sadness lies in that parental expectations are being betrayed daily by
people in positions of trust.
Tom McKay,
29 Manitoba Crescent,
East Kilbride.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO>GH951125-000087</DOCNO>
<DOCID>GH951125-000087</DOCID>
<DATE>951125</DATE>
<HEADLINE>From coffee breaks to those power lunches</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>Ann Shaw</BYLINE>
<EDITION>1</EDITION>
<PAGE>11</PAGE>
<ARTICLETYPE>features</ARTICLETYPE>
<GRAPHIC>Photograph</GRAPHIC>
<RECORDNO>975208536</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
Women may have closed the credibility gap, but the reality gap is still wide
open. Cherie Lunghi makes a glossy, astute company head in the coffee ads, but
the real head of its parent company is a man. Women directors are still rare.
Ann Shaw looks at a new scheme to encourage more women to reach for the top
WOMEN who believe hard work will get them to the top are sadly mistaken. And
they are making an even bigger mistake if they mix and socialise only with
other women or, even worse, join all-women organisations.
For the main obstacle keeping women out of the boardroom, according to an
Edinburgh-based research project, is . . . other women.
Women, it seems, spend too much time with others of the same sex rather than
networking with influential men, the ``movers and shakers''. And among other
reasons given as to why so few make it to the top are:
n A lack of a personal public profile;
n Their shortage of experience at senior company level;
n The Old Boys' Network.
While levels of prejudice are breaking down, and companies are often keen to be
seen to be promoting equal opportunity, firms are often unable to find suitable
women for the boardroom because they never come across them in the circles in
which they move.
``The reason so few women achieve boardroom appointments tends not to be lack
of knowledge or skills but a lack of confidence in their ability to be
successful in this environment and often a lack of access to the right
networks,'' says Louise Ewart, of Lothian and Edinburgh Enterprise Limited, the
company which commissioned the study to find why, in spite of equal pay and
opportunities, there are so many blocks to women's progress up the executive
ladder.
However, all that is set to change with the launch on Tuesday of Boardroom
Mentors, a programme devised by Lothian and Edinburgh Enterprise Ltd, designed
to help women into the fast track It brings together top business people and
senior women who want to become non-executive directors.
Initially, 25 women will be selected for the programme. They will be linked
with mentors of the calibre of Bob Maiden, former managing director of the
Royal Bank of Scotland, and David Nicholson, managing partner of KPMG in
Scotland and president of the Edinburgh Chamber of Commerce &amp; Enterprise.
They will provide advice and support as well as introducing senior women to
influential networks. They will meet at least once a month, and take part in a
series of networking events which will introduce them to corporate financiers,
venture capitalists, bankers and others in the financial world.
If this smacks of old boy networking then so be it, because it is essential for
those women with their eyes set on the boardroom, says Ewart, who is
responsible for the launch of the project.
``Boardroom Mentors cannot guarantee any individual a board appointment, but it
can increase your access to any opportunities that emerge,'' she says.
``Women mix too much with other women. They join all-women organisations,
which, while worthwhile because they provide a refuge and support, do not offer
a fast track to the top. If women want to get on then they must mix socially
with men, not women. They must be seen at all the right social events.''
In Scotland, fewer than three per cent of women are on the board of directors.
``But the reason given over and over again during our research was that men
would like to appoint women if only they knew a few names,'' says Ewart.
For those determined to reach the top Boardroom Mentors may be the answer. You
send in a CV and a letter explaining what you could contribute as a
non-executive director and what benefits you could bring in return to your
mentor. If selected you will join the scheme for a year.
FOR further information contact Louise Ewart, Boardroom Mentor Programme,
Lothian &amp; Edinburgh Enterprise Ltd., Apex House, 99 Haymarket Terrace,
Edinburgh EH12 5HD, telephone 0131-313 6234.
COLD FACTS BEHIND THE ILLUSION
Cherie Lunghi may appear to be in control, but her character in the television
advert is very much the exception to the rule:
20% of managers in Scotland are women.
Four per cent are in middle management.
Three per cent are non-executive directors in PLCs.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO>GH951125-000088</DOCNO>
<DOCID>GH951125-000088</DOCID>
<DATE>951125</DATE>
<HEADLINE>Conflict on use of drug to treat MS</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>ALAN MacDERMID</BYLINE>
<EDITION>1</EDITION>
<PAGE>8</PAGE>
<RECORDNO>975208537</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
THE NHS Management Executive in Scotland is planning urgent talks with the
country's 25 consultant neurologists, on whether the new drug Beta Interferon
should be prescribed routinely for Multiple Sclerosis patients.
The Multiple Sclerosis Society last night expressed deep concern at the
possibility of patients in Scotland having to enrol in clinical trials to
receive the drug - with half receiving it and the other half receiving a
placebo - while in England, patients thought likely to benefit were given it
outright.
A memorandum sent by the executive to health board and trust managers last
week, advises purchasers and providers what steps they should take to prepare
for the anticipated licensing of the drug, which was shown in an Amercian trial
to reduce relapse in the disease.
The chief medical officer, Dr Robert Kendell, said he had received a letter
signed by all 25 consultants stating that, in their view, there was not enough
evidence to recommend the drug to MS patients in routine clinical practice.
Instead, they wanted all their patients to participate in placebo-controlled
trials examining the drug's effect on disability, measured in a valid way.
Mr Peter Cardy, chief executive of the MS Society, said it was disturbed by the
move, which is contrary to the stated opinion of the Association of British
Neurologists.
</TEXT>
