<HEADLINE>Couple had stolen alcohol</HEADLINE>
<EDITION>1</EDITION>
<PAGE>8</PAGE>
<FLAG>news digest</FLAG>
<RECORDNO>975208538</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
A COUPLE appeared in court yesterday charged with handling more than #700 worth
of stolen cigarettes and alcohol.
Jessie Fraser and her husband James, of Craigton Avenue, Inverness, admitted
reset at Alder Place, Culloden, on March 31 this year.Sentence was deferred
until November 30.
Radioactive dust
AN investigation was under way at Dounreay nuclear plant in Caithness after a
worker inhaled radioactive dust. The incident happened last month as waste
drums containing the dust were being repackaged for dumping.
Rapist jailed
A MAN was jailed for nine years today for the rape of a teacher just a month
after he was released from jail for attacking another woman. Orlando Baker, 28,
was found guilty of raping the teacher in his bail hostel.
Heroin seized
SIX men were being questioned by Customs investigators in Dover yesterday after
the seizure of 60kg of heroin with an estimated street value of #6m. The six,
all Poles, were arrested by Customs staff at the port following a routine check
of a ferry from Calais.
Beach agreement
AN agreement was reached yesterday on the cleaning up of pollution on Granton
beach, Edinburgh, which locals have blamed for a pungent smell that has plagued
the city for years. Officials from Lothian Chemicals, who have a plant near the
beach, met council and water officials to agree a deal. A full report will now
be considered by the district council on December 4.
Oil firm honoured
GLOBAL Marine Drilling Company of Aberdeen has become the first oil-related
organisation to receive an award from the Royal Society for the Prevention of
Accidents for its commitment to health and safety standards.
Murder attempt
POLICE are treating as attempted murder an incident in the Barmulloch area of
Glasgow early yesterday when a fire was discovered in a flat in Torryburn Road.
The fire is believed to have been started with inflammable liquid being thrown
through a window. The two occupants of the flat were not injured.
Salmon museum
A NEW museum depicting the history of the salmon-netting industry on the Tweed
is being created in a Victorian boathouse in the grounds of Paxton House in
Berwickshire.
Owner warned
ARTIST Ronald Turnbull, 43, has agreed to an order being made by Berwick
magistrates to keep his Jack Russell under proper control after it bit a
10-year-old girl on the lip at Chatton near Berwick.
Barn destroyed
FIREFIGHTERS tackled a blaze which destroyed a barn at an Ayrshire farm
yesterday. An estimated #30,000 worth of damage was caused at Lawhill Farm, Law
Brae, West Kilbride. A police spokesman said a youth had been reported to the
procurator fiscal in connection with the incident.
</TEXT>
