<DATE>951125</DATE>
<HEADLINE>Recipe for dreams that come true</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>Ann Shaw</BYLINE>
<EDITION>1</EDITION>
<PAGE>11</PAGE>
<ARTICLETYPE>Features</ARTICLETYPE>
<RECORDNO>975208539</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
THE ENTREPRENEUR
ALL entrepreneurs share the ability to see windows of opportunity, a
risk-taking mentality, and supreme self-confidence - and Glasgow millionaire
Vera Weisfeld, co-founder of What Everyone Wants, is no exception.
This is typified by, believe it or not, a cookbook. She has persuaded the Great
and the Good to write it for her, with Liz Taylor, Nick Faldo, the Aga Khan,
Jeffrey Archer, the Duchess of York, and the Pope all contributing their
favourite recipes.
Even Versace was persuaded to design the cover - for free. And it's all for
charity. The book, Recipe for Life, reflects the kind of entrepreneurship that
sets women like Weisfeld apart.
She has made the colossal leap from a council house in Coatbridge and her first
job as a 15-year-old shop assistant to a multi-millionaire with luxury homes in
Scotland and the South of France. But speaking from the boardroom of the former
Goldberg store in Glasgow's Argyle Street, the latest joint business venture
with her husband Gerald, she says: ``I did not set out to become a millionaire.
It just happened.''
A former pupil of St Patrick's School, Coatbridge, she recalls attending one of
their speech days and her dismay at the downbeat message that there were 5000
unemployed in Lanarkshire and jobs only for 500. ``I put myself in the shoes of
those youngsters listening to that and my heart sank. So I wrote to the school
and told them so. Next year I was invited to do the speech. I told them I was
born only 50 yards from the school and if I had sat there and waited for work
in Coatbridge I would still be waiting.
``I said `hands up those of you who want to go and work down the mines'. Not
one hand went up. I pointed out to them that while some jobs go others open up.
Coatbridge has now got the Time Capsule, restaurants, and hotels.
``Get into the workforce. That's the most important thing. It doesn't matter
what you do. Then you can start working your way up. My father gave me the best
advice ever: `The #1 you earn is your best friend. Don't rely on anyone else'.
''
Her speech received a standing ovation, and this gung-ho optimism has served
her well over the years. But she's also a pragmatist. ``I'm not against
education. But there's a myth that started about 10 years ago that if you got
yourself a university education you automatically got yourself a good job.
That's absolute nonsense.
``What they don't teach you in school, and what is desperately needed, is a
degree in Life. We can't all be doctors, lawyers, and accountants.''
One of the founder-members of the newly established Scottish branch of the
British Association for Women Entrepreneurs, Weisfeld's story is well known:
she left school at 15 to work as a shop assistant with C &amp; A. Marriage, two
children and a divorce led her as a single parent back into the workforce,
again starting at the bottom. She worked her way up and applied for a job as
manager of a small dress shop in the wrong end of Argyle Street selling
discount frocks. Her aim was simple: to give value for money. ``You had to, or
your customers wouldn't bother to trail to that end of town again.''
Her early pragamatism paid off: ``Who would leave a good job with Marks &amp;
Spencer, C &amp; A or British Home Stores to come and work in a small dress shop in
the wrong end of Argyle Street? So I had to train my own staff. I sold them a
dream and the dream came true. They ended up earning large salaries and driving
expensive cars.''
After selling their business, the Weisfelds chose to remain in Scotland instead
of retreating to a tax exile. For the past five years they have devoted much
energy to fund-raising for charities. More than 50 charities have been major
beneficiaries of the Weisfeld Foundation, including the setting up of a Teenage
Cancer Trust. Meanwhile, Vera's two sons from her first marriage, Michael and
John, are in the family business and she has six grandchildren of whom she is
extremely proud.
But now the Weisfelds are back in the retail business, unable, one suspects, to
resist a challenge. Why start again? Why, when you have made a million, or as
in the case of the Weisfelds, #50m, do you want the hassle of starting all over
again, especially when you have reached comfortable middle-age, a time when
most people are thinking of winding down, not winding up again?
``Scotland is my home,'' says Weisfeld. She says she wants to do ``her bit'' to
help the Glasgow renaissance. The truth is that Weisfeld can't resist a
challenge. ``I have built up so much expertise and knowledge it's a pity not to
use it.''
</TEXT>
