<HEADLINE>Major-General Eric MacLachlan Mackay</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>General Sir William Jackson</BYLINE>
<EDITION>1</EDITION>
<PAGE>12</PAGE>
<ARTICLETYPE>Obituary</ARTICLETYPE>
<RECORDNO>975208540</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
Major-General Eric MacLachlan Mackay, CBE, Chief Engineer of the British Army
on the Rhine, 1973-76; born December 26, 1921, died November 16, 1995
ERIC MACKAY, whose family came from the village of Camlup, near Kingussie in
the Grampians, made his name with his epic four-day defence of the school
building overlooking the famous bridge at Arnhem over the Lower Rhine - ``The
Bridge Too Far''.
He had led his Sapper paratroopers throughout 1st Parachute Division's
operations in the Mediterranean - Tunisia, Sicily, and Italy. By the time they
landed at Arnhem in September, 1944, they were an experienced body of 60
battle-hardened men, most of whom were marksmen.
During the first day, Sunday, Mackay and his men fought their way through
Arnhem to join the 2nd Parachute Battalion at the northern end of the bridge.
2nd Para occupied the buildings on the western side of the approach ramp to the
bridge, and Mackay fortified the dominating three-storey school building on the
eastern side, from the upper windows of which he could bring fire down upon any
vehicles trying to cross the bridge.
As Monday dawned, a force of Panzer Grenadiers in armoured half-tracks, led by
armoured cars, came across the bridge from the south.
Having no anti-tank weapons, Mackay had to let the cars go by, but his Bren
gunners and riflemen dealt with the unroofed half-tracks. The first was stopped
by a well-thrown grenade. The driver of the second was killed by rifle fire,
and its crew shot down as they scrambled out. The third vehicle's driver was
wounded and, in trying to reverse, hit the fourth, which burst into flames,
partially blocking the bridge.
The fifth half-track crashed down the embankment, ending up under the window of
the school, from which Mackay was directing fire.
He wrote later: ``It was about five feet away and I looked into its commander's
face. His reaction was quicker than mine; for with a big dirty grin he loosed
off three shots with his Luger. The only shot that hit me smashed my
binoculars, which were hanging round my neck.''
The Sapper marksmen quickly dispatched him and the rest of the crew. Another
two half-tracks met a similar fate, finally blocking the bridge completely.
During Tuesday and Wednesday, Mackay's marksmen inflicted heavy losses on the
German infantry trying to drive them out of the school. Tank guns gradually
made more and more of the school untenable. Nevertheless, morale remained high
because gunfire of 30th Corps could be heard coming closer.
The situation changed dramatically on Thursday. Two large Tiger tanks began to
reduce the school to rubble; and the Germans tried to force both 2nd Paras and
Mackay's men out by burning the buildings around them. Neither could sacrifice
their wounded in the cellars by further resistance. Mackay ordered his
second-in-command, who was among the wounded, to surrender while he and his
last six unwounded men tried to break out.
Unfortunately, he ran into a force of infantry and tanks. He dispersed his men
and played dead himself, but a bayonet thrust into his thigh forced him to
surrender.
His first attempt to escape failed, but he slipped away with three of his men
from a prison camp on the Rhine. Luckily, they found an unguarded rowing boat,
and the strong current carried them down the river to the Allied front line at
Nijmegen.
Eric MacLachlan Mackay was the son of Ian MacLachlan Mackay, an advocate who
practised initially in Edinburgh, and later in Lahore, India. His father died
young and Eric was brought up by Sir Harry Scott-Smith. He was educated at
Fettes, enlisted in the Royal Scots Fusiliers in 1940, and was commissioned
into the Royal Engineers in October, 1941. He served from 1941 to 1945
continuously with the 1st Parachute Squadron, RE.
He was a smallish, dynamic Scot who loved life and always enjoyed a party. He
excelled at high-speed sports.
In 1954, he had married a Swiss rally driver, Ruth Therese Roth. They had only
one son who was born handicapped. She died in 1985. His second wife is Margaret
(Hadders) Hadcock, nee Shepherd, whom he married last year.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
