<TEXT>
Junior Walker, Motown's leading saxophonist during the label's heyday and
leader of the All Stars, died on Thursday of cancer in Battle Creek, Michigan
BORN Autry DeWalt Jr. in Blytheville, Arkansas, in 1942, Junior Walker was
famous for the incandescent tones of his alto sax and the gravelly breathiness
of his vocals, crafting such r &amp; b-flavoured hits as Shotgun, How Sweet It Is,
Shake And Fingerpop, Road Runner, and These Eyes with the All Stars.
He had recently toured with the Four Tops, the Temptations, and other Motown
stars, according to Willie Woods, the All Stars' co-founding guitarist.
Walker had been ill for the past two years, said Wood. ``When he got back from
the Motown tour he had lost the strength in his legs. He never really came back
to where he could walk again.''
Walker and Woods started playing together in the mid-1950s. Their first band
was called the Jumping Jacks. They moved to Battle Creek in the late 1950s. It
was there they found a regular gig at El Grotto, a lounge credited with helping
to get the band noticed.
The band signed with a small label owned by Harvey Fuqua which was later taken
over by Motown.
</TEXT>
