<DOCNO>GH951125-000093</DOCNO>
<DOCID>GH951125-000093</DOCID>
<DATE>951125</DATE>
<HEADLINE>Louis Malle</HEADLINE>
<EDITION>1</EDITION>
<PAGE>12</PAGE>
<ARTICLETYPE>Obituary</ARTICLETYPE>
<GRAPHIC>Photograph</GRAPHIC>
<RECORDNO>975208542</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
Louis Malle, film director; born October 30, 1932, died November 23, 1995
LOUIS Malle, the French film-maker who died on Thursday in California at the
age of 63, was one of the most enduring and varied directors of postwar cinema.
He won audiences - and stirred controversy - on both sides of the Atlantic.
Malle brought freshness and sensitivity to subjects that ranged from the
frivolous to the grim, showing himself unafraid to explore such taboo themes as
incest, child prostitution, and French collaboration with the Nazis during the
Second World War.
Very much an actors' director, he launched the screen career of Jeanne Moreau
in the late 1950s and won wide acclaim for his work with children in such films
as Zazie dans le Metro (1960) and Au Revoir les Enfants (1987).
Malle's films covered virtually all genres, from thriller and spoof Western to
absurdist comedy. Equally at home in French or English, he was one of the few
French directors to win acclaim in the United States with a series of films
including Pretty Baby (1977) and Atlantic City (1980).
Malle himself felt his best films were the ones that attracted most
controversy, either for their explicit sexual themes or their unflinching
examination of the past. ``My ambition is not strictly to entertain,'' he said
in an interview shortly after the 1992 release of Damage, the story of an
upper-middle class British family destroyed by the insidious power of sexual
passion.
Louis Malle was born into a wealthy sugar-producing family in the northern town
of Thumeries on October 30, 1932. He quickly turned his back on his bourgeois
background and strict Catholic education - the butt of much social criticism in
his films - enrolling first as a political science student at the Sorbonne and
then in film school.
Unlike many of his New Wave contemporaries who entered film-making via the
radical critical magazine Cahiers du Cinema, Malle started off spectacularly
when he was picked to help the explorer Jacques-Yves Cousteau make an
underwater documentary. The result, Le Monde du Silence (The Silent World),
remains a classic of its kind and won a clutch of prizes on its release in 1956.
His first feature, the atmospheric thriller Ascenseur pour l'Echafaud (Frantic)
starring Moreau and featuring music by Miles Davis, followed two years later
and won the Prix Delluc. The big breakthrough came, however, with Les Amants
(The Lovers), starring Moreau as a middle-class woman who discovers the
emptiness of her life through a passionate sexual encounter.
Along with fellow New Wave luminaries Jean-Luc Godard and Francois Truffaut,
Malle delighted in an iconoclastic rejection of classical film-making in favour
of a radical new style. His most audacious experiment was Zazie dans le Metro,
the absurdist story of a foul-mouthed eight-year-old let loose on Paris.
Throughout the 1960s Malle turned out films of a stunning variety from Le Feu
Follet (The Fire Within), the grim story of an alcoholic driving himself into
the grave, to the spoof Western Viva Maria, starring Moreau and Brigitte
Bardot, and the period crime drama Le Voleur (The Thief of Paris). In 1973 his
film Lacombe Lucien, about a peasant boy who sides with the fascist authorities
in Nazi-occupied France, sparked an anxious debate about extent of wartime
collaboration.
Malle had blown apart a national myth that ordinary people all worked for the
Resistance, a theme he was to explore again in the much-lauded Au Revoir les
Enfants - about the betrayal of a Jewish schoolboy - a decade later.
He did not reserve his social criticism for France, however. Following his
first successes in America, he made Alamo Bay (1984), a highly political tale
of Texas fishermen and their harsh treatment of Vietnamese boat people. It was
flop, persuading Malle to return home in the mid-1980s despite being married to
American actress Candice Bergen with whom he had a young daughter.
His taste for unusual or difficult subjects never wavered, however, and the
explosive sexual content of Damage, starring Jeremy Irons and Juliette Binoche,
brought him new controversy. ``I think predictability has become the rule and
I'm completely the opposite,'' he said. ``I like spectators to be disturbed.''
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO>GH951125-000094</DOCNO>
<DOCID>GH951125-000094</DOCID>
<DATE>951125</DATE>
<HEADLINE>Peter Grant</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>David Belcher</BYLINE>
<EDITION>1</EDITION>
<PAGE>12</PAGE>
<ARTICLETYPE>Obituary</ARTICLETYPE>
<GRAPHIC>Photograph</GRAPHIC>
<RECORDNO>975208543</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
Peter Grant, rock group manager; born April 5, 1935, died November 21, 1995
IT is ironic that Peter Grant's death, on Tuesday at the age of 60, occurred in
the same week another member of his much-maligned breed - the rock manager -
stands accused of having grossly undersold the peak earning-capacity of his
most successful act.
This weekend's TV documentary about the Beatles will re-state the facts about
Brian Epstein's financial naivety in committing the band to pitifully-low
record-royalty rates of one pre-decimal penny per disc sold.
In contrast, Peter Grant's principal clients, Led Zeppelin, profited lastingly
from the forceful certainty of Grant's approach to the rock business. Indeed,
while Grant's ultra-low public profile never came close to matching that of
such managers as Epstein, Andrew Loog Oldham, Malcolm McLaren, or Colonel Tom
Parker, his no-nonsense negotiating techniques revolutionised the financial
reality of top-level concert tours, tipping the scales in favour of artists
rather than promoters.
A gruff and physically intimidating figure, 6 ft 5 in tall and weighing 18!s
st, Grant won most of his battles thanks to the ferocity of his verbal attacks.
His greatest triumph lay in securing Led Zeppelin 90% of concert
ticket-receipts, instead of the then-customary 50-60%.
He evidently never forgot the lessons learned during his first involvement in
the rock'n'roll business, as a UK tour manager with embittered, underpaid
pioneers like Gene Vincent, Little Richard, and Chuck Berry.
However, Grant understood the value of rock's intangibles, too. Led Zeppelin's
rise to prominence was speeded by their aura of underground credibility, a
direct consequence of Grant's decision the group would not appear on TV, nor
sully their art by releasing anything as unhip as a single.
Born into poverty-stricken illegitimacy in London's east end, Grant compensated
with combativeness. For a spell, he was a semi-professional wrestler - Count
Bruno Alessio - and also worked as a bouncer at Soho's famous 2I's coffee bar,
his introduction to the music business.
To his young band, Grant always displayed a brusque, fatherly consideration -
as well as an impeccable honesty. With others, he could be fearlessly
aggressive.
He routinely made record-company lackeys run for cover and music-paper critics
tremble. Entering the crowd at one live Led Zep show, he snatched the tape out
of a bootlegger's recorder. Spotting Robert Plant and Jimmy Page  being
harassed by American sailors in New Orleans airport for the crime of sporting
long hair, Grant lifted one of the sailors off his feet before posing the
immortal question: ``What's your problem, Popeye?''
Peter Grant effectively retired from the music business at the end of Led Zep's
prime era, the seventies, when the band opted not to continue in the wake of
drummer John Bonham's death in 1980. Yet his contribution to the worldwide
cause of musicians was not forgotten, Grant being inducted on to the Roll of
Honour by the International Managers' Forum during the summer.
In addition, Grant was honoured more recently by Phil Everly at an after-show
party following an Everly Brothers' concert in London's Royal Albert Hall.
Presenting Grant with a silver cane, Everly paid him a heart-felt tribute which
refuted the common notion all rock managers are rip-off merchants and shysters
who prey upon the music-making innocents in their charge.
``This man made it all possible,'' said Everly. ``Without his efforts,
musicians had no careers. He was the first to make sure the artist came first,
and that we got paid properly.''
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO>GH951125-000095</DOCNO>
<DOCID>GH951125-000095</DOCID>
<DATE>951125</DATE>
<HEADLINE>On the fast track to the top</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>Ann Shaw</BYLINE>
<EDITION>1</EDITION>
<PAGE>11</PAGE>
<ARTICLETYPE>Features</ARTICLETYPE>
<RECORDNO>975208544</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
THE RISING STAR
DEBORAH Findlay is a super-cool 29-year-old, one of the new wave of young women
fast making their way in the financial world. As manager of retail marketing
with Dunedin, an Edinburgh-based investment company, she has a staff of seven
and is responsible for an annual budget of #500,000.
So, how did Findlay come to be fast-tracking it to the top while still some way
short of her 30th birthday? ``I skipped university for a start,'' she says. ``I
had a place to read English at Edinburgh but decided to take a secretarial
course and a year out.''
She liked the working environment so much she decided to stay, reckoning it
would give her a head start, a hunch that has turned out to be correct. She
reckons she is doing the kind of job now that she would have had to wait until
her early thirties to get if she had gone to university.
But it was a calculated risk, a decision that called for a certain maturity and
self-confidence. Where did she get if from? What schools did she go to?
``St Leonard's and Gordonstoun,'' replies Findlay. Say no more. She has the
kind of confidence which public schools are so good at instilling into young
people; and you've got to admire it. Meeting challenges, team-building and
getting on with people are qualities drilled in from an early age. She doubts,
and probably quite rightly, that university would have developed this further.
Findlay is typical of many young women now making their presence felt in
today's fast-changing business world. They are confident, self-assured and tend
to work for young innovative companies which thrive on new ideas, and young
people. For women like Findlay, feminism is something an older generation
fought for. They simply take equal opportunities for granted.
She says there is no such thing as a typical day with Dunedin, a company she
has been with for the past four years, and that is part of the reason she finds
her job so challenging and interesting.
``We have a range of retail investment products and the overall aim of my job
is to market these products, control the retail budget, run two departments
involving a staff of seven, and take care of advertising and PR for the
company.''
Surprisingly for such a high-flier she is not a workaholic; she does not belong
to that new breed of youngsters who so alarm older employees because they are
prepared to work excessively long hours in order to reach their goals.
``There's more to life than work. A balance between home, social life and work
is essential.''
The future, it has been said, is female. In tomorrow's world women will play a
major role in decision-making. And it's women like Deborah Findlay who are
making it.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO>GH951125-000096</DOCNO>
<DOCID>GH951125-000096</DOCID>
<DATE>951125</DATE>
<HEADLINE>Sleuth is sure of a big surprise</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>Allan Laing</BYLINE>
<EDITION>2</EDITION>
<PAGE>15</PAGE>
<ARTICLETYPE>Features</ARTICLETYPE>
<GRAPHIC>photograph</GRAPHIC>
<RECORDNO>975208545</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
Allan Laing previews the best in next week's small screen entertainment, and
welcomes the return of Inspector Morse, a cop show for grown-ups
TODAY
n.SCREEN TWO: STREETLIFE (BBC2) - Welsh film-maker Karl Francis wrote and
directed this tough tale (highly commended when it was premiered at Edinburgh
Film festival this year) about a single mother's struggle to survive against
the odds in a South Wales housing scheme. His inspiration for the story was a
newspaper report of the discovery of a baby's body in Swansea Marina. Rather
than damn as a monster the mother who had abandoned the child, Francis
considered the possible events which had led her to such a desperate act. The
result is a powerful and harrowing film, etched with black humour and cynicism.
Helen McCrory delivers a truly great performance as Jo, a character of our sad
and depressing times, who descends into a spiral of despair when her spirit is
finally broken. Quite brilliant.
n.TX: THE FINAL KICK (BBC2) - On July 17 last year, around two billion people
tuned in to watch the World Cup Final between Brazil and Italy live on
television. German documentary producer Andreas Rogenhagen dispatched camera
crews to 40 different locations, their remit to capture simultaneously the
reaction of viewers around the world to the game and its nail-biting penalty
shoot-out. The result is a funny and often tense portrait of the emotional
extremes generated by the Beautiful Game. From a cafe in Japan to a car factory
in Iran; from a monastery in Prague to a harem in Cameroon...... all human life
is captured.
n.THE BIG SNOG (C4) - A genuinely impressive list of comic turns (including Lee
Evans, Eddie Izzard, Julian Clary, Steve Coogan, Lenny Henry, Harry Enfield,
and Jenny Eclair) line up to raise a laugh on behalf of a very serious subject.
Recorded live at London's Astoria, it's a benefit gig to raise money for Aids
research. On the downside, the show also features Mariella Frostrup and Dale
Winton.
n.ROYAL VARIETY PERFORMANCE (ITV) - A genuinely unimpressive list of comic
turns (including Sir Cliff Richard, Elaine Paige, Brian Conley, Des O'Connor,
and Robson and Jerome) line up in a (presumably vain) attempt to raise a smile
for the Queen and the Duke of Edinburgh. The Royal Couple, who could do with a
laugh these days, would be better off staying at home and switching the telly
on for C4. Frightening to think that 10 years from now Oasis and Blur will be
in the line-up.
TOMORROW
n.THE BEATLES ANTHOLOGY (ITV) - One can only hope that this long-awaited but
much-hyped series is better than the ``new'' single, Free As A Bird. A quarter
of a century after they called it a day, the Fab Four minus one re-unite to
deliver the authorised Beatles biography through this six-hour documentary
series. So what do we get? Well, tonight's opener traces the group's origin
from their respective childhoods in Liverpool through to 1963 and their first
No.1. Interviews with all four (some new, others from the archives) recall how
they were united by a common love for rock'n'roll and how they went to Hamburg
and played in red-light dives, discovering sex along the way.
n.THE FINAL CUT (BBC1) - And so sadly we reach the end of the line for Francis
Urquhart, a politician so slimey he could crawl under a snake's belly with a
top hat upon his head. The devious Prime Minister from Hell succeeds in
manufacturing his own Falklands-style war when civil unrest breaks out in
Cyprus. Things are going swimmingly when the British High Commissioner is taken
hostage by rebels. Now F.U has the perfect excuse to send in the troops - and
salvage his political career in the process. Meanwhile, Makepeace (Paul
Freeman) asks Claire Carlsen (Isla Blair) to acquire the MoD documents which
will prove Urquhart murdered the Evanghelos brothers. Is this the end for
Francis?
n.THE LAST EUROPEANS (C4) - Heavy-duty journalist Hugo Young presents this
three-part series which charts the UK's abject failure over the past 50 years
to endorse and join the process of European integration. The first programme,
Crossed Channels, examines our often difficult relationship with our
Continental neighbours from the end of the Second World War, through the
establishment (without us) of the Treaty of Rome, to the catastrophe of the
Suez Crisis. It was only after De Gaulle's demise in 1969 that the way was
finally clear for Edward Heath to champion Britain's entry into the Common
Market.
n.CRACKING STORIES: FOR RICHER FOR POORER (BBC1) - The third in BBC Scotland's
nifty wee documentary series follows the fortunes of Bliss, a glossy magazine
for Scots brides which (like a lot of marriages I know) folded after 18 months
with massive debts. Owner/publishers Samantha and Colin Belton's dream was to
produce a magazine which would be ``better than Vogue''. But it was a nightmare
for the staff as the venture struggled to survive. Bouncing pay cheques, long
hours, resignation and sackings (three editors in the space of a year), and
unpaid suppliers. The company collapsed owing #300,000. Today the Beltons have
set up another company (to produce Bliss North in the north of England) while
many of their former employees are still searching for work.
MONDAY
n.CRACKER (ITV) - Sadly, the final episode of the final series of Cracker
(though there'll be a one-off ``Christmas special'' next year, set in Hong
Kong). And maybe it's just as well for, brilliant though this last batch has
been, there have been slightly worrying signs of story fatigue creeping in.
Still, even on an off-day, this cop series is better than anything since
Between The Lines.
n.ALL YOU NEED IS CASH (C4) - Ah, the Born-again Beatles bandwagon continues to
continue. C4's contribution to the Great Hype of '95 is basically a spoiler
series of interviews with what you might call the Significant Others (ie the
people who were involved in the Fab Four's history but were not interviewed for
the Beatles Anthology). Unfortunately, since the ITV documentary series is so
comprehensive, the others are not particularly significant. What we have here
is the unauthorised version which claims to investigate how clashes over money
and managers contributed to the break-up. The film looks at how The Beatles
failed to make all the money they should have done and how Apple is now making
up for lost time (and profits) this year with the aforementioned Hype.
n.IN YOUR FACE: IRVINE WELSH (BBC2) - The next big controversial movie looks
set to be Trainspotting, an adaptation by the Shallow Grave team of Irvine
Welsh's Edinburgh-set, drug-culture novel. There is so much swearing involved
there is now some dubiety over whether or not the film will get a certificate.
This hard-hitting BBC Scotland documentary (the second of three about Scottish
writers) has more than its fair share of uncompromising language itself. It
will not be to everyone's taste. Sub-titled Condemn More, Understand Less, it
explores Welsh's writing through Britain's sub-cultures and the people who
inhabit them, and takes a journey through the author's killing grounds of
housing scheme poverty, drug addiction, football violence, and raves. The film
also includes dramatisations from Welsh's books.
n.WISH YOU WERE HERE? (ITV) - Not particularly. Wish I was somewhere else, to
be honest.
TUESDAY
n.GUNS N' ROSES - THE PHOTOGRAPHIC HISTORY (BBC1) - When you consider that lead
singer Axel Rose is an anagram for oral sex, it might give you some idea of
where this awful American stadium band is coming from, so to speak. Still, Guns
'n' Roses have sold a staggering 50 million albums so far and, in their last
tour, played to a total of 6,000,000 fans. Clearly, there is no accounting for
taste. This documentary is a record of the band's two-year ``Use Your
Illusions'' world tour, including interviews with the members and live
performance footage.
n.BUDGET '95 (BBC2) - A tragi-comedy drama based on actual events starring
Kenneth Clarke as a beleagured Chancellor of the Exchequer and David Dimbleby
as an ageing television presenter. Look out for cameo appearances from Peter
Jay as the BBC's Economics Editor, who's only problem is the fact that no-one
can understand a word of what he says, and Peter Snow as an insane computer
wizard. Taxing, very taxing.
n.PICTURE THIS: NO ORDINARY PEOPLE (BBC2) - This excellent documentary strand
reaches the end of its current series with Mike Fox's fascinating and intimate
study of the Resistance Movement in South-East France during WW2. The film,
narrated by Zoe Wanamaker, includes interviews with those who survived,
including Englishman Francis Cammaerts, an SOE agent who worked with the Maquis
in Provencal. The result is both a celebration of the perilous life these
extraordinary people led and a tribute to their bravery.
WEDNESDAY
n.INSPECTOR MORSE: THE WAY THROUGH THE WOODS (ITV) - Goodbye Cracker and
welcome back Morse after a three-year absence. The great thing about Carlton's
adaptations of Colin Dexter's terrific crime novels (with John Thaw as the
cantankerous Oxford detective and Kevin Whately as his sidekick) is the
wonderful way that they are allowed to evolve at an almost leisurely pace over
two hours. This is a cop show for grown-ups. Based on Dexter's last-but-one
novel (which, in turn, was inspired by a real case), The Way Through The Woods
centres on the apparent murder of Karen Anderson, a single woman who
disappeared while on a day trip to Oxford and whose body has never been found.
Steve Parnell, a man accused of killing five people including Karen, dies in a
prison fight before he goes to trial. The police decide to close the case but
Morse is not convinced that Parnell was responsible for Karen's death.
n.MODERN TIMES: CHERYL'S TRIAL (BBC2) - Earlier this year Cheryl Tooze's
boyfriend, Jonathan Jones, was convicted of the brutal murder of her parents.
Relatives and local people were convinced that justice had been done and that
the guilty party had been jailed. However, Cheryl remains convinced Jones was
innocent and is now campaigning on his behalf. In this documentary she talks
about her profound loss, her attempts to have her boyfriend released, and how
her efforts have thrust her into the public eye and made her own life a trial.
THURSDAY
n.ENNIO MORRICONE (BBC2) - Anyone with even a passing knowledge of film scores
will be familiar with the name of Ennio Morricone. His wonderful haunting music
has graced the soundtracks of some of the greatest movies of the past 30 years
- The Battle of Algiers, The Mission, Once Upon a Time In America, The
Untouchables, and Cinema Paradiso to name but a few. This documentary, which
includes a rare interview with the man himself, charts his rise from the early
days when he penned the music for his old school chum Sergio Leone's spaghetti
Westerns. There are also contributions from, among others, John Boorman, Brian
de Palma, and Bernardo Bertolucci, and Sir David Puttnam. Above all else, there
is the magical music.
n.SECRET LIVES: MARIE STOPES (C4) - Having done up Edward VIII like a kipper,
C4's documentary-series-with-attitude (very much the SAS of the genre) turns
its evil eye upon Britain's original agony aunt. Dr Stopes, of course, was the
author in 1918 of Married Love, the first ever sex manual. What you didn't know
is that, though married, she was still a virgin when she wrote it at the age of
37. Best known today as the pioneer of birth control, Dr Stopes is widely
regarded as having been a kind, caring, humanitarian. According to Secret
Lives, however, her achievements were not motivated by a compassionate instinct
but by a combination of relentless self-promotion and (more sinister) a desire
to create a master race.
FRIDAY
n.FILM: RAN (BBC2) - Kurosawa's contribution to the Beeb's ``100 Best Movies of
all Time'' season is an epic and lavish masterpiece. A loose adaptation of King
Lear, it is the story of an ageing ruler who rashly cedes his lands to the
eldest of his three sons. When his youngest criticises his decision, he
banishes the boy. Before long, the heirs to the throne are at each other's
throats and war and chaos (``ran'' is Japanese for ``chaos'') ensue.
n.WOMAN ON THE RUN (ITV) - One of those exploitative American TV-movies,
allegedly based on a true story. Tatum O'Neil stars as Lawrencia Bebenek, a
woman who served 10 years in prison for the murder of her police officer
husband's ex-wife. The cops claimed she killed the woman to free her hubby from
crippling alimony payments. She claimed she was set up by the police and her
husband.
</TEXT>
