<HEADLINE>Stanley Bowen</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>Lord Hunter</BYLINE>
<EDITION>1</EDITION>
<PAGE>12</PAGE>
<ARTICLETYPE>Obituary</ARTICLETYPE>
<GRAPHIC>Photograph</GRAPHIC>
<RECORDNO>975208546</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
An appreciation
by Lord Hunter
Stanley Bowen, former Crown Agent for Scotland; born August 4, 1910, died
November 19, 1995
STANLEY BOWEN was a very distinguished public servant, a great figure for many
years in our unique system of criminal prosecution, and a humorous and amusing
friend and colleague. In the course of a long and busy life he had many friends
of different generations who touched his long career at various points.
He was born in Carnoustie more than 85 years ago and was educated at Barry and
Dundee. He studied at University College Dundee, as it then was. In 1932 he
qualified as an enrolled solicitor in Scotland and by entered the
procurator-fiscal service a year later. He chose well because his abilities lay
strongly in that direction.
After a hard training under fiscals of the old school he served relatively
briefly as a fiscal at Hamilton and later Airdrie. In 1941 he went to the Crown
Office as a legal assistant. He was promoted in 1945 to be principal assistant,
Deputy Crown Agent as the post would later be called.
In that capacity he spent the next 22 years of his working life under steadily
increasing pressure and the truth is that he became indispensable.
In 1967 he was appointed Crown Agent for Scotland, a post which he held until
retirement in 1974. After no fewer than 41 years in the fiscal service never
were a CBE and honourable retirement better earned. His retiral dinner in
Parliament Hall was an unusual tribute to the standing in which he was held.
Stanley Bowen had a quite remarkable knowledge and experience of Scottish
criminal law and of the content and intricacies of our system of criminal
justice and procedure. He was an expert at Indictments and was by nature a
traditionalist.
He also had a nose for things going wrong, as inevitably they do from time to
time in the fields in which he operated. He may even himself have made a very
occasional mistake during his long years in the fiscal service but if he did
they were the product of his humanity which never became calloused by the
nature of his work.
Many people will have different memories of Stanley Bowen, each in their own
way. He had a wide knowledge of the fiscal service of his day and a remarkable
grasp of the personalities, strengths and weaknesses of individuals serving in
it. His first instinct was loyalty.
He was impatient of delay and sought to provide from the Crown Office what he
used to call a 24-hour service. This he did even during the period when the
part of the office from which he worked consisted of a few small rooms in the
old premises at Parliament House.
To advocates depute and also to law officers, his attitude was in their early
months in office polite, positive, and helpfully critical but never in the
slightest deferential. Later on when they started making the mistakes of
over-confidence he brought this home in a variety of ways depending on the
individual.
In the early years of his retirement Stanley Bowen did duty as a honorary
sheriff and also undertook a considerable weight of other voluntary public work
on official committees and working groups. These dealt with a variety of
subjects within fields familiar to him, which included forensic pathology
services, police discipline, and identification evidence in criminal cases.
He also gave of his time to a number of voluntary bodies, among them the
Scottish Association for the Care and Resettlement of Offenders.
A great interest was the Corstorphine Trust which he served as chairman for
nearly a decade. He lived out his life in that ``village'', as its inhabitants
know Corstorphine, and not without success helped to do what could be done to
preserve it entire and undamaged. He found time also to tend his own garden
there at Dovecot Road.
</TEXT>
