<HEADLINE>Surgical strike at central fiction of British life</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>Ian Bell</BYLINE>
<EDITION>2</EDITION>
<PAGE>15</PAGE>
<ARTICLETYPE>review</ARTICLETYPE>
<GRAPHIC>photograph</GRAPHIC>
<RECORDNO>975208548</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
SHE CAME, we saw, she conquered. Purely as a television contest, Princess
Diana's Panorama appearance (BBC1, Monday) so far outstripped her husband's
Dimbleby confessional of last year as to make you wonder what all those decades
of royal ``training'' were ever supposed to achieve. If this was her first solo
television interview, God alone knows what she might manage with a bit more
practice.
True, the fact that Martin Bashir kept it straight and simple can only have
helped. Imagine only what Frost or any other member of the paid-up simpering
classes would have made of this delicately wrought exchange.
Having helped to spin the web of myth, could any of them have sustained this
pitiless assault on the central fiction of British life? One begs leave to
doubt it.
But what really separated this performance from that of the Prince of Wales -
Bashir's resolute refusal to fawn aside - was its lack of self-pity. Where
Charles appeared both spoiled, arrogant, and sorry for himself, his wife merely
said what she had to say. And if her lines seemed polished and well-rehearsed,
that is doubtless because she has had many bitter months in which to learn
them. It all left this reviewer with one thought: if the House of Windsor can't
live with her, can it really expect to survive without her?
To which the sane reaction might be, who cares? But as the concluding part of
Channel Four's excellent Secret Lives: Edward VIII -The Traitor King (Thursday)
demonstrated, we have squandered so much social and emotional capital on the
Windsors (and never mind the hard cash) as to bankrupt the political process.
Like children reduced to awe by a bit of simple conjuring, we forget to ask how
the trick is done. The royals only matter because we believe they matter. If
one of them turns out to be a fascist eager to sell out his country, whose
fault is that?
Still, best leave politics to our betters. The horrifying conclusion left by
Monday's disgraceful The Beatles - All Together Now (ITV), meanwhile, is that
if this was a taste of the six-hour documentary series ahead we are all being
taken to the cleaners for the full service wash with added starch.
Little better than a 30-minute plug for a pop video (which turned out,
unsurprisingly, to be the only watchable moment in the piece), this shameless
little exercise offered experts of the calibre of Cilla Black and Lulu to
repeat at intervals that the boys were just fab, y'know, while younger
nonentities wondered aloud just what the quartet had that they so conspicuously
lack. It was grim, depressing, and insulting.
Almost as bad, in fact, as the obligatory matching high-brow discussion of
Apple's product relaunch on Late Review (BBC2, Thursday) in which Mark Lawson
and three other full-paid chatterers gave a word-perfect demonstration of
absolute ignorance. Paul Gambacini aside - a man who understands pop the way a
Kwik-Fit fitter understands Formula One - it was clear, first, that the team
didn't know what they were talking about; second, that such a hindrance wasn't
going to stop them.
The Late Review's survival after the assassination of The Late Show was always
something of a mystery. Where the parent programme at least offered some
semblance of expert opinion, its offspring gets by with capsule reviews,
Lawson's faintly childish determination to have the last word, and the kind of
parochialism that London has made its own. Without Tom Paulin, who managed to
be both acerbic and intelligent, it is as nothing.
Meanwhile Coogan's Run (BBC2, Friday) is better than nothing, but only just.
Steve Coogan is a man of many talents but his determination to show them all
off at once hardly justifies the praise heaped on this series before it had
even begun. His comedy lacks focus, his interlinked narrative seems too much
like a series of sketches, and his versatility appears, even at this early
stage, like a vice.
Peter Sellers, to whom Coogan is often compared, had the same weakness: just
because you can ``do'' a dozen different characters doesn't mean you have to;
just because you can invent an amusing character it doesn't mean you can forget
about an amusing script. Think only of the many cinematic disasters Sellers
inflicted on himself, despite his gifts, and you are left with the hope that
Coogan will shortly get a grip.
There is no chance, one assumes, of such a fate ever befalling Eurotrash
(Channel Four, Friday), which returned last week with its ``world tour'' and
the reassurance from Antoine de Caunes that there would be plenty of tasteless
rubbish ``in a desperate a'ttemp to improve the ra'tings' an' kip you sad
Brrritish bastards interested''. Given that Jean Paul Gaultier immediately
cracked a joke involving Mexican fowl that does not bear repeating, this
promise was a mite superfluous.
Eurotrash is no more than its title: tasteless, sexist, camp, leering, cheap,
nasty - and infused with more genuinely wicked comedy, not least at the expense
of ``you Brrritish tubes'', than you'll find this side of the Panorama
cutting-room floor. The central joke is that the British are repressed yet
lecherous hypocrites who exist only to be insulted. The film clips are
incidental; the hosts a reproof to the sort of country that can make stars of
Reeves and Mortimer.
Or, for that matter, the sort of country that can become obsessed with a sad
character like Brian McKinnon. Public Eye: The Lives of Brian (BBC2, Thursday)
saw Jackie Bird doing her best to unravel the inner workings of this strange
and faintly disturbing star of tabloids everywhere.
A 32-year-old pretending to be a teenager is strange enough; a 32-year-old who
seriously wants to repeat his schooldays is authentically bizarre. But ask
yourself: is ``Brandon Lee'' any weirder than the adults in the media who give
him this sort of attention? This column is still none the wiser.
Sane, impeccable, entertaining, and educational: Jancis Robinson's Wine Course
(BBC2, Friday) drew to a close last night with a flourish entitled ``Grapes in
Ferment''. The series has been a revelation, even for those of us who thought
they had been applying themselves to the subject for years, and I shall miss
it. What Robinson has proved, time and again, is that knowing your stuff is not
enough; knowing how to say it is everything.
The Prince of Wales should take note.
</TEXT>
