<HEADLINE>Springboard, Assembly Rooms, Edinburgh</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>MARY BRENNAN</BYLINE>
<EDITION>1</EDITION>
<PAGE>18</PAGE>
<ARTICLETYPE>Review</ARTICLETYPE>
<RECORDNO>975208549</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
ONE of the aims behind this Assembly Alive! season is to make the public aware
of the venue and the various activities that go on there beyond the yearly
eruption of the Fringe. A key part of that profile just has to be Dance Base,
with its increasingly popular roster of classes for all and its valuable
support structures for dancemakers working in Scotland.
This weekend sees Assembly Alive! teaming up with Dance Base to present a
cluster of events that reflect the different ways in which this Edinburgh
agency is servicing the dance community at all levels. This afternoon, for
instance, (between 12 and 4pm) there's a free ``taster'' session where you can
sample the range of dance styles offered in the schedule of classes before
making your personal choice - sadly tango is now off the list, Dance Base's
teacher has been head-hunted to coach Madonna for her role in Evita . . . Now
that's an incentive to sign on, surely!
Last night, however, was by way of a platform for new work. Four short pieces -
well, two fragments really, an extract and a short piece - by Scottish
dancers/choreographers. It was nice to see dance aimed specifically at children
- the excerpts from Escapades and Adventures, devised and performed by
Ethelinda Lashley-Johnstone and Winifred Jamieson.
Voice-overs conjured memories of their own childhood which the movement
extended with bright, clear-cut gestures - nicely pitched and unstuffy. The
complete work may well tour in Scotland next spring. Paul Joseph took the term
``mixed race'' as the starting point for Kultyer Dance Theatre's short piece
Arcadia ``2 And 'Fro''.
Using an Afro wig as a central, symbolic prop, Joseph and his two dance mates
went through some terse statements of racial conflict, harassment and
confusion. Joseph himself is a compelling stage presence - one longed for him
really to explode into dance.
As it was, this seemed a work in need of further development, not simply so as
to show off the dancers' abilities but also to explore the issues so sketchily
evoked.
</TEXT>
