<HEADLINE>Cronin just the man Glasgow needs to tackle his roots again</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>JOHN BEATTIE</BYLINE>
<EDITION>2</EDITION>
<PAGE>32</PAGE>
<ARTICLETYPE>profile</ARTICLETYPE>
<RECORDNO>975208551</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
IT is not good to see a hulk lying in bed, and as Damian Cronin dwarfed the
standard issue metal frame in Level 8 of Glasgow's Western Infirmary, it was
hard not to feel a twinge of pity for the big man with the shoulder tattoo.
And another thought struck me. Here's the perfect guy to try to attract to
Glasgow rugby. He's big, he's got quality, he's maybe nearing the end of his
top-level career at 32, but he ain't going to play for the rest of his life in
France, is he?
``I want to come back to Britain to play,'' said Cronin. ``It all depends on
what is around, and it might be London Scottish.''
Cronin has his own reclamation business - he has been fitting a new floor to
Sting's house - and all he needs is to rent a yard and off he goes. He actually
played in France last Sunday, you know, the day after the Western Samoan game,
but phoned Jim Telfer earlier in the week to tell him the knee was not right.
Jimmy Graham, the surgeon, pulled out a bit of cartilage.
Visiting time over, I got on the phone to a few hoods in the city. Cronin, I
thought, had played a reasonable game against the Western Samoans.
He is not everyone's cup of tea, he was not that fit, but there were not too
many Scots taking the ball to the opposition, whereas Cronin did. Instead, the
old frailties of Scottish rugby were exposed once again, and some new ones came
to light as well.
Maybe the boys in blue were not taken by the sword, and slain, but it was
patently obvious that this was a side that did not gel.
First up - tackling. We have long been a nation of brave defenders. But, for
just as long, we have also been hopeless in our tackling technique. Not one of
our team can tackle the way the All Blacks, South Africans and, yes, the
Samoans do.
I'd like to see what drills we do for tackling, because the rugby league boys
at Leeds that I watched the other week spent much of the session lifting up
heavy tackle bags and dumping them for a whole length of a pitch.
It was a race for them. In school here, we are told as kids to tackle low, and
then slide down the legs to pin them. These lads tackle much higher, above the
centre of gravity, and wham you back. Not pretty, but effective.
We have a mentality that has been drummed into us since school that a tackle is
quite a gentle art, but I rather fancy that in the brave new world of higher
level rugby, the attacking tackle where the ball is dislodged as the tackler
parts an opponent's ribs will be the one that wins.
When was the last Scottish player cautioned for a high tackle?
Next - awareness on the ball and passing ability. Our players are hamstrung by
the fact that they train in the mud of a winter's evening. That will never
change. But what about this: I have just been watching some of Scotland's top
swimmers, all of them amateur and young, training at five in the morning and
then at night after school. In the same pool is a bunch of veteran chappies and
chappesses who get started at 6.15.
Rob Wainwright says that when he was in Natal during our summer, there were
many players who would visit the gym at five in the morning to get themselves
ready for rugby.
Nick Broughton, the Melrose and Otago forward, says his club back home trains
for 80 minutes, and that's all. Yes, the length of a game. If we can't pay our
players enough to make them become full-time rugby players - and it is entirely
possible that the SRU cannot raise enough cash for that - then the players have
to realise that in taking the 20 grand they need to put some amount of effort
in for that.
I think the SRU can get the high ground here. If they were to negotiate with
some of the prime health clubs and sports centres in Scotland that their
players could use the facilities for free very early in the morning, then it
puts the players in some position, doesn't it? That would be a good one.
And another thing in this rant. In this country, we have a work ethic that
goes: work, work, nose to the desk, don't take all your holidays - then die.
Come on employers, give your top rugby players some time to practise. Become
part of the action. Don't you want the boys to win?
We're all a long time dead.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
