<HEADLINE>One step from fifth title in seven seasons Melrose ready for the crunch</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>DEREK DOUGLAS</BYLINE>
<EDITION>2</EDITION>
<PAGE>32</PAGE>
<GRAPHIC>Photograph</GRAPHIC>
<RECORDNO>975208552</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
MELROSE captain Bryan Redpath is in no doubt whatsoever. For the men from the
Greenyards today's premiership clash with Stirling County is the biggest game
of the season, bar none.
Victory at Bridgehaugh will almost certainly mean that Melrose will be
champions for the fifth time in seven seasons - a record which serves only to
underline the Borderers as the most consistent performers of recent times.
Yesterday he declared: ``Oh, yes. This is the biggest game of the season
without a doubt. We've both probably been let off the hook to a certain extent
by other sides being beaten but, for us, it's all to play for and we're really
up for it.''
Holders Stirling will not make it easy for Melrose, and they must fancy their
chances given that a win today would represent their fourth successive victory
against the Borderers.
However, Redpath says that his side are really ``up for it'' and his only fear
is that, with so much at stake, the game might be spoiled as a spectator
spectacle.
The scrum half, who won his fifteenth cap against Western Samoa last Saturday
and was one of a handful who emerged from the game with plus points, has been
enjoying his rugby this season and has been particularly enthused by the
cut-throat nature of the eight-team divisions.
However, like many, he considers that if the eight-team format is to be
preserved then just the one side should be considered for relegation. ``There
is so much at stake this season. If clubs, and not districts, are to represent
Scotland in Europe next season then the outcome of the championship will be
crucial.
``I'm not sure which format I favour. If it is to be clubs then the positive
thing is that European money would come to the clubs and not the districts, but
if the clubs do get the go-ahead then we would probably have to recruit five
new players for the first-team pool.
``Either way, I just want to be involved. If it's to be district sides in
Europe then I want to be involved with the South,'' he said.
Already, Redpath can feel the rejuvenated Gary Armstrong breathing down his
neck. The Melrose man has seen off the challenge of Derrick Patterson and that
of the equally restored-to-fitness Andy Nicol to make the Scotland No.9 shirt
his own.
Armstrong was on the bench at Murrayfield on Saturday and on Monday night, in
an Edinburgh Borderers versus Peebles Select game to hansel Peebles ground
improvements, the Border duo will be involved in a head-to-head contest which
will be of immense interest to the international and South of Scotland
selectors.
``Let's take it one game at a time and first-up it's Stirling County. At the
start of the season Gary was just delighted to have got back from injury and to
be part of the Scotland set-up again. But I know that won't be enough and he'll
want to get back into the South and Scotland sides.
``The competition is good for all of us. All that I can do is play my own game
and hope that it's good enough. Before I even start thinking about that,
though, we've got a big game against Stirling tomorrow and that's what I'm
focusing on right now,'' he said.
Elsewhere today, Boroughmuir who trod on a banana skin at Myreside last
weekend, need a win over Heriot's FP and a Stirling victory over Melrose if
they are to maintain their cham-pionship challenge with a finishing line clash
against the Bridgehaugh men; Edinburgh Academicals are looking for a Division 1
lifeline against Watsonians and Hawick, minus leg-break victim Derek Turnbull
who will be sidelined for 12 weeks but has not considered retirement, are at
Netherdale for the latest instalment of their century-old rivalry with the Auld
Enemy, Gala.
q THE SRU fixtures working party met on Thursday night against a backdrop of a
growing clamour for league reconstruction, with many clubs now favouring a
10-team premiership. Apparently, the meeting was unable to reach any definite
conclusions as dates are still awaited for the European Championship which
Scottish clubs or districts will enter for the first time next season.
q INTERNATIONAL squad agent Ian McLauchlan has dismissed reports that
representatives of Kerry Packer are attempting to resurrect the Australian TV
mogul's rebel circus plans, with a global club championship and that Scottish
internationalists have been involved in talks. However, this latest initiative
comes as the top 12 Welsh clubs are discussing the possibility of a global club
championship bankrolled by a major brewery.
</TEXT>
