<HEADLINE>The Duke rides again</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>WILLIAM RUSSELL</BYLINE>
<EDITION>1</EDITION>
<PAGE>18</PAGE>
<ARTICLETYPE>profile</ARTICLETYPE>
<GRAPHIC>Photograph</GRAPHIC>
<RECORDNO>975208553</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
WHAT you saw on screen is what you got in real life. John Wayne, all-American
hero, worked hard, played hard and lived the life of a film star to the full.
He had all the trappings - the private jet, a yacht, helicopters, three wives,
seven children and the status of an icon.
His eldest son, Michael, who now runs his father's film company, Batjack, makes
clear his father did not confuse his screen personality with his real life.
``He was an actor, not a cowboy,'' he says. ``But he came to represent American
men to people throughout the world and he did possess values and qualities
people look up to - honesty, courage, independence and self reliance. He had
them inside him and he was able to project them onto the screen.''
Michael Wayne, who looks like his father, although not so tall, has just
restored Hondo, the first film Wayne made as an independent producer. It has
clearly affinities with Shane - lone woman living on a lonelty ranch with her
small son falls in love with handsome drifter - although none the worse for
that, it is being released on video.
Made in 1953 in a normal and a 3D version, as some of the shots show, Hondo has
not been seen for 16 years. Wayne was not at the peak of his career, because
his career was remarkably consistent in its success, but in his prime at the
time. When it was released on video last year in the United States it sold
550,000 copies, an amazing sale for a film starring a man who died 16 years
ago. But Wayne's appeal has never waned with the public.
``We have Harris polls in the United States and in the last two he was second
only to Clint Eastwood as America's favourite actor,'' Michael says. ``He beat
Cruise, Schwarzenegger, Stallone and whoever else there is. I find that
amazing.''
In Hondo, Wayne's co-stars are Geraldine Page, making her Hollywood debut and
gaining the first of her eight Academy Award nominations, and as his sidekick,
the wonder-dog, Lassie. It is a classic Western in which Wayne, as Hondo Lane,
utters one of those lines everyone remembers and everyone gets wrong, a line
which sums up the character he played so often on the screen: ``A man ought to
do what he thinks best.''
It was one of his favourite films, although the fact it was his first as
producer at a time when actors were thought unfit to tackle such roles, might
have had something to do with that. Hondo, which Hollywood had hoped might
fail, also proved one of the fastest in cinema history to pay out, recovering
its costs in the first eight weeks.
Michael says his father had told him the film he was proudest of was The Quiet
Man, not because of his own performance, but because everyone in it was so
good. He had also liked The Searchers, although he had always felt John Ford's
film did not receive the recognition it merited from the Academy, and was proud
of the Pacific war film, The Sands of Iwo Jima.
As for Hondo, that was the film in which he felt he had looked his best. But in
a career that started in silent films and during which he made over 150 films
it was hard for him to pick out favourites.
Michael preferred his father playing bad guys, and cites The Searchers, The
Sands of Iwo Jima and Red River. ``He played those roles with such
conviction,'' he says.
In fact, the roles are not so much those of bad guys, as of men with flawed
characters who are redeemed. He insists his father's screen persona was not all
that different from his real life one, unlike some Hollywood stars revealed as
having been anything but the kind, honest, generous, loving men they played to
public acclaim.
The film has been out of circulation for various reasons, chief among which was
that the original negative had been damaged by flood water in the vault where
it was kept.
``Restoration took a year,'' Michael says. ``It now looks like a brand new
film. It has only been shown on television twice in the last 35 years and if
you are under 25 you will never have had an opportunity to see it, so, to all
intents, it is a new film. The views it expresses about women and native
Americans are also amazingly contemporary even although it is now forty years
old.''
He says Wayne, although he ``drank hard, played hard and never did anything
half way,'' was a family man who took his children on the set with him and made
them work.
``We got to visit him during the summer on location, which is why a lot of us
gravitated into the film business, and we would get little jobs to do,'' he
says. ``On Hondo I was a gofer and had to look after the horses and the extras.
I ended up walking round with an attache case full of money to pay the Indians,
who had to be paid daily.''
As for Wayne the family man, guess who decorated the Christmas tree? Big John.
What about his father's reputation for holding extreme right-wing views?
HE replies: "John said if you were not liberal when you were young you had no
heart, and if you were not conservative when you were old you had no brain,''
Michael replies. ``He said it was the world around which had changed and he
felt he was a liberal. But he did have very strong views. He would, however,
listen to what people said. He once told me: `I cannot get any liberals to
listen to me.' He felt he was a liberal in the classical sense of the word and
he did not always vote the same way. You could not peg him exactly. He was
conservative in economic matters and very liberal in social matters.''
Big John really was big. He was 6ft 4in tall which, Michael says, presented
problems for some of his co-stars, film actors being notorious for being
vertically challenged.
``He also had the constitution of a bull,'' Michael says. ``Some people said he
drank enough to float a battle ship. On Hondo we had three days out when we
could not work because of some Mexican public holidays, so the cast and crew
ran on tequila and played poker for the three days. John won all the money, and
ended up winning Lassie and the other eight stand-in Lassies, as well as his
station wagon, from Rudd Wertzheimer, who trained the dogs. It was hot and he
made Rudd suffer for three or four days before he gave them back.''
n Hondo, released by VCI, is available in video stores now.
