<HEADLINE>Last four place for Gibson</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>GILLIAN DORRICOTT</BYLINE>
<EDITION>2</EDITION>
<PAGE>32</PAGE>
<RECORDNO>975208554</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
BADMINTON
SCOTTISH champion Anne Gibson moved into the semi-finals of the Scottish Open
yesterday, when she led Tanya Grove 11-3, 5-0 before the English girl retired,
suffering from a migraine, after just 15 minutes.
Gibson was scheduled to have a dress-fitting for her September wedding today,
so sure was she that a semi-final place was outwith her reach.
But she surpassed expectations to outstrip her best performance in the event
and do her Olympic cause a power of good.
``I'm normally at home watching Grandstand on the Saturday of the Scottish
Open,'' said Gibson, who will meet No.1 seed Catrine Bengtsson next.
Bruce Flockhart was not so lucky. He came up against English champion Anders
Nielsen, antagonised by a recent run-in with the Badminton Association of
England, and with a point to prove.
Nielsen destroyed the Scottish champion 15-2, 15-1 in just 20 minutes, wound up
by his dismissal from the England team and the withdrawal of his funding.
GILLIAN DORRICOTT
