<HEADLINE>Open all hours,  and game for a laugh</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>ANVAR KHAN</BYLINE>
<EDITION>3</EDITION>
<PAGE>10</PAGE>
<ARTICLETYPE>Features</ARTICLETYPE>
<FLAG>weekender</FLAG>
<GRAPHIC>Photograph</GRAPHIC>
<RECORDNO>975208555</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
THE carnival is permanently stationed at Blackpool. Residents shop at
Woolworth's and Food Giant alongside the persistent noise of puggies, the sight
of Kiss-Me-Quick hats, and the smell of burger and onions. The only indication
of spiritual wealth is a school for probation officers and a Methodist Church
in the middle of the shopping precinct.
There is a consistent level of child-like immaturity here, borne out by the
names of amenities such as the Tache Niteclub, the Bellyfull Cafe, the Red
Peaches Chinese Restaurant, and the Honeycombe Sizzler Grill, which sounds like
an Elvis haunt in one of his sunny Hawaiian movies.
Blackpool is not unpretentious, it's tacky. It wants your money. But we're not
talking about casual spending. A week in Blackpool, after all, could get you a
fortnight in the Costa del Sol. No, this is where sad people go, where the
miserable go to get depressed. Enjoyment is gauged by how much you can drink,
eat, and lavish on trinkets only those who are used to being ripped off could
muster up enough enthusiasm to buy.
Harry Ramsden's fish and chip parlour on the promenade is always busy, the
waiters show you to a salted tablecloth and a bottle of brown sauce with all
the hush and verve of a French Maitre D'. I don't even want to think that this
could be the case, that Harry's is the Malmaison of the North. Most pubs have a
video karaoke and bingo, and there's always a talent contest in Linekar's Bar,
although you can't imagine anything more glamorous taking place than the
National Gurning Championships, when old men and women take their teeth out and
suck their faces.
Blackpool is an all-purpose venue, not a resort, hosting everything from
ballroom-dancing finals to Tory party conferences. Its most recently-opened
exhibition is The World of Coronation Street. I don't think a town can thrive
when it cannot rear its head above the restraints of working-class, popular
culture.
Here, you have to live with the promise but not the fruition of a good time. It
stultifies the soul. Every time you want to buy chops for tea you have to walk
past a gaping hypermarket selling popcorn and candyfloss, and pubs with
out-of-work brickies as bouncers, with pop songs pumping from the basement into
the street.
Blackpool's on hold. The beach isn't clean because from December to April,
there aren't any visitors to impress. The sea returns everything dumped in it,
secrets wash up on the shore and in Blackpool it's dummy tits and lager cans.
For five months during the off-peak season, the town limps along in a
half-life. On the promenade everyone is anoraked and cold, stopping in the
shut-up doorways of seasonal tourist traps to eat disposable cardboard trays of
chips. And magnificent Blackpool Tower, with its crazy nugget of electric
silver which zips repeatedly around its crown, puts up a ominous hum, like a
combustible generator in Gotham City.
Under Blackpool's umbrella of pleasure, there are people lurking, trying to
scratch a living, by providing more of it. These are independent businessmen
and women with no connection to Sea World or McDonald's. Their trade is housing
passing strangers who stop off for a week or weekend of fun. The Blackpool
landlord and landlady, while the rest of the town is in a constant state of
expectation, are embroiled in overhaul. Theirs is the sharpest perspective on
the town's crowd-pulling habit.
Some guest houses close during the winter, others stay open, a move which
immediately transmits the message that they didn't have a good summer season.
And there is always work going on, as owners of hotels try to improve their
facilities; new carpets, new wardrobes, shinier taps, brighter curtains. Behind
potted, leafy plants and the calm exterior of Reception, there is a back room
or kitchen being taken apart.
The Scots landlord lives in a place where being one step ahead of the game
means being able to lock a toilet to provide standard room accommodation, and
open it again for en suite. The Trentham Hotel is one of many on the prime site
of Albert Road, parallel to a multi-storey car park and walking distance from
the aforementioned burger giants.
McDonald's spend millions researching every spot in every street of every
country they want to sell in. They will only install a fast food joint where
there is enough human traffic and surrounding business to sustain it. Their
logo signifies untapped gold, like an oil rig in the middle of a desert. In
this way, by his proximity to the global octopus, Matt Allan, owner of the
Trentham Hotel, is assured that he has the best number of potential customers
in the town.
Matt Allan, 53, was born in Fife. When he left school he went to work for Rank
Cinemas in Glasgow and Ayr. He ran the Partick Tivoli. He ran a hotel in
Aviemore, complete with bingo and disco. He left for London and Mecca Leisure.
He's been living in England for 28 years and has run the Trentham for eight. To
the companies he worked for, he was a troubleshooter, a man who could implement
enough ideas to get the punters in and paying.
``I've moved 32 times. If you're willing to move and take on a place that's run
down, you get a cut of the profits you make, and I've made a lot of money in my
time.'' Matt's married to Sue, 37, but their relationship looked dodgy for a
while.
``The first year in Blackpool, we nearly went bankrupt. We had to take anything
with two legs and two arms. I nearly threw myself off the pier with the bloody
dog. We just didn't have enough money to get by. Sue went and sat on the wall
one night, during the evening meal, contemplating the same, because we'd had an
argument while cooking together. That's how bad it was.
``People were booking in at eight o' clock at night and I was walking up the
road to get bacon and eggs because we didn't have enough money to carry any
stock. We had beer crates, bricks, and tins of beans holding up the beds. It
was horrific. We survived by opening during the winter; now everybody's doing
it.''
Some Blackpool hoteliers are two years in arrears with their mortgage. One
place tripled in size during the boom in the seventies, but didn't triple in
business. There is a gentleman's agreement on the prices of a stay at each
hotel on the Albert Road, a sort of voluntary monopoly. Matt is one of four who
charge the same amount in the higher bracket.
``There are 3200 establishments like this in Blackpool, there are more beds
here than in Portugal. Twenty years ago people were trapped by train and car.
Now there are planes to take them all over the world. Some landlords forget
that.''
Most guests come twice a year. Eighty-two per cent of business is repeat and
referrals. Matt is the only landlord he knows who's on-line. The others think a
good butty and a warm room are enough for a hotel to stick in the imagination.
He uses the computer to send out material to past residents and therefore
advertises effectively, targeting business. He's managed to unearth guests who
stayed as far back as 1990. And then some.
During their opening year, Sue and Matt advertised the hotel in the Sunday
Post, and an old couple responded by turning up on their doorstep and asking
for a specific two weeks. They couldn't do it. The old lady burst into tears.
Turns out they'd got married in Blackpool 50 years before. ``They'd stayed here
in a certain room,'' says Sue. ``We eventually managed to get them in and they
come here every year. They brought us one of the original bills,'' she says
proudly, ``from Trentham Boarding Establishment 1944.''
In season, from Saturday to Saturday, the Trentham Hotel is full. And people
steal kettles, duvets, curtains, curtain hooks and tie-backs, and TVs. ``You've
got to be trusting,'' says Matt, but last year he caught a boy and a girl
nicking two plants from the main entrance, and his Christmas lights ``don't
last two minutes''.
He now has the hotel entrance on close circuit camera. But the Allans aren't
cynical. Last year, two guys from Clydebank spent so much at the hotel boozing
they ran out of money, so he and Sue decided to lend them #100, thinking they'd
never get it back, but they did, first thing on the Monday.
``I get to know everyone on a first-name basis. You do get attached to
people,'' says Matt. ``A lot of our guests are friendly, they tell us all about
their varicose-vein operations. I've sat in the bar until 3am with blokes going
through a divorce. Bartenders are taking the place of ministers and doctors,
you hear the same story again and again but from a different angle.''
When the season's over, the phone is mobbed by salesman selling double-glazing,
tiles, bed linen, and timeshare. They presume the Blackpool landlord is rich
and they want a slice. ``The past five years we've been the poorest we've ever
been in our life,'' says Matt. ``We've spent the value of the property on the
property again. The next five years is ours.''
Sue begins a typical day by doing the breakfasts, cleaning the kitchen, setting
the dining-room up, changing sheets and tidying the lounge. ``I can't sit down
for more than 15 minutes. Matt says to me, `Why do you eat so fast?' For the
simple reason that I can't sit down for being disturbed.''
While the obvious question forms in my head, Matt volunteers an answer. ``As a
couple it is very difficult to have any kind of relationship, especially on the
sexual side - you have to make an appointment.'' Not so, however, for some
guests. ``You get `the bonkers', as we call them,'' he says, ``booking in and
staying an hour during the afternoon.'' They pay for a night but deposit the
keys when they're finished. Sue changes the sheets and the room is up for grabs
again.
This is completely out of context, and shouldn't be mentioned in the same
breath, but they get a lot of MPs during the Tory conference too. Indeed, the
MPs' wives play bingo with Sue while their husbands get drunk. One lady guest
harangued Phil Gallie, insisting that she had seen him before. She decided that
he was a bus driver on her regular route, and chinned him for trying to argue
otherwise.
``The quality of life, running a hotel, is not particularly good,'' says Matt.
``You get used to working late nights, but I couldn't work nine to five. What
would I do with myself?'' The Allans are due to go on holiday to Lanzarote, but
they don't yet know how to relax.
They survive on the job. When they work, they have a reserve of energy and
aggression which allows them to fool around and have a laugh. Sue's speciality
is a plastic fried egg on a breakfast plate, especially for the man with the
hangover, usually placed with his wife's encouragement. This is pure Blackpool,
where fun is equal to companionship and a practical joke. And people come here
for a giggle, after all.
n Call the Trentham Hotel, 21 Albert Road, Blackpool FY1 4TA, on 01253 22018
for a free brochure.
</TEXT>
