<HEADLINE>Suffering from a lack of post haste</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>HARRY CONROY</BYLINE>
<EDITION>1</EDITION>
<PAGE>24</PAGE>
<ARTICLETYPE>Features</ARTICLETYPE>
<FLAG>business extra </FLAG>
<GRAPHIC>Photograph</GRAPHIC>
<RECORDNO>975208556</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
IT is not only courier companies for whom Christmas has come early as a result
of the postal strike. Firms such as Edinburgh computer specialist CGC have been
inundated with enquiries and orders for modems (and computers) over the last
few days. It seems everyone now wants to be on the Internet.
Companies have discovered it is a great way to communicate, and it's proving
good business for CGC. It's just a pity it won't be able to take full advantage
of the situation, having just sent out 12,000 catalogues to customers - by post!
Budget breakfast
is just the ticket
HERE'S an opportunity for anyone who wants to quickly get a grasp of what
Tuesday's Budget means. KPMG Tax Advisers will be up at the crack of dawn on
Wednesday, November 29, for a Big Budget Breakfast at Glasgow's Moat House
Hotel.
Guests will enjoy a full Scottish breakfast, light entertainment and expert
comment on what could be the last Budget before the election.
The editor of CA Magazine, Neil Fitzgerald, will give his own individual, and
we are told entertaining, interpretation of Kenneth Clarke's pronouncements.
And, to bring us all down to earth, KPMG tax partners Joy Travers, Donald
Adamson and Campbell Denholm will assess Tuesday's highs and lows as well as
their impact on business.
Attendance is by invitation only, but Business Diary in an exclusive scoop (I
can't remember when I last had one of those) has arranged with KPMG for 10 free
tickets to the Big Budget Breakfast to be made available to our readers. To win
one all you have to do is answer this simple question: who was the last
Scots-born Chancellor? The tickets will go to the first 10 people who give
Fiona Campbell at KPMG the correct answer either by telephoning her on 0141 226
5511, extension 3416, or by fax on 0141 204 3092.
KPMG has also kindly agreed to donate the value of the tickets to the Princess
Royal Trust for Carers, and John Paterson, fundraising director of the charity,
will attend the breakfast to accept the cheque.
Praise for Scots
business skills
SCOTLAND, it seems, was coming in for a lot of praise for its efforts to
increase the level of entrepreneurship in its economy at the Europe 500
conference in Ghent recently.
Present were entrepreneurs and academics not only from Western Europe but also
the former Eastern Bloc countries and the US.
The four-day conference heard how Scotland was leading the way in improving the
business birthrate. Jimmy Gordon and Vera Weisfeld were among those attending
but I am assured it was not a case of self-praise.
Russel Griggs, director of business development at Scottish Enterprise, gave an
address having arrived from Madrid where he had been speaking to European
businesses, and he was pleased with the way Scotland was being viewed by the
European business community.
I was sorry to hear, however, that Ron Lander, chair of the Scottish
Entrepreneur Exchange, became unwell while attending Europe 500, but I am glad
to say he is recovering well and will be returning to Scotland early next week.
Gift of the garb
for the President
HANDS up those readers who said who is that guy with Ross Harper? It is, of
course, President Nelson Mandela of South Africa whom Professor Harper met
while on a visit to Johannesburg in his capacity as president of the
International Bar Association.
Harper led a delegation of 16 African bar leaders on a visit to President
Mandela's private residence in Pretoria.
He presented the President with an International Bar Association tie and a pair
of cufflinks. It was only after making the presentation that he spotted that
President Mandela was dressed in his favoured garb, a traditional African-style
shirt not normally accompanied by a tie or cufflinks!
Old east-west
divide still exists
EUROPE might think we are doing well in the entrepreneur field but George
Hammersley, chief executive of Business Ventures Ltd, is not so sure.
At BVL's annual dinner during the week he told his audience at the Stakis
Grosvenor Hotel in Glasgow: ``What we are finding is that there is no shortage
of quality entrepreneurs in Scotland but there is a marked lack of ideas.
``As a nation, we tend to focus too much on our own backyard, and not take in
what is happening not only in the UK but globally. This parochialism is not
just on a national level either. many would-be businessmen limit their view of
the horizon to what the competition next door is doing.''
I can understand what Hammersley was talking about. I recently had reason to
talk to an Aberdeen firm which had opened an office in Falkirk. When I asked
why Falkirk, I was told it had been advised that if it opened in Edinburgh,
Glasgow companies would not deal with it and vice versa.
Good business for Falkirk.
Return to sender
address unknown
PATRICIA McGhee of PMG Events is wondering if she is a victim of a pre-emptive
strike by postal workers in Edinburgh.
She had attended the opening of the the Edinburgh International Conference
Centre and enjoyed it so much she decided to drop Trevor McCartney, the sales
and marketing director of the EICC, a little letter thanking him.
This she did, carefully addressing it to Mr T McCartney, Sales and Marketing
Director, EICC, Morrison Street, Edinburgh EH3 8EE. You can imagine her
surprise when the letter was returned to her office in Coatbridge by the Royal
Mail marked ``address incomplete''.
Business Diary checked the address with the EICC and it confirmed the postcode
and everything else was correct. The only thing missing was The Exchange, which
should be inserted before Morrison Street. However, I was assured mail arrives
every day (when there isn't a strike on) without this particular addition, as
originally it was not part of the address.
Perhaps the postie couldn't see the EICC for looking at it.
</TEXT>
