<TEXT>
``HEGGIE'S gone soft,'' I wrote in my notebook during Iain Heggie's first
full-length play in five years. I suppose I was thinking back to Clyde Nouveau
and the performance of a pre-Lipstick On Your Collar Douglas Henshall, eyes
staring manically, veins pulsing across his forehead, as the playwright's
unforgiving dialogue took brutal control.
By contrast, this play even brings to mind Alan Ayckbourn, an idea not
discouraged by Laurie Dennett's restrictively dominating back-garden set.
Though tougher, more plausible and less bourgeois than much of Ayckbourn's
stuff, An Experienced Woman treads similar territory - love, lust, truth, lies,
and the way relationships are governed as much by self-deception as by the
deception of others.
Heggie plays a fascinating game, because he knows the line between revealing
sex comedy and complacent sitcom is easily crossed. He deliberately goes into
the grey area where cliche meets truth, picking apart the entanglement of
trivia and profound feeling, deliberately confusing the facts - Is she a
virgin? Did he two-time? - to show us that deeper motivations matter more.
If the play doesn't hit the great comic highs and tragic lows it portends, the
scatter-gun language is still a joy. At its best it bounces like a basketball
between a brilliant league-topping cast - Siobhan Redmond, David Tennant, Jenny
McCrindle, Alastair Galbraith and Alexander Morton - with loads of great
one-liners fuelled by the comic release of characters saying exactly what they
think.
Matthew Lloyd's production is bright, vivid and sharply-timed, even if the
inclusion of an exploding garden shed suggests he thinks he's directing a naff
West End farce. The only shame is you have to travel upwards of 200 miles to
see it.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
