<DOCNO>GH951125-000109</DOCNO>
<DOCID>GH951125-000109</DOCID>
<DATE>951125</DATE>
<HEADLINE>Hendrie takes a standby role</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>BILL SUTHERLAND</BYLINE>
<EDITION>2</EDITION>
<PAGE>33</PAGE>
<RECORDNO>975208558</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
BERWICK Rangers manager Tom Hendrie might not agree with the description that
his team are ``in the middle'' of a slump. He probably would prefer to think
that they are towards the far end of it.
Unhappily, Tuesday night's goalless draw against Queen of the South did nothing
to help the cause, with Mark Wilson being carried off in the first half with a
recurrence of a knee injury. However, granted the severity of the crisis -
Hendrie has had to put himself on the bench - things could be much worse.
Today, Berwick make the long trip to Forfar, whose morale cannot be great after
having just become the first team to lose to their neighbours, Montrose. The
Albion are home to Stranraer.
Stenhousemuir last week became the first visitors to win at Methil, and are at
home today to Clyde. The bottom two, Ayr and Montrose, clash at Somerset Park.
Like East Fife upstairs, third-division leaders Livingston also lost at home
last week and have seen their advantage cut to four points. Jim Leishman's men
should find it easier away to Albion Rovers and it will be interesting to see
how many of their new-found support travel to follow the team.
Cowdenbeath hope to upset the second-placed team, Ross County, when the
Dingwall men visit Fife. High-scoring Caledonian Thistle, shut out last week by
their Highland rivals, should have too much power again for Alloa, while
Brechin City should confirm that Queen's Park are poor travellers.
</TEXT>
