<DOC>
<DOCNO>GH951125-000110</DOCNO>
<DOCID>GH951125-000110</DOCID>
<DATE>951125</DATE>
<HEADLINE>Smash Hits Roadshow, SECC, Glasgow</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>DAVID BELCHER</BYLINE>
<EDITION>1</EDITION>
<PAGE>18</PAGE>
<ARTICLETYPE>Review</ARTICLETYPE>
<RECORDNO>975208559</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
BEING neither 13, female, nor febrile, I spent most of last night trying to
hear myself think above 8000 hormone-addled shriekers. I pondered many topics.
The deliberate mis-spelling inherent to Ultimate Kaos's very name. For more
truly they are Ultimately Kack. And oh, the cruel aptness of a common
abbreviation of Smash Hits' title: the teeny-bop magazine shall forever be
called S. Hits.
More relevantly, I considered the links between Britpop and Britpap. Someone
played All Or Nothing by the god-like Small Faces during last night's interval,
see. Small Faces, 1965; conceived as prefabricated pretty-boy Britpap to make
girlies scream.
And it is with the long-lost Mr Marriott and Co that contemporary Britpop, as
practised by Blur and Supergrass and generally perceived to be A Good Thing,
has its roots.
So who among last night's mammoth bill will spark a critically-acclaimed
movement 30 years hence? Eeh. Um. Ah. Who will still be remembered next week?
Er, well . . . there is a certain lumpy charm to Clock, a boy-girl duo who
plainly care not that their on-stage musical virtuosity makes Milli Vanilli
resemble the Grateful Dead. And one of ASAP's vocalists resembled Firhill
legend Chic Charnley. Only Chic can probably sing better.
And deuce are almost as good as the terminally-clueless Brotherhood of Man.
Some feat, you'll agree.
Ach, I can't kid you, though. Today's Britpap. It's ...it's ... there's a word
I'm looking for. It rhymes with "Brit".
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO>GH951125-000111</DOCNO>
<DOCID>GH951125-000111</DOCID>
<DATE>951125</DATE>
<HEADLINE>HIGHLAND LEAGUE</HEADLINE>
<EDITION>2</EDITION>
<PAGE>33</PAGE>
<RECORDNO>975208560</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
HUNTLY assistant manager Willie Lawson yesterday defended player-manager Doug
Rougvie amid claims the former Aberdeen and Chelsea star lacks finesse in
man-management.
Lawson scorned suggestions Huntly are on the slide under Rougvie's leadership,
and stressed this week's walk-out by Brian Thomson, who has scored 149 goals in
five seasons at Christie Park, was an isolated incident. The champions face
title-challengers Keith today in a derby match.
Lawson said: ``Doug has taken us to the top of the league, we've won the
Highland League Cup, and under his leadership, we can win the treble.''
Rougvie misses today's tie because of flu, while Huntly are also without
suspended Eddie Copland and Alan Selbie. Steve Gray is back after serving a
two-match ban, but Arthur Murphy is out with cartilage trouble.
</TEXT>
