<DOC>
<DOCNO>GH951125-000112</DOCNO>
<DOCID>GH951125-000112</DOCID>
<DATE>951125</DATE>
<HEADLINE>Front-line chairmen are determined to show fans they are on the ball Rangers still able to profit from loss</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>KEN GALLACHER</BYLINE>
<EDITION>2</EDITION>
<PAGE>34</PAGE>
<GRAPHIC>Photograph</GRAPHIC>
<RECORDNO>975208561</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
RANGERS remain undaunted in their search for success despite gloomy results in
the Champions' League, and they are already being given huge backing from their
support as they attempt to build a side which can add European success to their
many triumphs at domestic level.
The signing of Brazilian striker Jardel from the South American champions,
Gremio, has been agreed, and he will be at Ibrox early in the New Year to begin
his premier division career.
More than that, the champions will add further to their squad because of the
immense increase in turnover they are experiencing this season.
While they have failed on the field in the Champions' League, they have been
able to draw in more than #5m from their three home games, television receipts,
and the payout from the European Union.
I understand that gives Rangers a profit of #4m and allied to their new Nike
deal and increased gates for their domestic games, their annual turnover could
reach an astonishing #30m over the financial year. Much of that money will be
ploughed into buying new players.
Jardel, who scored 41 goals in 49 games for the Brazilian champions in their
league programme, is, unusually for a Brazilian, in the British mould. That is
what has attracted Rangers.
The 6ft 2in, 22-year-old is powerful in the air and aggressive. The only
problems Rangers have still to clear are those of a work permit, which will not
be a stumbling block for a player of this calibre.
But the worrying thing for the remaining sides in Scottish football is that
chairman David Murray and his manager, Walter Smith, are not ready, this time
round, to wait for the close season and then attempt to fashion a side which
can do well in Europe within a few months.
They want to spend now. And they will do so. Jardel at #2.5m is just a
beginning. At least one more major player will come in to boost Rangers in
their title bid and then be allowed to settle into the squad before Europe
looms once more.
The money is there. And the money will be spent. Scottish football will be left
looking on in envy at just what the Champions' League can produce even when you
are less than successful. It is, quite simply, a passport to riches.
For today's trip to Easter Road, the champions have a number of their
first-team squad suffering from injuries, some serious, others not, but all of
them enough to stop Smith naming a pool of players for the match against Hibs.
Yesterday, Smith ruled out Ian Ferguson and indicated that Stuart McCall was
very doubtful, then limited himself to talking in general terms about the game
itself.
``Hibs are still sitting third in the table,'' he said, ``and they are a team
we always thought would be in there challenging at the top. Nothing so far has
changed that view for me, but we want to go there and get a result. It still
rankles that they beat us at Ibrox and we would like to turn that result round.
``However, it will not be easy. It is always a difficult place to win points
for us. But I doubt if the midweek result will affect the players. If there was
going to be any way their confidence was to be affected, then it would have
happened before this. As it stands, our premier division form has been very
good and we want that to continue.
``We have had a couple of home games, now we face two tough away games and we
want to win them.''
Hibs will have Michael O'Neill back after suspension, although the Northern
Ireland man will begin another three-game ban soon. Still, he is a big occasion
player and nothing comes much bigger for Hibs than a visit from the Ibrox club.
Manager Alex Miller said: ``If we are to get a result then we will have to make
Rangers work. And we have to make them work hard. They know they can never just
come here and get a result, and we will have to prove that to them again.''
If they can do that, then Hibs may open up the race for the title. If they fail
to repeat their early season result at Ibrox, the title could become a dogfight
between Rangers and their Old Firm rivals, Celtic.
What is essential for Miller and his men today, however, is making sure that
they can keep themselves involved in that battle at the top. Not only for
themselves, but for all of Scottish football.
</TEXT>
