<DATE>951125</DATE>
<HEADLINE>Lyon's strong message in presidential contest</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>DAN BUGLASS</BYLINE>
<EDITION>1</EDITION>
<PAGE>26</PAGE>
<RECORDNO>975208562</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
THE race to succeed John Ross as president of the National Farmers Union of
Scotland is hotting up with the young pretender, George Lyon, of Bute, setting
the pace.
Mr Lyon, who announced his candidacy at the November council meeting, is
challenging the two vice-presidents, Sandy Mole and Stewart Whiteford, with a
radical manifesto designed to take the union and its 17,000 members into the
next century.
Mr Lyon is part-way through a series of at least 14 speaking arrangements aimed
at getting his message across to the grass roots of the union whose views he
believes are too often ignored. Speaking in the Borders, Mr Lyon said:
``Frequently we have been both backward and inward looking. I want to change
that and put the union on a more pro-active footing.''
Mr Lyon reckoned that the CAP will change after 2000 as the Gatt package on
world trade begins to bite, and that Scottish agriculture must be ready for big
changes and a more competitive era.
Mr Lyon also said he wished to see the NFU become more involved in marketing
the industry.
Environmental and welfare issues, claimed Mr Lyon, were likely to be even more
important. He said: ``I see this as more of an opportunity, but we have to
build bridges with the mainstream organiations and make them our allies. We
have to get out there and talk to them and let them know what Scottish farming
is all about.''
The lobbying between the three candidates will continue until the union's
annual meeting in Ayr next March, but of more immediate concern to Mr Lyon is
the Government's consultative paper on animal transport and welfare.
</TEXT>
