<DATE>951125</DATE>
<HEADLINE>Research head predicts phasing out by 2000 EU warning over milk quota system</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>ROBERT ROSS FARMING EDITOR</BYLINE>
<EDITION>1</EDITION>
<PAGE>26</PAGE>
<RECORDNO>975208563</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
THE system of milk quotas is beginning to look increasingly inconsistent with
European Commission thinking on how the Common Agricultural Policy should
evolve, according to Jim Ward, head of agricultural research with land agents
Savills.
Cuts in milk support prices, together with the phasing out of quotas after the
year 2000, is an increasingly likely prospect, he suggests in his firm's latest
monthly CAP briefing.
``The combination of quotas and high milk prices does not sit comfortably with
farm commissioner Franz Fischler's new emphasis on participation in the growth
of world trade and the importance of competitiveness and the need to export
without subsidies,'' he said.
``The quota system could be retained but the Gatt constraint is likely to force
reductions in quota and thus higher prices. Loosening the quota system via
cross-border trading is a political non-starter and two-tier quota on the sugar
beet model appears to be too difficult to administer and too open to fraud for
it to gain widespread political support.''
The remaining option, he suggests, is to cut intervention prices, probably with
compensation, and to phase out quotas over a period of about five years from
the year 2000.
``Remembering that Franz Fischler has a preference for supporting small farming
units, and that previous reforms have either introduced or attempted to
introduce capping of compensation, there is a good case for maintaining as many
separate dairy businesses as possible.''
Mr Ward reports persistent speculation that there will an effective 1% milk
quota increase this year - via a technical adjustment to butterfat
calculations. ``The official Commission line is that only the Dutch are in
favour and little support is expected from other members states or the
Commission,'' he added.
Any threat to the quota system will be taken seriously by the dairy industry
where quotas have become a valuable asset capable of being traded in their own
right. They have become the means whereby farmers have been able to consider
early retiral either through selling quota or leasing it out to produce a
regular income without the seven-days-a-week hassle of dairy farming.
Out of the quota system has grown a quota market, providing an additional
source of business for brokers.
The concept of quotas has not been without its critics. One regular complaint
is that quotas, and the values attached to them, make it difficult for new
entrants to get a start in farming, especially in the dairy and sheep sectors.
The CAP briefing points out that Commissioner Fischler's views on the need for
reform are in marked contrast to what was the official Commission line earlier
in the year - that what was required was a fine tuning of a successfully
reformed CAP.
The new emphasis could mean less price support, separate and transparent income
support, and a goal of integrated rural development. There is an implication
that environmental and income support should become a member state
responsibility.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO>GH951125-000115</DOCNO>
<DOCID>GH951125-000115</DOCID>
<DATE>951125</DATE>
<HEADLINE>Talks on offal disposal levy</HEADLINE>
<EDITION>1</EDITION>
<PAGE>26</PAGE>
<RECORDNO>975208564</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
REPRESENTATIVES of meat companies and livestock auctioneers are to meet in
Edinburgh today for talks on how the disposal of specified bovine offal (SBO)
should be financed.
Special measures for disposal - as part of the BSE eradication process - have
been costing abattoirs an average of #7 per animal. The meat companies'
proposal that #3.50 per animal should be deducted by auctioneers from the
selling price caused a rift between meat companies, auctioneers, and farmers.
One attempt at negotiation failed earlier this week when a meeting in
Birmingham was cancelled. Auctioneers and meat companies agree the problem
affects all the industry and that an all-industry solution would be best.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO>GH951125-000116</DOCNO>
<DOCID>GH951125-000116</DOCID>
<DATE>951125</DATE>
<HEADLINE>Plastics supplier cast from unique mould</HEADLINE>
<EDITION>1</EDITION>
<PAGE>24</PAGE>
<ARTICLETYPE>Features</ARTICLETYPE>
<FLAG>business extra</FLAG>
<GRAPHIC>Photograph</GRAPHIC>
<RECORDNO>975208565</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
TEN years ago there was scarcely a plastics industry in Scotland. Then, with
the massive expansion of foreign investment in plastics-using industries in the
Central Belt, great opportunities opened up for specialist manufacturers.
Blazing a trail as Scotland's number one supplier of plastic injection moulding
in a full range of engineering thermoplastics is Inchinnan-based Silleck
Mouldings (Scotland), November's TrailBlazer of the month.
John Adams, Silleck's managing director, has presided over a number of
trailblazing achievements, which are all the more creditable given that, as
part of a group which included three operations bought by its management in
1983, their holding company went into receivership in 1992.
The engineering company EIS bought the two profitable Silleck companies, one in
Stockton-on-Tees, the other at Inchinnan. A third operation, in East Kilbride,
was acquired by another group but closed down within six months.
Since then one of the keys to Silleck's success has been capital investment by
EIS. Close to #4m has been put in since January 1993. This has helped it more
than double its annual turnover of #5m to an estimated #11.5m for 1995 and to
double its factory production size.
It has also allowed the company to buy state-of-the-art machinery: top of the
range robotics equipment, milling machines linked with auto CAD, and material
handling systems which are second to none. In two years, it has gone from
having 24 moulding machines to 48.
The holding company's investment in capital intensive equipment has been
accompanied by a well-justified hands-off approach to local management. Silleck
Inchinnan has driven all its own achievements, says John Adams - it operates
entirely independently.
EIS's investment in automation has not only increased the company's capacity,
but has also enabled it to produce a wide range of plastic components in a
variety of materials.
One new investment with which Adams is particularly pleased is a 20-tonne,
40-foot storage container. It has improved cost effectiveness of the company's
bulk material handling enormously. Silleck is the first plastics company in
Europe to use this in preference to the more traditional silos.
Around 90% of Silleck's business is within 50 miles of Inchinnan, so it can
easily supply quantities at the required quality with speed and flexibility to
customers who are themselves mostly expanding exporters to a world market. The
machinery operates round the clock, seven days a week, so orders can be
processed and delivered, when necessary, within 24 hours.
Because plastics moulding is such a new industry there is a skills shortage.
Adams is justifiably proud of Silleck's training record. It is the first
Scottish plastics firm to have an organised training scheme recognised by the
British Plastics Training Board. Each year it takes on a number of apprentice
moulding technicians and toolroom engineers. Among the 260 staff, it has the
most highly qualified moulding technologists in Scotland.
``Silleck Moulding impressed the judges by its spectacular growth, its
commitment to training, the investment in state-of-the-art technology and the
way it has re-organised and developed its facilities using best practice from
all over the world,'' comments John Ker, head of entrepreneurial services at
Ernst &amp; Young's Glasgow office. ``It is a worthy winner for November.''
The award and how to enter
The scheme is a joint initiative of The Herald and Ernst &amp; Young, business and
financial advisers, to recognise organisations which demonstrate innovation and
ingenuity in their operations and procedures. Forms can be obtained by sending
in the coupon below.
Entries should be based on one or a combination of:
innovation/ingenuity
business performance
product/service quality
management calibre
marketing flair
contribution to the local/Scottish economy
Rewards
The monthly winner will be presented with an award certificate and will be
featured in an article. The overall TrailBlazer of the Year will send a company
specialist on an agreed specialist management training course at the renowned
Harvard Business School.
