<DATE>951125</DATE>
<HEADLINE>Quick chance for leaders to patch up their bruises</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>HUGH McKINLAY</BYLINE>
<EDITION>2</EDITION>
<PAGE>33</PAGE>
<RECORDNO>975208566</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
INJURIES have hit the headlines as far as the first-division leaders,
Dunfermline, and a few others, are concerned. But bruised egos after last
week's results probably have required psychology rather than physiotherapy, as
preparation for today's matches.
Dundee United, for example, might be expected to be on a downer after last
week's derby defeat. No chance, according to coach Maurice Malpas.
The fact that their neighbours are involved in a cup final at Hampden which may
see European football arrive just down the road from Tannadice, will add steel
to their visit to Broadwood to face an equally thrawn Airdrie side whose lack
of goals have given them their major problems so far.
Take your pick for a result from that one, although Malpas admitted yesterday:
``We have got last week out of our system, but we know Airdrie will be
difficult.''
Dunfermline manager Bert Paton has good news for a change. Back come skipper
Norrie McCathie, Allan Moore, Hamish French, and Ivo den Biemen. Marc Millar
also looks a starter, but striker Stewart Petrie is trying to recover from flu.
Ryan Hegarty, who made such an impression against St Johnstone last week, has
been signed after having scored in Dunfermline reserves' 6-1 hammering of
Cowdenbeath. Still better news is that Andy Smith and Brian Rice also soon will
be available, Smith being the long-term broken-leg victim who could turn round
the Fifers' fortunes if he can find again the form that made him such a
favourite with the fans at Airdrie.
The visitors to East End Park today are Morton, who have had to be treated for
bruised egos from last week's home derby defeat by St Mirren.
Peter Cormack is suspended, defender Steve McCahill faces a fitness test, and
manager Allan McGraw puts his trust in Craig McPherson in midfield for his full
first-team debut. Filling the Derek McInnes gap is a big task for anyone.
St Johnstone are at Clydebank, and trying for their fourth straight victory -
dare manager Paul Sturrock hope for such a feat - while the resurgence of St
Mirren should, on paper, take care of Hamilton at Love Street.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO>GH951125-000118</DOCNO>
<DOCID>GH951125-000118</DOCID>
<DATE>951125</DATE>
<HEADLINE>Greenkeeper sees red at Norman's criticism</HEADLINE>
<EDITION>2</EDITION>
<PAGE>32</PAGE>
<GRAPHIC>Photograph</GRAPHIC>
<RECORDNO>975208567</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
GREG Norman came under fire from course superintendent Graeme Grant yesterday
on the second day of the Heineken Australian Open at Kingston Heath.
Following criticism by Norman over the pace of the greens, Grant said there was
a lack of understanding of what he and his team were trying to do, and added:
``He's made it very difficult for me and my staff. They were upset, concerned
and demotivated - and very hurt.''
Norman had reckoned the greens were faster than Augusta National. ``Some of
them must have been 15 on the stimpmeter,'' he claimed.
``They were under 12,'' Grant fumed, ``and if there were any nightmarish putts,
as he claimed, there are places you shouldn't be on these greens. It's down to
him to hit the ball in the right place.''
Norman, who had a better day yesterday with a 69 that included 31 putts, said
the course was in great shape and he was pleased to be back in contention ``on
a course I enjoy.'' His total of 141, three under par, left him alongside John
Daly, three behind the leader, fellow Australian Peter McWhinney.
Daly led on seven under par after eight birdies in the first 14 holes including
six in a row from the fourth. ``I don't know how the hell I did that,'' he
said. Then he bombed with four bogeys. ``I don't know where they came from
either,'' he smiled. Leading scores (Australians unless stated):
