<DATE>951125</DATE>
<HEADLINE>LET US SPEAK IN TONGUES</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>JOHN HODGERT</BYLINE>
<EDITION>1</EDITION>
<PAGE>19</PAGE>
<ARTICLETYPE>Features</ARTICLETYPE>
<GRAPHIC>Illustration</GRAPHIC>
<RECORDNO>975208568</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
MIBBIE MacDiarmid's drunk man wisnae sae drunk efter aw when he went on tae say
``a miracle's oor only chance'' an he wisnae referrin tae the holy grail o
Scotland's World Cup hopes, but the need for a miracle tae rekinnle oor
cultural identity an belief in oorsels as a nation. Is a miracle indeed oor ane
an only hope?
As we pey tribute tae auld Saunt Aundra at this time o year, it's shairly time
tae reflect on the state o Scotland the day, an tae ask whit dae we really feel
aboot oor wee country an whit does it really mean tae caw oorsels Scots? Dae we
no hae enough confidence on oorsels tae dae withoot miracles, or are we still
wannerin roun in circles, lik the lost tribes o Israel, wi the pessimists
wailin ``this is oor fate, we maun dree oor weird?'' An a gey weird lot we are
tae!
Thinkin aboot the need for miracles shoud remind us St Aundra widnae blate at
workin a miracle or twa, an mibbie we coud dae wi some o his divine
intervention the day. For a stert he is the maist symbolic patron saint o the
state o Scotland an Scottish identity in aw its contradictions. Efter awe,
we've aye had oor crosses to bear throughoot history, wi steyin next tae the
English, never mind haein tae pit up wi ane anither.
But oor flag reminds us tae o a crossroads; mibbie the crossroads o oor
history? An tae tell the truith, we're no aw that shair whaur we go fe here,
sae in the meantime we'll just byde whaur we are, an argue aboot whit wid be
the best road tae tak, or blame ithers that we're nae further furrit. Lik the
tribes o Israel we've been here afore, an in fact legend has it we are the
loast tribe!
Yet mibbie Aundra's auld cross can be seen as an intersection? But is that no a
kinna ambiguous symbol: as lines gaun oot in opposite directions fae the
centre, a symbol o a nation pouin in different directions at the same time an
gaun nawwhaur, or is it actually possible tae see the intersection as fower
lines meetin in the centre an thus a symbol o unity?
We are nae dout a puzzle tae ither nations: a nation withoot a state that
cannae, or mibbie disnae want tae, agree about whit kinna political expression
oor sense o nationhood shoud hae. While we're often fanatical supporters o oor
national teams, especially agin the English, are we really as Jim Sillars says,
90 meenit patriots? Or is it jist we cannae get the gither tae agree aboot
onythin ither than supportin a daurk blue jersey?
Is it at aw possible tae reconcile at least some o oor differences, an fin
somethin we can aw agree aboot, or is that somethin that wid need no just wan
miracle, but a hail bagfu, mair than een a Michael Scott or Merlin coud've
managed? As Willie    McIlvanney says, there's nuthin mair divisive in Scottish
politics than a call for unity!
If we really are doomed aye tae disagree, mibbie we are in sair need o
miracles. But jist haud on a meenit! Think o the wey oor tartan tribes o fitba
supporters hae brocht aboot a miraculous transformation in oor image: nae
langer are we seen as hordes o alcoholic Huns, but as the best behaved
frienliest fans in Europe, an that's official! Even if some o oor scaffie tykes
cannae afford tae support the team, nae maitter; it's nearly enough tae mak us
believe in miracles efter aw, an it's definitely wan up on the English!
Yet, a suppose we hae tae gie the English their due. Whaur wid we be withoot
thaim? For a stert, wha else wid we hae tae blame? For if it's no easy tae
define oor identity in a positive sense, it's aye easy enough in a negative
wey: we arenae English! Furthermair, is it no pairtly thanks tae thaim that we
hae twa o oor greatest claims tae fame in world history?
Naw, I'm no referrin tae the invention o fitba an gowf, but furstly tae the
fact Edward I, ``hammer o the Scots'', hammered us, in mair weys than ane,
intae a nation, though it taen a Bruce tae hammer oot aw oor differences an mak
us fecht tegither tae become the furst nation in history tae assert oor richt
tae exist as a fre an independent nation.
An the secont claim? We wir without a dout, the furst nation tae vote itself
oot o existence as an independent nation, even if it wis wi a wee bit o help
fae English gowd tae persuade mony o oor guid Scots Lords (``sic a parcel o
rogues'') o the economic advantages o the Union. Twa fursts in world history!
We arra peepul, eh?
Whither this entitles us tae be seen as unique or uniquely daft, an whether the
Union has brocht us mair advantages than disadvantages, we can argue aboot till
we're tartan in the face, but if we jist leuk at the history o Nor sea ile an
gas owre the last twenty year, or leuk furrit intae the twenty furst century,
it's nou as obvious as clabber on a coo's erse that we hae buin asked tae
swalla lees that Goebbels wid hae been prood of: eg, that there wisnae aw that
much ile there onywey, an it wid suin run oot, especially if we voted for
independence, an that we get faur mair than oor share o Government spendin etc.
Only a numptie coud believe whids o this size, but then mibbie we are a nation
o numpties, for a helluva lot o us hinnae yet waukent up tae the fact that they
are lees at aw! Sae mibbie that diagonal cross is ment tae be vertical, an jist
got cowped on its side, a bit lik the state o Scotland the day? For whit ither
country has discovert ile an edit up worse aff?
Whiteer we think aboot the economics o the Union, it's gey hard tae avoid the
fact the cultural legacy wis near fatal. Insteid o benefittin fae the positive
influences o a kizzen language an culture, we suffered the humiliation an
repression o cultural imperialism an bein brainwasht intae thinkin aw oor
native languages, Gaelic an Scots, wir only fit for barbarians an sheuch
howkers, no for educatit folk at aw. Nae wunner we still hae teachers an
parents, an ``odd'' judges whaw shoud ken better, a perpetuatin ignorance an
prejudice aboot ony form a Lowland Scots, rural or urban. Withoot a doubt, the
``dinnae say ay'' mentality is deeply implanted intae maist Scots' heids lik a
genetic tumour.
Yet mibbie language is in fact the key, for in some weys it's oor language that
maks us whit we are, or at least tries tae say whit we are; say mibbie language
hauds the key tae oor identity? While plenty o folk hae pruived Edwin Muir
wrang aboot only bein able tae think in English but feel in Scots, mibbie this
is still at the root o mony o oor problems, baith individually an as a nation.
An if we are leukin for miracles, shairly it's nuthin short o miraculous, that
in spite o aw the forces tryin tae kill aff the Scots tongue for the past two
thrie hunner year, it is faur fae deid, for its ruits are gey deep, an its
words spread lik thistle seeds on every braith o win.
An whit further pruif o the resilience o Scotland's tongues dae we need than
the fact we hae seen a great flooerin o Scottish Literature an culture in this
century, expressin itsel in aw oor leids, Gaelic, Scots, an English, or a
mixture o twa or even sometimes thrie o them, an a lot mair o this is nou bein
taught in oor schuils. Even in the Scottish Education Depairtment things are
chyngin, for we noo hae a glisk o ane or twa sma miracles at work there, for
believe or no it is in fact S.E.D. policy tae encourage the uise o Scots in oor
schuils.
Whit we really need though is tae stert seein oor linguistic diversity an
flexibility as a great cultural asset, no as a problem, an tae equip oor
students an teachers tae cope we genuine bilingual education, sae that aw Scots
weans learn tae read an write in Gaelic or Scots as weel as English. Thus we
coud hae a genuinely independent Scottish educational system tae be prood o,
ane that celebrates the rich linguistic heritage o a Scotland o mony different
tongues, includin the new anes brocht here bi       mair recent incomers, a
genuine multi-   cultural Scotland. If ither wee countries or minority cultures
can manage this, why no Scotland?
At the same time it micht offer us a model o hou we shoud see oorsels an hou we
shoud relate tae ithers: in ither words a culture that values its ain diversity
an appreciates that diversity is whit maks us interestin as individuals an as a
species, a country that values its ain culture an identity, withoot thinkin
itsel inferior or superior tae ithers; for it's only fae a genuine love o ye
ain culture an whit maks ye byordinair, that yet can develop a love an respect
o whit maks ither folk unique, an sae value their differences as important an
complementary tae yer ain culture; for if ye dinnae love yer ain folk, wi aw
their imperfections, ye cannie love the rest o the world.
Yet accordin tae the heid boy o the Labour pairty, Tony Blair, ``Nationalism,
no matter how it is dressed up, always leads to narrow chauvinism.'' If this is
representative o the deal depth o his thinkin then he clearly needs tae think a
lot less in sounbites an cliches. Chauvinism is a legacy o Imperialism, a
pervertit form o Nationalism that leuks doon on ithers as inferior, a twin o
racialism, often a legacy o imperialism, somethin that Britain still hasnae
managed tae shake aff.
An ironically there wis nae shortage o chauvinistic Union Jack wavin at baith
Labour an Tory Conferences in October, makkin it gey hard tae distinguish ane
fae the ither.
Genuine nationalism is ruitit in a love o yer ain freedom but equally values
ither folk's freedom, an kens richt weel, fae yer ain experience, that
respectin the freedom o wee nations, an minority cultures, is the best wey tae
bring aboot freedom an human richts for the haill world, somethin that
chauvinists, racist, religious or political fanatics, or Empire builders o ony
form, cannae thole or jist dinnae unnerstaun.
Haein the richt tae be oorsels disnae mean turnin inwards an only carin aboot
oorsels, but in learnin tae respect, tolerate an byde in peace wi oor fella
Scots an ither folk, stertin wi oor neebours, especially fae sooth o the
Border. In fact if we stertit blamin thaims a lot less an oorsels a lot mair,
that wid be a furst step in the richt direction, for oor future lies in oor ain
hauns, if we hae the smeddum tae wrastle wi it, no in blamin ithers for oor ain
failins, or in waitin for miracles fae Westminster or God.
A cultural seachynge, even a wee earthquake or twa is whit we'll need tae bring
aw this aboot though, but the signs are there that at least it micht need
somethin short o a miracle. Comin tae terms wi oor language an identity micht
no solve oor political an economic ills, bit it micht at least gie us the
confidence tae stert believin in oorsels as a nation an tae show the rest o the
world, but furstly tae oorsels, that we are stertin tae grew up, or wauken up,
that we hae staggered oot o the mists o Brigadoon, an dinnae need fairytales or
miracles tae survive as a nation. As MacDiarmid's drunk man says: ``Pu Scotland
up an wha can say it winnae bud an blossom tae.''
If it isnae aw clear whit St Aundra's auld cross stauns for as a national flag,
mibbie a thistle plantit in the middle o it wid gie us a faur clearer symbolic
statement aboot the nature o Scotland an a bein a Scot.
Nae dout oor critics coud say that wid jist show whit a prickly lot we are, but
folk that ken mair aboot thistles ken that as weel as jaggy leafs an thorns,
they hae deep ruits, an bonnie wee purple flooers that scatter a hairst o
thristly seeds driftin tae aw the fower airts, an will suin tak ruit again, nae
maitter how puir the syle is, or that when it is cut don, it suin lowps back up
again: a teuch, yirdy, an bonnie symbol for the survival o oor languages and
identity, as weel as the contradictions in oorsels that we sairly need tae
grapple wi, if we are ever tae ``rise an be a nation again'', an no jist sing
aboot it.
Sae jyne me in a toast tae the saltire an the thistle, but whether or no ye
think this has buin jist anither drunk man leukin at the thistle, I'll lea up
tae yersels.
n.John Hodgert is a teacher of English in Ayrshire and is the author of a Scots
language play ``Bessie Dunlop, Witch of Dalry.''
</TEXT>
