<HEADLINE>SCO Chorus, Glasgow City Hall</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>CONRAD WILSON</BYLINE>
<EDITION>1</EDITION>
<PAGE>18</PAGE>
<ARTICLETYPE>Review</ARTICLETYPE>
<RECORDNO>975208569</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
Music
THE Scottish Chamber Orchestra's trip to Japan left a gap in its Scottish
programmes successfully filled this week by the SCO Chorus with a group of
young brass players from the RSAMD. The resultant concert of psalms, motets,
part-songs, and brass pieces, built around a beautifully pure account of
Poulenc's G major Mass, may have lacked audience appeal, to judge by the number
of empty seats in Glasgow last night, but it provided
elcome chance to hear some good music outside the SCO's normal scope.
With the focus firmly on the 40 choristers on an otherwise bare platform, the
Poulenc made a serene impression as it floated and soared towards its ecstatic
Agnus Dei, in which Margaret Stockwell was the admirable solo soprano. The air
of mock lightness with which Poulenc characterised his most serious
compositions was here perfectly judged by the conductor, Timothy
Byram-Wigfield, in a performance of silvery tenderness.
But the solemnity of the Schutz psalms that framed the programme was no less
telling, and the splendour of Ecce Sacerdos, last of a group of Bruckner
motets, resounded grandly in so reverberant a hall.
Unaccompanied choral music by Mendelssohn (sweetly euphonious) and Brahms (more
severe) provided other pleasures. But it was a pity the brass players deleted
their promised performance of Matthew Locke's Musick for His Majestie's
Sackbutts and Cornetts rather than Leonard Salzedo's Divertimento, which in the
context of this programme sounded disappointingly trivial.
</TEXT>
