<DOCNO>GH951125-000121</DOCNO>
<DOCID>GH951125-000121</DOCID>
<DATE>951125</DATE>
<HEADLINE>Turandot, London Coliseum A</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>BENEDICT BROGAN</BYLINE>
<EDITION>1</EDITION>
<PAGE>18</PAGE>
<ARTICLETYPE>Review</ARTICLETYPE>
<RECORDNO>975208570</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
THIS remarkable production comes from the Welsh National Opera, where it
originated in 1994, and English National Opera deserve applause for taking it
on. Visually we are back to the wows of the Coliseum's recent glorious past.
Musically, ditto. But this extraordinary effort fails vocally, and in a way
that can do the company no favours in its present circumstances. A potentially
strong cast falls far short through diction so appalling it made a mockery of
ENO's claim to be opera in English.
Director Christopher Alden, designer Paul Steinberg, and conductor David
Atherton deserved the rave applause they received on opening night, if only for
the excitement. They were booed, even! With primary colours, cool lighting, and
a refreshing simplicity of design, Puccini's tale of the Chinese princess
Turandot and the three riddles she poses to her potential lovers is presented
in clear, delightfully emotional images.
A banner declares ``3 enigmas = death'', the cast are in bright 30s fashions,
and the madness of the Chinese court is relayed in the deliciously
camp-dramatic gesturing of the chorus. The mug-shots of Turandot's 100-plus
previous victims are on display against the curved corrugated-iron backdrop to
remind us of the odds. The ENO orchestra, its horn section spilling over into
the balconies to add a wondrous punch, is on fine form.
Janice Watson stands out as the slave girl Liu, but the rest of the principals
are a disappointment. Edmund Barham as the hero Calaf is weak in voice, and
often indistinct. With Sophia Larson as Turandot they make a wooden pair, arms
akimbo, boring us rigid. And if she's singing in English, then I'm a Chinaman.
</TEXT>
