<DATE>951125</DATE>
<HEADLINE>Telecommunications software firm Atlantech Technology is aiming to be the Microsoft of the 21st century World-beating ambition to communicate</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>ALF YOUNG</BYLINE>
<EDITION>1</EDITION>
<PAGE>24</PAGE>
<ARTICLETYPE>Features</ARTICLETYPE>
<FLAG>business extra</FLAG>
<GRAPHIC>Photograph</GRAPHIC>
<RECORDNO>975208571</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
IT does not happen very often in Scotland, in my experience. The young managing
director of a three-year-old start-up, sitting across the boardroom table, is
talking big. Very big.
``Where are all those new Apples and Microsofts of the 21st century going to
come from?'' he presses. ``Well, we plan to be one of them. We are going to run
hell for leather for dominance in our global marketplace,'' adds David Sibbald,
just to underline that his ambitions for Atlantech Technologies are boundless.
Cumbernauld-based Atlan-tech is in the business of developing network
management software systems for the global telecommunications industry. Its
first major product, AccessVision, is already being supplied to the likes of BT
and Telecom Italia. It hasn't a single customer in Scotland. Even so, from a
standing start in April 1992, Atlantech already employs 35 highly skilled staff
and is heading for sales of #7.5m this financial year.
But Sibbald, a graduate in the late seventies of what is now Glasgow Caledonian
University and an expatriate for most of the following decade, is not content
to become a niche supplier to the telecoms leviathans. He argues that the
revolution in the personal computer industry of the eighties, which saw
Microsoft emerge, within 14 years, as a global corporation with net assets
greater than its Seattle planemaker neighbour Boeing, is about to sweep through
the telecommunications industry in the rest of the nineties and beyond.
``The big players in computers, like IBM and DEC, became fat, dumb and happy in
the eighties. Then along came new aggressive young companies who knocked them
off their perch. Exactly the same thing that happened in computers in the
eighties is happening in telecoms now.
``If ever there was a time and an industry in which to start a company, this is
definitely it. If you get the best people marching to the same drum, you've got
a hell of a chance of succeeding. And we've got some of the best people in the
world working in Atlantech right now.''
This is refreshing, intoxicating stuff even from an entrepreneurial Scot. But
is it just braggadocio? ``You may come back in a few years and find we've
failed,'' Sibbald concedes. ``But we are going to make our mark on this
landscape.''
That's the kind of determined ambition which seldom leaps out of the pages of
business plans or corporate strategies. ``A lot of big companies have
traditional ways of looking at markets,'' he says. ``They analyse market
shares, pricing points, how long before they'll get a return, factors like
that. But that's totally inappropriate for markets that don't even exist right
now. For entrepreneurial companies wrestling with what these markets might look
like, you can't do the analysis. In the end you have to go for the leap of
faith.''
Parts of Atlantech's leap of faith are already bearing fruit. Fibre-optic cable
and digital technology are ensuring that what can happen on a phone line is
much, much more than two people talking to each other. We are well used to
document exchange by fax and buying insurance and other financial services by
phone. And some of us are now exploring the internet.
There is talk of interactive television, video-on-demand, home shopping and
countless other wonders, accessible through the telecoms networks of the
future. Multimedia is the catch-all term. But is David Sibbald convinced that
wired-up existence is what people will want in the first decades of the next
millennium?
``No, I'm not,'' he answers. ``But all the developments that are going to sweep
telecommunications are not held hostage to the public's acceptance of
interactive TV. We know that telecoms in the future will be able to deliver to
larger and larger numbers of people a mass of multimedia data and allow them to
interact with it. We are looking at the common denominators in a lot of these
applications that the software architecture we are developing can address.''
After college Sibbald went to work in South Africa for three years, came back
to London for four more, then headed for San Jose, in the heart of Silicon
Valley, for another two. It's a typical career pattern, he believes, driven by
the dearth of companies in Scotland doing work of a sufficiently challenging
technical nature for the graduates we produce.
And yet, having returned home to start Atlantech with two colleagues, he finds
that one of the biggest constraints on growth is finding more people of the
calibre it needs to pursue its leap of faith. ``There is not a pool of
available talent in Scotland,'' he reports. In the short term Atlantech is
casting its recruitment net around the world. Longer term, he says, the
Scottish education system has got to get its act together.
He has even harsher words for the venture capital community and the UK banks.
``Initially we boot-strapped, using our savings to get off the ground, working
in my bedroom. I was used to meeting venture capitalists in California. But
here the picture is very different. There's an aversion to risk, an aversion to
start-ups and an incredible aversion to anything hi-tech.''
The trio thought of going back to the US and starting there. Instead, they put
their software development work on the back burner and began making some money
by providing American telecoms companies with a technical entre to the European
marketplace.
``That generated some cash, allowed us to employ some people and spin off some
guys to work on our core architecture product.'' By selling skills to Americans
interested in a telecoms foothold in Europe, Atlantech pushed sales to #1.5m.
That gave it the credibility to revisit the venture capitalists. In 1993,
Scottish Enterprise came up with #250,000 of seed capital. More recently, SE
and 3i provided additional backing of #2.2m. Atlantech has just moved into a
modern office block in Cumbernauld's new Broadwood Business Park.
It may, as David Sibbald concedes, all end in tears. But it's great to hear a
young Scot with belief in the technical skills of his team and just enough of a
track record to convince you he's on to something saying: ``The sky's the
limit.''
</TEXT>
