<HEADLINE>Accies asked for inquiry</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>DEREK DOUGLAS</BYLINE>
<EDITION>2</EDITION>
<PAGE>32</PAGE>
<RECORDNO>975208572</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
MELROSE are to press for an investigation into the eye injury suffered by
loose-head prop Mark Ross during their premiership match against Edinburgh
Academicals two weeks ago, writes Derek Douglas.
Ross, who was allegedly punched during the game, had to undergo emergency
surgery on the left eye after a build-up of internal pressure and there were
fears that the eye might have been permanently damaged. He goes to see a
specialist again early next week. The Raeburn place game, which Academicals
lost in the last minute after a series of penalties was also the setting for
coach David Sole's post-match comments when he described the performance of
referee Colin Henderson as having been ``tantamount to cheating''.
Melrose secretary Stuart Henderson said that the club president had contacted
Academicals but as the Edinburgh club appeared to want a formal approach, it
had been decided to write requesting that they investigate the circumstances of
Ross's injury.
q FORMER All Black John Gallagher has given up hope of playing for Harlequins.
Gallagher, who turned professional five years ago when he joined Leeds and last
season played for London Broncos, is desperate to return to his union roots and
has been training with Quins for the last two months. However, the full back
has been told he must serve a 120-day qualification period before he could turn
out for the Quins.
</TEXT>
