<HEADLINE>Couldnt Be Better bet</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>ROBIN COOK</BYLINE>
<EDITION>1</EDITION>
<PAGE>31</PAGE>
<GRAPHIC>Photograph</GRAPHIC>
<RECORDNO>975208574</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
ONE MAN put in the race of his life to win the Hennessy last year and comes to
the start this year after an identical preparation with an impressive run at
the same Ayr meeting.
I tipped him to win last year, but cannot recommend a bet at the outrageously
short odds on offer today.
No horse has won the Hennessy for a decade carrying more than 11 stones, and
favourites have a dire record in this event.
Couldnt Be Better could be the better value at these weights.
He ran well in the early part of his campaign last season and opened his
account for this one with an impressive win over Chatam.
Clifton Beat won over course and distance in October (Stompin Held) and can
score again in the Gerry Feilden Hurdle.
Kissair beat him soundly in the Triumph Hurdle, but Martin Pipe's star appeared
to need his first run last year and prefers a cut in the ground.
Conquering Leader lived up to her name last season, storming home 14 lengths
clear on this course, and her only defeat was a close third at the Festival.
She is weighted to win the Akzo Nobel Hurdle with a big pull on Jibber The
Kibber for a two-length defeat on her reappearance (Silver Wedge well held).
At Newcastle, Absalom's Lady can profit from Mysilv's defection to land the
Fighting Fifth's Hurdle.
David Elsworth's classy mare may be a veteran but last season's campaign was
her most successful, including two wins at Kempton over Large Action and Atours.
With a decent reappearance run behind her, she can outspeed Chief Minister.
Emerald Storm looks like going off at an attractive price in The Ladbroke Chase.
He showed much promise for Nicky Henderson last year and has continued to
progress for Peter Monteith, winning comfortably at Kelso and chasing home
Whaat Fettle last time.
He looks the best of a strong field, though Pims Gunner and Brave Buccaneer
have their chances.
</TEXT>
