<DOC>
<DOCNO>GH951125-000126</DOCNO>
<DOCID>GH951125-000126</DOCID>
<DATE>951125</DATE>
<HEADLINE>Amec's #132m McAlpine bid</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>ANDREW WILSON</BYLINE>
<EDITION>1</EDITION>
<PAGE>21</PAGE>
<RECORDNO>975208575</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
CONSTRUCTION group Alfred McAlpine confirmed yesterday that it has received a
#132m offer from Amec which, in turn, is under threat from engineering giant
Kvaerner of Norway.
In a brief statement, McAlpine said that it would respond to the two for one
offer which values each McAlpine share at 192p when the outcome of the talks
between Amec and Kvaerner were known. On Thursday, Kvaerner raised its long
standing 2% stake in Amec to 12% through a dawn raid at 100p costing #20m.
Amec closed 3p easier at 99p, while McAlpine ended 18p stronger at 159p.
Kvaerner, Europe's largest shipbuilder and owner of the Govan yard in Glasgow
said it would not pay more than the dawn raid price.
The approach has puzzled some on the grounds that, if Kvaerner is interested
primarily in Amec's UK North Sea exposure it would be entering into a
highly-competitive market.
If a deal can be reached, there could be co-operation between the two using
Kvaerner's fire-power and ability to win large contracts to provide comlete
plant installations for rigs where the Amec Matthew Hall subsidiary's expertise
in topside installation would be invaluable as it would also be in power
stations. It has been a leading sub-contractor in the Sizewell B nuclear
station, while the Amec parent's long experience in civil engineering would be
a valuable marketing tool in winning international contracts.
Chief executive Erik Tonseth said that he was surprised that Amec had made its
approach to McAlpine, but he conceded that the picture is now more complicated
than expected. He added that nothing was ruled out.
The Amec move on McAlpine comes after the two companies had been in talks for
some time about co-operation. They have already won a #145m joint consortium
bid to improve the sub-standard A1 between Peterborough and Alconbury where it
branches off towards the M11 and a smaller #35m contract to widen the A417
between Swindon and Gloucester.
McAlpine warned in September that it was contemplating the possibility of
withdrawal from general contracting, with total UK orders down one third.
Interim pre-tax profits amounted to a mere #56,00 on turnover of #361m.
Chief executive Oliver Whitehead, who came into the group after leaving
Babcock, has been squeezed between the family interests and the leading
shareholders - the latter wanting him to find a bidder in a sector which has
far too much capacity.
</TEXT>
