<HEADLINE>Professionalism a distant dream for Scotland's No.1 woman on the baize Given a break, Julie would put personality into potting</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>ian paul</BYLINE>
<EDITION>1</EDITION>
<PAGE>30</PAGE>
<ARTICLETYPE>Profile</ARTICLETYPE>
<GRAPHIC>Photograph</GRAPHIC>
<RECORDNO>975208576</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
VIVACIOUS is not the first adjective that springs to mind when searching for
the right word to describe today's stars of the snooker table. Without
disrespect, there is a seriousness about the champions of the green baize which
would make vivacious about as appropriate as skint.
Perhaps, one day, the lack of ebullience, of the bubbly nature that can be such
a marvellous promoter for any sport, will emerge if the women players can reach
the standard required to break into the higher echelons of the game.
If Julie Gillespie, Scotland's best woman player, were part of the TV circuit
she would fit the bill admirably. Only 5ft 1in, this 20-year-old student at
Strathclyde University has a personality twice that height and, bearing in mind
the stage of evolution which women's snooker has reached, a game to go with it.
Julie would be the first to admit that she is a fair way behind the best in the
women's game, rated 25, let alone the Stephen Hendrys and Ronnie O'Sullivans of
the business, but if there had been a real opportunity to make a living at the
game she might well have had a go at chasing after a place on the highest plane.
That is the problem that faces the women who find they have made fair progress
at the cue-ball game. If they are ever to progress to the top level as a group
they have to face the competition that breeds hardness, skill and concentration
of a type that requires full-time application. There is not enough money around
for the girls to forsake their day jobs.
Yet it could be the game's loss in the long run. Snooker is one of the few
sports where there is no physical advantage, no bonus in muscles, that can
affect the hand and eye skills of the snooker player. Julie Gillespie agrees
that theoretically women could be just as expert under the lights but
acknowledges that it could be a long way off, maybe unattainable.
``There is still a very big gap and even our best players have not been able to
qualify for the later stages of the TV tournaments,'' says this petite young
woman from Doune who is studying maths, statistics and accountancy, ``and I
don't know if it will ever be the case. There are only a couple of
professionals in the real sense among the women, because there is not enough
money around.''
That explains why there will be a good representation of the best women in the
sport today and tomorrow at Spencer's Snooker Club in Stirling, where the Regal
Masters first prize is #1000. Julie is desperately keen to do well at her own
club, the place where she is given immense encouragement and the best of
facilities to try to improve her snooker.
Most of the world ranking players will be there and although her listing at 25
would suggest she will not get very far, the fact that she has managed to take
part in only two of the ranking tournaments is an indication that she might be
a fair bit better than the bare statistics hint.
She would be delighted if she could get to the last 16 . . . ``anything after
that would be a bonus.'' Maybe she could make a few extra bob taking on macho
men who reckon this slim, curly-haired girl would be easy snooker fodder. They
would be making a mistake.
Taking away the professionals at Spencer's, which include the best player in
the world, Stephen Hendry, she reckons there are about five men who are either
better or on a par with her when she is on form. This is confirmed by the fact
that she is in the Spencer's league team, the only woman. ``That fact doesn't
even cross my mind any more. They don't treat me any different.''
Julie hopes to be a chartered accountant when her studies are over, but has not
entirely given up the prospect of taking up the game full-time. ``If women's
snooker should take off in a big way, like golf or tennis, for example, I would
definitely have a go, especially if I had my qualifications behind me.''
Neither of her two sisters has any interest in snooker, nor her mum, and so it
is dad who has to hold up his hand. That is appropriate, as he asked others to
do so often enough when he was a maths teacher, a profession from which he has
taken early retirement. From the beginning Julie's dad has been her chaperon,
coach, opponent and supporter, maybe as much in surprised fascination as
anything else.
Her interest in the game began when the family visited Aberdeen friends where
the wee boy of the house had a small table. Julie tried it, liked it, and
pestered dad and mum to get her a junior 6ft x 3ft table. That, as they all
say, was that.
She and dad were off and running, first playing each other in the house, then
it was down to the local snooker hall, and eventually to Spencer's.
She began to take part in competitions, junior league matches, and soon was
having a go at the world ranking and Scottish ranking tournaments. ``Spencer's
gave me free practice time which helped a lot and that made the difference.''
It was while at school she was able to find time to practise enough to climb
the rankings until she had reached No.13. By then she had to make a choice,
having got the grades she needed at school to go on to university.
``I decided it was not really possible to go full-time, although I was tempted.
If I had thought I could have made it my living I might have not gone to
university. But there just was not enough prize-money around. Since then I have
slipped in the rankings, because I can't find the time to take part in the
ranking competitions. Most of them are down south. Before, when I was at
school, dad used to take me down there.''
Even so, she can remember when there was more cash about than nowadays, and can
recall winning something like #1500 at the Sky World Masters after reaching the
quarter-finals of the mixed doubles.
Julie has the advantage, when she finds time, to practise with top class
players like Billy Snaddon. She can be found at Spencer's three times a week,
sometimes helping out behind the bar between spells, and in the last month as a
result of putting in hard practice feels her standards have recovered a little.
She can't see women catching up with the men in the next 10 years but would
like to be around if it happens. Meanwhile she continues to share her time
between studies and practising. Her boyfriend, a keen footballer, can bank on
only one night a week in her company, but ``is very understanding.''
The fact that she is a class act on the snooker table will come as a surprise
to many of her student pals, although her other friends are well aware of her
night job.
Julie, whose best effort yet in the Regal Masters was to reach the
quarter-finals, has been working hard to get set for this weekend, accompanied
as ever by dad. ``Mum finds it hard to watch. She gets too nervous.''
The Gillespie girl is in good form, winning the Scottish Ladies' Anniversary
tournament at Spencer's last Sunday, but points out that no snooker player can
ever be sure exactly how he or she will play.
Maybe she will surprise herself as well as a few higher rated challengers.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
