<HEADLINE>Collins' respect for Carr</HEADLINE>
<EDITION>1</EDITION>
<PAGE>30</PAGE>
<RECORDNO>975208577</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
BOXING
NIGEL Benn will be an invited VIP ringside guest at The Point in Dublin tonight
- and that should be a pointer to a two-title world super-middleweight showdown
against Steve Collins taking place next spring.
This is certainly no time for the 31-year-old Collins - the ``Celtic Warrior''
- to be outfought by Middlesbrough's unsung Cornelius Carr in the second
defence of the WBO title he wrenched from Chris Eubank in March, and retained
in a return in September.
``I'm not going to insult Cornelius Carr by talking about an upcoming fight
with Nigel Benn. But yes, of course, I have my eye on one,'' said Collins.
``Benn is on record as saying that, now his clash with Roy Jones looks
increasingly unlikely to come about, a fight with me is the one he wants to go
out on. Fine, but he won't be going out on a winning note.''
Carr, 26, has campaigned without attracting any high-profile attention since
turning professional in 1987. He won the British super-middle title by
outscoring James Cook, but gave it up to campaign at middleweight. Now Carr has
gone back to the 12st division for this big chance.
Said Collins: ``Carr may not have fought the kind of guys I've been in with,
but he's still a guy getting his chance at the big time, and that alone is
going to lift him.
``Eubank made the mistake of taking me lightly in our first fight. He thought I
was a stop-off on his world tour. I have no intention of making the same
mistake against Carr.''
q COMMONWEALTH lightweight champion Billy Schwer defends his title against
David Oodhi Tetteh, of Ghana, at Dagenham tonight and should be good enough to
win shortly after the halfway mark.
</TEXT>
