<HEADLINE>Danger of taking biased advice</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>R E Dundas, Christopher Sims , Aidan O'Carroll</BYLINE>
<EDITION>1</EDITION>
<PAGE>23</PAGE>
<ARTICLETYPE>Correspondence</ARTICLETYPE>
<FLAG>personal finance</FLAG>
<GRAPHIC>Illustration</GRAPHIC>
<RECORDNO>975208578</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
q I have inherited #25,000, #15,000 of which I would like to invest in the
medium to long term for capital growth. The remaining #10,000 will be kept
accessible for current use.
It appears to be a minefield out there. I have seen financial advisers from
banks and building societies. Each adviser recommends his own firm's PEP
(#6000) and bond (#9000). Where can I find independent financial advice from
someone who does not benefit from selling his own company products?
I have also visited my lawyer. As I do not want to invest directly in the Stock
Exchange and put all my eggs in one basket, he recommended I invest the #15,000
in a small portfolio of investment trusts.
My current investments are a Tessa, SAYE and paying into my company's AVCs. I
am a taxpayer in full-time work. I may give up work within the next 18 months
to start a family and may not return, or may only do so part-time. A PEP
interests me, but if I give up work soon and become a non-taxpayer, is it worth
starting one, or would I be better with the investment trusts? Or do you have
another suggestion?
n For the most part you seem to have been shopping in the wrong places. Your
advice has not been independent since you have been talking to advisers tied to
their own products. They should have told you that they were not in a position
to recommend the products of other companies, even if they were better suited
to your needs.
There are independent financial advisers who are not tied to the products of
one company, but for the most part they are not High Street names. Fortunately,
you have already obtained some excellent advice from your solicitor.
Given the sum of money you have at your disposal and the fact that you are a
basic rate taxpayer, any benefits you obtained from a PEP might be largely
offset by the management charges. In any event a PEP is only as good as its
underlying investments. Many have disappointing track records.
By contrast, most investment trusts sport superior performances over the medium
to long term and provide an ideal way for the small investor to build up
capital. Dividends are generally small, so the tax paid is small. You would be
able to reclaim the dividend tax credits if you became a non-taxpayer.
Similarly, you would not need to pay tax on the interest earned on your #10,000
to be kept accessible for current use.
However, it is only fair to point out that investment trust shares are quoted
on the Stock Exchange. They differ from the shares of commercial and industrial
companies in that the capital is invested in a wide spread of other shares,
often overseas as well as in the UK. In that sense they are less risky than
other types of equity investment.
You make no mention of a mortgage, but if you have one you might want to use
some of your inheritance to reduce it, especially if at some stage there would
only be one income to service it. In any event, you are wise to allocate some
of your funds to long-term capital growth.
q I have recently subscribed to Commercial Union's Monthly Income Plus PEP on
advice from my financial adviser. It is my intention that any income be
reinvested for the foreseeable future. I have subsequently read that corporate
bond PEPs are designed principally for income seekers and are not the best use
of funds seeking growth. Should I be concerned about this or, in general terms,
does reinvesting income amount to the same thing as investing for growth?
n If you do not intend to take the income for some years then your adviser's
choice of fund is rather odd, unless you specifically wanted a lower risk
investment. Corporate bonds have a lower risk profile than shares, though they
are not risk-free and are certainly riskier than gilts.
So letting the fund roll-up within a PEP would be a legitimate strategy for the
risk-averse, though monthly income, the extra costs of which often mean a lower
yield, would certainly not be necessary. However, if you would not need the
capital for, say, five years you could afford to invest in funds targeting
capital growth. Outside of a PEP, tax factors mean the difference between
income roll-up and capital growth is more marked.
q I am about to sell some shares I received last year as a gift from my father
and I am confused about the calculation of indexation allowances for capital
gains purposes. I think it used to be the case that the allowance was
calculated from the date the shares were originally purchased by my father, but
this may have changed. Can you say what the current position is?
n Prior to March 14, 1989, where a gift of assets was made, the donor and donee
were able to elect that any gain arising at the date of gift was held over. The
donee acquired the asset at its market value less the gain that would otherwise
be chargeable and indexation in respect of any future disposal was calculated
on that reduced value from the date of the gift.
Hold-over relief in respect of general gifts was withdrawn on March 14, 1989,
and from that date applies only to the gift of business assets, shares in an
unquoted or family company, agricultural property and certain transfers to
trusts.
The gift of shares by your father is, therefore, chargeable for capital gains
tax purposes and his original cost plus indexation from date of purchase are
used in the calculation of any gain arising at date of gift. Your cost is the
market value of shares at that date plus indexation from the date of gift to
date of sale.
q Must a company employing a temporary employee deduct tax or can the latter
hold him or herself to be self-employed?
n An employer must apply PAYE to wages paid to all employees including those
who are casual or temporary. Usually it is easy to decide whether a person is
an employee or not, but in cases of doubt it is best to refer to the Inland
Revenue leaflet IR56 Employed or Self-Employed or to seek a written decision on
the position from either the Inland Revenue or DSS.
A person cannot hold him or herself to be self-employed if that is not
supported by the facts, and an employer who fails to account for PAYE when he
or she should, could have to pay the tax and national insurance due plus
interest and penalties with no recourse to the employee.
q I write hoping that you can give me some advice about Scottish National
shares which I hold as follows: income 1160, capital 464, zero dividend
Preference 464, stepped Preference 232, warrants 92. I do not understand all
the implications of the various units and wonder if I should be taking action
about all or some of them.
n Scottish National is a split-level investment trust in which the income and
capital growth elements are split between various classes of shares. When the
trust is wound up in September 1998 the shares are ranked according to their
entitlement to the assets.
Priority lies with the stepped Preference which will be entitled under a
formula fixed at the outset of the trust to about 171p. Once this requirement
has been met the remaining assets are applied to repaying the zero dividend
Preference at 325p a share. The income shares come next with 100p and finally
any remaining assets go to the capital shares.
With under three years to go it is likely the assets in the trust will be
sufficient to meet all the prior charges, leaving something for the capital
shares. However, the warrants are and will probably remain worthless.
Leaving aside the capital shares, your other holdings, presently worth some
#2700, will reach #3060 on maturity. The capital shares are now worth only #93.
The total assets of the trust have to grow by only 3.8% compound for the
capital shares to have the same value on maturity. Should the assets grow by 5%
the capital shares will rise by 30% compound so they are highly geared. Should
asset growth be 10% your holding would be worth nearly #800.
If the stock market sees only marginal growth over the next three years, it is
not worth retaining your investment in Scottish National. If, however, the
market grows by, say, 10% a year you would have a gain of a third on your
present total investment.
The way your investment is divided between the various classes means you have a
low-risk stake in the stock market. If it falls modestly over the next three
years you are unlikely to face a capital loss. If it grows strongly you will do
quite well.
Caledonian Newspapers Limited and the editor of The Herald accept no legal
responsibility for the answers given in these columns. Readers are invited to
submit concise questions for answer in the paper. No correspondence can be
entered into.
</TEXT>
