<HEADLINE>Dixon's vote of confidence Jim's fixing it fine at Dens</HEADLINE>
<EDITION>2</EDITION>
<PAGE>34</PAGE>
<GRAPHIC>Photograph</GRAPHIC>
<RECORDNO>975208579</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
RON Dixon walked through the front door of Dens Park yesterday for the first
time in a year and declared: ``The reason I stayed away was Jim Duffy.''
The Canadian millionaire chairman of Dundee finally answered the riddle of
whether or not he would turn up to attend their Coca-Cola Cup final with
Aberdeen at Hampden tomorrow by arriving in Scotland on Thursday.
He immediately made it clear he saw no big deal in the fact that he had
remained out of sight for so long. ``I have been accused by some people of not
being a football man. I would argue against that by pointing to the fact that
it was myself who appointed Jim Duffy as coach at this club.
``The truth is there has been no reason for me to be here, because I know that
Dundee Football Club has been in the best of hands with Jim at the helm.
``Sure, I had other business commitments and these contributed to my long
absence. But once I am sure any sector of my business interests is running
smoothly then I believe it is time for me to move on and concentrate on
something else.
``I predicted within a month of appointing Jim that we had a cracker of a coach
and I don't think anyone will ever argue with that.''
Dixon's return to Scotland came just one month short of the five-year
commitment he gave when he first bought the club, but he insisted: ``That was a
minimum commitment on my part. A couple of pieces of the puzzle have still to
fall into place and I want to see them taken care of.
``It has taken Jim Duffy one year to find out the culture of the club and
another year to turn things round. Now he is ready to take us further down the
road.''
Despite his lenghty absence from the Scottish football scene, Dixon made it
plain he believes what road Dundee should be taking in the near future. That
includes sticking to his vow to plough no more money into the club.
``The way ahead for Dundee is the way Jim has already begun to develop. That is
by giving young players the chance to come here and get a chance to play early
in their careers.
``People like Tommy Burns, Jimmy Nicholl and Jim Duffy give youngsters in a
hurry and with ambition the chance to make something of their careers far
earlier.
``Jim gets them playing out of their skin because he treats them exactly right.
He has not made a single mistake, in my view, since he came here. Look at young
Jim Hamilton for instance. Jim bought him for #15,000 and snatched him out of
Aberdeen's camp.''
But Dixon could not supply a guarantee that young stars like Hamilton will be
retained indefinitely at the club. ``Sometimes there is nothing we can do to
stop sales. Kids do well and feel they can move on to a higher level, like
playing for Manchester United. You can't hold on in these circumstances. And
for the board of any football club the first order has to be survival.''
q The Golden Shots- Page 33
</TEXT>
