<HEADLINE>Fighting back to fulfil a sporting dream</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>vDAN BUGLASS</BYLINE>
<EDITION>1</EDITION>
<PAGE>30</PAGE>
<ARTICLETYPE>Profile</ARTICLETYPE>
<FLAG>SPORT</FLAG>
<GRAPHIC>Photograph</GRAPHIC>
<RECORDNO>975208580</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
A SPORTS injury more than two years ago is directly responsible for the journey
to Atlanta which Sarah Baillie will make next summer to compete in the Olympics.
Sarah was a student at Jordanhill, studying for a BA sports degree. Always
exercise-oriented, she had participated in a wide range of activities,
representing Lanarkshire at ski-ing, and winning trophies and medals in
show-jumping. But it was neither of these relatively high-risk activities which
transformed her life - it was a freak football injury.
``I was playing as part of my course, went into a tackle, and just landed
badly,'' says Sarah. ``I suffered serious nerve damage to one leg and have a
lot of problems with my back. I can walk only a very short distance with the
aid of crutches. For all practical purposes, I am confined to a wheelchair.
``They wanted to throw me off the course - I was in my first year - because I
could not do the practicals. I convinced them you don't need to be able to do a
sport to coach it.''
She completed her BA, took up wheelchair basketball, and now, after two years
in the sport, has also graduated to a place in Atlanta. Last weekend, at the
European championships in Holland, Sarah and fellow Scot Laura Bleakley helped
the British women's wheelchair team to success over Israel, booking the UK's
place in the Paralympics next year.
In one of sport's more bizarre results, guaranteed to baffle quiz freaks until
Judgment Day's final whistle, the British girls had to lose to qualify.
Sarah and Laura, both of whom play for Inverclyde Colts, were the only Scots in
the UK team at the European championships. With the first three guaranteed an
Olympic place, Britain were involved in a double-header against Israel for the
bronze medal.
The Britons won the first match by seven points, but at full-time in the second
game, the scores were tied at 31-all. Nearing the end of the five-minute period
of extra time, the scores were still level.
Knowing that in further overtime the girls could lose by more than seven
points, the coach instructed them to concede one basket. At the last moment,
the Israelis were allowed to score - game lost, Olympic place won.
``Perhaps that doesn't sound terribly sporting,'' concedes a shame-faced Joe
Fletcher, chairman of the British Wheelchair Basketball Association. He points
out, however, that during the early part of the final match an electronic fault
led to a failure to record a British score. ``We think justice was done.''
Now the girls will fly into the British Olympic holding camp in Tallahassee
next summer the day after the last of the able-bodied Olympians move out and
head home. Costs will be borne by the British Paralympic Association, but that
falls way short of the #2000 cost of titanium chairs, spare wheel at #140, or
even tyres, four of which (#15 a time) can go in one match.
Perhaps even more problematic than funds is arranging practice time. ``It's
difficult to get courts for wheelchairs, with five-a-side football
everywhere,'' says Laura, from Barrhead.
Now 22, but having had no use of her legs since she was four, she has a
qualification from Caledonian University and is employed full-time as a
canoeing coach at Castle Semple.
In that, Laura is more fortunate than 27-year old Sarah. Despite her degree,
and having taken separate qualifications to coach basketball, volleyball,
badminton, fencing, table tennis, short tennis, swimming, gymnastics,
trampolining and boccia, Sarah cannot find employment, other than temporary
work with the Glasgow Council for Voluntary Services, at a school for children
with physical disability, and with Glasgow City Council.
Sarah, from Lesmahagow, says: ``I would like a post as a sports development
officer, for which I am well qualified. But I have to say that my disability
seems to count against me.''
</TEXT>
