<HEADLINE>Personal goal is still in Sir Iain's sights</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>NICOLA REEVES</BYLINE>
<EDITION>1</EDITION>
<PAGE>21</PAGE>
<ARTICLETYPE>profile</ARTICLETYPE>
<GRAPHIC>Photograph</GRAPHIC>
<RECORDNO>975208583</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
BT is Britain's second largest company and one of the most competitive
telecommunications companies in the world. The man who has presided over this
transformation from a moribund state monopoly into a world class efficient
company is Sir Iain Vallance.
Sir Iain has been chairman of the group for nine years and chief executive for
ten years. Last year he was knighted for services to the telecommunications
industry.
Sir Iain was born in 1943 and was educated at both Glasgow and Edinburgh
Academies. His parents still live in Edinburgh and he often returns to Scotland
where he can indulge his passion for hill walking.
He is a graduate of Brasenose College Oxford and the London Business School. He
began his working life in the Post Office in 1966, when he worked in the
chairman's office. In 1967, he married Elizabeth McGonnigill who has a
successful professional career of her own in academe. They have one son and one
daughter.
In addition to his role at BT, last year Sir Iain was appointed vice-chairman
of the Royal Bank of Scotland. He has been touted as a possible successor to
Lord Younger, Royal Bank's chairman, who is due to retire in the next few
years. Sir Iain also serves on a number of other bodies including the CBI,
British-American Chamber of Commerce, the Police Foundation and the Princess
Royal Trust for Carers.
He is not the most diplomatic of people. He prompted outrage earlier this year
when in justifying his #663,000 salary he said it might be quite ``relaxing''
to be a junior hospital doctor. What is not in question is that Sir Iain puts
in the hours. He is said to be usually at his desk by 7.30am and regularly
works a 12 hour day in the week and one day at the weekend. Added to which the
global nature of the business is such that he is often abroad.
Sir Iain has been vocal in his views on the challenges and opportunities facing
BT in the telecommunications revolution. BT attracted publicity during the
Party conference season when it announced a ``superhighways'' agreement with
the Labour Party.
He has a personal goal to see BT become the largest telecommunications company
in the world. Having brought the company this far, he may well succeed in his
ambition.
The view in the City is that it is more than time for clarity at the top of the
company regarding who does what, and therefore his decision to give up the
chief executive role will be warmly welcomed.
</TEXT>
