<DATE>951125</DATE>
<HEADLINE>Nomads lift sevens trophy</HEADLINE>
<EDITION>2</EDITION>
<PAGE>32</PAGE>
<RECORDNO>975208585</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
JOE Tauiwi, skipper of the Kiwi Nomads, lifted the Emirates Airline
International Trophy after two hard days of competition in the Dubai Exiles
International Sevens. Tauiwi, a member of the winning All Blacks team in the
1994 and 1995 Hong Kong Sevens, was one of six Bay of Plenty players in the
winning team, who defeated Bahrain-based invitation side Warblers 47-19.
The fitness and training schedules achieved by All Blacks sevens coach Gordon
Tietjens and his men meant the Warblers could not live with them, despite
leading 19-7 at the break, as the winners ran in five second-half tries.
Earlier, Bath stars Adedayo Adebayo and Steve Ojomoh were in top form as
Warblers beat Hawke's Bay 24-19 in the semis.
Anglo-Scottish Invitation side Thistles took the Plate with a 21-12 win over
UBC Old Boys from Canada as Richard Moon skippered his side cleverly from scrum
half. Mark Appleson notched two of the three Thistles tries and converted both
as well as improving a try from Martin Gregory. The Canadian side had earlier
beaten Leicester 15-12 in sudden-death extra-time in the semi-finals. Results:
Plate: Quarter-finals - Leicester 31, Crawshay's Welsh 17; Romania 12, UBC Old
Boys (Canada) 28; Roma 0, Thistles (Scotland) 38; Irish Wolfhounds 21, Atlantis
(USA) 24. Semi-finals - Leicester 12, UBC Old Boys 15 (aet); Thistles 29,
Atlantis 17. Final - UBC Old Boys 12, Thistles 21.
Gulf Championship: Quarter-finals - Hawke's Bay 33, Froggies 12; Warblers 19,
Queensland 15; Kiwi Nomads 43, Suntory (Japan) 19; Natal 15, Korea 17.
Semi-finals - Hawke's Bay 19, Warblers 24; Kiwi Nomads 48, Korea 0. Final -
Dubai Exiles 36, Bahrain 14.
</TEXT>
