<DATE>951125</DATE>
<HEADLINE>Lomu's mine insisted Evans</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>KENNY LOGAN</BYLINE>
<EDITION>2</EDITION>
<PAGE>32</PAGE>
<GRAPHIC>Photograph</GRAPHIC>
<RECORDNO>975208586</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
TO Stradey Park, Llanelli, on Tuesday night for Ieuan Evans' testimonial match.
It was a British Isles XV against an International Select and we won 68-57,
Ieuan grossed - it is said - #100,000 and the 12,000 spectators all went home
happy. After events at Murrayfield on Saturday, three days certainly is a long
time in rugby.
The fact that Llanelli were permitted to stage a testimonial to mark Ieuan's
service to rugby shows just how far the game has come in last few months.
It was a star-studded occasion with players from all over the world on parade.
Sean Fitzpatrick, Jason Little, Thierry Lacroix, Olivier Roumat, John Gallagher
from rugby league, and Rudy Straueli were all there. There were five Scots -
the Hastings brothers, Rob Wainwright, Craig Chalmers, and me.
But the biggest draw was Jonah Lomu. The guy is a superstar and was mobbed
everywhere he went and that included a couple of pitch invasions by young
autograph hunters. Before the kick-off Ieuan and I held a strategy meeting, the
main item on the agenda being who was going to mark the monster. Ieuan said he
wanted to do it - and it was his game after all - so bang went my tackling
practice plans.
The game itself was intended very much as a crowd-pleaser but you can't put all
of those international players on the park without there being a bit of an edge
and neither side wanted to lose. Lomu had a couple of tries which took the
International Select to a 38-33 lead at half-time.
In the second half Ieuan kicked the conversion which took us from 57-54 behind
to a 61-57 lead (whether it actually went over or not is a private matter
between Ieuan and the touch judges) and I got a second try near the end to
bring down the curtain on a 19-try bonanza and a superb evening's
entertainment. It might only have been a bit of fun, but I needed a game like
that after Saturday's shocking performance against Western Samoa.
Today it is back to serious premiership business and our game against Melrose
at Bridgehaugh must be the crunch game of the season. If Melrose win then they
are almost certain to win the championship and if we win then the championship
race is going to go right down to the wire.
When you consider that just six weeks ago we were battling to avoid relegation
then you get some indication of just how desperate this league has been. It's
certainly not been for the faint-hearted.
Craig Joiner is recovered from his foot injury and back on the right wing for
Melrose today which means that we will be in direct opposition. It's good to
see ``Jackie'' back and I wish him well, but he knows that after last weekend
I've got a point or two to prove.
I'm not the only one. Craig Chalmers will also want to put on a bit of a show
today after the Samoan Test. He reckons that he doesn't deserve all the
personal criticism that came his way and the duel between the two fly-halves
will be especially interesting, because our Mark McKenzie is still on a high
after having such a good game for North and Midlands against the Samoans.
We've beaten Melrose thrice in a row and when we went down to the Greenyards at
the beginning of October we beat them by the odd point in 53. Neutral observers
reckoned that it was one of the best games of the season and, hopefully, it
will be more of the same - with the same outcome - today.
</TEXT>
