<DOC>
<DOCNO>GH951125-000138</DOCNO>
<DOCID>GH951125-000138</DOCID>
<DATE>951125</DATE>
<HEADLINE>RADIO</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>MARCELLA EVARISTI</BYLINE>
<EDITION>1</EDITION>
<PAGE>18</PAGE>
<ARTICLETYPE>review</ARTICLETYPE>
<RECORDNO>975208588</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
AS the poet Gerard Manly Hopkins wrote: ``The mind, the mind has mountains,
cliffs of fall, sheer, no man fathomed.'' The line kept coming to me as I
listened to Michael Ignatieff's Secret Theatres of the Mind (Radio 3).
How ultimately ignorant we are about the causes of manic depression or
dyslexia, Alzheimer's or autism, and although the tentatively preferred
theories with their careful trail of qualifications, made one think on
questions of genetics, environment and heredity, the painful power of this
series lay with the experiential reality of the sufferers.
In the case of dyslexia ``sufferer'' was clearly as ignorant labelling. It
became clear how much suffering and insult was caused to dyslexics by the
assumption that the ability to be literate is simplistically linked to
intelligence.
English lessons were hell. Constantly being spoken to as if she were stupid,
one woman tried to make us understand by saying that the awful driving-test day
feeling, was her feeling every single day. The dyslexic's visual and spacial
awareness takes precedent over the story and word dominance of the world. But
the point was made that our word-based civilisation is not eternal -
``technology creates a freedom not available when you pick up a pen''.
It is difficult for me to imagine what is meant when someone says that he does
not think in words. I can understand when it explained that ``segments'' as a
word holds difficulties but the imagined shape of an orange is the
word-equivalent in the dyslexic imagination, but I find it hard to move beyond
that. What about remembered conversations? An experience that needs to be
related? It's a good programme that makes you not just think, but makes you
think about thinking.
The metaphor Ingatieff used was that of a forest; where the non-dyslexic sees a
path through, the dyslexic sees nothing but inchoate branchings and darkness.
The pun becomes nonsense and the joke, while others exclusively guffaw, becomes
far from ``brillig'' (as in ``slithey tove'').
Everybody knows the emotional zig zag of high to low, but the mood swings of
the manic depressive's shift from exaltation to the bleakest of terror is often
unbearable.
One woman's depression lasted 18 months - then one morning she woke up and the
demons had gone. For no reason accessible to her clever, questioning mind, her
anguish had - temporarily - absented itself.
Without romanticising things, Ignatieff points to the number of artists stuck
with this particular torment; Beethoven, Van Gogh, Schumann, Plath, Byron.
Going out too far, burning the lamp too brightly is dangerous, and can end in
the bitterest of tears.
But one woman spoke of the special privilege of her state. She said that it led
to a generosity, an understanding and acceptance of the pain of others, and
indeed she exemplified the questioning stance she associated with her
condition. It was humbling to hear her talk of herself with such unassuming
clarity, as if she were her own child, fascinated, helpless and dignified.
Ignatieff himself was the child and grandchild of women with Alzheimer's
disease. It was almost unbearably moving to hear him describe his feelings as
he watched two women he loved slowly disappear from sight, for all his attempts
of connection, for all his articulate love.
He interviewed a woman called Kate, in her fifties, her voice young and vibrant
as her words chilled the soul. She was acutely aware that her memory was being
eaten away. She said she could remember when she began to forget, her mind like
a sieve with all the information that made herself herself, dribbling away.
The resilience and plain goodness of people assisting scientists in their
research for the disease that will not be cured in their lifetime - helping out
as they consciously experienced their own disintegration - astounded me. The
cruelty of nature is truly a thing beyond man to fathom.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO>GH951125-000139</DOCNO>
<DOCID>GH951125-000139</DOCID>
<DATE>951125</DATE>
<HEADLINE>Post Office monopolists fail to get the message</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>GEORGE BIRRELL</BYLINE>
<EDITION>1</EDITION>
<PAGE>19</PAGE>
<ARTICLETYPE>Features</ARTICLETYPE>
<RECORDNO>975208589</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
MOST people I have spoken to about the postal strike are deliriously happy. No
longer, they say, do they have to suffer the shiver of fearful anticipation
slithering up their spine when they hear the plop of their morning mail through
the letterbox.
They can live quite happily, thank you, without the final reminders, whose
siren message, invariably in bright red, stares out from the corner of the
envelope window just     sufficiently to cause breakfast apoplexy.
None seems to regret the absence of those missives from the bank which, with
impeccable logic, inform you they are adding #15 to the overdraft you should
not have had in the first place.
Nor do they despair at not receiving notification from Readers Digest, or some
similar outfit, informing us, for the third time that month, that we are
virtually guaranteed a gold Rolls Royce/expenses paid trip to the
Bahamas/#100,000.
It is a fantasy, of course. A day of reckoning beckons. And they will be left a
lot less chirpier when the cheques don't turn up, the invitations are missed
and letters from loved ones arrive too late.
It would be so simple to blame it all on the wildcat strikers who instigated
the dispute at the Portobello office in Edinburgh.
After all, trade unionists are Luddite. It is not just a British trait. Even in
America when the mail was being transferred to rail from the Pony Express there
was friction from stagecoach operators and those who had the concession on
horse shoes. It was simply resolved, however. No need for interdicts or
expensive lawyers just a couple of gentlemen with inexpressive eyes and
eloquent trigger fingers to act as adjudicators.
Or we could blame the union of communication workers, a misnomer in itself. It
seems the last thing this body of brothers can do is communicate, either with
their own members, whom they claim to have discouraged from going on strike -
and have palpably been ignored - or with the management.
However, this would be a cop-out. It is like blaming workers' pay rises for
causing inflation. They cannot be held responsible; only governments can by
putting the printing presses on overtime.
The fault lies squarely with the monopoly which the Royal Mail has in shifting
our letters. It is one of the last ghettos of socialism. We have privatised
gas, telecommunications, electricity and changed the status of water in
Scotland - all the public utilities which we were once told were inviolable.
Only the Post Office remains, a memorial to absolute power and its corruption
absolutely.
A handful of Tory backbenchers     - those supposed One-Nation Conservatives,
easily identifiable with the yellow streak down their backs, colluded with
not-so-New Labour to force the Prime Minister into abandoning privatisation.
The original plan was to sell 51% of Royal Mail (which used to collect and
deliver letters) and Parcelforce, the Post Office's loss-making parcels service.
Post Office Counters, the retail arm which runs a network of 800 town-centre
post offices and 19,000 privately owned sub-post offices, were to stay under
the aegis of the state.
Of course, this all developed into a bogus battle about little grey-haired
grannies, eeking out an existence in sub-post offices in Highland villages,
being threatened with eviction by the rampant forces of capitalism. There were
gut-wrenching stories about whole communities which would disappear if these
outposts were axed; which says much about the viability of these communities if
this is all that keeps them together.
This was a much needed privatisation but it fell because the Government had
such a small majority in the Commons. So, the forces of darkness prevailed with
their claim that, because the Post Office had fat profits and falling costs,
there was no need for change.
It is true the Post Office is more efficient and profitable than it has ever
been but it is not, and should not be, an arm of the social services. This is
the way to create fewer jobs overall, not more. The service carries too much
fat - which at the end of the day means we all pay more than we have to - and
needs private-        sector disciplines.
National post offices face competition whether they like it or not, from one
another, from courier firms and from electronic communications. Just think of
the use of faxes, E-mail and interactive developments in fibre optics.    The
time is not far away when sending a letter in the traditional way    will be as
unusual as writing with a quill pen.
What the post office desperately needs is for the chains to come off and for
them to be allowed to make their own investment decisions, raise their own
capital - under existing rules, nationalised industry debts count as additions
to the public sector borrowing requirement - and create offshoots of their
business.
It works, even in former nanny-states like Sweden whose postal service lost its
monopoly two years ago yet remains profitable and efficient. The Germans, next
year, intend to revive theirs.
What would be helpful is for the European Commission to take steps to genuinely
create a single market in postal services. Its directive last July steers away
from competition in the industry. It was supposed to liberalise the laws so it
came up with the scheme that countries would be able to ``reserve'' letters
lighter than 350g (12oz) for delivery by the national post office. As the
normal letter weighs about 15g not much change there. As for incoming mail that
will remain a preserve of the monopolists until the next millenium. Only
express-mail - costing five times as much - is open to competition.
Its argument that there has to be a monopoly to ensure delivery to rural areas
is specious. The cost of a universal service is offset by economies of scale
and any company which offers to deliver anywhere, everyday would have an
irresistable selling point. Who do you think delivers to the far north of
Sweden? Santa Claus?
We should not waste energy targeting the rednecks who have initiated the strike
nor the eunuch of a union which cannot do anything about it. Competition will
mean better paid jobs for postal workers and a cheaper, more efficient service
for the rest of us. It's a pity you can't write to your MP about it.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
