<DOCNO>GH951125-000140</DOCNO>
<DOCID>GH951125-000140</DOCID>
<DATE>951125</DATE>
<HEADLINE>Yggdrasil Quartet, Elphinstone Hall, Aberdeen</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>ALAN COOPER</BYLINE>
<EDITION>1</EDITION>
<PAGE>18</PAGE>
<ARTICLETYPE>Review</ARTICLETYPE>
<RECORDNO>975208590</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
A NEWLY commissioned string quartet by Martin Dalby which the Yggdrasil Quartet
were to have premiered on Thursday will now have to wait until February. Second
violinist Per Oman was struck down by a virus which confined him to bed,
however the remaining three players seemed positively to relish the opportunity
to rummage in their repertoire and they came up with a performance every bit as
polished as anything else to date.
Haydn's Divertimento No.8 in B major and Beethoven's String Trio in C minor
were the ultimate in intimate rapport between chamber players. Clearly
everything had to have been thoroughly planned yet the playing sounded so
spontaneous, with every change in pace or tone shining through a pellucid
string texture.
Lead violinist Fredrik Paulsson emerged from the Sonata No.3 in D minor for
violin and piano by Brahms, his face bathed in perspiration. Pianist Robert
Howie, brought in for the occasion, emerged cool and collected. This mirrored a
performance in which the passion flowed from sensuous glossy violin playing
which the piano never attempted to edge into second place.
The real fun though came from a little-known surprise item. Johan Halvorsen was
a Norwegian violinist and composer born in 1864 who apparently spent part of
his career in Aberdeen. His variations for violin and cello on a Passacaglia by
Handel demand startling virtuosity. Fredrik Paulsson and cellist Per Nystrom
went at it with relish. They even managed a suggestion of self parody just to
hint that they do not take themselves too seriously.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO>GH951125-000141</DOCNO>
<DOCID>GH951125-000141</DOCID>
<DATE>951125</DATE>
<HEADLINE>Aberdeen and Dundee pledge that final way is forward Hampden race to decide who will be golden shots</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>KEN GALLACHER: Chief football writer</BYLINE>
<EDITION>2</EDITION>
<PAGE>33</PAGE>
<GRAPHIC>Photograph</GRAPHIC>
<RECORDNO>975208591</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
ABERDEEN and Dundee will contest the fiftieth League Cup final at Hampden
tomorrow afternoon and, fittingly, it will be a sell-out occasion for the
country's youngest major tournament. Whatever happens, it would seem from the
pre-match promises emanating from both camps that this will be a golden
anniversary to remember.
At Aberdeen, the captain, Stewart McKimmie, has already declared: ``This can be
a high scoring game, a match which will see a lot of attacking play.'' And the
Dundee manager, Jim Duffy, stressed: ``We have attack-minded players in
midfield and so do they. So, while as a manager, I would worry about losing
goals, I have to admit that the two teams are filled with players who want to
go forward.''
The news from Pittodrie yesterday that Eoin Jess will play is just another
factor which will improve Aberdeen's status as favourites to take the trophy.
They will be without Dutch goalkeeper Theo Snelders, but manager Roy Aitken
already has given Michael Watt, who will now move to centre stage at Hampden,
his vote of confidence.
Aitken also has added MS victim Brian Irvine to the group of players who will
travel south though it looks unlikely that the man who is fighting illness so
powerfully will take part in this important final.
Duffy has had no injury problems to concern him and the team he plays will
reflect the positive attitude he wants to take into every game.
``We are at our worst,'' he claims, ``when we are up against a team who are
trying to shut us down.
``We are looked on as a team who might be winning promotion and so the lesser
teams simply want to stop us playing and the lads get frustrated. But Aberdeen
won't do that.
``Like ourselves, they have midfield players who just want to get into forward
positions.
``We go in as underdogs and that suits me fine. It is not a problem for us and
we won't feel any pressure at all. At least, not until Sunday afternoon.''
That possible pressure point is confirmed by one of the main threats to the
premier division side, winger Neil McCann.
The Scotland Under-21 player maintains: ``Right now, I feel totally relaxed and
that is what the manager has been preaching. ``I don't think it's going to hit
me until just before the game. There is no danger of any of us freezing. We are
ready for the game and none of us have been able to believe the level of
support we are going to be getting. It's incredible that the club has sold
17,000 tickets.
``We all think that we can do it. We have proved what we are capable of doing
against premier division teams by beating Kilmarnock and Hearts.
They have the example of Raith Rovers last season to sustain them and the sure
knowledge that no matter what happens in the game, the cash-strapped club will
have made enough money to secure the future of the players.
As for Aberdeen, the cash will not mean so much. What will count most is the
glory, especially after their dismal time last season.
Now Aitken has managed to bring back the form of such as Jess and Scott Booth,
and encourage the burgeoning skills of Stephen Glass. And while the team still
lack consistency in the premier division, they have rediscovered the appetite
for the big occasion.
No-one need look further than the semi-final against Rangers for confirmation
of that.
Less than a year ago that type of result would have been beyond them, and now
Europe beckons. Just one match lies between them and that place among the
Continental giants their fans believe is their destiny.
It will not arrive easily. The gritty resolve of Duffy and his players will
make sure of that.
The bookmakers have decided that Aberdeen will take the Coca Cola Cup back
north, and they will probably be right. But their odds reflect their memories
of Raith Rovers defeating Celtic last season and, perhaps also, a growing
knowledge that Dundee have the opportunity to prove yet again that the gap
between the two leagues is narrowing.
ABERDEEN - Second round: v St Mirren (Pittodrie) 3-1. Scorers: Dodds, Booth
(two).
Third round: v Falkirk (Brockville) 3-1. Scorers: Clark (og), Booth, Woodthorpe.
Fourth round: v Motherwell (Fir Park) 2-1 aet. Scorers: Dodds, Inglis.
Semi-final v Rangers (Hampden) 2-1. Scorer: Dodds (two).
DUNDEE - Second round: v East Stirling (Firs Park) 6-0. Scorers: Wieghorst,
Hamilton, McCann (4).
Third round: v Kilmarnock (Dens Park) 3-1. Scorers: Shaw, Wieghorst, Hamilton.
Fourth round: v Hearts (Dens Park) 4-4 aet, won 5-4 on pens. Scorers: Shaw
(two), Tosh, Wieghorst.
Semi-final: v Airdrie (McDiarmid Park) 2-1. Scorers: Tosh, McCann.
</TEXT>
