<DATE>951125</DATE>
<HEADLINE>Grants rules become less of a lottery</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>DOUG GILLON</BYLINE>
<EDITION>1</EDITION>
<PAGE>30</PAGE>
<FLAG>SPORT</FLAG>
<RECORDNO>975208592</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
THE Government, it emerged yesterday, is beginning to listen to sports' voices
demanding a review of National Lottery regulations.
The Herald, in concert with most sports agencies, has campaigned for relaxation
of rules confining grants solely to capital items. Only yesterday, former
Sports Minister Sir Hector Monro, in our personal column, Arena, admitted that
the awards system needs greater flexibility.
The argument goes that funding the building of swimming pools and sports
centres without helping to finance running costs, or assisting the elite who
perform in them, is a flawed policy.
Heritage secretary Virginia Bottomley has ordered a lottery review next month,
and the Central Council of Physical Recreation conference in Warwickshire heard
yesterday that this could pave the way for change.
David Carpenter, head of the Sports Council's National Lottery Unit, told
leading sports administrators that finance may become available by the middle
of next year, for coaching, sports medicine, and sports science. Cities hosting
major championships are also likely to qualify for help.
This drew an immediate response from Glasgow, which earlier this week was
designated Scotland's first National City of Sport. ``Obviously this could help
both with the provision of facilities, and our bid to bring more interntional
events to the city,'' said Brian Porteous, depute director of Parks and
Recreation.
Relaxation of the 50% guideline for lottery funds vis-a-vis local authority
finance will, however, help every part of the UK.
Allan Alstead, chief executive of the Scottish Sports Council, welcomed the
prospect, but voiced a note of caution: ``We would remind the Treasury that any
money is additional, not a replacement for existing funds.''
Despite Carpenter's fear that elite funding may remain restricted, his
political masters have hinted otherwise. Sports Minister Iain Sproat recently
referred in the House of Commons to Prime Minister John Major's #100m
aspirations for a British Academy of Sport: ``It will have the world's highest
standards of coaches, training facilities, sports science, and sports medicine
. . . We need to make sure that in an increasingly competitive world, our
athletes are properly supported financially, and we are determined to do that.''
Mr Sproat spoke of 500 full-time residential competitors on scholarships.
Where, you might ask, would funding come from? Sproat's reply to the House,
reported in Hansard, is the clearest indication yet of new lottery rules to
embrace revenue funding: ``There will almost certainly be endowment funding and
revenue funding for the academy.''
</TEXT>
