<DOC>
<DOCNO>GH951125-000143</DOCNO>
<DOCID>GH951125-000143</DOCID>
<DATE>951125</DATE>
<HEADLINE>Profits soar at Grampian</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>ROBERT POWELL</BYLINE>
<EDITION>1</EDITION>
<PAGE>21</PAGE>
<GRAPHIC>Photograph</GRAPHIC>
<RECORDNO>975208593</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
CONTINUING losses at Scot FM have failed to dent soaring profits at Grampian
Television, where advertising revenue has risen sharply.
The Aberdeen-based television station boosted its pre-tax profits by 62% to
#2.9m during the six months to August 31.
The company pushed its turnover ahead by 25% to #12.6m.
But City analysts briefed by Grampian officials said there had been a sharp
downturn in advertising in the second half, which was likely to dampen growth
in the second half.
Reflecting this discreet warning, Grampian share price remaineded unchanged at
204p yesterday, despite an effective 39% increase in the dividend.
Grampian chairman Calum MacLeod attributed the dramatic rise in first-half
profits to a 10.4% increase in advertising revenue and good income from the
sale of successful programmes such as ``Highlanders'' and ``Selina Scott meets
Donald Trump''.
But he gave little away about the continuing losses at Scot FM, the Leith-based
radio station covering central Scotland which began broadcasting in September
1994.
Mr MacLeod said Scot FM continued to run up trading losses, but he said that
revenue was improving, boosted by radio station's acquisition of exclusive
rights to live coverage of football matches in Scotland.
``I expect to see trading results continue to improve as the station enters its
second year of broadcasting,'' Mr MacLeod stated, without saying when it would
break even.
Scot FM has been bedevilled by cost overuns and staff problems from the start.
Former managing director Tom Hunter, who sacked many of the station's early
broadcasters, was himself shown the door earlier this month.
Grampian's former director of television, Bob Christie, was then rushed down
from Aberdeen to take charge of the situation.
Anthony de la Renaga, a media analyst with Panmure Gordon in London, reckoned
it would lose about #250,000 in this financial year after #400,000 last year.
Grampian Television's 10.4% increase in advertising revenue during the first
half outshone a 7.7% improvement for the ITV network.
This was down to a dynamic performance by TSMS, the advertising sales house
which it switched to in late last year.
Despite slower advertising growth in the second half of the year, full-year
profits still look set to increase for the eighth year in a row.
City analysts are pencilling a pre-tax figure of #5.3m to #5.6m, up from #4.4m
in 1994/95.
</TEXT>
