<DATE>951125</DATE>
<HEADLINE>The arrival of Bonfield is unlikely lead to any alteration of company strategy BT to split roles of chairman and chief executive</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>NICOLA REEVES</BYLINE>
<EDITION>1</EDITION>
<PAGE>21</PAGE>
<GRAPHIC>Photograph</GRAPHIC>
<RECORDNO>975208594</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
BT is to split the roles of chairman and chief executive with Sir Iain Vallance
continuing as chairman. This in keeping with the Cadbury recommendations of
best practice in corporate governance.
Peter Bonfield, currently chairman and chief executive of the computer group
ICL, is to be the new chief executive from January 2.
Michael Hepher, currently managing director of BT, is to leave the group after
four years and is expected to return to the financial services industry. Before
joining BT, he was chief executive of Abbey Life. He has ruled out taking the
chief executive slot at rival Cable &amp; Wireless, a position which became
available earlier this week following a boardroom coup.
Mr Hepher will continue to be paid by BT until the end of his annual contract
on August 7, 1997. Mr Hepher's basic salary is #430,000. Sir Iain said that, as
there has been a change in circumstance, the board felt it was right to
continue the payments.
The appointment of Mr Bonfield is viewed in the group as particularly apt given
the convergence of the telecommunications, computer, amd media industries. Mr
Bonfield is a widely respected figure both within and outside the information
technology industry.
He is a non-executive director of Zeneca and of BICC and is deputy chairman of
the British Quality Foundation. He is to remain on the board of ICL as deputy
chairman after a short period as non-executive chairman. Keith Todd, director
of finance and business strategy, will take over as chief executive of ICL.
The arrival of Mr Bonfield is not expected to lead to any change in strategy.
The company's aim remains to become the world's largest telecommunications
company through overseas expansion. It is currently in discussions on possible
acquisitions and joint ventures, although it is not interested in acquiring
rival Cable &amp; Wireless. However, this does not rule out the possibility of it
purchasing Cable &amp; Wireless's valuable 57.5% stake in Hong Kong Telecom.
Recent signs of a deterioration in BT's relationship with the regulator, Don
Cruickshank of Oftel, sent the shares to a 17-month low earlier in the week.
Mr Cruickshank accused BT of failing to implement fair trading throughout its
business and suggested that BT felt there was no harm carrying out
anti-competitive practices ``unless and until the regulator intervenes''.
Although the UK is the most liberalised telecomunications market in terms of
ease of entry for new participants, it has one of the toughest regulatory
environments. BT cites the terms of its operating licence, and price cap as
evidence of this.
While the current regulatory environment was seen as appropriate at the time of
privatisation, BT now feels that 10 years on, the time is right to have a fresh
look at the regulatory system. It believes that given the rapid pace of change
in the industry, in terms of technologies and the globalisation of the
industry, it is too much to expect one person alone to supervise the industry.
It favours lighter regulation via a supervisory committee or the right of
appeal on decisions.
The City welcomed the unexpected board changes at BT and the shares gained 2!sp
to 357!sp. Robert Fleming Securities raised the stock from a sell to a hold.
Analyst Laurence Heyworth said BT's management changes ``could act as a
positive catalyst'' for the shares. In any case, BT's current yield of 6.5%
will underpin the shares.
</TEXT>
