<HEADLINE>Test chance is still there for Malcolm</HEADLINE>
<EDITION>2</EDITION>
<PAGE>32</PAGE>
<GRAPHIC>Photograph</GRAPHIC>
<RECORDNO>975208595</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
DEVON Malcolm was given a glimmer of hope last night after another day of deep
depression. The Derbyshire fast-bowler's prospects of playing in next week's
second Test looked as dead as the Springbok Park pitch on which 15 overs had
brought him only one wicket - and plenty of punishment.
But manager Ray Illingworth - a lapsed member of Malcolm's fan club for much of
this tour - refused to add to the misery. ``It's a slow pitch and all I can ask
is that Devon rolls up his sleeves and runs in,'' he said. ``I think he tried
to do that.''
Malcolm attempted to bowl quickly but, all too often, the ball went even faster
off the bat as Orange Free State recovered from early afternoon trouble to
reach 245 for nine declared. His figures never looked encouraging, but an
18-year-old student, who never had played first class cricket before, put the
finishing touches to them.
Hendrik Dippenaar, star of last summer's South Africa Under-19 tour to England,
hooked Malcolm for an effortless 6, added two more 4s and was mobbed by his
Bloemfontein College mates after making 46.
Illingworth wisely declined to discount England's fastest bowler, just in case
next week's Test pitch at The Wanderers proves to be right up Malcolm's street.
Johannesburg traditionally provides the quickest surface in South Africa, and
it now holds the one sliver of hope for Malcolm.
John Crawley fully deserves to step out at The Wanderers, but will not do so
unless one of his batting rivals suffers an injury before Thursday.
The Lancashire player stroked an undefeated 69 - packed with 10 boundaries and
brimful of confidence - as England reached 121 for one second time around,
while extending their overall lead to 192.
Crawley, given a chance to open after having been denied by Thursday's
declaration, lost skipper Mike Atherton (13) to a firm clip to mid-wicket but
then shared an unbroken partnership of 77 with Mark Ramprakash.
