<TEXT>
STODDARD Sekers International, the Scottish manufacturer of quality carpets,
has suffered its first loss in 10 years.
The company, based at Elderslie, near Paisley, incurred a #625,000 loss during
the six months to September 30 as turnover slipped 11.4% to #25.9m. That
compared with a pre-tax profit of #565,000 in the first half of 1994.
``It is the first time we have registered a loss for 10 years,'' said chief
executive Ralph Ellis, noting that sales between July and September were 15%
down on the same period of 1994. But he was cautiously optimistic about an
improvement in the second half. Stoddard halved the interim dividend to 0.375p,
triggering a 3!sp plunge in the share price to 23p.
WEIR Group has secured an order for #2m of equipment to distill drinking water
from sea water at a Libyan oil refinery. Its Weir Westgarth factory in Glasgow
will deliver two desalinisation units to the Arabian Gulf Oil Company's Tobruk
refinery.
TOM Steele, who was head of news when Radio Forth started broadcasting in 1975,
will become managing director of the Edinburgh station in May. He replaces
Richard Findlay, who becomes chief executive of the parent company, Scottish
Radio Holdings.
Mr Steele started his career as a journalist in Dumfries and worked as a
political correspondent of the Scottish Daily Mail before moving to Radio Forth.
WELSH Water's profit surged in the first six months of the year, rising 63% to
#80.6m. Turnover inched up to #269.5m. There is an interim dividend of 12.6p
compared with a previous payment of a restated 6.9p.
</TEXT>
