<HEADLINE>The transformation of Dame James</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>Mary Brennan</BYLINE>
<EDITION>1</EDITION>
<PAGE>5</PAGE>
<ARTICLETYPE>Profile</ARTICLETYPE>
<FLAG>weekender</FLAG>
<GRAPHIC>Photograph</GRAPHIC>
<RECORDNO>975208600</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
This is man's work: Jimmy Logan looks forward to another Glasgow panto run in
the kind of wigs that even Bet Gilroy's collection couldn't shake a stick at.
TIGHTS! Bosoms!! Action!!! Panto-time approaches and already the Dame is
slipping into something suitably uncomfortable. Feet that arrived in sensible
black lace-ups are being edged into pointy-toed peerie heels. Bits that follow
the natural inclinations of gravity are suddenly wheeched and chivvied in
untoward directions, all in the interests of comedy. Something which looks like
a nine-day-wonder-bra appears and in the twinkling of a hook and eye, the Paps
of Jura have relocated themselves under the Dame's chin.
In slightly more than an hour, from stepping through the stage door as himself,
Jimmy Logan is giving us a twirl in a glittering glamarama gown that suggests
the evergreen hand-grenade joke: pull out the pin and it's every man for
himself!
Logan is - no question of it - a Grande Dame among great dames. Even back in
his teens, when he was part of the famous family act that kept Scotland and
beyond in happy stitches, he dabbled in damery.
``My father pooh-poohed the whole idea. I was about 17 and I'd been playing
this wee boy. Short trousers, torn shirt, a tyke. And it would go down very
well. Very well. But I knew I couldn't go on doing that. Apart from anything
else, producers were coming to see the show, I was starting to branch out, do
other things. So I told him I'd like to change a few things. Go into long
trousers, smarten up a bit. And do this one routine as a dame. Well as far as
he was concerned, it just wasn't on. Until I did it. And it went down so well
that he wanted me to do everything else as a dame!''
In fact, Logan's first forays into pantomime took him all over Britain and into
the company of some of the leading comics of the time - but not as a dame, to
begin with anyway. ``My first-ever pantomime was at the Empire Theatre in
Greenock, where the whole family was playing in Dick Whittington and his Cat.
I'd be about 15 and I was the cat. And I remember we were all staying with my
aunt Jean, my mother's sister, in Gourock. And she was a very clean woman, my
aunt Jean - an awfu' clean wummin - and she washed the catskin. Hung it up
outside the house to dry...... and it shrunk.
``So there I was, following this principal boy around, to London, on board
ship, all that - and I'm just about bent double inside this skin that's now too
wee. Sore back, sore legs. It was absolute murder. Standing up straight
afterwards...... murder!''
The next step was filling the Giant's shoes in Jack and the Beanstalk at the
Gaiety Theatre in Leith. This was to prove another instance of suffering for
the panto art. He describes how the Giant's feet had to be strapped into these
huge boots with an 18-inch platform and tin sides that went halfway up the
shin...... falling over was a perpetual, painful hazard. Never mind Jack's
swash and buckle - even a stray matchstick underfoot was enough to coggle this
ogre, who was himself baking in his own juices like a human pie.
``In order to bulk myself out properly for the
Continued on page 7
Continued from page 5
part, I wore two heavy overcoats under the costume - and boy, was I roasted!''
Logan laughs at the recollection of past discomforts. Only - what has changed,
exactly? He's just about to spend the next three months harnessed to the
traditional rigmarole of the Dame in Babes in the Wood at the King's in Glasgow.
Watching Logan prepare himself as Dame is to see, and hear, that tradition come
alive in a way that is both a personal and a theatrical history stretching back
to the forties. Wee weans - even their mums and dads, maybe - will roar and
guffaw at Logan's expert antics without ever knowing the half, the nth, of his
achievements within British variety and British theatre.
As he dights foundation over clean-shaven jaws, the anecdotes and panto-lore
issue from the changing face in the mirror. ``Five and nine, that was all you
used to need, Leichner's sticks in five and nine. Things have got a bit more
subtle - it's more a brown base now, not pink with the rouged dots, like a
clown.'' He talks of pantos done with Arthur Askey - Askey hospitalised after
being caught in a stage trap - of topping a bill with the legendary Douglas
Byng when Howard and Wyndham Productions ruled the stages. The Palladium in
Fountainbridge, Edinburgh, the Palladium in London - Logan played them all.
Suddenly the dressing-room is full of jostling dames and comics, their voices
and reminiscences all emanating from this figure now carving out a cupid's bow,
with extra curve on the corners. ``It helps with the smile.'' The lips stretch
into a ``will I eat you now or save you for later?'' grin, guaranteed to raise
laughs and goosebumps in equal measure.
Dames have to have this ambiguity, he says, as - peering over two Everests of
fibrefill - he slips on a pair of tights. Logan's legs are, by the way,
drop-dead, catwalk brilliant. Last year, at Kirkcaldy, I overhead this chap say
to a female colleague - ``He's got better legs than you''. ``I know,'' she said
mournfully, ``it's not fair.'' A size 11 pair of black high heels accentuate
the shapely calves and up he rises for the finishing touches.
``The audience have to know it's a man inside all the gear. That's the joke.
But at the same time, the Dame has to be like - like a granny, or the wummin up
the stairs, someone they'll know. Someone they'll laugh at, but trust. Because
it's all about good winning out over evil you know. And about putting the stars
in a child's eyes. That, most of all.'' And in a swoosh of frou-frou, a last
pat of an Ab Fab blonde hairdo and the teensiest dab of rouge, our dame is
ready to sashay centre stage. For sheer guts - and garters - there is nothin'
like a Dame.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO>GH951125-000150</DOCNO>
