<DATE>951125</DATE>
<HEADLINE>The Butcher stirs and London heeds the threat</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>Michael Fry</BYLINE>
<EDITION>1</EDITION>
<PAGE>45</PAGE>
<RECORDNO>975208657</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
LONDON, November 25 - The Duke of Cumberland is on his way north today, after
his father, King George II, this week gave him supreme command of the forces
deployed to halt the Jacobite invasion of England.
The appointment, the first sign that a darkening situation is being taken in
hand, was greeted with relief at Westminster and in the streets of the capital.
It was met with cheers and celebrations by the soldiers likely to face the
brunt of the clans' onslaught, the 15 regiments of infantry and five of cavalry
immobilised for several days at Lichfield, Staffordshire, through the illness
of their general, Sir John Ligonier.
Cumberland, only 24, is the hero of these veterans rushed home from the war in
Flanders. He commanded there for just one campaign, and was actually beaten at
the Battle of Fontenoy in May. But that did not dent the popularity he had won
by his bravery on the field of Dettingen two years ago. Wounded in the thick of
the fighting, he still helped to snatch victory from potential defeat. Now the
king has placed his hopes on his son again, as alarm spreads in a previously
complacent London.
After taking Carlisle, Prince Charles Edward Stuart has seized the initiative
and is marching rapidly south with little to stop him. Appalling conditions in
the mountains of Cumberland and Westmorland seem not to have hampered the
Jacobites' movements at all. Nor does their lack of equipment. As they have no
tents, they are advancing in two columns, one a day ahead of the other, so that
they can use the same quarters in the towns they pass.
The prince, leading the second column, refuses to ride and marches on foot as
well, wearing Highland dress with a blue sash and bonnet, sporting a white rose
in the band. His pipes and drums play The King shall enjoy his own again. His
clansmen carry banners with slogans - ``Liberty and Property, Church and King''
- meant to reassure onlookers.
Charles arrived at Penrith on November 21, covered 27 miles over snow and ice
to Kendal on November 23, and has now arrived at Lancaster. At Preston, where
the road improves, he will be able to rendezvous with his vanguard under Lord
George Murray.
Preston was the southernmost point reached by an army of English and Scottish
Jacobites in their last rebellion. There they were surrounded and forced to
surrender 30 years ago almost to the day. No such thing is likely to happen
this time.
Just one attempt has so far been made to intercept the invasion. Before
Carlisle fell, General George Wade tried to relieve it by crossing the Pennine
Hills from Newcastle, only to be beaten back by the atrocious weather. The
Government has no other troops closer than Lichfield.
The Lord Lieutenant of Lancashire, the Earl of Derby, called out the militia 10
days ago. At the muster he found it so raw and ill-equipped that he decided it
could not even make a token stand. He rejected Wade's advice that it might at
least harass the Highlanders by sniping from behind hedge rows. Instead he has
ordered it off the main road south and sent it to Liverpool. There it will be
disarmed and dismissed, and its equipment stored on ships to prevent capture.
Derby is himself leaving for London, along with many other local landowners.
The flight of the gentry rules out the organisation of any resistance, and is
bound to depress the Lancastrians' morale. It must do the same as refugees
arrive here in the capital. The king, according to sources at court, has
adopted an attitude of ``obstinate, angry, determined practicality''.
But there can be no mistaking the deep worries of the Cabinet, especially of
the Prime Minister, Henry Pelham, and of his brother, the Duke of Newcastle,
the Whigs' parliamentary manager and electoral organiser, who has stated that
George II's crown is in ``the utmost danger''. The Secretary of State for
Scotland, the Marquis of Tweeddale, is under a cloud for abject failure to nip
the rebellion in the bud. The king has instead been taking advice on the
Scottish situation from Lord Marchmont, a Tory though not a Jacobite.
There are even rumours at Westminster that the Pelham brothers might be able to
live with a restoration of the Stuarts so long as they could ward off a French
landing in the South of England - though it is for the very purpose of opening
up two fronts that Prince Charles has invaded the north. The Government's
overriding concern is to avoid giving France a victory that would let her
finish the war in Europe and dictate the terms of peace. This would lose
Britain some of her colonies and other trading advantages.
In sending forces to engage Prince Charles, the Government risks leaving the
English coast unprotected. Since the Jacobite victory at Prestonpans in
September, the French have assembled shipping at Calais, Boulogne, and Dunkirk.
They have concentrated 15,000 troops in the area, mostly regiments for King
Louis XV's Irish Brigade. But the commander appointed for the expedition, the
Duc de Richelieu, has yet to move out of Paris.
Arrival of the first small reinforcement from France was reported, however,
three days ago in Scotland. After evading the Royal Navy in the North Sea, Lord
John Drummond landed at Montrose, Stonehaven, and Peterhead with a Scottish and
an Irish regiment in the French service, 800 soldiers in all. He is a brother
of the Duke of Perth, one of Prince Charles's generals.
He immediately issued a proclamation which, on his own initiative, exceeded the
terms of the Treaty of Fontainbleau signed last month between Louis XV and the
Jacobite ambassador to Versailles, which specified French help only for
Scotland. Drummond promised that his troops would join in the conquest of
England and Ireland as well, and that he would soon have 6000 more of them.
n Another dispatch next week.
</TEXT>
