<DATE>951125</DATE>
<HEADLINE>All your Basques in the one exit</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>Deirdre Chapman</BYLINE>
<EDITION>1</EDITION>
<PAGE>40</PAGE>
<RECORDNO>975208658</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
SUCH an elegant city is San Sebastian, a city innocent of slouch sox and zip
tops and the chain stores which sell these things. Along the Avenida de la
Libertad every heel has a little height, every throat and earlobe a little
gold. All skirts are slim, all blouses worn tucked in. Older men wear linen
jackets and the Basque beret, Picasso-style. Older women had their hair done
yesterday. Possibly it is in the by-laws.
But what is elegance without exuberance, or hair up without hair down?
The Donostia Tourist Award for Cultural Balance, then, to the gang of four I
found peeing against a wall in the old quarter on the night of the Basque
Regatta, caught short after a gallon or two of celebratory txakoli. I know it
was celebratory because they were wearing pink; the dusky, slightly faded
Schiaparelli pink of the winning team rather than the
damask-napkin-blotted-with-crevettes-Marie-Rose shade of one of the losers. The
Celtic v Rangers quality of regatta night in San Sebastian is utterly redeemed
by the absence of primary colours.
The teams, from fishing villages along the Spanish Basque coast, wear T-shirts
in shades of bougainvillea, mimosa, and avocado. Their support is numbered in
thousands; whole hillsides heave with pale lilac; monuments, terraces, and
boulevards are a toppling mass of iced pistachio.
We were watching from the sea, on the Lord Mayor's boat, on a blowy day with
brisk little waves rocking open boats like elongated soup tureens which, since
breakfast time, had been ferrying friends, families, and sporting citizens (the
Basques are wild betters) out to the perimeter of the three-mile round-the-bay
course.
The bay of San Sebastian is nothing if not spectacular. From the headland of
Monte Urgull, where a giant statue of Our Lady balances on a slim pinnacle in
modest imitation of Rio de Janeiro, to the heights of Monte Igueldo behind the
town, the city wraps itself around its three beaches and the mouth of its
sparkling river with the jagged shapes of the Pre-Pyrenees for a backdrop, as
befits the home of a film festival, gourmet capital of Spain, and summer
retreat of the pre-Franco royals.
Patrician Madrilenos of last century flocked here in the wake of Queen Maria
Christina, escaping north to the mountain air rather than south to the Sahara
breath that turns on northern Europe.
Much as London society followed Queen Victoria to Deeside, they built their
splendid villas beneath Monte Igueldo and, social revolution coming slow to
Spain, most citizens can remember aproned maids scurrying out on to Ondaretta
Beach each day with linen and fine china and the endless courses of a Basque
lunch. Franco, too, came here each summer, but in this utterly divergent region
that has Guernica in its hinterland, was not much seen outside his walls.
Today the royals go to Majorca and the Basque separatists dangle their banners
equably enough among the regatta team colours along the promenade, albeit their
slogan translates ``Those who wear the blue ribbon are the murderers'' - a
reference to the groundswell of protest against the separatists' tactics of
kidnapping prominent citizens; dissenters wear blue lapel ribbons.
The utter distinctiveness of Basque culture and language is not laboured, as
the cosmetic fiddling with Spanish place names might suggest. Euskadi is the
region comprising the provinces of Gipuzkoa, Bizkaia, and Araba; San Sebastian
in Basque is Donostia, and this form is favoured on direction signs; personal
names are constructed out of discarded Scrabble tiles and torn-out end pages of
dictionaries. Arantxa is not Basque, but her name is. Olazabal scores on both
counts. The Basques are thought to have arrived from the Caucasus around 4000
BC - the language has links with Georgian - and they got here first.
You may still come across a spray-painted ETA sign - Euskadi ta Askatasuna,
Freedom for the Basques - but the present degree of autonomy, which makes the
parliament here the only regional one with tax-raising powers, has brought
about a general reaction to strong-arm methods.
This is, after all, the most ordered society in Spain with, tucked away between
a coastline reminiscent of the French Riviera and an Alpine hinterland out of
The Sound of Music, the peninsula's heaviest industrialisation and 96% of
Spain's Michelin-starred restaurants.
If there is a Basque word for regatta I wish I knew it, to distance this
boiling bayful of people from the Henley model. Erratic oompahs across the
water herald the approach of the band boat which wobbles past, dangerously
overcrowded with plump musicians in sailor suits and Harpo Marx hats, balancing
upright, all brass and elbow, two miles out.
The 12-man racing boats rowing an abbreviated Oxford to Cambridge course in the
open sea commemorate the pre-mechanised local fishing industry when the crews
or rival villages would race the catch back to the quay to get the best prices.
All this, mark you, is a bit distant and theoretical for anyone brought up on
Sportsnight sinew close-ups.
But we certainly know when the race is finished. Engines rev and everything
converges at speed - motor launches, yachts, fishing boats, inflatables, kayaks
- some making serious waves, others bouncing off them, and the winners, the
pretty pink party themselves, rowing against the tide, clamber on to our deck
for the presentation.
San Sebastian's own Alan Partridge, all designer suit and tangled mike flex, is
hoisted across a gap from a motor launch. The human bouillabaisse claps and
cheers. Back on shore everyone settles down to a celebratory four-hour lunch as
a prelude to the evening's tapas bar crawl.
We are staying in the Hotel Maria Christina, San Sebastian's finest. My window
looks down the Paseo de Republica Argentina past giant hoardings of Mel Gibson
in woad. The hero himself arrives in two days time for the film festival.
Whichever way you walk from here you hit water, and, if you're lucky, a
happening.
Strolling early along the River Urumea, admiring the litter-free pavements, the
trees, the benches, the elegance of the joggers, past the art-deco Kursaal
Bridge and the rococo Maria Christina Bridge built by Gustave Eiffel, I hear a
pipe band playing Scotland the Brave.
Across the sparse early traffic stream comes a willowy, olive-skinned cohort of
mock Scots in Black Watch tartan, followed by a detachment of Redcoats playing
The British Grenadiers on fife and drum, a few horsemen in purple with white
berets (Portuguese, someone whispers), Napoleon on foot, and someone who may be
the Duke of Wellington mounted, and a detachment of young terrorists in shades
and black berets.
Those of us about in this late-rising weekend city, follow the band out on to a
headland where they reward us by setting off a number of bombs. Next to me a
stout lady sits down on the sea wall and starts to sob. The cannon fire that
follows is therapeutic by comparison, and when it is returned from the wooded
slopes of Monte Igueldo we are hardly nervous at all.
Throughout the morning I keep running into the procession, good-naturedly
exchanging small arms fire with householders on their balconies, or accepting
the French surrender, for all this is to commemorate the raising of Napoleon's
five-year siege of San Sebastian by the British and Portuguese in 1813 for
which, to this day, people are only moderately and retrospectively grateful.
The fire the British started destroyed most of the city and caused the loss of
more than 2000 lives. The resulting rebuilding, however, with broad avenues,
stunning squares - one has an island housing a duck pond, a Japanese bridge,
and banana plants - and architectural influences from all over Europe is the
source of San Sebastian's present glory.
It is the partevieja, the old quarter, a maze of tiny passages crammed in
beneath Monte Urgull, which houses the city's most atmospheric pinchas bars,
pinchas being the delectable Basque version of tapas, as well as two stunning
churches whose facades are first glimpsed in slices at the end of the little
streets. The sixteenth-century Gothic San Vicente and the eighteenth-century
baroque Santa Maria, are survivors of the great blaze, following which the
townspeople decided to rebuild the city. Today's citizens are every bit as
resourceful, the traders voting successfully to keep all chain stores out of
the city.
After dark during Basque festivals - that is to say, a lot of the time - the
steep-sided Constitution Square in the old quarter, once a bullring, has
musicians playing Trikitrixas, even the most sophisticated cafe-goers drop
their pinchas, raise their arms Highland style, and perform what is surely the
fastest free-form folk dance on earth.
And then there is pelota, a sort of killer squash peculiar to the Basques,
played in a fronton, with heavy gambling right to the last point, the
cigar-smoking spectators tossing their bets to courtside bookies in hollowed
out tennis balls. I spent two hours at a fronton utterly enthralled. There is a
bar, but no-one is drunk. The paired players have the appearance of mutated
lobsters with one giant right claw - the basket strapped to the wrist - to
launch the hard ball at the wall. The sustained and shifting betting pattern
produces such an adrenalin high that the best players are regularly flown to
Macao to provide sport for Asia's gambling capital.
None of this eccentricity prepares you for the classic alpine scenery of the
hinterland. The Regil Valley is a stunning confection of severe perpendicular
mountain dwellings, steep plantings of maize and apples, and pasture that
reaches to the summits and provides contrast for the high, bare peaks in the
distance.
At Loyala, birthplace of Ignatius, founder of the Jesuit order, the paved
courtyard in front of Spain's biggest basilica, where the Pope's helicopter
once landed, has the air of a village square in evening, which indeed it is.
Small boys do wheelies, mothers perch with their babies on the wall, chatting,
against a sweeping avenue of trees donated by the world's Catholic countries.
The great eroded stone lions of the balustrade are silhouetted against steep
hillsides with grazing cows. The church, part baroque, part Renaissance, holds
4000, and built into its overwhelming opulence is the substantial stone house
where Loyola was born in 1491. The museum here is excellent, all the better for
the contrast of its remote setting when you come blinking out into the light.
Up and down the Basque coast there are a host of steep-sided fishing villages,
all with wonderful fish restaurants.
Getaria, south of San Sebastian, was home to Sebastian Elcano, the first man
actually to circumnavigate the globe (Magellan, who gets the credit, died on
the way home). Not to mention Balenciaga, and Placido Domingo's mother.
Nearby Zarautz is a surfers' mecca. Heading north towards the French border,
Hondarribia (Fuenterrabia), the last town in Spain, has wonderful centuries-old
houses and restaurants, a sandy beach, and the most haunting and oldest of all
paradors in the eleventh-century castle of Carlos V, restored just enough to be
habitable, so that you may sit in a glassed-over half-courtyard looking out on
to a massive shattered tenth-century wall, or sleep in a bedroom whose window
recesses alone could shelter a homeless family.
FACTFILE
IBERIA flies Heathrow to Bilbao, a one-and-a-half hour flight from #169 return
with special offers available. San Sebastian is an hour's drive away.
There is a ferry connection from Portsmouth.
Local transport is excellent. Hotels tend to be pricey - the five-star Maria
Christina is 23,800 pesetas for two sharing a double room (CIGA reservations:
0800 353535) - but there are inexpensive pensions and an excellent campsite at
Barrio Igueldo.
Hondarribia's Parador El Emperador (no restaurant) is a bargain at from 16,000
pesetas for a double room.
For further information and details of Basque Fiestas contact the Spanish
National Tourist Office, 57-58 St James's Street, London SW1A 1LD, Tel: 0171
449 0901.
</TEXT>
