<TEXT>
astards Of Melody, Love Nut (One Fifteen/Interscope)
q Eh up, granddad, we're living in a punked-up, post-post-grunge world of
non-specific guitar grindings and shouty vox. But don't turn your deaf-aid
down. Love Nut, a perky bunch who apparently hail from Baltimore, add nasal
Beatloid vocal melodies to the standard market-led mix, seemingly moved by the
sarky spirit of moptop Johnny Lemondrop rather than the blankness of Burt
Cokain. Thus it is Love Nut's Nirvana-style statements of teenage alienation -
``I'm a loser, I'm nothing, I'm never gonna be what you want'' - come over with
a measure of amused irony. Love Nut music is crisp as well as loud; deft as
well as muscular. And you'd have to be very, very aged not to tap an
appreciative toe to Love Nut's steamroller version of the Lemon Pipers'
splendid chestnut Green Tambourine.
Everyday I Wear A Greasy Black Feather On My Hat, Moondog Jr (Island)
q An assembly of rasping Belgians, one of whom is a temporary refugee from
deUS, seek to be moved by the holy ghost of Troutmask Replica. At their best,
they're like Captain Beefheart and the Magic Band mixed with War and Tom Waits.
At their most ordinary, Moondog Jr resemble the Red Hot Chilli Peppers trying
too hard to be Captain Beefheart and the Magic Band mixed with War and Tom
Waits. Overall, some pleasing moments of atonal funkiness. But for that
full-flavour Beefheart Martian-delta blues experience, you're best advisd to
dig out your copy of Lick My Decals Off, Baby.
A Recipe For Disaster, DJ Food (Ninja Tune)
q DJ Food isn't so much the name of the act as part of this album's philosophy.
It was assembled by Ninja Tune's ruling duo, Jonathan More and Matt Black,
better known as Coldcut, and is intended to demonstrate the sonic happeningness
of blokes who, instead of employing cumbersome and outmoded musical
instruments, wield turntables and programme beat-boxes and samplers. So how
good is it? Well, its sleeve provides an inadvertent summing-up. It features a
photograph of a take-away pizza. Next time round Coldcut should enlist the help
of more live musos to cook up something fresher.
</TEXT>
