<DOCNO>GH951125-000153</DOCNO>
<DOCID>GH951125-000153</DOCID>
<DATE>951125</DATE>
<HEADLINE>Making for safe waters</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>Peter Evans</BYLINE>
<EDITION>1</EDITION>
<PAGE>42</PAGE>
<RECORDNO>975208660</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
WHEN four teenagers drowned in the sea after a canoe paddle along the Dorset
coast went tragically wrong, the shock waves reverberated through outdoor
centres the length and breadth of Britain - and forced government action to
improve safety regulations.
The Activity Centres (Young Persons' Safety) Act became law in June this year
and a consultation document is now being considered concerning its practical
implementation in the form of regulations covering commercial providers of
adventure activities.
But while the welfare of young people attending activity centres is widely
recognised as important, there are fears that if adventurous pursuits are
hedged about with too many regulations, youngsters will be deprived of
enjoyment and may be excluded from taking part in ``risk'' sports.
The Activity Centres Act was the direct result of what has become known as the
Lyme Bay tragedy. On March 22, 1993, a party of eight sixth-formers from a
school in Plymouth set off on what was intended to be a two-hour return trip
from Lyme Regis to Charmouth. With them were their teacher and two
outdoor-centre instructors.
What should have been a straightforward exercise turned to disaster when the
youngsters were swept out to sea and their canoes capsized. The group was
eventually rescued by helicopter, but it was too late for four of the teenagers
- two boys and two girls - who had been in the cold and increasingly rough sea
for three hours or more.
Their deaths caused a public outcry after a 16-day trial at Winchester Crown
Court revealed that the trip had been a catalogue of errors - not least of
which was that neither of the instructors in the party had even the most basic
supervisory qualification in canoeing.
The trial led to the managing director of the company running the activity
centre which organised the outing being jailed for three years for
manslaughter. A powerful call was issued by the judge, Mr Justice Ognall, for a
Government inquiry into the running of activity centres, and improved safety
controls.
Where parents and teachers entrusted their children to those who ran activity
holidays, the potential for injury or death was too obvious for safety
procedures to be left to the inadequate vagaries of self-regulation, he said.
The stinging comments could not be ignored by the Government, particularly when
backed up by parental pressure for action, and the Activity Centres Act was the
almost inevitable result. The Health and Safety Commission has circulated a
consultation document to interested parties on the detailed specifications of
the Act and the deadline for responses was yesterday. After they have been
examined, the commission will draw up proposals for a series of regulations
designed to tighten up on safety at commercial outdoor centres.
But Peter Hitt, a former adviser on outdoor education for Lothian Region, who
now runs a consultancy specialising in risk assessment and management, believes
the whole exercise is something of a knee-jerk reaction, and that health and
safety legislation already in place offers a sufficient degree of control.
``The Lyme Bay tragedy was one tiny incident in terms of the overall numbers of
children taking part in outdoor activities,'' he said. ``If we applied the same
rules to travelling on the road we just wouldn't go.''
That was not to say that people should not be qualified to supervise
youngsters, simply that the whole thing should be kept in perspective. The
Health and Safety Commission document itself acknowledges: ``There is
widespread recognition that some degree of risk is unavoidable if these
activities are to accomplish their essential purpose. The activities allow
young people to develop by meeting challenges they do not necessarily face
every day, and to experience a sense of achievement in overcoming them.'' It
also says that ``there have been few accidents and the numbers involved have,
in statistical terms, been low''.
The criteria laid down for deciding which adventure activities should be
subject to statutory licensing are those involving a significant risk of death;
where the activity is vulnerable to changes in weather or the natural
environment; and where there is a significant risk to the safety of the group
if things go wrong. The competence of instructors and leaders is also regarded
as crucial.
``It was the failure of management to make proper provision for these factors
which led to the tragedy at Lyme Bay in 1993 where four young people lost their
lives. The few similar tragedies point to the same conclusions about the main
sources of risk,'' states the document.
Activities to which the criteria apply are listed as caving, climbing, mountain
walking, paddle sports (including canoeing), sailing, and skiing. The document
indicates that: ``When instruction or leadership in any of the activities
within the scope of the statutory scheme is offered on a commercial basis to
young persons under 18, the provider would need to obtain a licence.''
The commission makes it clear that ``it does not wish to cut across the freedom
of voluntary and national youth organisations to offer the opportunity to
members to participate in adventure activities on a non-commercial basis. It is
therefore proposed that voluntary associations should not be subject to
statutory licensing except when they choose to act in a commercial manner.''
One such voluntary organisation is the Scout Association. David Shelmerdine,
chief executive of its Scottish Council, has been examining the proposal
document and its potential impact.
``Parents are looking for some reassurance that their sons and daughters will
be under the supervision of competent people if they are going to outdoor
centres,'' he said. ``What it's leading to really is a reassurance to people
that there aren't cowboys operating in the sector.
``I think everybody acknowledges that where there is adventurous activity there
is an element of risk; but obviously there needs to be risk assessment and
that's where you come on to needing competent and approved staff.''
One problem the association is grappling with before responding to the
consultation document is that it will be forced to obtain statutory licences
for its two activity centres in Scotland - one at Lochgoilhead in Argyll and
the other at its Fordell Firs headquarters near Dunfermline in Fife - if it
wishes to continue letting them out on a commercial basis.
The costs involved in setting up and running the licensing authority, plus the
costs to providers of making improvements to their safety management have been
estimated at between #2.7m and #5.3m over a period of 10 years, depending on
the number of centres covered by the scheme, thought to be between 1000 and
3000.
Once the regulations are in place, any provider who should have a licence and
does not, or any holder of a licence who contravenes its conditions, could be
liable to a fine or up to two years' imprisonment. A licensing authority for
the whole of Britain will oversee the scheme and centres will be subject to
inspection. All licences will have to be renewed annually, and a fee paid. The
consultation document acknowledges that ``it is unlikely that the benefits of
the regulations will ever exceed the costs'', and that ``if the licensing
scheme was extended to schools and voluntary organisations, it is estimated
that the costs would exceed the quantifiable benefits by a ratio of 20 to one''.
In this area though, where children's lives are at stake, cost-benefit analysis
and cold calculation come a poor second to emotion.
Parents must have the confidence that their children are properly cared for
when they attend outdoor centres. It is equally important, though, that the
regulations are not so stringent and complex that they lose out on the
opportunity to take risks and test themselves in the outdoors.
</TEXT>
