<DOCNO>GH951125-000154</DOCNO>
<DOCID>GH951125-000154</DOCID>
<DATE>951125</DATE>
<HEADLINE>Flowers of the forest</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>Sarah Nelson</BYLINE>
<EDITION>1</EDITION>
<PAGE>40</PAGE>
<RECORDNO>975208661</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
MUNCHING through tart lemony leaves, I cried triumphantly ``wood sorrel!'' as
alarmed ladies strode their dogs through the beautiful, ancient Birks of
Aberfeldy.
``Wild carrot, wall lettuce, wild garlic!'' Fired with enthusiasm, I realised
how few friends would now risk calling at my house for a salad.
Thousands of outdoor people, I suspect, have shared my hang ups and
frustrations on the whole topic of wild flowers and plants. Trudging through
heather, meadows, glens and bogs, ever more intrigued by splashes of colour or
delicate waving rock beauties, we long to know what they are, or how much rare
saxifrage we've passed blindly in a day.
But birds (when they keep still) look satisfyingly like the books: the yellow
flower we hold before baffling, jargony texts could be one of 30.
Armed with my formidable knowledge of dandelions, sinister spotted orchids, old
lupins and killer foxglove leaves (from Agatha Christie) I finally seized
courage and enrolled on a wild flower identification course with Scottish
Conservation Projects: first in the Birks' woodland habitat, then in the
mysterious peatlands of Scottish Wildlife Trust's nature reserve on Flanders
Moss. Dr Veronica Howard, SCP's training services manager, was our excellent,
knowledgeable and infectiously enthusiastic tutor.
The charity runs dozens of training courses each year (mainly at weekends) on
many topics related to conservation and environment, along with numerous other
activities.
We met British and foreign students, retired lecturers, a ranger who wished his
bosses came on such courses ``because they're the ones who need to'', and a
former health visitor who'd changed tack to study for a rural resources degree.
Some people belonged to one of SCP's 75 active affiliated local groups and
midweek groups, which attract an even greater variety of volunteer members
including unemployed and retired people, and school leavers.
Howard's courses were particularly valuable to novices in keeping groups small,
and in combining straightforward, relaxed and jargon-free exploration with
useful lecturers and written material which included glossaries of baffling
terms.
You learn to think about basic clues before peering at flower illustrations:
what's the habitat, altitude, season, climate, tree or shrub layer?
You learn to be observant about which similar plants have hairy or smooth
leaves; to sniff carefully, discovering many new aromas of pineapple or fetid
unpleasantness: and if you're a writer, you marvel at the richness of language
and description. Solomons Seal, Yellow Archangel, Wood Sanicle, Marsh
Woundwort, Doves-Foot and Cranesbill.
There are only two problems. First, this is a complex absorption which must be
followed up. Compared with birdwatching, you forget this amazing new knowledge
quickly unless you keep pursuing it. That could be dangerous, especially if you
acquire a zest for herbs and edible plants: I've already forgotten what hemlock
looks like.
The second warning is that still more than birdwatching, it encourages bizarre
obsessive behaviour - in my case, sniffing through weeds on hands and knees at
Crieff Hydro, then being driven from allotments on suspicion of loitering with
intent.
n Scottish Conservation Projects can be contacted at 24 Allan Park, Stirling
FK8 2QG. Tel: 01786 479697.
</TEXT>
