<DOC>
<DOCNO>GH951125-000155</DOCNO>
<DOCID>GH951125-000155</DOCID>
<DATE>951125</DATE>
<HEADLINE>How hard to walk away</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>KEN GALLACHER</BYLINE>
<EDITION>1</EDITION>
<PAGE>47</PAGE>
<ARTICLETYPE>Profile</ARTICLETYPE>
<RECORDNO>975208662</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
SOPRANO saxophone star Bob Wilber has startled the jazz world by announcing
that he is to retire from playing in May next year.
If Wilber follows through on this intention then he will be the first jazz
musician of note to give up playing while still physically able to lift his
horn to his lips.
In present times when longevity is being celebrated with records from still
active veterans still being made and issued, it is an astonishing decision and
one I hope Wilber will reconsider.
There are personal reasons behind my wish that Wilber continues to play, not
just an admiration for his skills on soprano saxophone, clarinet and, to a
lesser extent tenor as well.
Wilber, the one-time protege of Sidney Bechet, has been a seminal figure in my
own jazz experiences. He was a member of the Eddie Condon All Stars who toured
Britain in l957 and while I was a young reporter on the Dundee Courier Wilber
was one of the first American musicians I heard in the flesh and was able to
interview.
He was still under 30 himself then. I can still recall his clarinet feature in
the Caird Hall that night - he played Love Me Or Leave Me without a hint of the
rhapsodic Bechet in his tone because by that time he had moved away from his
first major influence to embrace the styles of Benny Goodman and others.
By the time I next caught up with him it was New York in l968 and Wilber had
returned to playing soprano and was a charter member of The World's Greatest
Jazz Band, a stellar group which helped revitalise Wilber's playing and
resurrect his career.
By now the Bechet legacy was only a faint echo with Wilber using a curved
soprano and he admits: ``From the very first notes I played on it, I heard a
definite difference from the straight soprano sound I was used to. My first
influence was Johnny Hodges and then I added Louis Armstrong and I began to
feel that this was the distinctive musical identity I had been looking for.''
His feature when I heard him in the Rainbow Grill, high above Manhattan that
night, was One Morning In May and it was the hint of Hodges that captivated me
and which did give Wilber the individual voice he had been seeking.
That voice continued to be heard when he left the WGJB and formed one of the
most exciting small groups of the seventies, Soprano Summit, with fellow reed
man Kenny Davern.
The group remained together for three years and has been revived on occasions
in recent years as Summit Reunion with Wilber playing soprano, clarinet, alto
and tenor while Davern limits himself solely to clarinet. The music has again
been memorable and it is hard to believe that Wilber will walk away from all of
this in a few months' time.
In his autobiography Music Was Not Enough he wrote tellingly: ``Things outside
music have become important to me. I no longer need to be a success; I don't
need to make it. I already am and I already have!''
I hope he thinks again because he is one of the keepers of the flame, a link
going back to the giants of the music and a player who respects the jazz
tradition and understands it.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO>GH951125-000156</DOCNO>
