<HEADLINE>Preying on predators</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>PAUL YOUNG</BYLINE>
<EDITION>1</EDITION>
<PAGE>42</PAGE>
<RECORDNO>975208664</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
I AM continually fascinated by the lengths to which some anglers will go in
their passionate pursuit of one particular species of fish. The general
perception of a Scottish angler is, perhaps, of a happy chappy who enjoys the
odd winter day fishing for grayling, a cast or two for spring salmon, a holiday
outing sea-fishing with the family, and maybe a more focused couple of days for
trout on, say, Loch Leven or salmon on a reasonably priced beat of one of our
Scottish rivers.
That may be true, but there are also the addicts; those with a partiality for
pike, a sympathy with salmon, and a tantalising taste for trout or tope. Fine
chaps all, but it seems to me that those who choose the most difficult option
are the ferox fanatics.
Those who number this so-called cannibal trout as their own personal addiction
are destined to have a difficult time. They will spend many fruitless hours in
its pursuit on the large and sometimes featureless ferox lochs of Scotland, but
those with a smidgeon of knowledge of its habits and habitats will, as ever in
fishing, have an advantage over the chap who turns up at the waterside with a
vague idea of how to go about it.
One man who I suspect has never had a vague idea in his life, is Ron Greer. As
far as I can tell, all his ideas have been definite and well thought-out, and
his new book, Ferox Trout and Arctic Charr . . . A Predator, its Pursuit and
its Prey is proof of his dedication to and interest in this fish.
Greer comes at his subject from several directions. Having worked at the
Freshwater Fisheries Laboratory at Faskally, gives him scientific credence. His
work with the Loch Garry Tree Group marks his care and concern for the country.
And his cheerful guidance of that happy band of fanatics, the Ferox-85 Group,
shows a deep-seated sense of humour and patience while pursuing this often
difficult quarry.
Starting with the premise that the ferox, and its prey, the charr, are a legacy
of the climatic changes during successive Ice Ages of the Pleistocene era, the
ferox being the aquatic equivalent of the wolf, perhaps, Greer suggests that
land-based plants and animals can be touched, picked, watched, and photographed.
People identify with the conservation of this wildlife, especially if it has a
nice smell or a ``kittenish'' face, whereas fish live in an alien aquatic
environment, and their lives are largely unknown. When wolves brought down
Irish elk for food in the Shannon basin and bull reindeer battled for mates on
the shores of what is now Loch Shin, ferox and charr were even then engaged in
the same roles that they play today. Underwater, we are transported back to the
Ice Age.
Ferox are to be found in many lochs and lakes in northern Europe. They are not
to be confused with the American lake trout, which is actually a species of
charr. We are talking about a member of the salmon family, a true trout, Salmo
trutta. ``Ferox trout'' covers virtually every aspect of the fish and its life.
There is a wealth of information on how to go about catching this fascinating
fish. Details of fishable lochs, baits, and terminal tackle, and most important
of all, protective clothing for those long wet days, are given with great good
humour.
It is suggested that ferox fishing can be bum-numbing and brain-numbing, but I
reckon that anyone reading Greer's book will find the subject fascinating. And
he and the Ferox-85 Group know what they are talking about. In April 1993,
their experience and relentlessness (an important word in ferox fishing)
brought them a new British record brown trout . . . 19lb, 103/8oz, to be
precise. Greer reckons there are bigger ferox to be caught in Scotland, and
this well-researched, passionate, and humorous book will certainly put you in
the mood to out-ferox the Ferox-85 Group. But remember, you'll have to be
especially relentless!
n Ferox Trout and Arctic Charr . . . A Predator, its Pursuit and its Prey,
published by Swan Hill Press, #19.95.
</TEXT>
