<HEADLINE>The nimby factor hits capital's plan for a leper colony</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>Jim Hewitson</BYLINE>
<EDITION>1</EDITION>
<PAGE>42</PAGE>
<RECORDNO>975208665</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
n THE Big Interview No.6 - Elspeth Hopringle (tenants' leader) Edinburgh,
November 1591.
Myths: For decades Edinburgh has lagged behind other parts of Scotland in
providing a local leper sanctuary. However, the city's decision today to back a
plan for the construction of a small house for lepers north of Calton Hill has
not met with universal approval. Elspeth Hopringle is secretary of Greenside
Tenants' Association. You say, Mistress Hopringle, that you're infuriated by
this decision but are you not leaving yourself open to charges of overriding
self-interest?
Hopringle: Have you ever shaken hands wi' a leper? I mean, given his hand a
right good shake. Of course, you haven't. Everyone is nervous about having
lepers around. It's only natural. We realise the need for a sanctuary. It's a
damned disgrace that Aberdeen, Glasgow, and Ayr have had sanctuaries long since
and the capital is only now getting round to facing the problem. But we
sincerely believe the wrong place has been chosen. Let's face it - would the
cooncillors have a leper colony at their front door?
Myths: Am I right in thinking that your association represents only the
occupiers of a few dilapidated shacks on the road to Leith?
Hopringle: They might just be shacks to you, son, but they're home sweet home
to us. Wi' property values already having slipped thanks to those years o'
feuding between King Jamie and his mammy this latest brainwave is bound to send
prices into the basement. Mind you, that's just a side issue, it's the
principle we're concerned wi'.
Myths: Are you not reassured by the arrangements for the operation of the
hostel which the council announced today? The leper house is to be run to a
very strict set of rules with only five residents, two with their wives. The
lepers are, under no circumstances, to stir from the house, to go about looking
for alms, no visitors will be permitted. From sunrise to sunset the door is to
be kept locked fast and the only concession to contact with the outside world
is that wives will be allowed to go to market and each patient will take in
turns to sit at the door with a clapper and beg on behalf of the house from
passers-by.
Hopringle: Oh aye, that's all very fine but oor bairns play on that hill. Can
the council assure us that the air thereaboots will be fit to breathe. This is
the thin end o' the wedge. Our fear is that Greenside will become the dumping
ground for folk wi' all sorts of anti-social problems, Spaniards, plague
victims and the like. Look, my brother was a leper and a nicer bloke you
couldna meet. But did we invite him to dinner? Did we hell. They must be kept
apart from the community. Has anyone thought o' the Bass Rock?
Myths: Is there any further action your association can take to prevent this
proposal becoming reality?
Hopringle: We thought about delivering a barrow load of pig-shit to the front
door of the council offices but we reckoned that would be a waste of good
manure. I don't want to give too much away but there's talk of lying down in
front of the builder's cairt when construction begins.
</TEXT>
