<GRAPHIC>Photograph</GRAPHIC>
<RECORDNO>975208666</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
Highlights from the Plugged Nickel, Miles Davis (Colombia)
q Taken from the exhaustive and exhausting eight-CD set, these six Davis
standards present a fascinating, warts and all, fly on the wall view of his
second great quintet (Wayne Shorter on saxophone; Herbie Hancock, piano; Ron
Carter, bass; and Tony Williams, drums) working in the intimacy of a club at a
time when colder concerts were taking over. The band is by turns expansive,
accommodating, and collectively goading, and the leader's trumpet wavers edgily
between hurt defiance and devil-may-care belligerence as only he could.
Swingin' Spirits, Ian Cruickshank with Pearl Django (Fret)
q Guitarist and Django Reinhardt disciple Cruickshank flew from his Berkshire
home to Tacoma, Washington, to play with a local string trio who, although you
might not know from this recording, embraced Reinhardt's music all of two years
previously. The tunes are substantially Cruickshank's in-the-style-of originals
with a few lesser-played Reinhardt items, crisply played and with a mixture of
reverence and freshness which puts this above the ``just another Django tribute
album'' allegations.
</TEXT>
