<DOC>
<DOCNO>GH951125-000160</DOCNO>
<DOCID>GH951125-000160</DOCID>
<DATE>951125</DATE>
<HEADLINE>Red dots in the sunrise</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>Clare Henry</BYLINE>
<EDITION>1</EDITION>
<PAGE>46</PAGE>
<ARTICLETYPE>Profile</ARTICLETYPE>
<GRAPHIC>Photograph</GRAPHIC>
<RECORDNO>975208667</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
CALLUM INNES has had a hectic year. And more hullaballoo is certain to break
next week when he appears on Channel 4, as part of the controversial London
Tate Turner Prize.
Nominated for both Britain's top art awards: the Tate Turner to be announced on
Tuesday, plus the Jerwood Painting Prize seen at London's Royal Academy and
Edinburgh's Royal Scottish Academy during this summer's Edinburgh Festival,
it's the kind of situation that only arises in books or films. It gave him the
possibility of winning a total of #50,000. I wonder what the bookmakers' odds
were?
Certainly Scottish art aficionados have all been keeping fingers and toes
crossed for this Edinburgh-born, Aberdeen-trained, Glasgow School of Art tutor
who is both an international shooting star and, for my money, the nice guy of
the art world.
Within his now ever-spinning, international circuit (shows this year include
Zurich, Paris, Stuttgart, Amsterdam, Nottingham and Dusseldorf, with Florence
in December), Innes's studio must seem a haven of peace with its white-walled
calm and inner courtyard. The studio complex was created in contemplative,
oriental style by artists Bob Callender and Liz Ogilvie and subsequently bought
for a lot of money by veteran American abstractionist Sam Francis. Soon
afterwards, it was rented to Innes.
Innes's original studio was in the old 369 Cowgate building, where his
distinctive abstracts that brought him to national notice in the 1990 British
Art Show, spilled out on to the corridor. Renting Frances's place has not
really solved his space problem, for Innes's large pristine canvases need lots
of room: room to be painted, studied and stored. However, its bright, top-lit
rooms; ``it has such beautiful light - though it was like a hothouse this
summer!'' did bring colour into his work. That, and perhaps the arrival of his
first child. ``I like the way colour can motivate; make you feel happy or sad.''
Saturated red and yellow canvases light up the space. ``Yellow is an extreme
colour. I wanted to push my painting to another extremity.'' He's aware of the
dangers of becoming decorative: ``I'm always walking a tightrope - but it's
nice when you surprise yourself.''
The new abstracts are bigger. ``I'm already looking for a larger studio,'' he
told me. ``I want to get back to what I had been expecting to do this year,
that is keep things quiet and slow, push the work forward, experiment, return
to large watercolours and paper works. My wife, Hyjdla, is a photographer as
well as looking after our son, so a studio is vital. I must find someone
interested in art with a big, cheap space to let! It's not easy.''
Ironically Francis pioneered rumbustious American abstract expressionism, only
to take a splashy oriental, minimalist swing to simplicity after a long tour of
Japan in 1957. Innes's own work relied heavily on chance at the start, as he
dripped turpentine vertically down white, cream, grey, olive or brown
monochromatic canvases, so marks bled or imploded against each other. These
vertical dribbles and rivulets soon became ``subtracted zips'' or
pinstripe-lines as the marks on canvas were controlled, structured, ``almost
completely planned,'' via subtraction.
``Callum wants to give the impression the marks left on the canvas look natural
and impersonal, the product of natural forces such as gravity and surface
tension. But he coaxes turps into channels and certain widths with great
precision. The end result is anything but chance,'' says the National Gallery's
Keith Hartley. Innes calls these landscapes: ``It's not landscape painting.
It's about walking in the hills or along Scotland's East Coast where the light
filters through in an incredible way.'' Ironically his work is rarely seen in
the UK. Zurich, Germany and Antwerp are more sympathetic.
By 1994/95 he had moved on to ``exposed'' paintings, where part is thickly
painted; another part stripped back, washed of its original oil to leave a
shadow of stain, a hint of hue. Atmospheric yet geometric; minimal yet complex,
these are above all elegant pictures. The paint can be luscious and thick, or
thin and ethereal. It can shimmer like shot silk or shantung, or drift mistily.
A methodical craftsman and perfectionist, his immaculate studio with its top
light, clean floor, precisely remade walls, ``nothing was flat or straight''
and plastic-wrapped canvases, ``it costs #90 to get them stretched - and I use
a lot'' bear witness to his care. He has an assistant, Alan, and many rows of
brushes and piles of Schmincke paints. ``I've always spent money on quality
pigment.''
This summer Innes had the unique problem of deciding how to present two very
different major London shows. He chose to ``keep the Jerwood cool'' with
characteristically restrained canvases, (white on white; black with grey) while
his current major space at the Tate has newer work done in the last two months.
``I'm very happy with the Tate show. The comments have been very favourable. So
far it's gone really well. I'm enjoying it.''
BBC2's Late Show discussion of the four finalists for the #30,000 Turner prize:
notorious dead sheep 'n' shark man Damien Hirst, racehorse fanatic Mark
Wallinger and sole woman, Mona Hatoum, had several round table pundits voting
for Innes to win.
New oils include red dots dancing on a pale shellac surface. Again it looks
like a random scatter gun pattern. In fact it's all put on with a small brush.
``A bit like manoeuvring mercury - but you only get one hour's grace before it
dries!'' He continues: ``I wanted to roughen things up again. People find it
difficult because there are several languages going on in my work.'' A solitary
square Cadmium Red canvas has an audacious single dot - not quite dead centre -
``to bring a tension,'' while a small, orange rectangle hangs near a purple and
violet residue painting which has, he says, ``a nice weight''.
The paintings may look geometric, pretend to be hard-edged, but all the edges
are drawn by hand, never by ruler. ``They are slightly squint; off the square.
There's still human frailty here!'' Pavel Buchler, who appointed Innes as
Creative Fellow at Glasgow School of Art to teach one day a week, told me:
``Innes shows there is no bottom line to painting; no end to what can be done
with paint. He's proved you can go beyond the monochrome.''
``I've tried to make the Turner pictures quite pacy,'' Innes explains. ``I want
a spatial feel. All the work is from 1995.'' He edits ruthlessly, leaving the
studio stacked with ``not-quite-good-enough'' paintings. ``Sometimes it takes
two months to realise it hasn't got the tension I want. If I'm not happy with
it, I scrap it.'' A pile of rejects bear witness to that.
One favourite olive ``rivulet'' oil hangs in his own house. ``They are so hard
to do. I don't want to part with it. It sounds ludicrous but I can only do the
olive ones in winter because crunchy beetles settle on them. The beetles won't
touch the orange and red canvases though! That's what comes of having a sort of
garden shed as a studio!''
</TEXT>
</DOC>
