<HEADLINE>Fright before Christmas</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>KENNETH WRIGHT</BYLINE>
<EDITION>1</EDITION>
<PAGE>47</PAGE>
<ARTICLETYPE>Review</ARTICLETYPE>
<RECORDNO>975208668</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
TIM BURTON'S NIGHTMARE BEFORE CHRISTMAS, retail, #14.99; also available to
rent; cert PG.
n.DO not do unto others as you would have them do unto you: they may not have
the same tastes. George Bernard Shaw sums up the moral of this rich and strange
fairy-tale, the best Christmas film since the 1947 Miracle On 34th Street and
the best animated film since Snow White.
Directed by Henry Selick but produced and scripted (and probably dreamed too,
Couch Potato reckons) by Tim Burton, Nightmare Before Christmas is a story of
good intentions gone wrong.
Jack Skellington, Pumpkin King of Hallowe'en Town, tires of the annual
Walpurgis revels and makes a takeover bid for Christmas, reasoning that Santa
Claus, whom he benignly kidnaps, will appreciate the holiday. But when the
children of the world are far less delighted than Jack expects to open their
presents and have snakes or disembodied heads pop out, Santa must be rescued
from Jack's crew of walking nightmares and sent off on his sleigh before
Christmas Night is over.
The visual style of the stop-motion animation reflects perfectly Jack's (and
Tim Burton's) ambivalent blend of mischief and goodwill. Both figures and
background have a garish funfair gaiety about them - especially Skellington's
henchmen Lock, Shock, and Barrel and the genuinely frightening bogeyman Oogie
Boogie. Even the sweetness provided by Jack's rag-doll girlfriend Sally is of
rather an eerie kind, and the single tune that composer Danny Elfman repeats
with variations has a menacing jauntiness.
In the (happy) end, though, the overall effect is of a playfully spooky kind of
innocence, and, although Couch Potato wouldn't show Nightmare to an easily
scared eight-year-old, most children will enjoy on a simple and harmless level.
It's us grown-ups who'll have nightmares.
A HARD DAY'S NIGHT (#10.99)/ HELP! (#10.99)/ THE MAKING OF A HARD DAY'S NIGHT,
all retail, #10.99/ #10.99/ #9.99
all cert PG.
n.A Hard Day's Night (1964, b&amp;w) can still make Beatles fans of a certain age
break down and cry. It's the boyish, soon-to-be-curdled energy and enthusiasm
of the Fabs themselves; the dazzling songs, composed at the peak of Lennon and
McCartney's high pop style; and perhaps most of all it's the girl in the
audience whom you can lip-read shouting George through tears and mascara.
Help! (1965) - marred by colour, a plot, and too much self-conscious wackiness
- has some wonderful moments too, but the bloom was already off the rose.
These re-issues acquire extra nostalgia value by including cinema trailers,
contemporary newsreel clips, and behind-the-scenes studio footage. Most of the
thirtieth-anniversary documentary The Making Of A Hard Day's Night, however,
was filmed too long after the fact to possess much Beatle glamour. Only the
inclusion of the You Can't Do That sequence, dumped on the cutting-room floor,
gives it any interest for anyone but Beatles obsessives (eg Couch Potato).
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
