<DATE>951125</DATE>
<HEADLINE>MY BEST AND WORST CLIMBS</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>Tom Weir</BYLINE>
<EDITION>1</EDITION>
<PAGE>40</PAGE>
<RECORDNO>975208669</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
MY best climb came after the war when I was working for Ordnance Survey. A
party of four of us attempted six peaks in the Himalayas and climbed four. One
of the things I'll never forget is the sight of so many trade routes about
20,000ft up that were used by the Tibetans on their way to India.
The worst took place on a May night in 1970 when I went out with an outstanding
rock climber, Len Lovett, to a place near Glencoe. I was leading the climb and
all of a sudden I shot into space, skyrocketed over his head and fell 160ft. He
managed to get a rescue party and by 5am I was in Stirling Royal with a cracked
hip, squashed spine and broken ribs.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO>GH951125-000163</DOCNO>
<DOCID>GH951125-000163</DOCID>
<DATE>951125</DATE>
<HEADLINE>A history too big to understand</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>ugh Ouston</BYLINE>
<EDITION>1</EDITION>
<PAGE>42</PAGE>
<RECORDNO>975208670</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
THE tourist buses for Iona twist along the Ross of Mull like boats on a short
Atlantic swell, rocking back and leaning forward over the switchbacks and blind
corners, yawing through narrow defiles and humpback bridges. The high rainy
grasslands of the hills are left behind; the sky grows flatter and lightens.
The eyes of the passengers are drawn to the west, following their thoughts,
looking for the first glimpse of grey rock beyond red, of white sand beyond
black seaweed, of Iona beyond the Mull.
Fifty years ago there was grass growing down the road's spine. The first time
George Macleod, who would have been 100 this year, came to Iona he birled down
the Ross in a pony and trap. In the nineteenth century, as for a millennium and
a half before, you straddled a Highland horse or you walked. After passing
along the Ross of Mull in 1799, Sarah Murray wrote: ``I am astonished how the
inhabitants of that quarter escape breaking their bones and necks, in
scrambling over that distance . . .''. No wonder that almost everyone who
travelled to Iona, or indeed on the west coast at all, travelled by sea. The
Ross then was effectively another island, settled on its sandy bays and grassy
glens but for the most part forbidding cliffs fronting unforgiving moor.
On the north coast of the peninsula, Loch Scridain offered shelter and fishing
to the iron age clans, the ancestors of the Macleans. They built their little
forts on the volcanic platforms that sit above the shore line and grazed their
stock in the rushy valleys. Every generation since then had walked as I did on
an early April morning through the cattle tracks of a slope of willow carr,
letting the warmth on the back of their hand link that spring with all the
springs before.
In the oxters of boulders and between the toes of trees the primroses were
growing. The woods had hardly a burr of green; the grass was sere and the
ditches full. But the bright acid yellow of the primroses gladdened the land.
What cultural baggage did the iron age farmers carry to the sight of the
flowers of spring? I could not begin to reach it, only its echo in poetry and
story. But I do not believe it was so different from my own: the cruel joy of
mere survival, the tingle of recognition reaching back into the arms of
childhood, the deep-breathed pause between work and work.
The difference? I was a visitor to the landscape which was life or death to
them. They had mixed their labour with it; I, only my thoughts. Well, the land
was big enough for both, I told the yowes on the heather knoll above the wood.
For in truth the pre-Columban Celts and I were alike, recent specks on a huge
and ancient land. Nearby, the fossil garden of Ardtun is folded under the
volcanic rock. There you can read that 60 million years ago Mull was as hot as
Florida and lotus and magnolia grew in clearings of redwoods. The great
outpourings of lava which reach their highest point on Ben More to the north
took place somewhere near the equator.
It seemed far enough away that evening when I walked round the rim of the
basalt platform that made the little peninsula of Rubha Dubh. A thrush flew
from the broken dyke of another holiday house and vanished in a fold of
gloaming. The sea was gently filling the empty slipway excavated from the loose
rocks at the head of a creek. I made my way round the sheep paths at the edge
of the cliffs and lay leaning over a geometric column where the water shifted
and broke directly below.
Looking back at me were a scatter of reptilian faces, glossy and dark with a
bright green eye and a forward curving crest. Others peered round the columns
further along, silhouetted against the westering light. As I watched, the last
two or three flew in from the sea, rising at the last to settled webbed feet on
an empty column cap. For these shags, it was still winter and their evening
roost not their nesting caves was where they went at dusk. They flew in from
their fishing grounds on the sealochs and headlands of west Mull, to gather for
safety where the lava had flowed and hardened and the sea had chipped and mined
a 60-foot cliff with flat ledges for sleeping and no access for predators from
below or above. These fishermen had been here for longer than men.
So had the grey seal which swam 100 yards off shore. It bottled from the water,
sitting at ease in the narrowing track of yellow light as if it was swinging on
the surface. A silver cow, she lazed and looked, on the other side of the year
from the hurly-burly of birth and mating. She would be pregnant with next
September's pup, though there are plenty who would wish it otherwise.
Grey seals are among Scotland's special fauna, one of the world's rarer seals
yet commonest in our waters, their numbers still rising since the last cull in
1978. She hung there alone on the skin of the ocean as I rose up from the damp
grassy skin of the land and we each took our histories away in the spring
evening.
In order to engage with the landscape of Scotland you must try to understand
its history and its natural history. There on the black headland, Rubha Dubh,
the history seemed too big to understand. The forts and fields of the iron age,
like the skerries of the grey seals and the roosting ledges of the shags, were
created by the slow and continuing ripping apart of Europe and America. The
evanescence of primroses is closer in scale to your own life. Think too much
about it and the Ross of Mull seems to buck beneath you as it does beneath the
tourists in their buses. And so it should.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
