<HEADLINE>Isolation of our best man RAYMOND WILLIAMS Fred Inglis Routledge, #19.99</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>ALEXANDER LINKLATER</BYLINE>
<EDITION>1</EDITION>
<PAGE>12</PAGE>
<ARTICLETYPE>Book Review</ARTICLETYPE>
<FLAG>Weekend Extra</FLAG>
<GRAPHIC>Photograph </GRAPHIC>
<RECORDNO>975208671</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
n.Mixed emotions: despite the admiration and passion which clearly prompted the
book in the first place, Inglis appears to have ended up not really liking, or
even admiring, his subject, pictured above.
RAYMOND Williams brought class struggle into English classrooms. Not just by
talking socialism, but by acting out with his life a deep contradiction in the
heart of 1960s Cambridge. The son of a Welsh railwayman, he sought and found
the intellectual language through which he could express the culture of his own
class within the conditions of the dominant class, without being diminished or
absorbed by it.
In fact the term ``culture'' as we understand it today was largely clarified
and passed down to us by Williams. Culture not as artistic production, but as a
way of life held, lived and renewed in common; he brandished the idea of social
resistance as an act of creativity and union as great cultural forms. His books
Culture and Society and The Long Revolution set him at the centre of the
post-war British left making him, in Edward Thompson's words, ``our best man''.
His work on the media was instrumental in formulating the notion of
communications studies, and his analysis of the power of the press still stands
as the bottom level in timely reminders: ``Idealism you are allowed ..... but
truth about capitalism is forbidden ..... Once you know who owns the press, you
know what to expect of it.''
However, it is not only his thinking, but his presence and integrity as a
figure which make him important in the history of British socialist thought. In
1989, the year after his death, Terry Eagleton described the liberating impact,
and dignity, of Williams's Cambridge lectures: ``Through the medium of his
authority I felt somehow authorised to speak myself, and through me all those
relatives and friends who could never speak properly, who had never been given
the means to say what they meant, whom nobody ever bothered to ask what they
meant.''
His solitary strength was a mark not of individuality, but of the sustaining
power which emanated from a formative experience of Welsh working-class
solidarity and mutual support. So it is fitting that the best parts of Fred
Inglis's biography should not be about Williams himself but the family, class
and geographical background which formed him. And Inglis is excellent with
historical digression and sensuously alive detail.
But when it comes to the adult Williams, and his writing, it seems as if Inglis
has woken up to a biographer's nightmare. Despite all the admiration and
passion which clearly prompted the book in the first place, he appears to have
ended up not really liking, or even admiring, his subject. The book is lavished
with eulogies for Williams's achievements, but in an exaggerated or barbed way
which is sometimes sickening and suggests lack of conviction. The criticisms,
by contrast, ring consistently true.
In what seems like a laborious attempt at even-handedness there is a constant,
to-fro motion of praise and criticism which usually favours the latter.
For example, take Inglis's comment on Williams's novel, Border Country: ``I am
deeply attached to the book, but it has awful weaknesses.''
Or this truly weird form of damning with great praise: ``I love Manod; it's his
best book for me; I can't see its many faults.''
Or the straight annihilation of Williams's ``thick, at times downright dreary
prose'' in which Inglis interjects with an astonishing little exclamation of
his own in brackets: ``blah, drone.''
It should be admirable that a biographer be explicit about his opinions; the
illusion of neutrality usually disguises a whole range of covert ideological
operations. But Inglis splatters opinion about as if honesty were a nervous
tick.
And the ultimate irony is that he's not honest. This book claims to be an act
of reverence, but it strangely twists itself about to become a personal and
intellectual attack. The withdrawn character it residually leaves us with is an
isolated, rather dull egoist - bad with students, women and foreign countries.
It does Raymond Williams, and post-war socialism, no favours at all.
ALEXANDER LINKLATER
</TEXT>
