<HEADLINE>Glorious failure to compromise FIGHT &amp; KICK &amp; BITE: The life and Work of Dennis Potter W Stephen Gilbert Hodder &amp; Stoughton, #18.99</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>ALLAN LAING</BYLINE>
<EDITION>1</EDITION>
<PAGE>12</PAGE>
<ARTICLETYPE>Book Review</ARTICLETYPE>
<FLAG>Weekend Extra</FLAG>
<GRAPHIC>Photograph</GRAPHIC>
<RECORDNO>975208672</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
DENNIS Potter accomplished three genuinely remarkable things in his life. Two
of them were television serials - Pennies From Heaven and The Singing
Detective, dramas quite beyond compare. The third was a wonderful rage against
the television establishment. For a time, he alone was the creative conscience
of the industry.
These achievements are sufficient to establish a legendary place for Potter in
the hearts and minds of those (and there are many) who care about the craft of
screen writing, a talent which is too often given scant regard in the scheme of
things. But beyond them, you are struggling to identify anything else in his
career which, when compared to these immaculate standards, emerge as truly
great.
A substantial portion of this absolutely enthralling biography is set aside for
an appendix of Potter's creative output, a detailed description of his
journalism, his literary work, and his television and film scripts. He was most
certainly a prolific writer. The aforementioned television dramas, for which he
is probably best known, were nothing short of brilliant. Other work - like his
1965 BBC play, Stand Up, Nigel Barton; his controversial stage play Brimstone
And Treacle in 1977 (deemed too strong for television adaptation but eventually
turned into an unspectacular movie); and his peculiar, evocative, wartime TV
drama, Blue Remembered Hills, in 1979 - were quite outstanding.
Then we come to a body of work which was, in Potter terms, merely good. His
six-part BBC2 drama serial, Casanova, and his seven-part adaptation of The
Mayor of Casterbridge, again for BBC2. And finally, there is the average. His
screenplays for Nicolas Roeg's Track 29 and Michael Apted's Gorky Park; his
latter-day television dramas Lipstick On Your Collar, Christabel, and
Blackeyes. Of course, ``average'' for Mr Potter would amount to ``great'' for
most other writers.
W Stephen Gilbert, a novelist, critic, and journalist, has written an engaging
profile which is not only a frank and profound biography of Dennis Potter but
also a revealing history of television drama from the sixties to the present
day (so important was Potter to the medium that you really cannot do one
without the other). The author's achievement is all the more remarkable when
you consider that his subject's family gave little or no assistance to the
project.
It is something which, we learn early on in the book, Potter could never have
done himself. We are reminded that he once wrote: ``Autobiography is by far the
most boot-lickingly brutish of all the literary arts, especially when it
purports to wrestle with personal motive ..... I do not believe what writers
say about themselves, except when they think they are not saying it about
themselves.''
Nevertheless, Gilbert asks: ``What writer has laid himself quite so bare, quite
so unsparingly, quite so often as Dennis Potter? His work bursts with the
circumstances of his own life. He has confronted the most intimate of human
concerns to a degree that simply could not be contemplated unless they were
deeply felt, entirely personal. In his work he stands before us naked .....
more than naked; bleeding, his flesh flayed, his guts spilled.''
Potter's was not an easy life. Born to a working class family in a mining
community in the Forest of Dean, he was educated at Oxford and started out as a
journalist. Early on he discovered that he was suffering from psoriatic
arthropathy, a rare and progressive disease which was to perpetually haunt, not
only his personal life, but also his creative process.
He eventually found his metier in television drama. It was ``the true national
theatre.'' To him it was the only medium that really counted. ``It is the
biggest platform and you should fight and kick and bite your way on to it,'' he
said. The great thing about Potter was the fact that, once there, he continued
to fight and kick and bite.
Dennis Potter's torturous and premature demise reads like one of his scripts.
The writer, physically twisted by the effects of a lifelong ailment and wracked
with the pain of a terrible cancer, works frantically to complete two scripts
before he dies. A classic case of a man who suffered for his art. Whether this
final game was worth the candle has yet to be decided. The works, Cold Lazarus
and Karaoke have yet to be seen.
This book is a tribute to Potter, to his talent, his tenacity, and his glorious
failure to compromise. It should stand as an inspiration to any writer of any
medium.
ALLAN LAING
</TEXT>
</DOC>
