<HEADLINE>Attractive properties at good discounts</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>KEN CLAYA</BYLINE>
<EDITION>1</EDITION>
<PAGE>22</PAGE>
<ARTICLETYPE>Features</ARTICLETYPE>
<FLAG>personal finance </FLAG>
<RECORDNO>975208673</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
PROPERTY values and, therefore, the discounts at which property company shares
trade in relation to their assets are nothing like as precise as the discounts
for investment trust shares. But a discount of around 25% for Scotland's
largest property company, Scottish Metropolitan, at a current share price of
around 70p, has attracted the interest of stockbroker Charles Stanley.
It notes that the company had a difficult time after moving into the South of
England four years ago, but says: ``The damage has been repaired and some 70%
of its portfolio is now in Scotland.'' And it believes that property
development in Scotland is now showing signs of recovery which, with the
discount, makes the shares ``look cheap''.
In its latest Stockmarket Independent newsletter, the firm comments that the
property sector of the market has under-performed by nearly 20% so far this
year and ``yields on average portfolios are now above bond yields. The gap, of
course, will be widened if the expected cut in interest rates materialises
after the Budget. A cut would also make a further downgrading of property
values less likely.''
That makes it feel there should be at least stability in the share prices of
major property companies and, although this is not a risk-free situation, ``a
bounce in property shares in the first quarter of 1996 is possible''.
It likes British Land, presently at 372p, saying it expects its net asset value
to rise from 421p to 465p a share, giving a prospective discount of around 20%.
Since the newsletter went to press, British Land has announced a #120m deal to
give it full ownership of the prestige Broadgate development in the City of
London. It also announced a one-for-six rights issue at 370p to bring in some
#225m to fund other purchases including seven Tesco superstores and three
retail parks.
Stockmarket Independent editor Alan Watson comments: ``This is not the cheapest
property share on the market but it is the most innovative and the Broadgate
deal looks brilliant. It is difficult to tell at the moment, but I would guess
that the discount will emerge at around the current level.''
MEPC, which reports full-year results on December 1, is predicted to see
earnings per share of 19.7p against 18.2p and the broker thinks the company
will maintain its dividend at 20p net to give a yield of 6.5%. Net asset value
``should emerge at 480p compared with 473p, a discount of 21%''.
Giving MEPC a buy rating, it says next year's earnings should provide ``modest
cover'' for the dividend.
Land Securities, as the biggest company in its field and the only one currently
in the FTSE-100 share index, ``will participate in any recovery in the sector''.
The November survey of fund managers carried out for stockbroker Merrill Lynch
indicates, however, that UK fund managers are still selling property assets.
The broker reported that the money men and women were also ``still wary'' of UK
shares generally and continuing to sell US shares. But it was optimistic about
gilt-edged securities.
The Merrill Lynch strategy team's November look at the FTSE-100 companies
comments that the world economy is weakening and leading indicators suggest
this trend is ``unlikely to reverse'' soon. But with inflation under control,
it says: ``We are probably seeing a growth pause rather than recession.'' On
that assumption, the team is ``reluctant to take big negative bets on
industrial companies that offer good value and are producing good news flow''.
It has added British Aerospace to its bull list, commenting that while the
company is unlikely to be helped by the weak world economy, it is seeing good
profit growth. Others it likes are TI and GKN.
While the world economy is weak and forecasts of dividend increases for the
market generally are slipping, the team sees more appeal in BAT Industries, the
tobacco and financial services giant, which is ``safe and cheap'' and where
analysts are upgrading their profit and dividend forecasts.
It considers financial companies as still attractive on high yield and rising
dividend considerations, and adds Royal Insurance to a bull list which already
includes Abbey National and Standard Chartered.
ICI is being taken off the buy list as the prices of basic materials slip. The
broker comments that the correlation of chemical prices with the price of ICI
shares seems loose, but it does not see anything to drive the price up at the
moment. This view on basic materials also leads it to put British Steel and
Arjo Wiggins Appleton on the            sell list.
Taking the stance that inflation is not only low but likely to remain so, the
broker says it is keeping low growth companies such as Unilever and Sainsbury
on the sell list. It notes that a lot of firms regarded as defensive have
performed well over the past few months because they are felt to have safe
profits.
But it adds: ``Many of them are low growth companies that are seeing pricing
pressure. Our belief is that inflation will remain low so there does not seem
to be much reason to suppose that they are about to be baled out of their
current position. Food producers and retailers, such as Unilever and Sainsbury,
fit the bill and although their share prices have been weak we still regard
them as strong strategy sells.''
Similar logic brings the broker to add Guinness to its sell list. The
specialist analyst following the company also rates it as a sell, although
Unilever and Sainsbury are given a hold rating by their analysts. Guinness
shares have a price-earnings rating above the general market level at the same
time as analysts are lowering their profit estimates for the company. Its price
is seen as too high in relation to Allied Domeq and Grand Metropolitan.
In contrast, the strategists keep Tate &amp; Lyle on their buy list as they feel
the company's price earnings rating is too low.
</TEXT>
