<HEADLINE>Home work need not be taxing</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>ANGUS GAWN</BYLINE>
<EDITION>1</EDITION>
<PAGE>22</PAGE>
<ARTICLETYPE>Features </ARTICLETYPE>
<FLAG>personal finance</FLAG>
<GRAPHIC>Photograph</GRAPHIC>
<RECORDNO>975208674</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
ON dark wintry mornings the thought of working from home can seem attractive.
And if the tax inspector can be persuaded to offer some incentives the idea
becomes even more appealing. This is no flight of fancy. More and more people
find themselves, whether through necessity or convenience, working from home.
Advances in computer technology have brought the reality of the self-contained
office within the reach of most of us. As a result many individuals are finding
they can work just as effectively from the comfort of their own home.
When it comes to claiming tax relief for home expenses, the self-employed
person is generally in a stronger position than an employee who works for
someone else. The self-employed need only show that their domestic expenses
have been incurred ``wholly and exclusively'' for the purpose of their
business. Employees, on the other hand, must also show that the expense is
``necessary'' for the performance of their duties.
Thus an employee who normally works at his or her employer's premises cannot
claim tax relief for maintaining an office at home. The same principle prevents
employees from claiming tax relief on their travelling expenses from home to
work, because their duties are deemed not to begin until they get to their
office or workplace. The home has to be the base of operations before tax
relief can be claimed.
However, this rule does not prevent employees such as sales representatives
claiming a deduction for expenses where they operate from home but continually
travel about in the performance of their duties.
Broadly, home workers fall into three categories:
q Those who work wholly or mainly at home.
q Those whose business is itinerant in nature with some administrative work
performed at home at the beginning and end of the day.
q Those who have their main base away from home but also work there for part of
the time.
Individuals in the first two categories should generally be able to claim their
travelling expenses in full from home on business journeys. They can also claim
a proportion of domestic costs - such as heating, lighting, insurance, repairs
and maintenace - relating to the accommodation used as an office or workshop.
Those in the third category may find their tax claim restricted to heat and
light used for the hours actually worked at home, and then only if they are
self-employed rather than employees.
A proportion of council tax can also be claimed as this is a property-based tax
similar to the old-style rates, whereas the community charge or poll tax was a
personal tax.
Establishing the precise amount of expenditure which can be claimed against tax
will involve negotiation with the tax inspector, but any fair and reasonable
method will normally be acceptable. For example, in a house which has five
rooms plus kitchen and bathroom, with one room used as an office, it would be
sensible to claim for a sixth of the relevant expenses (kitchen and bathroom
counting as one).
A word of warning: if a room is used exclusively for business purposes, the
capital gains tax exemption which applies on the sale of the family home could
be put at risk. Strictly, the tax inspector could assess that part of the gain
which relates to the business use - one sixth in the example given above. To
avoid this, it may be prudent to claim only 95% of the relevant costs. The
other 5% will represent the occasional use of the room for private purposes.
The self-employed should have no difficulty claiming tax relief for business
telephone calls made from home. It is also usual to claim part of the rental
charge proportionate to the business use, although this might be challenged by
the tax inspector on the basis that the rental is not incurred wholly and
exclusively for business use, since private calls are also made.
As anyone with a mortgage knows, the tax relief on mortgage interest has been
drastically cut, and is now restricted to 15% of the interest paid on a loan up
to #30,000. This represents a fairly paltry tax saving of #7 per week on a loan
of #30,000 where interest is payable at 8% a year.
Following a recent Inland Revenue concession, it is now possible for
self-employed people using part of their home exclusively for business to claim
mortgage interest relief on the part of the loan attributable to this use. This
will enable them to get tax relief at 25%, or even 40%, on part of the interest.
Thus someone with a loan of #50,000, using one-fifth of his or her house for
business purposes, could claim interest relief on #10,000 against business
income, in addition to MIRAS tax relief on #30,000.
Everyone agrees that simplification of our tax system is long overdue. Kenneth
Clarke could take a small but significant step in this direction if he
introduced a realistic scale of tax allowances for those who require to work at
home on a regular basis.
To prevent abuse, the allowance would only be given against income actually
derived from the home-based source. It is unlikely the loss of revenue to the
Exchequer would be significant and it would be offset by time saved at the tax
office examining expense claims and discussing them with taxpayers.
With the advent of self-assessment in just over a year this would make sense.
It could also encourage skilled workers who are tied to the home to find ways
of generating income from this base with added benefits for the community.
</TEXT>
