<HEADLINE>Get on track for low-cost investment</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>GILLIAN BARTON</BYLINE>
<EDITION>1</EDITION>
<PAGE>22</PAGE>
<ARTICLETYPE>Features</ARTICLETYPE>
<FLAG>personal finance</FLAG>
<GRAPHIC>Photograph</GRAPHIC>
<RECORDNO>975208675</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
INVESTMENT managers spend their lives trying to out-pace each other in their
choice of shares, and while some have proved they can consistently out-perform,
for many others the struggle hardly seems worthwhile.
So, why bother to try and beat the market when you can achieve perfectly
respectable returns for investors simply by picking the same shares as the
stock market indices? Why indeed, particularly when, thanks to lower management
costs, the charges you have pay on these ``tracking funds'' are falling fast.
Legal &amp; General has abolished initial charges on its range of personal equity
plans. It reckons its Index Trust, which shadows the FT All-Share index, now
represents the cheapest tracking fund on the market.
L&amp;G's move follows the lead set by Virgin Direct with its Index Tracking Fund
and Gartmore which has also dropped the initial charge on its tracking funds.
HSBC, the biggest player in the tracker market, dropped the 4% charge on its
FTSE-100 index fund last year and now plans to scrap the 5.25% initial charge
on all its other index funds.
While cuts in initial charges help this type of fund get off to a better start,
the managers still make a yearly charge. At L&amp;G, for instance, it's 0.5% plus a
flat fee of #25. Annual charges and dealing costs mean the growth of tracker
funds typically lags about 1% a year behind the index they're shadowing.
Another point to bear in mind for risk-averse investors tempted by the idea of
their money going up (or down) in line with general movements in a particular
market is that not all funds slavishly follow the index they're tracking.
Some do, buying all the shares which make up the index - that's 900 in the case
of the FT All-Share - and in the same proportion. Others buy the same major
stocks, but then choose only a few of the smaller companies, taking the view
that there is more scope for making money out of actively dealing in smaller
company shares than the giant household names.
Another variation is to track the FTSE-100 index - affectionately known as the
Footsie - so concentrating on the 100 biggest companies which account for
around 75% of the stock market by value. But you don't have to confine your
attention to the UK market. HSBC has a wide range of funds tracking indicies in
continental Europe, Japan and the Far East for example.
Many tracker funds can also be wrapped in a personal equity plan or PEP so both
income and growth will be tax free.
It is only right that investors should benefit from lower charges on this type
of fund - after all, managers don't need very much skill simply to follow an
index. But there is also scope for cost cutting for those who prefer much more
active management of their investments.
Research by Edinburgh stockbroker Bell Lawrie White suggests thousands of
investors are now holding investments in PEPs with several different managers -
and paying too much in charges as a result. Consolidating your PEPs with just
one manager could well cut down on costs - and paperwork - as well as giving
you the chance to revise your holdings so they complement rather than duplicate
each other.
``Take the case of someone transferring #40,000 of PEP holdings to us,'' says
director Brian Johnstone. ``On our sliding scale of management fees investors
would pay 1% on the first #20,000 and 0.35% on the rest. That means a yearly
charge of #270 before VAT. That's a saving of #230 on the typical yearly PEP
management charge of 1.25%.''
It is important to check other costs before making a transfer. Many plan
managers slap on exit charges if you move your holdings out - or even insist
that you sell before transferring.
While unit trust and PEP charges have always been disclosed in percentage
terms, most investors probably have no idea what they amount to in hard cash -
but that is set to change. The unit trust regulatory watchdog, the Personal
Investment Authority, has proposed new rules which will force all unit trusts,
unit trust PEPs and investment trust savings schemes to set out their charges
in cash terms as well as percentages.
But, unlike the rules which came into force for life insurance companies at the
beginning of this year, unit trusts won't have to show how charges could affect
investments at different assumed growth rates.
``Unit trusts are very different from life insurance policies and can be much
more volatile,'' says Emma Weiss at the Association of Unit Trusts and
Investment Funds. ``Projections based on a particular growth rate give the
wrong impression that there will be a steady increase over time.''
Instead, investors will see an example of how charges will affect their
investment if there is no growth at all and if it doubles in value. The new
rules are expected to be finalised by January and come into force next summer.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO>GH951125-000169</DOCNO>
<DOCID>GH951125-000169</DOCID>
<DATE>951125</DATE>
<HEADLINE>No Headline Present</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>J P Leach</BYLINE>
<EDITION>1</EDITION>
<PAGE>19</PAGE>
<ARTICLETYPE>Features</ARTICLETYPE>
<RECORDNO>975208676</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
FOR a second I felt a hint of the sense of achievement that working around the
home is supposed to inspire. When the bathroom cabinet fell, however, it all
dissolved in a flood of temper.
In our house last week the irresistible force (my reluctance to do any sort of
work outwith office hours) was fated to meet the immovable object (a pile of
cruddy jobs needing done). When these two collide, the first casualty is
usually my good humour.
Before the sixties swung along, people had working days and they had rest days.
On work days they worked, and on rest days they went to some form of religious
service, read The Sunday Post, ate a fried breakfast, and went on a day-trip to
justify a few beers in some hotel or other.
Maybe it was a side effect of mass unemployment, maybe it was the widespread
availability and affordability of electrically powered workmen's hardware, but
for whatever reason, it's become de rigeur to know one end of a jig-saw from
the other.
Guys whose idea of manual labour was filing a letter suddenly had to spend all
day Sunday insulating the loft before they could hold their head high in the
office on Monday. And worse, these people will waste an entire weekend
footering around, producing workmanship of which even the most cynical cowboy
would be ashamed.
``It's cheaper when you do it yourself,'' say the apologists. This is true, as
long as you consider your free time to be worthless (an hour's overtime would
pay for someone competent to produce the same result as your eight hours of
fumbling), and as long as you don't count the money spent on repairing the
cables you drill through.
There can be only one thing worse than actually wasting time performing DIY,
and that's having to listen to some boring git blabbing on about doing odd-jobs
round the house. I think there's more chance of a Rangers player getting a
European win bonus than there is of me engaging anyone in chat about Rawlplugs,
but my brother gets honorary membership of the DIY Bore's Club by virtue of the
fact he owns a drill.
I can't believe some guys actually get a sort of pleasure out of using noisy
electrical gadgets made by Black and Decker. Mostly this is the same type who
finds the inner workings of the Ford Escort interesting; the kind of bloke (the
word ``guy'' is never entirely appropriate) who can say ``twin cam'' with the
assured tone of one who knows what it actually means. Not so much a man's man
as a bore's bore.
IN the nineties, although it's definitely not on for a woman to be given a
piece of household equipment for birthdays or Christmas (and rightly so!), it's
still quite acceptable to give the average anorak-clad saddite a power drill
for his festive cheer. Sad Man is then as happy as a pig in a patrol car, and
while, come Christmas morning, Real Man is reading his copy of Playing for East
Fife - Number 93 (The Glory Years), Sad Man sits vacantly, dreaming of his
progression from boring other people to boring holes.
Why is there such a middle-class obsession about performing manual tasks around
the house? Maybe it works the other way too. I wonder if, for instance, joiners
get up on a Sunday morning desperate to get stuck into a bit of DIY Quantity
Surveying?
DIY should be banned for social and economic reasons (ie all the skilled
tradesmen should be saying ``Bloody estate agents! Going home, doing our
jobs!''), but there are other good reasons. I get in such a bad mood when faced
with any sort of household tool (Quiet up the back there!) that it tends to
provoke all sorts of profanities.
That's the thing about women - they want men to express themselves more, then
go in the huff when you tell the flatpack wardrobe exactly what you think of it
when it falls down. There should be particular bans on DIY in homes with
children, however. Surveys have shown (flannel alert!) that children learn more
swear words following an episode of paternal thumb-hammer interface than they
would get from a hundred viewings of American videos.
The break-up of the family unit is almost certainly due to the increasing
popularity of DIY. Sociologists will soon cotton on to the fact the divorce
rate is rising at exactly the same rate as the number of DIY superstores.
Habitual DIY is definitely a sign of an abnormal mind. You can almost hear the
neighbours now: ``Look, there's that nice Mr West working away in the garden
again. That Rosemary doesn't know how lucky she is.''
</TEXT>
