<HEADLINE>At home in the mud</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>HUGH OUSTON</BYLINE>
<EDITION>1</EDITION>
<PAGE>44</PAGE>
<FLAG>weekender, birdwatch</FLAG>
<GRAPHIC>Illustration</GRAPHIC>
<RECORDNO>975208677</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
n.``THE punt gunner's bread and butter'' is how Peter Scott described the poor
wigeon between the wars. Despite being the quarry of wildfowlers for half a
century since, they are still bread and butter to birdwatchers and walkers on
the estuaries of Scotland in winter. In dense packs wigeon ride out the high
tide on the open sea, graze the cold wide mudflats or waddle through the grass
of seaside fields.
Every mudflat that can grow eelgrass will have its pack of wigeon by now,
though many move south as winter hardens. Each year too they are becoming more
common on inland fields and floods.
The other reason is that familiar birds can be seen with fresh eyes in
different contexts. Wigeon are exciting when they flight to feeding fields at
night, whistling from the dark side of the moonlit sky. Or in summer, a pair on
the rushy fringes of Loch Morlich allow time to study their delicate
proportions and the yellow pate, chestnut head and neck, grey lined flanks and
white splash on the forewings which make the drakes so handsome.
A few hundred breed in forest-edged upland lochs in Scotland, but the 40-50,000
which winter here are from more northern forests. In either place they are
susceptible to acidification of the water. It would be a great misfortune if
the numbers of wigeon did ever decrease - not least because the main food of
adults and chick on their breeding lochs is the ubiquitous midge.
</TEXT>
