<HEADLINE>Salvaging the fragments of a stolen childhood</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>Julia Langdon</BYLINE>
<EDITION>1</EDITION>
<PAGE>4</PAGE>
<ARTICLETYPE>Book Review</ARTICLETYPE>
<FLAG>Weekender </FLAG>
<GRAPHIC>Photograph</GRAPHIC>
<RECORDNO>975208678</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
SHE was eight years old when the comforts and stability of her little world
were shattered. By the time she had lived - or, more realistically, survived -
another eight years she had experienced being hounded as a Jew across her
native Poland, then rounded up and deported.
She had lived a life of utter deprivation in Siberia and Kazachstan, seen death
and despair, and at the end of the war had been shipped back to Krakow to
discover the meaning of the Holocaust. When she was 15 her parents sent her,
their only child, alone to start a new life in Britain.
They sent her away, their little sunshine, although it broke their hearts,
because there was no future for her in Poland and they felt it would be selfish
of them to keep her. ``Life is not fair, but we must try to be fair,'' they had
told her, and when she asked why, as she always did, they replied, as they
always did: ``Because we have to live with ourselves.''
It is a fearsome story that Janka Goldberger has told in an autobiography of
her amazing childhood. It is a story of those times which seems impossibly
remote 50 years on, but it carries a message for today's generation about the
meaning of hardship, about what it takes to survive. And it brings to life in
personal terms the experiences of the generation that we are now recalling with
the anniversary of the end of the Second World War.
In many ways the story is almost unbelievable. Reading the book, you can
understand why, at first, when she used to talk about the things that had
happened to her, she would find that people would give her an odd look and say:
``Oh, how interesting'' because, quite simply, they would think she was making
it up.
And yet her story: the ghastly transportations, the endless cold, the hunger,
the deaths - all this she describes as ``a picnic'' compared to the other story
she has told. This is the biographical account of her husband's wartime in
Warsaw, alone as a child of 13 after the capture of his parents and his brother
by the Germans. Having escaped because of his blonde hair, he found an uncle
and together with him, in the ghetto and the sewers, cheated death at every
turn.
It has taken her a long time to write these books, although she has rehearsed
them over and again in her head these past 50 years. Although she had always
wanted to write, she did not know if she wished to record these histories. It
was a famous publisher, Frederick Ullstein, who had been responsible for
publishing Kafka, who saw a draft of what she had written and told her that she
must persevere. ``You're a writer,'' he told her. ``You should write.'' She was
very excited.
But even so, her own story was one thing; that of her late husband, Egon
Weiner, who she had met on the boat to Britain, was truly terrible. Just as
others had not believed her account of her own experiences, she once had her
doubts about his. Was he not boasting? Could it really all be true? Could a Jew
dare to hide inside the Nazi headquarters?
Following his death in 1975 she pieced together the fragments and found it all
true and because he and the uncle were such remarkable and exceptional men she
felt she owed it to them to tell their story, too.
And there was another reason: she felt that by writing these books, retelling
the grim history of these horrors, she could show how even in the most hideous
circumstances, a child who is taught humane values at an early age can survive
hardship and become equipped to shape his or her own life.
Now here is the middle-aged lady; calm, dignified and still very handsome,
drinking coffee in one of London's smarter hotels and making light of much that
she went through, as, indeed, she manages to do in the books. She does not
diminish the stories but they are told, extraordinarily, through the eyes of
the young girl rather than through the refracted vision of a woman of wisdom
and knowledge. She is very matter-of-fact, but concedes that her approach was
shaped entirely by her parents.
``There have been other books written about the same subject - but quite
different because most of them tell a tale of woe. My story was partly funny:
it was not undiluted tragedy and there was even a glimmer of humour in what my
husband went through.
``If you are going to live through life and just cry, and say: `Poor little me!
How dreadful!' it isn't going to be worth it. We only have one life and might
as well make the best of it.''
She was taught by her parents always to consider herself lucky - even when they
sent her away to Britain, speaking not a word of English - and to be
optimistic. ``I can never think that anything bad is going to happen to me.''
The consequence is that when anything awful does happen, it comes as a
tremendous surprise, she explains, managing even to laugh as she does so.
As a mother and grandmother she knows that ``the package comes ready-made'',
but believes profoundly that it is still of huge importance for parents to
guide their children as she was guided by hers.
At the time of her earlier exile in the former Soviet Union, she felt then, as
she does now in her memory, that it was all an enormous adventure and greatly
exciting by comparison with the formality and organised routine of a wealthy
middle-class Jewish childhood in pre-war KraKow. Never could she have guessed
the adventures that were to lie ahead.
If her life had taken a more ordered path she had hoped to become a scientist.
She nearly fulfilled this ambition, even despite the upheavals of her youth,
after she arrived in London. She passed her matriculation within a year, having
quickly mastered the language, and to her delight was offered a place on a
psychology course at the University of London.
``All my life, since the time I was a little girl people have stopped me and
told me their problems, their life stories. I have the most extraordinary
experiences of people on trains asking me if they should get divorced or have
an affair.'' When she was offered this place, as an exceptional favour, she
cannot recall ever being happier. Her guardian did not see it like that.
``Perhaps you would like me to be a secretary!'' she remembers saying to him,
and him replying: ``Now, that's a good idea.'' She went to her room and decided
to jump from the window. The optimist and the humourist could not be quelled,
however. She looked before she leapt and the little courtyard below was full of
dustbins. After what she had already experienced she could not bear to die in
such circumstances, she decided.
Since then she has married, borne three children, lost her husband and had to
fight to raise and educate her family alone, and had several successful
business careers. Like everything else about Janka Goldberger it is a story of
survival. She remarried in 1980 and has now embarked, in her sixties, on
writing as her new career; another book is almost written and several more are
planned. ``I have always been reasonably capable,'' she says. It is a
considerable understatement.
n.Stalin's Little Guest and Surviving With Uncle, by Janka Goldberger, both
published by Janus at #15.99 each.
</TEXT>
