<HEADLINE>Naked talent</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>Douglas Thompson</BYLINE>
<EDITION>1</EDITION>
<PAGE>2</PAGE>
<ARTICLETYPE>Profile</ARTICLETYPE>
<FLAG>weekender</FLAG>
<GRAPHIC>photograph</GRAPHIC>
<RECORDNO>975208679</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
SHE'S the Lady Godiva of the screen and glossy magazines and the most highly
paid leading lady in the world. However good an actress you want to argue Demi
Moore is or isn't, the cash register, for the moment, is The Body.
She's displayed it naked, pregnant, and painted on magazine covers, and
advertised it by squeezing into gowns splashing a cascade of cleavage which
must have the Wonderbra people in a tizz about their patent. If you want
someone to heave a bosom on screen there's no-one better.
In her film The Scarlet Letter which opens in Britain this month, she is coyly
dressed Hester Prynne with a demure lace cap, just about keeping the lid on her
passions in the disjointed and dismaying ``freely adapted'' version of
Nathaniel Hawthorne's classic tale of Puritan pride and prejudice. Of course,
the cap gets lost during her roll in the hay with Gary Oldman's Rev Arthur
Dimmesdale.
With Moore the star we could have anticipated an exceptionally horny Hester.
But, in one of the few links between the novel and flopmaster British director
Roland Joffe's movie, ``sin'' has a price. Pregnant, she is forced to wear a
scarlet ``A'' for adultery - yes, that ``A'' heaves on her chest - having upset
the strict social conventions of seventeenth-century New England.
Even Moore couldn't save the $50m pillage of Hawthorne which is a giggling mix
of piety and hysteria. But The Body still prospers. Although it is hard work.
Today Moore is in Fort Lauderdale, Florida, filming her lead role in the movie
version of the great comic novel Striptease. Miami-based journalist Carl
Hiaasen's book is a wonder of words and set among the low life of the Atlantic
coastal communities. Moore's Erin is in a child custody battle with her
deranged husband (he steals hospital wheelchairs for profit in the geriatric
homes of the Americas) and needs cash. She strips. Rather wonderfully. Her best
friend in the film is played by Pandora Peaks who boasts or possibly regrets a
figure of 72HHH- 24-36.
The marvellous craziness of the novel and, hopefully the film, revolves around
the strip club so it's all tangles and tassles and, well, you know.
Moore's are impressive beneath a black satin blouse as she talks in the suite
of a rather nice hotel about her impressive, almost workaholic regime. As well
as The Scarlet Letter we will see her in the next months in Now and Then (which
she also produced), in The Juror with Alec Baldwin, as well as in the
much-anticipated Striptease.
But she's also been seen in a rather unflattering photograph - ``a bad snap''
according to her agents - of her jogging along a beach in her bikini. There are
stories that Striptease scenes had to be delayed until The Body was in perfect
shape for the camera. But cameras know more tricks than car salesmen and it is
difficult to imagine Demi Moore having trouble with her image.
``I certainly don't say `shoot my worst parts' when I'm filming,'' she says
with a flash of Beverly Hills hypnotising teeth. After you blink she goes on
about the bathtub sequence - Hawthorne didn't write it - in The Scarlet Letter
which is already on the Internet.
``We really needed to find a way of showing the body that reflected an
innocence and excitement and a sense of courage to go beyond the rules, to
break the rules and embrace oneself. So it needed to be shot in a way that you
could feel that kind of excitement and sweetness and thrill.
``Even though I was literally naked it was much more figurative about how naked
one feels to be looking at themselves for the first time.
``In the days of The Scarlet Letter you took a bath with a sheet over you. A
modesty sheet that they would actually place over the entire tub because it was
considered indiscreet to even look at yourself naked, let alone somebody else.
Today? I don't know. It goes on. It depends on the percentage of fear that
exists in our community because that's what it is really about.''
When she found international fame in the out-of-this-world fantasy romance
Ghost her image was white-T-shirt girl-next-door, with cropped hair, neat
smile, and big eyes on a fresh face, and not much evidence of hips or waist.
She was demure. And unthreatening. Without doubt she's now Wonderbra woman. And
intimidating.
Since she had fun playing with clay in the supernaturally successful Ghost,
she's flashed a sculpted and daily - three hours every day after the birth of
her children - exercised body on and off screen and in some sensational
photographs.
In today's Hollywood she's not just The Body but The Boss. And photographs of
her not looking in perfect shape have dismayed her quite extensive group of
advisers. ``Rotten picture,'' is the word and, for once, you feel obliged to
accept the Hollywood word. For this is an actress who has supervised the system
to be the success she is. She's the manipulator. Few stars have worked so hard
- and successfully - to present the image they want.
For Striptease she is being paid $12.5m and also has a share of the profits of
the movie which is going to be the one to beat at the box office in 1996. This
is a millennium moll.
This is not a surprise. As well as making public appearances snuggled into
outfits which emphasise all the right bits she has the look and attitude which
could set off fire alarms and certainly encourage loin alerts. This one-time
wide-eyed, innocent-looking Brat Packer is totally in control. She's also the
screen's queen predator.
She has an off-camera reputation for being ``assertive'' and going after
everything she wants with a passion. She admits she does not hold back. It won
her showy roles in A Few Good Men (as a tough Navy legal officer opposite Tom
Cruise and Jack Nicholson) and Indecent Proposal (as the wife Robert Redford
offers $1m to spend the night with).
It also helped her become Michael Douglas's tormentor in Disclosure, which was
the film adaptation of Michael Jurassic Park Crichton's controversial study of
sexual harassment in the workplace. She is Douglas's boss and wants him in the
office and in bed. In fact, she wants him anywhere. Her determination to get
her prey made T-Rex seem like a cuddly toy.
If you thought Michael Douglas had problems with Glenn Close in Fatal
Attraction that was before he became lust object of harridan harasser Moore.
The Royal Mounted Police should have appointed her their new mascot. This is a
lady who will always get her man.
``Don't you think I was perfect casting?'' she laughingly asks about her
Disclosure role.
In real life she did get her man but rather more romantically. Bruce Willis was
so overcome by her that he flew her to Las Vegas for a ``surprise'' wedding.
Half a dozen years and three children later they are one of Hollywood's few
stable power couples. They share the chores and the kids but have separate
film-production companies. In Hollywood, love is having his and her hit movies.
Moore can cope with fame and family but still wants more. ``I just want the end
result of things to be the highest quality they can be. I want good work. I
want things to be the best they can be. I want greatness.''
Well, you can't knock ambition. So far, she's had a good run of movies. Her
children, Rumer Glen, six, Scout La Rue, four, and Tallulah Belle, 20 months,
are given every consideration. She's proved it's possible to juggle motherhood,
a high-profile celebrity marriage, and superstardom.
Her daughter Rumer (after British novelist Rumer Godden, author of Black
Narcissus) was born, not in some trendy Hollywood hospital, but in the tiny
town of Paducah, Kentucky. Bruce Willis was on location there. He had arranged
with the movie's producers to have his pregnant wife with him on location and
the best facilities available for the birth - which he videotaped.
But even his superstar clout and negotiating talents pale against his wife's.
She has a reputation as relentless in getting what she wants. When she produced
the movie thriller Mortal Thoughts she cast Willis as the abusive
husband of a friend of her character's.
``I don't think we'll work together often but if something like that comes up
it's silly not to do it. Bruce really responded to the character - and it made
it easier for the family to be together,'' she said. And then in a remarkably
candid moment she talked a little about their set-up which, in Malibu, has been
blitzed by paparazzi, mud slides, and earthquakes:
``You know, I think we support each other. We always come and share our
experiences once the films are done. We come to each other's sets. One of the
more positive qualities and elements of our relationship is that we actually
keep our work very separate.
``Our time together is not about work. It's about having our family, and if
he's happy doing what he's doing I'm happy.
``I don't need to read his scripts. I don't need to tell him what to do and
vice versa. At the same time if he wants me to read something, if he cares for
my opinion, then I'd love to give it to him and I really think that has been a
saving grace. There's a lot of pressure to have a film succeed.
``I certainly don't need people criticising if we have chemistry on screen, so
I'd rather just keep Bruce and me separate from that for now. I assure you
there's enough chemistry at home. I'm very embracing, very maternal, and I
think I'm a grounding force, a centre that I provide for Bruce. But we have
created a tremendous foundation of a family. I have been through a lot of
things and come out of that as an example, a light of sorts - a light of
possibilities. Almost in the same way, there was an embracing and reassuring of
values that Bruce gave me that no-one had ever given me before.''
In California-speak she went on: ``Bruce made me feel important. That filled me
with strength to step forward with courage that, if I stepped a bit further, I
knew I wasn't going to fall. And if I fell it wasn't going to be quite as hard.
``It's very easy for me to see what I've got and where I've come from, but you
don't know. You don't know. I can be OK and know that I've got today but what's
going to happen next year, what's going to happen in the future? I don't like
to think too far in advance. Maybe I'm superstitious, afraid that what I've got
may go away.
``But I'm not cautious about what I'm doing. I plough ahead like there's no
tomorrow.''
Unhappily, tomorrow brings The Scarlet Letter but when you are a multi-million
dollar lady that's just a hiccup. For the unfortunate director Roland Joffe who
bombed with Fat Man and Little Boy and City of Joy there is a much larger
question mark over a career which is in expectation but not delivery.
Moore sees The Scarlet Letter and Striptease as linked: ``It's an interesting
point of view. We live in a puritanical society that fears the fact that you
might expose your body. And I wonder why this is. Why are we so afraid?
``Why do we judge the way you use your body? And why do we have a stereotypical
concept of what a woman is because she chooses to strip as a profession? I
might not want to do it but at the same time I feel it's providing me with an
opportunity to be more in touch with my own body.
``To understand how it makes me feel to move and to be free and not to be
repressed and shut down.''
But, remember, she does heave rather well.
</TEXT>
