<DOCNO>GH951125-000173</DOCNO>
<DOCID>GH951125-000173</DOCID>
<DATE>951125</DATE>
<HEADLINE>Long live the Queen</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>Jack Webster</BYLINE>
<EDITION>1</EDITION>
<PAGE>8</PAGE>
<FLAG>weekender</FLAG>
<GRAPHIC>Photograph</GRAPHIC>
<RECORDNO>975208680</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
THAT greatest of luxury liners, the Queen Mary, built at John Brown's of
Clydebank in the 1930s, still dominates the skyline of Long Beach, California,
where she has lain for more than quarter of a century as a major hotel and
tourist attraction.
Periodically there have been threats that, because of high operating costs,
this great monument to Clydeside workmanship might be sold off or scrapped
altogether, consigned to the oblivion which befell her sister-ship, the Queen
Elizabeth, mysteriously burned to death in Hong Kong harbour in 1972.
But the good news about the Queen Mary, as she approaches the diamond jubilee
of her maiden voyage in 1936, is that her operators have just been given a new
20-year lease, raising hopes that the ship is safe for the foreseeable future.
And to crown this major development, Prince Michael of Kent has given his royal
patronage to that operating body, the RMS Foundation.
At a private dinner in London, Prince Michael told me of his pleasure in
accepting the role of patron, which confirms the interest he has been taking in
the Queen Mary in recent times. His visits to the ship have included the
celebration to mark the 60th anniversary of that day in 1934 when the Mary was
launched at Clydebank.
``I was delighted to see that she is still maintained to the high standards
which greeted my grandparents on that launching day,'' he said.
The occasion of Prince Michael's London dinner was to launch the 1996
celebrations that will mark the diamond jubilee of the maiden voyage. That
voyage began at Southampton on May 27, 1936, when the greatest luxury liner the
world had ever seen set sail for New York.
As the rich and famous clamoured to secure first-class suites, the lucky ones
included President Kennedy's mother, Rose, actress Frances Day, and designer
and photographer Cecil Beaton.
As Henry Hall's orchestra played for dancers, the music could be heard in both
Britain and the United States, one of the early broadcasts which linked the two
countries.
Well, the Queen Mary doesn't sail any more but, in her diamond jubilee year,
her non-profit-making operators are offering 1996 packages which include
accommodation in first-class staterooms, big-band dancing, elegant meals in the
Sir Winston and Chelsea restaurants, and the champagne Sunday brunch which is a
regular feature of the Queen Mary's existence as a hotel.
There are events throughout the jubilee year, including a Scottish festival,
Fourth of July celebrations, fireworks every Saturday night, a festival of
light, and a Hogmanay finale to round off 1996.
Back in Britain, Clydebank will have its own celebration while Southampton,
where many of the Queen Mary's former crew members still gather, will have
exhibitions and a gala dinner.
A feature of the diamond jubilee will be the showing of a cine-film only
recently unearthed from the archives, in which a bank manager from Rotherham in
Yorkshire, Charles Chislett, took some intriguing pictures of the maiden voyage.
The Queen Mary was on her sixth round trip in August 1936 when she captured the
Blue Riband for the fastest-ever crossing of the North Atlantic. In 1937 the
honour was regained by the French liner Normandie. But a year later the Mary
won it again - and held the record for the next 14 years.
With the arrival of transatlantic jets in the 1950s and 1960s, luxury liners
were running out of fashion as the fastest way to America. The Queen Elizabeth
was sold off to Hong Kong owners and the Queen Mary was bought by the city of
Long Beach for the purpose it still fulfils.
It stood adjacent to the distinctive dome which was built to house the
much-publicised Spruce Goose flying-boat, belonging to the legendary Howard
Hughes. The Goose moved away but the dome has been used by Hollywood for films
like Batman Forever (1995) and is now to become an entertainment venue.
The new-found confidence in the future of the Queen Mary is fortified by the
fact that Long Beach has a $650m seafront project which includes a $100m
aquarium of the Pacific.
This renewed activity in Long Beach, a city the size of Edinburgh, has revived
memories of another age, when it was a centre of film-making before Hollywood
became the favoured location. People like W C Fields, Buster Keaton, and Fatty
Arbuckle lived there and visitors could watch those early movies being shot
around the city.
The great W C Fields could regularly be seen driving along Ocean Boulevard to
and from his home, now known as Weathering Heights and still visible from the
palm-lined boulevard.
Back at the Queen Mary, the boss of RMS Foundation, Joseph Prevratil, has
promised further restoration of the ship, which still looks remarkably like the
great lady which left Clydebank in the 1930s.
That brings the welcome news that the famous Verandah Grill, which had gone
down market as a fast-food area for the million people who visit her annually,
is to be restored as an elegant venue for banquets and receptions.
The ship is now on America's Register of Historic Places and her prospects for
an extended life are enhanced by the interest being shown by the British royal
family.
By coincidence, the new patron was born on American Independence Day of 1942,
just a few weeks before his father, the Duke of Kent, was killed while flying
on war service. President Roosevelt became one of his godfathers, which
explains his name of Michael George Charles Franklin.
As the patron of the Queen Mary's future, Prince Michael is showing the same
kind of enthusiasm for Scotland's greatest ship as was shown by his grandmother
when she came to Clydebank in 1934 and revealed the secret which had been
remarkably well kept: that Ship No 534 would, in fact, take the name of the
lady herself - Queen Mary.
</TEXT>
