<HEADLINE>Heathcliff, lord of the moor</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>Bruce Sandison</BYLINE>
<EDITION>1</EDITION>
<PAGE>44</PAGE>
<FLAG>weekender ways &amp; means </FLAG>
<GRAPHIC>Photograph Map</GRAPHIC>
<RECORDNO>975208681</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
EVERY dog must have its day. Even Heathcliffe my wife Ann's Yorkshire terrier.
Heathcliff and I enjoy a relationship based entirely upon mutual distrust. I
know that the moment my back is turned he will be up to no good. He knows that
the moment Ann's bank is turned that I will give him a less than
dog-user-friendly pat in payment. We exist together in an uneasy state of armed
neutrality, constantly on the alert for angst.
Heathcliff goes everywhere with his mistress; up mountains, dinner parties,
shopping, over soggy moors, bed, concerts, beach walks, holiday, the library,
fishing expeditions, business meetings and, on one unforgettable occasion, a
wild, uncontrolled terrier race at a game fair. In the car, the brute travels
in style, draped muffler-like round Ann's neck, his beady black eyes scanning
the horizon in search of trouble.
Ann's strict rule, when Heathcliff was a lad, was that he must always be kept
on the lead out of doors, even although we lived in a remote area of the north
of Scotland. The need to do so became apparent after his first, and only,
encounter with a sheep on the shores of Loch Treigh near Fort William. I had
spent an hour, screaming over the hill, yelling Cathy-like, ``Heathcliff,
Heathcliff!'' before I found him.
A tup had trapped the dog in a tiny cove. Heathcliff, who detests water, was
soaking wet and yapping plaintively; perched on a bare, wave-lashed rock, a
yard from the bank, faced by a hissing, angry, monster which would not go away.
I recovered the poor beast and, after a ``pat'', bore him back to his
distressed owner. Ever since, when sheep appear Heathcliff disappears, whether
he is on the lead                or not.
However, and grudgingly, I have to admit that Heathcliff is one of the most
competent hill walkers I know, and one of the fittest. His sense of direction
is unerring, his stamina endless. Fifteen miles round Beinn an Eoin (855m),
Poca Buidhe, Loch nan Cabar and Baosbheinn (875m) in the Flowerdale Forest,
south from Loch Maree, is, to him, just a warm up stroll.
Even at the age of 11 the prospect of a scamper up Ben More Assynt (998m)
brought a sparkle to his eye. His brown, hairy face, slashed by tightly
gritted, white teeth, twisted into a hideous grin of anticipation. At the end
of the day, in the glen of the Traligill Burn, he caught the scent of a rabbit
and was off like a shot in hot pursuit; bursting for action, fresh as new-baked
bread.
Which is why there is never any problem about birthday presents. Ann insists
her little darling's birthday should include a decent walk. Before the
statutory, candled, cake. A once-a-year treat, properly served, with
Heathcliff, feet on the table, napkin round his neck, munching happily. The
damn brute knows, too, almost to the minute, when the event is to take place;
and, at least on that day, that he is pretty safe from my tender love and care.
This year, on his birthday, we took Heathcliff on one of our favourite walks,
between Bettyhill and the mouth of the River Borgie in North Sutherland. The
walk combines the best of both worlds, including a mile or so along a
wonderful, deserted beach, as well as a happy scramble over heather-topped
Lewisian gneiss. Something for everyone: wild flowers and geological formations
for Ann, a wide variety of bird life and prehistoric monuments for me, rabbits,
hares and the chance of a roll in a dead seagull for Heathcliff.
</TEXT>
