<TEXT>
THE day will probably start with a plate of cornflakes or honey nut loops and
that's me. A cup of tea at the office and that's it until lunchtime when I eat
with the players. Lunch is soup and pasta with a bolognese or a cream sauce,
cooked in the Walfrid Restaurant up the stairs at Celtic Park. There's fruit
afterwards and that's it until half past six when I'll have something at home,
perhaps, fish, potatoes and peas, or more pasta, or steak. I don't linger over
food but I might have tea and a wee biscuit if I'm hungry between meals.
I've always been fortunate enough not to put on a great deal of weight - and I
still train with the players. I don't overeat except perhaps sometimes on a
Sunday when we go out for lunch.
I can cook, not a big fancy meal, but a nice cheese and ham omelette, beans on
toast, or whatever's from Marks and Spencer. If that's cooking, I can heat it
up. I could end up being taken to a lot of restaurants through my work - but I
don't do it.
As a kid I liked mince and potatoes, and still do. And I love home-made soup -
my wife makes a fabulous minestrone. There's nothing I like more than a nice
cup of tea. My favourite dish is lasagne, although if I'm hungry I can eat
almost anything, including a McDonald's. There are very few things I would turn
my nose up at.
n Celtic manager Tommy Burns was talking to LEILA FARRAH.
</TEXT>
