<TEXT>
THE PENGUIN BOOK OF SCOTTISH FOLKTALES
Edited by Neil Philip
Penguin, #8.99
SCOTTISH fiction springs from a tradition where stories were told to entertain.
This oral tradition is based on a familiarity, which, when transferred to the
page, allows the writer to take the reader into strange and exciting worlds
which would otherwise be inaccessible.
It is the tradition whose influence is often overlooked but which becomes
obvious when we consider the importance, power and role of the first person
narrator in Scottish writing. It appears in many guises and there are few
Scottish fictions from any period where the reader is not aware of being told
the story.
The engine that drives it all is the voice. This is one of Scottish fiction's
most appealing and mystifying aspects, something which has obviously helped its
survival, which inspires much of its uniqueness and which is a direct and
irrefutable statement of national identity.
It has been a necessary component of Scottish fiction from the beginning and
has to do with rhythm, speech, class, dialect and position. It is one of the
few devices open to a writer which fulfils more than one function
simultaneously and is often the first decision a writer makes. It is missing
from many stories in this collection.
The folktale is one of Scotland's richest literary legacies. In his
introduction, Neil Philip remarks that there are two distinct story-telling
traditions, Gaelic and Lowland Scots. The Gaelic tradition has many affinities
with Irish story-telling, where the narrator has an honoured place in the
community and convoluted plots are related in heightened language. Lowland
tales are sparser and the language is more direct: and while there has been a
conscious effort to preserve the Gaelic stories, the Lowland tales appear to
have been saved almost at random.
In an essay on Jeannie Robertson as a story-teller, Hamish Henderson remarks
that prior to the School of Scottish Studies being founded at Edinburgh
University, remarkably few Scots tales had been recorded. Robert Chambers'
Popular Rhymes of Scotland were practically the only specimens. Peter Buchan's
Ancient Scottish Tales are somewhat wooden Anglicised recensions he says.
It is the most obvious feature of this new collection. Many texts have been
weeded of the voice, therefore lack distinction and sound the same. The Gaelic
stories have obviously been translated, and it is only when we come upon
transcriptions of spoken Lowland tales that we find recognisable voices
fulfilling their distinctive function. Our appreciation of Lowland Storytelling
has recently been transformed, says Neil Philip, ``by the revelation of a
vigorous living narrative tradition among Scottish travellers''. These voices
give the stories distinction.
There are more than 100 tales gathered here; many, like Red Etin and The Well
at the World's End, are very familiar, others not so well known. Philip has
searched widely and selected well, gathering the stories in headings such as
Wonder Tales of the Lowlands, Tales of the Supernatural and so on.
Betsy Whyte's wonderful story The Man in the Boat is not published here for the
first time. A version recorded by Alan Bruford is in The Devil and the Giro, an
even a cursory comparison shows what a wonderful story-teller she was,
obviously altering the dynamics and pace of the narrative to suit her audience.
By implication, it also shows what we have lost in the stories whose collectors
were blinded by narrative and considered the tellers art unimportant, or maybe
like folksong, thought it ``as natural as birdsong''.
</TEXT>
