<TEXT>
Catherine Brown wends her way through a maze
of dried fruits
A QUICK recce round a large wholefood shop, an oriental deli, the local
supermarket, and our up-market neighbourhood grocer, and I have a haul of dried
and candied fruit, and nuts, which is taking some sorting out -
value-for-money-wise.
Why pay over the odds now for Australian Muscatel raisins (with pips) when
there are jumbo South African ones (without) which are just as good at almost a
quarter of the price? Or Lexia raisins, which are scarce this year, so the
price has shot up.
Was there any point in paying extra for organic? And what about bulk buying?
There is a risk, of course, but also a huge saving at the oriental grocers.
Whole almonds: unit price per kilo #5.99 v #11.50 in the supermarket.
But first, to sort out the eating from the cooking; the nuts and dried fruits
with the best flavours which need nothing added and nothing taken away.
I am advised, in large lettering, on this 100g supermarket packet of (Sundora)
dried apricots that they are ``ready to eat''. Spectacles go on to investigate
the smaller - and almost unreadable - lettering, which reveals that one of the
ingredients is water. But I thought they were dried. Apparently not. The
manufacturer has very kindly soaked them in water for me.
Besides water, I also have the benefit of citric acid, malic acid, sugar, and
preservative E220. At a unit price of #7.80 a kilo, these ``dried'' apricots
have cost more than a kilo of lamb chops!
I need a calculator now to work out the extra cost of these organic whole
almonds from Italy, compared with the kilo I've bought in the oriental deli,
and discover the organic cost is almost double (#5.99 v #10). The cheapo
oriental deli and the expensive Italian organic are blind-tasted by some
nut-fanciers who come back with the verdict that the organic nuts are the best
they've ever tasted.
This packet of dried fruit for eating from a large wholefood shop is described
as ``sun-dried African pineapple''. Ingredients: pineapple. It is dried fruit
at its simplest and least processed which is most commonly found in wholefood
and specialist food shops.
During the drying process, fruit loses its natural colour and turns varying
degrees of dark brown. To preserve the natural colour, and to lengthen the
shelf life, many are treated before drying with sulphur dioxide to prevent
browning. Also with a dressing of vegetable oil or glucose syrup to prevent
them ``sugaring'' (developing sugar crystals) and sticking together. Both
processes change the natural flavour of the fruit. Some children may also be
allergic to sulphur.
While wholefood and specialist food shops are the places to find the widest
range of dried fruits, candied peels, and nuts. Some also have a policy of
packaging themselves, and passing on the savings to their customers which
should mean cheaper prices generally.
At Real Foods in Edinburgh, they also have a policy of reducing the price of
Christmas dried fruits and nuts by about 15% because of increased turnover at
this time of the year. They also claim to have a sleuthing service which will
track down any request from a customer.
Stuart Jackson, buyer for the shop, has just discovered a source of excellent
South African dried pears and peaches which had been requested by a customer.
Thanks to other requests, and their own searching out of new lines, they now
have Italian candied citron caps, undyed black and gold cherries, dried
blueberries and cranberries, Californian desert dates and Black Mission figs,
in addition to a large range of organic dried fruits and nuts.
What they do not have, however, is Arabic dried fruit ``leathers'' which have
been made with pureed dried fruit and pressed out into thin-as-leather sheets
and folded into neat, colourful parcels with cellophane between the layers to
prevent them sticking.
At Reza, the Iranian food emporium in London's Kensington High Street, there is
a deeply orange-coloured apricot leather (known as amardine), another is a dark
burgundy-coloured plum leather, and there are others made with crimson
barberries and dark red mixed fruits.
Soft enough to chew like fudge, fruit leathers can be cut into diamond or
square shapes and eaten as a delicacy with seeds, nuts, cheese, or apples. Cut
into strips, they can be added to stewed fruit to make a rich tangy sauce;
shaped with fancy cutters, they make a decoration on cakes and puddings; warmed
slightly in a pan, they can be used as a sticky glue on rich fruit cakes to
help ``fix'' the marzipan.
Jackson has never heard of fruit leathers, but he will investigate. Watch these
shelves.
n.Real Foods, 37 Broughton Street, Edinburgh. Tel: 0131 557 1911. Mail Order.
n.Reza, 345 Kensington High Street, London W8 Tel: 0171 602 3674.
n IN FOOD shopping terms, the next four weeks are the resplendent climax of the
year. Imports of figs, dates and nuts from the Near East have started arriving
in large quantities, while the citrus season is already in full swing.
This is also the time of year to consider buying a half or whole cheese for the
centre of the festive table and as a useful standby.
``A half Colston Basset Stilton,'' says cheesemonger Iain Mellis, ``is around
#35 for 8 -9 lb, (normally #5.12 a lb). ``A goats' milk half Harbourn Blue from
Devon is #25 for 3 lbs, while a half Dunsyre Blue from Lanarkshire is #21 for 3
lbs.''
Mellis also stocks a range of minature territorial cheeses which are smaller (2
1/2 lb) including Keen's cheddar, award-winning Mrs Kirkham's Lancashire, and
Mrs Appleby's Cheshire.
Iain Mellis, Cheesemonger is at 30a Victoria Street, Edinburgh. Tel: (0131) 226
6215 and 492 Great Western Road, Glasgow Tel: (0141) 339 8998.
