<TEXT>
Lesley Duncan weaves the tale
of a family firm
which is still
clothing the gentry
THREE life-size marble goats disport themselves in the restaurant courtyard at
Johnstons of Elgin. They are cashmere goats, given to the woollen firm in 1993
by a Chinese supplier ``as recognition of more than 140 years' experience of
Chinese cashmere at Newmill''. The animals come with a Chinese proverb: ``Lucky
goats with events as wished.''
The goats themselves bear this out, for though badly damaged in transit they
have been seamlessly repaired. However, they could also serve as the wider
motto for this flourishing company which has been manufacturing top-quality
cloths at its Elgin base for almost two centuries. The firm, Elgin's biggest
and oldest employer, will celebrate its bicentenary in 1997.
The story of Johnstons represents in many ways the story of Scottish
manufacturing processes in the industry over the same period - of the constant
need to adapt to new machinery, processes, raw materials, and changing consumer
demands and expectations. That Johnstons has survived when so many firms have
not is testimony to shrewd management by succeeding generations of owners,
first the original Johnstons family and then the Harrison family since 1920.
Now Johnstons have produced something quite unwoolly. It's a book called
Scottish Estate Tweeds. Its author E P Harrison is a former chairman and
managing director of the company.
Scotland and tartan may be synonymous but another form of patterned cloth, less
spectacular and showy, is also native to Scotland. Estate tweeds are defined as
checks or designs ``which must belong to a particular estate and must have been
used to clothe the owners and their staff''.  Their origins can be traced to
the aftermath of the '45 Uprising, the Clearances, and the introduction of
Cheviot sheep to the Highlands. Because of economic change and fecklessness of
many of the chiefs, estates were sold in the early nineteenth century or rented
out for grouse shooting, deer stalking, and fishing. Sir Walter Scott - by
making the Highlands a focus of romance - and Queen Victoria - by taking up
summer residence on Deeside - influenced the new sporting focus.
The Sobieski Stuarts added their Jacobite imprimatur to clan costumes and deer
stalking. Landseer immortalised the stag at bay. Roads and railways also helped
popularise field sports in the north. The dispossessed clansmen of an earlier
generation were transmogrified into ghillies. And they needed clad.
When the foundation stone of Balmoral Castle was laid in 1853, Prince Albert
promptly designed the Balmoral tweed for use by all stalkers and ghillies on
the estate.
One of the first true estate tweeds, it is today a very dark blue design with
white sprinkled with crimson. The overall appearance is grey, imitating the
granite of the Aberdeenshire hills round Balmoral. Thus it provides ideal
camouflage for sporting activities. Johnstons' records show that ``Super
Balmoral Tweed'' was woven on July 13, 1853, though there is no note of the
original colouring. Prince Albert also designed a Balmoral tartan, but which
came first is not known.
Balmoral Tweed and 184 other patterns are beautifully reproduced in E P
Harrison's book. Each has a little history attached, the result of painstaking
research, either by  Harrison or by his late father E S Harrison, who in 1968
wrote an earlier study of Scottish district checks.
The Lovat Mixture - a soft green - has a longer entry. It was one of the
earliest instances of protective colouring and was first woven in Johnstons'
mills in 1845. Apparently the wartime hero Lord Lovat told how, when he was a
small boy, he heard that the idea of the colour came to his grandfather as he
looked across from the south side of Loch Morar.
His grandfather pointed out to his grandmother how the contrasting colours of
the primroses and bluebells - then in full bloom on the far side of the loch -
blended in with the hill, the white sands of the loch shore, the bracken, and
the birch trees. From that idea came the celebrated tweed with its invisibility
on the hill.
The entries also represent a history of the ever-changing land ownership in the
Highlands. Take Glenample, for example. The estate on Loch Earn was bought in
1992 by Senor Raphael Cruz Conde from Mr D Abbot, who in turn bought it from
the Stirlings of Keir in 1988. The tweed, a diagonal-effect cloth of yellowy
grey with bright lines of blue and orange through it on warp and weft, was
designed by Senor Conde with Haggarts of Aberfeldy and introduced as recently
as last year.
Though its earliest examples go back 150 years, Johnstons of Elgin had no
monopoly of estate tweed manufacturing and this book acknowledges other makers
such as Haggarts of Aberfeldy, Hunters of Brora, the Islay Woollen Mill, and
Campbells of Beauly. Estate tweeds are still manufactured for local clients at
Elgin, but Johnstons now largely concentrates on finer fibres. The estate
tweeds remain, however, the basis of inspiration for lighter-weight tweed
jackets for the general public.
High quality scarves, plain and patterned, cashmere accessories, clothing, and
tartans are major products. The raw material for Johnstons' Borders knitwear
factory is also prepared in Elgin.
The transformation of great bales of unwashed cashmere, merino, and lambswool
through a variety of ingenious processes and dyeing, to the fine material of
cloth or knitwear is in its way as impressive as the final products.
Much of Johnstons' output is exported to the Continent (Italy and Germany in
particular), Japan and the Far East, and America. The company won the Queen's
Award for Exports last year.
n Scottish Estate Tweeds by E P Harrison is published by Johnstons of Elgin at
#16.95.
</TEXT>
