<TEXT>
MARILYN MONROE: Her Life in
Her Own Words
George Barris
Headline, #17.99
n HERE is Marilyn Monroe's own, never before published account of her life,
accompanied by the photographs of photojournalist George Barris who spent six
weeks in the summer of 1962 photographing Marilyn at a beach house in Santa
Monica.
During the days and nights of these weeks Barris captured her every mood and
almost every move, as she unfolded her life story to him.
The book contains more than a hundred pictures in colour and black and white,
taken on the beach and in the seclusion of the timber house. They show Marilyn
at work, making-up, at play, dressing, eating, drinking, and cavorting in the
sand - some are obviously posed, others are quite candid.
Many of the images included have never previously appeared in print, and allied
to Monroe's own words they become a touching and revealing, if not always
flattering, insight into the private world of this movie legend.
The book also contains a list of people who featured in the star's life and the
categories into which they fell, ranging from ``close friend and confidante''
referring to a movie director/photographer, to ``heartbreaker and user''
reserved for one politician and one Attorney General.
Marilyn telephoned Barris only 24 hours before her death. He believes she did
not die by her own hand, but was in fact murdered.
</TEXT>
