<TEXT>
THE THOUGHT GANG, Tibor Fischer, Minerva, #6.99.
NOT since J P Donleavy's The Ginger Man and Derek Raymond's The Crust on its
Uppers - both of early-1960s vintage - has a funnier, racier, or more
intelligent lowlife novel of the monologue kind been written then Tibor
Fischer's second. Starring Eddie Coffin, a hard-drinking former philosophy
lecturer driven by tough luck and embezzlement into a career of crashing French
banks with a one-armed robber called Hubert, this exhilarating philosophical
thriller is simultaneously realistic and fantastical, accessible and arcane,
simple and profound.
Imagine the younger Martin Amis in collaboration with Quentin Tarantino and
you'll have some idea of the flavour of this crackerjack book.
A HARD DAY'S WRITE: The Stories Behind Every Beatles Song, Steve Turner,
Carlton, #12.99.
THE Beatles have inspired many more books (most of them very bad) than they
ever recorded songs (most of them very good). Steve Turner's diligent collation
of folklore and gossip, though often trite - what can the Higher Criticism say
about Hold Me Tight or Baby's In Black? - contains enough nuggets of insight
and background information to put it on the right side of the Beatle-book
divide.
From Love Me Do to Let It Be, it's all here, handsomely printed and lavishly
illustrated (if not all that well written).
WOODY ALLEN ON WOODY ALLEN, Stig Bjrkman (interviewer), Faber, #8.99)
STRUCTURED as 24 separate interviews focusing on all Woody Allen's films as
director from Take The Money And Run (1969) to Manhattan Murder Mystery (1993),
plus Herbert Ross's Play It Again, Sam (1972) - which makes 24 films - this is
a great book for committed Allen fans, but might be a little too fond for more
selective movie buffs.
Although Allen proves a great interviewee (funny, self-critical, always willing
to talk about detail, technique, and ideas), too many of Bjrkman's questions
can be reduced to Woody, tell me how and why you're so brilliant.
UNSENT LETTERS, Malcolm Bradbury, Penguin, #6.99.
AS a major-league academic (Professor of English Literature at East Anglia)
and as a successful novelist, Malcolm Bradbury gets many letters. Broadly
speaking, they fall into the categories of Can you get me a job?, Can you get
my novel published?, and Would you like to write my thesis for me?
The conceit of this genially acerbic collection of essays and disguised
autobiography is that it is couched as replies to suchlike inquirers, and the
result is a treat of literary drollery.
THE JIM THOMPSON OMNIBUS, Picador, #7.99.
IF Jim Thompson didn't invent the roman noir (as with the works of
Shakespeare, there are many claimants), this collection of four of his most
genre-perfect lowlife novels, all of them filmed, proves that he perfected it.
The Getaway, The Killer Inside Me, and The Grifters, boil the post-war American
malaise down to the hard brass tacks of money, sex, and power, while never
rejecting (Thompson was a solid socialist and a victim of the McCarthy
insanity) the possibility of redemption. Call him the Camus of crime.
</TEXT>
