<TEXT>
Looking for ways to beat the winter blast?
John Davidson tells how to really chill out
LET'S get practical. Want to beat the icy blasts and rainy downpours of the
Christmas shopping season? Just p-p-p-pick up a Puffa. You can choose the
authentic thing of course: a brand-name Puffa jacket. And very good value it is
too. But perhaps you'll opt for one of the many lookalike (and act-alike)
versions available this winter from fashion names both great and lowly.
Like an invasion from outer space, the Puffa has landed. Here is a light-weight
and weatherproof garment which fuses fashion and practicality. It's sporty,
it's serviceable, and it looks pretty good too. Of course anything quilted or
padded inevitably adds a great deal of bulk. But would you not happily trade a
temporary loss of figure for guaranteed warmth and dryness?
Designers are in on this act. Designers, that is, like Donna Karan, whose DKNY
collection includes the perfect warm, weather-proof jacket to cheat the
sub-zero temperatures of a New York winter. Thanks to Moschino, others can
dismiss winter's chill with a good-hearted shrug of a shoulder clad in dayglo
green quilted nylon.
Fashion, quite literally from the laboratory? Yes; by using high technology
performance fabrics, that's what Issey Miyake, the iconoclastic Japanese
designer, offers in his Windcoat collection. The finished garments cover just
about all that you could ever ask of a weather-coat or jacket. All, that is,
except a bargain price.
But familiar High Street names are equally keen to insulate their customers
against the bitterest elements. And every store has an area devoted to
variations on the quilt theme, with jackets and gilets usually well under #100
- sometimes under #50. So why not join this winter's invasion of the
body-snatchers? Better to be a quilted roly-poly than a shivering skeleton.
Just chill out, girl.
