<HEADLINE>Scent to make a world of  difference</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>Anvar Khan</BYLINE>
<EDITION>1</EDITION>
<PAGE>25</PAGE>
<RECORDNO>975208693</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
Anvar Khan sniffs around the latest oils and unguents designed to help you rub
along more smoothly
SMELLING is for dogs, but humans rely on the power of scent too. Take Proust.
He would travel 100km to Normandy each spring just to inhale the scent of apple
blossom because he believed it inspired him. Detractors might argue it didn't.
The German poet and dramatist Schiller, kept rotten apples in the drawer of his
desk, and would inhale them at moments where he found it difficult to find the
right phrase.
If I knew what the sweet smell of success was, I'd have that in my desk tidy
too. Writers and philosophers have such a tenuous relationship with the muse,
they are reduced, literally, to sniffing her out. I know she's female, that's
why she's temperamental.
Not so at Beauty Box, however, where copy flows effortlessly and eerily from a
distant part of the brain. The longer the road my thoughts have to travel, the
less responsible I feel, which provides me with that prerequisite of being a
scribe, a sense of moral detachment. A consistent selection of wiggy books,
dumping on the doormat, certainly helps, such as Create Your Own Perfumes
(using essential oils) by Chrissie Wildwood.
We learn that Napoleon used about 60 bottles of Rosemary cologne a month, but
objected to lover Josephine wearing a lesser quantity of musk. ``Je reviens en
trois jours, ne te laves pas!'' he said, asking her to refrain from washing for
three days, because he liked her to smell natural. The perfume Je Reviens was
inspired by his famous command, a fact which may or may not boost sales this
Christmas.
Wildwood does not skimp on the full story. After a brief introduction about the
hallucinogenic powers of drugs such as LSD, on which she sounds a little too
enthusiastic, she goes on to talk about provocative body scent. People who like
spicy food also plump for strong, penetrating fragrances such as patchouli,
sandalwood                   and ginger.
High dairy food consumers prefer light florals such as lavender and orange
blossom. Emotions, illness, the pill and other drugs as well as the hormonal
changes during puberty, pregnancy, menstruation and the menopause all influence
body odour and aroma preference.
This allegedly explains why the same perfume smells differently on each person
and why you can go off certain perfumes and flavours, only to return to them
later.
Interestingly, the perfume maker of ancient Egypt, was a priest or priestess
whose alchemical knowledge was employed to create sacred incense. Healing and
religion were interrelated, and sick people were ``smoked'' to exorcise evil
spirits. Indeed, the word perfume comes from the Latin per fumum, through the
smoke.
Frankincense resin was extracted from trees grown in South-west Arabia, and was
regarded as the mood-altering substance supreme. Yes, the infant Christ was
given a hallucinogenic drug as a gift from a King, but it was very expensive.
Frankincense is still burned today in Catholic churches.
In 1981 scientists in Germany investigated reports that altar boys were getting
``high'', and it was discovered that when frankincense is burned, it produces
trahydrocannabinole, a psycho-active substance which produces strange effects
on the imagination.
Apart from having a psychological effect on the brain, essential oils can
produce a physiological reaction. Perfumiers in France were often immune to the
plague, which led to the development of the Four Thieves' vinegar, a mixture of
garlic and aromatic plant essences, so-called after four thieves during the
Great Plague in Marseilles in 1722, sprinkled themselves liberally with it
before plundering the bodies of the plague victims. All four lived to plunder
again. The point of the book, however, by Wildwood, who sounds like a plant, is
to supply recipes for
Most interesting is the ``Love Potions'' section, which I have photocopied and
distributed to desperate girlfriends. You never know. ``I knew you were for me
the moment I smelled you,'' could soon be the one of the nicest things you hear
a guy say.
Create Your Own Perfumes by Chrissie Wildwood, published by Piatkus, #8.99.
