<TEXT>
Special travel correspondent Katie Wood casts an
experienced eye over the best in short breaks, long hauls, flights and travel
bargains
SCOTS rugby fans who are not yet booked up for the Irish International on
January 20 should act  now. One option is to take up the AT Mays package to
Dublin. Departure is on Friday, January 19 from Glasgow. For two nights B&amp;B,
airport transfers and the services of an AT Mays rep the cost is #265. Call
0141 951 8411, or see any AT Mays travel agency.
HISTORIC Scotland has received grants totalling #3,462,700 for the repair of
buildings of outstanding historic architectural interest. Properties benefiting
from this cash injection will be Nasmyth House Bridge in West Lothian,
Pollokshields Burgh Hall, Erskine House Stables, Culzean Castle and Sandrum
Castle, near Ayr.
SINGLE parents will be offered #60 off any Keycamp holiday taken between June
21 and September 2. Well priced European camping holidays have been their
speciality for many years, and in their new brochure you'll find many bargains.
They are also pushing low-cost spring bargain breaks, with prices from #145 for
10 nights. An average holiday in July and August will cost #328 for 12 nights
tent accommodation in Brittany, inclusive of return ferry crossings. Call 0181
395 4000.
ALTHOUGH it's far easier for the English to drive over to France for a villa
holiday, many Scots still make the pilgrimage each summer - particularly those
with a large family who don't fancy lashing out a four-figure sum on the
flights alone. For them Drive France is a name worth getting to know. This
specialist self-drive villa operator has launched a new look 1996 brochure,
featuring more than 400 properties, with prices starting at #195 per family
inclusive of ferry crossings and a week's accommodation in the Languedoc.
Accommodation featured includes a twelfth-century Presbytery in the Dordogne,
and a village house near Bergerac, complete with plunge pool.
Increased for this year are the number of larger houses that can accommodate
two families holidaying together. A house sleeping ten in the Dordogne costs
around #2000 for two weeks (#100 per person per week) in peak season. This
comes complete with swimming pool, table tennis and barbecue. Call 0181 395
8888 for a brochure.
BRITISH Airways are offering up to 47% off international flights from
Edinburgh to Dusseldorf (now #79) and Munich (#99). The same reduction applies
to flights from Glasgow to Dusseldorf (#79), Frankfurt (#89), and Milan.
Savings are also available on some domestic flights, with the reintroduction of
a seasonal low fare to encourage Scots to go Christmas shopping in London. This
runs until December 6 so hurry! Call 0345 222111.
SCANDIC Hotels has launched the world's first recyclable room in a move to
become one of the industry's most environmentally friendly hotel chains. The
Eco Room is an environmentally-adapted hotel room, 97% of which is recyclable
or biodegradable. It features wooden floors, furniture made from Nordic wood,
textiles in pure wool or cotton, and as few metal features as possible. The
group aims to develop at least two Eco Rooms in all of its hotels throughout
Europe during 1996/97.
BRITISH Midland is to provide a reservations booking service with payment on
the Internet - the first airline in the world to do so. Officially known as
CyberSeat, the service will be able to offer-last minute seat availability and
the latest fare offers as they are introduced. The computer can do every part
of the booking transaction and at the end of the seconds-long procedure a
booking number will be issued. The ticket can then be issued by the travel
agent, collected on check-in, or mailed.
To access the system in all its glory access the World Wide Web at
http://www.iflybritishmidland.com. From December 11, this will allow you to
make genuine bookings.
LOOKING for a quality coach holiday with a difference? Fife-based tour
operator DA Tours may have the answer. This member of the Association of
Independent Tour Operators has some packages not found in any of the big boy's
brochures. The combination of Paris and Bruges is one nice example; a Swiss
House Party is another. For New Year they are offering a six-day break in the
Monschau region of Germany.
Portugal, Spain, France, Italy, Germany, Austria, Switzerland, Holland, Denmark
and Belgium are all offered. Local departure points throughout Scotland are low
prices (#350 a week on half board is average). Call 0383 881700 for a brochure.
BELGIAN Travel Service currently have #31 off holidays with Eurostar to
Ostend, Ghent, Bruges and Antwerp, with the price for Bruges starting at #154
per person. A coach and hovercraft option has been added to their 1996 brochure
giving a good budget alternative. Two nights in Brussels now starts from as low
as #139. SunPark holidays in holiday camps throughout Belgium are available
with prices starting at #199 for four nights for a family of four in a villa.
Travel agents have brochures or call 01992 456156.
THE National Trust for Scotland has launched its Fair Isle Cruise brochure for
1996. The itinerary to Norway and the North Cape should make for a stunning
piece of travelling, especially as it is timed to coincide with the time of
year when darkness never falls. Sailing out of Leith on Wednesday, June 19,
your ports of call include Fair Isle, Lofoten Islands, Honningsvag, Murmansk,
Bodo, Trondheim and Bergen. You arrive back in Leith on Wednesday, July 3. The
all-in price starts at #1200 for an inside four-berth cabin and goes up to
#4410 for single occupancy of a superior cabin. Tel 0131 243 9333 for
information.
