<HEADLINE>Lost in the Celtic twilight</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>LORN MACINTYRE</BYLINE>
<EDITION>1</EDITION>
<PAGE>14</PAGE>
<ARTICLETYPE>Book Review</ARTICLETYPE>
<GRAPHIC>Photograph</GRAPHIC>
<RECORDNO>975208696</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
Yeats's World: Ireland, England and the Poetic Imagination
David Pierce
Yale, #30
THIS spring I was privileged to do some research in the archives of the Irish
Folklore Commission in University College, Dublin. I saw shelves of collections
of folktales in Irish stretching back to last century, including some written
up in school jotters. I recalled W.B Yeats's famous poem Among School Children,
beginning: ``I walk through the long schoolroom questioning .....'' It occurred
to me that Yeats, hailed as the greatest Irish poet of this century, could not
have read one line of what was written in these Irish jotters.
This fundamental paradox of Yeats, the English speaker as the voice of Ireland
is explored in Yeats's Worlds: Ireland, England and the Poetic Imagination, by
David Pierce, principal lecturer in English at the University College of Ripon
and York St John.
Though born in Ireland, Yeats went to school in Hammersmith, and lived for more
than half his life in London. The illustrations of substantial houses in
Pierce's study show a prosperous ancestry with English roots. The poet's
grandfather William Pollexfen, who came from a landed Devon family, ran away to
sea and found himself in Sligo, from where he controlled a shipping company.
It was while staying with his Pollexfen grandfather that Yeats developed an
obsessive interest in the Irish tradition which he tried to access through
English in ``Celtic twilight'' fashion. ``Because he never learnt Irish, Yeats
perhaps never thought deeply about the loss of language,'' Pierce argues.
``When he constructs his tradition of Irish literature, the Gaelic culture is
there, but his stress falls on continuity.
For someone who made so much of sincerity as a benchmark, he crossed certain
fault lines with consummate ease. It is extraordinary - but in keeping - that
in his Hanrahan stories in The Secret Rose (1897) he sought to identify himself
with Eogan Rua O'Sullivan, the red-haired Gaelic poet of the eighteenth
century, and no less extraordinary that he should imagine himself as the Gaelic
folk-poet Raftery and Maud Gonne as his Mary Hynes, ``a peasant girl commended
by a song''.
J.M Synge was much better equipped than Yeats to be an authentic Irish voice.
As Pierce points out, the author of The Playboy of the Western World had
studied Irish and Celtic civilisation at the Sorbonne, going to the west of
Ireland and the Aran Islands each year to improve his spoken Irish and
assimilate the lifestyle of the ordinary people. He spoke for them: ``..... it
is part of the misfortune of Ireland that nearly all the characteristics which
give colour and attractiveness to Irish life are bound up with a social
condition that is near to penury .....''
In Yeats's world, there was a romantic polarity between the peasantry and
``hard riding country gentlemen''. He hob-nobbed with the Anglo-Irish
Protestant ascendancy, most notably Lady Gregory at Coole, where he was seen
``stalking across the lawn ..... with fishing rod, basket and net, looking like
one of the gentry''. He became in effect an Ascendancy bard.
Pierce is instructive on Yeats's occult interests. My own belief is that he
dabbled in the paranormal because he believed that it was a way of
circumventing his lack of Irish to access the Irish psyche, a form of
``speaking in tongues''.
The questions raised by Pierce's study - the most honest I have read on the
venerated Yeats - are profound and sometimes disturbing ones which have
relevance to the status of Scottish as well as Irish Gaelic in our time, and to
the claim of writers in one language to speak for a culture that evolved
through an earlier language.
Sorley MacLean and Derick Thomson write in Scottish Gaelic, the language of
their tradition. Will they, and Irish poets such as Nuala Ni Dhomhnaill who
remain faithful to their native language, ever be recognised as the authentic
voices, or is this impossible because they are judged in translation in a
language in which much is lost and too much assumed, sometimes for political
reasons?
</TEXT>
</DOC>
