<HEADLINE>Zen and the art of Scots writing</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>DEIRDRE CHAPMAN</BYLINE>
<EDITION>1</EDITION>
<PAGE>13</PAGE>
<ARTICLETYPE>Book Review</ARTICLETYPE>
<FLAG>Weekend Extra</FLAG>
<RECORDNO>975208697</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
STONE GARDEN and Other
Stories
Alan Spence
Phoenix House, #15.99
INTEGRITY is not rare in Scottish writing. At times the Scots seem to have a
monopoly of it, a refusal to strike attractive attitudes merely to be
entertaining. Alan Spence has something beyond integrity, a sort of spiritual
purity that inhibits gut reaction before a drop of adrenalin has been shed. Now
that is rare.
If you equate harmony with blandness his stories ought to sag gracefully to a
limp conclusion. In fact Spence's great achievement, particularly in the
concluding three stories of this collection, is to make his attentive
non-judgmental way of looking at things - ``the music of what happens'' - as
triumphantly powerful as aggro-and-appetite stories and often more memorable.
His feeling for childhood recall - not at all the same thing as nostalgia - is
at its most direct in the brief Rupert Bear and The San Izal. The sick child is
off school, engaged in the eternal mysteries of Rupert and The Conjuror and
Tiger Lily, his mother delayed at the shops. Impossibly delayed at the shops.
He is jolted out of the luxury of fantasy to the overwhelming realisation of
dependence, from the book to the possibilities of the Poison label on the
disinfectant bottle by the sink.
Bland Umbrellas is the Aids story, an episodic tale intercut with flashbacks to
a Glasgow adolescence when two friends, fresh out of school, hitch to sixties
London, ``the end of the Yellow Brick road'', react psychedelically to a shop
sign, ``Bland Umbrellas'' and separate, the friend to stay in London.
The narrator now in mid-life, flying with briefcase to the capital, begins a
crossword puzzle which he concludes on the return journey, a journey where the
stewardess wears a perfume called Eternity and he is haunted by a meeting with
his sick friend. The crossword clue finally yields Totality. The story
concludes, ``The smell of eternity. The blandness of umbrellas. The shortness
of a life. Totality. The whole jing-bang. All of it''.
Spence does a lot of that, working towards an ordained conclusion with the use
of key words, as befits a writer whose engagement with Eastern philosophies has
been a major thread in his life.
In the less well-worked stories the device comes across as a mite too obtrusive
and committed for the seamless fabric he is aiming to weave. But the concrete
basis of all his fiction is the working-class Glasgow of the fifties and
sixties, a safeguard against pretension and, for Spence, an affirmation of
humanity and moral values in the midst of deprivation.
Sailmaker, about a grief-stricken widowed father and young son staunching their
wounds, one with drink and one with home work, is the finest of these childhood
stories, full of love and resilience, the son trying to find the father's
salvation in the practice of his forgotten skills. Anger has no place in these
stories but anxiety is always present.
Bird of Paradise and Milan Cathedral at the Bottom of the Sea move out to the
Caribbean and to Italy for more sophisticated and metaphysical adult tales,
I'll be Han-Shan. You Ne Shif-Te, returns to Loch Lomondside for a self-mocking
tale of an effortful Zen camping trip.
But easily the most accomplished is the concluding trinity of the title story,
Stone Garden, the McVitie Prize-winning Nessum Dorma, and Beyond the Wall, some
remarkable ruminations on running the Glasgow Marathon.
Stone Garden is set in Japan where a businessman seeking an order for his
Scottish firm encounters the Japanese life of the mind, a collage of restraint,
courtesy and aspiration, of rock gardens, Haikus and maple-viewing. Jogging up
out of the city and into the mountains he discovers a solitary Buddhist monk
living in a hut who draws him into a ritual in his ramshackle shrine and gives
him a T-shirt printed How would you like to keep 3 cats! Look you?
``How could growing up in Glasgow have led him there, to this? And yet. That
recurring sense of something familiar.'' The Spence alter ego, shorn of
limiting stylistic adhesions and open to the daily miracles of living, is never
truly surprised. The businessman who keeps a paperweight on his desk made from
the melted windows of his childhood home in Hiroshima and the interpreter who
draws from him memories of his former self are infinitely understandable,
echoes of a common past.
Nessum Dorma moves to Edinburgh and uses the Zen approach to astonishing effect
in a tenement setting. Pavarotti's voice blares from an open window in a ground
floor room where a woman sits, oblivious to everything, re-winding the World
Cup video tape.
Over the space of 24 hours the tape continues to play while the narrator's
memory of his father's Jussi Bjorling version and the story of the opera
Turandot blend with street scenes, sporadic thought trains, neighbour reactions
and a police visit building to an intentional anti-climax. ``The music of what
happens . . . Vincero.''
Beyond the Wall is perhaps the most impressive of all for its stealthy
conversion of a fun run through the streets of Glasgow with routine time
checks, medical bulletins, sightings of key addresses - single-end, school,
university - into a shining and integrated whole, the uncompetitive race a
metaphor for life lived to the best of one's ability.
A local story made translucently universal by application of the philosophy of
respect for all people and all things.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
