<TEXT>
ENGLISH grandmaster Mark Hebden took the Glasgow Open by storm earlier this
month, winning the #500 first prize with a 5/5 perfect score. The event, part
of the 34th Glasgow Congress, was sponsored by Luddon Construction and Glasgow
District Council. Some 350 players took part in the Congress, which took place
in Glasgow North College (November 3-5).
Hebden, a frequent visitor to Scottish Congresses, played superbly. Two of his
five victims were joint 1995 Scottish champions, Stephen Mannion and Colin
McNab. No-one came near him. Scottish international Andrew Muir, who managed to
avoid being paired against him, finished outright second on 4/5.
Much was expected of the only other grandmaster in the field, Colin McNab. He
took the #500 first prize in the General Accident Perth Open (October 6-8),
Scotland's strongest event last month. In Glasgow, however, McNab was ground
down in an endgame by Hebden and became just one more of the Englishman's
victims in his awesome, unstoppable run.
When Hebden is on form like this, he provides excellent value for the gallery.
A very practical player, he rarely runs short of time and is always prepared to
take calculated risks in pursuit of a win. His speed of play, aggression and
apparent nervelessness at the board, added to a well thought out, slightly
off-beat opening repertoire, are his prime assets.
